<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Hard Currency </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
China warns businesses about circumventing exchange controls
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ In a campaign to shore up the value of its
currency, China's government has warned businesses not to
circumvent foreign exchange controls, state media reported Monday.
	   The State Council, China's Cabinet, issued a recent directive,
threatening businesses with loss of licenses and other unspecified
punishment if they exploited legal loopholes, forged documents or
turned to the black market to trade hard currency.
	   Government policies confining conversion of the Chinese yuan to
international trade have largely protected it from the batterings
many Asian currencies have taken over the past 15 months.
	   Despite the policies and repeated pledges by Chinese leaders not
to devalue the yuan, however, back-door pressures on the currency
are mounting.
	   The government's dlrs 140 billion in foreign exchange reserves
has stopped growing this year as exporters hold on to more of their
hard currency earnings instead of remitting them to Beijing.
	   A black market exchange rate for the dollar that is 10 percent
above official rates suggests many Chinese fell less confident
about the yuan and government policies.
	   Analysts estimate as much as dlrs 13 billion a year drifts in
and out of China through holes in its foreign exchange regime.
	   The State Council directive was the highest-level order to date
demanding an end to questionable and outright illegal foreign
currency deals. In an indication of its importance, reports on the
circular were carried on state-run television and the front-page of
national newspapers.
	   ``Some people forge documents to purchase foreign exchange; some
local authorities and companies issue debt or raise funds overseas
without approval,'' said an editorial in People's Daily, the ruling
Communist Party's flagship newspaper.
	   Such dealings ``are not conducive to the international balance
of payments, yuan stability and the healthy development of the
national economy,'' the newspaper said.
	   The State Council ordered the State Administration of Foreign
Exchange to better police banks and enterprises allowed to trade in
foreign currency.
	   The administration was told to punish businesses caught trading
without documents or with forged ones and revoke import-export
permits of firms with more than dlrs 1 million in illegal deals.
	   Reports on the directive also said a nationwide computer network
would be set up linking customs and foreign exchange regulators to
better track the trade. 	   
</TEXT>
