w2296 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Australia-Indonesia-E     09-28 0329
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Indonesia-East Timor </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian opposition leader pledges East Timor referendum
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Indonesian political opposition leader
Amien Rais on Monday pledged to hold a referendum on
self-determination for East Timor if he became president next year.
	   Rais, who was in Sydney to give a public lecture on political
reform in Indonesia, told reporters a referendum was the only
solution for East Timor.
	   ``A referendum is the only solution to solve the problem,
however I believe a referendum must not be given as a quick fix,
because there are two conflicting groups in East Timor and we have
to ask them to sit down together and then to swear.
	   ``They have to really promise -- swear -- that whatever the
result of the referendum, they will respect it.
	   ``So after they have come to such consensus, then a referendum
can be given to the East Timorese people and it must be supervised
by United Nations bodies.''
	   Rais played a key role in bringing about the resignation of
President Suharto in May and is personally close to Suharto's
successor, B.J. Habibie.
	   Rais has declared himself as a candidate for the presidency in
1999.
	   The former leader of Indonesia's second largest Muslim
organization said he had resisted offers to join political parties
based on religion and started his own National Mandate Party
instead because he wanted a broader political base.
	   He dismissed continuing suspicions in the West that he advocated
an Islamic state, saying Indonesia's separation of church and state
was the best way to go.
	   ``I don't believe religion can be the basis of the state unless
99.9 percent of the people have the same belief,'' Rais said.
	   Indonesia's population is about 87 percent Muslim.
	   Indonesia invaded East Timor, a former Portuguese colony, in
1975 and annexed it the following year in a move not recognized by
the United Nations.
	   pjs
</TEXT>
