w2305 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Cambodia-NewGovernmen     09-28 0634
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-New Government </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cambodian rivals to negotiate formation of new government
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CHRIS FONTAINE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ A year after turning Phnom Penh into
a war zone, Cambodia's two largest political parties head to the
negotiating table this week in an attempt to diffuse post-election
tensions and form a new government.
	   An uneasy coalition between strongman Hun Sen's Cambodian
People's Party and Prince Norodom Ranariddh's FUNCINPEC party in
1993 erupted in violence four years later, and it seems unlikely
that the two leaders will be able to form a stable marriage.
	   Senior officials from the two parties will nonetheless try to
hammer out a comprehensive deal in ``working group'' sessions
beginning Tuesday.
	   Hun Sen is clearly operating from a position of strength.
	   His ruling party won a slight majority in the July 26 elections
_ the opposition says through fraud and intimidation _ and his
party retains iron-fisted control of the police, military and
local-level government.
	   In the days after the preliminary poll results came in, Hun Sen
demanded he be named premier and his party be given the presidency
of parliament and five key ministries _ defense, interior, foreign
affairs, justice and finance.
	   But FUNCINPEC and the Sam Rainsy Party _ winners of a combined
58 out of 122 seats _ can deny Hun Sen the two-thirds vote needed
in parliament to approve the new government.
	   After launching anti-government demonstrations last month
calling for Hun Sen's ouster and threatening to boycott the Sept.
24 opening of Parliament, they have successfully forced Hun Sen to
soften his stance.
	   CPP spokesman Khieu Kanharith said that although Hun Sen refuses
to budge on his candidacy for the premiership and that of party
president Chea Sim as chairman of the National Assembly, the demand
for the five ministries has been withdrawn.
	   ``Everything else is negotiable. We need this as a precondition
to show we are serious,'' Khieu Kanharith said.
	   Second-term lawmaker Ahmad Yahya, a FUNCINPEC steering committee
member, said that despite the concession, the opposition would
still argue that it should be given the presidency because Hun
Sen's party got it after losing the 1993 election.
	   The issue over the presidency could stall the working group
until after the National Assembly reconvenes Wednesday because
FUNCINPEC has decided that the leadership of parliament should be
determined before moving on to government positions, Ahmad Yahya
said.
	   ``What we decided is that our policy is to go step by step,'' he
said. ``Without consensus and agreement in the National Assembly,
we will not form the government.''
	   Hun Sen needs FUNCINPEC to gain the two-thirds vote needed to
determine the National Assembly leadership and approve the new
government, but the junior opposition party led by Sam Rainsy,
winners of only 15 seats, could get shut out of the deal.
	   Hun Sen has repeatedly said that his party prefers a two-party
coalition with FUNCINPEC, and Khieu Kanharith said Monday that it
is uncertain whether Sam Rainsy will even be invited to the working
group sessions.
	   The pressure is on both opposition parties to form the
government sooner rather than later following two alleged attempts
on Hun Sen's life after the election.
	   The Cambodian leader _ who has claimed several plots on his life
in recent years _ has blamed the opposition for the attacks and
threatened its leadership with arrest.
	   A foreign travel ban was placed on all opposition lawmakers, but
the restriction was lifted after the opposition attended the
opening session of parliament last week.
	   Both Ranariddh and Sam Rainsy tested their freedom of movement
with a Friday trip to Bangkok. 	   
</TEXT>
