<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Budget </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: Taiwan balanced budget last year, but red ink ahead
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ Taiwan recorded a budget surplus last year
for the first time since 1990, but rising spending points to a wave
of red ink in the future, a newspaper reported Monday.
	   Officials compiling a report due for release next month say
income exceeded expenditures by about 60 billion Taiwan dollars
(U.S. dlrs 1.74 billion) in fiscal 1998, the United Daily News
reported.
	   But this year's budget and those following will likely slide
into deficit again with the government upping spending on
infrastructure to help pull the economy through the Asian financial
crisis, the paper quoted the unidentified officials as saying.
	   Increased tax revenues were the main reason for the fiscal 1998
surplus, especially stock transaction taxes collected as the market
climbed to new peaks last year, the paper said.
	   Stronger than expected performances by state owned industries
and a slight decline in government spending also helped, it said.
	   Increased spending on everything from military hardware to
social welfare has saddled the government with over 1 trillion
Taiwan dollars (U.S. dlrs 30 billion) in debt accumulated over the
last eight years.
	   The government has committed itself to a balanced budget by
2001, but increased spending and assumption of local government
debts will render that goal difficult to reach, the paper said.
	   The relatively low level of public debt and strong foreign
currency reserves of over U.S. dlrs 82 billion have kept the
economy on an even keel as neighboring countries find themselves
devastated by the Asian economic crisis. 	   
</TEXT>
