<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-Vaughn Homers,0173 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Vaughn hits 50th home run
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PHOENIX (AP) _ San Diego's Greg Vaughn hit his 50th home run in
his final game of the season Sunday night, making 1998 the first
year four players reached the mark in a single season.
	   Vaughn sent a 1-2 pitch from reliever Aaron Small into the
Arizona bullpen down the left-field line in the eighth inning.
	   He joined Mark McGwire (70), Sammy Sosa (66) and Ken Griffey Jr.
(56) in the 50-homer club. The two-run homer, which gave San Diego
a 3-1 lead, also gave Vaughn a career-best 119 RBIs.
	   Vaughn is the 10th NL player and 27th major leaguer to hit 50
home runs in a season.
	   Up until two years ago, there had been just three seasons when a
pair of players reached 50. In 1938, Hank Greenberg hit 58 and
Jimmie Foxx had 50; in 1947, Ralph Kiner and Johnny Mize each hit
51; and in 1961 Roger Maris hit 61 and Mickey Mantle hit 54.
	   In 1996, McGwire had 52 and Brady Anderson hit 50. Last year,
McGwire hit 58 more and Griffey hit 56.
</TEXT>
