<SLUG> BC-Australia-BHP-Asian Crisis </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Asian crisis forces BHP to close rolling mills
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ADELAIDE, Australia (AP) _ The Asian economic crisis has forced
steel and mineral giant BHP's Whyalla steelworks in South Australia
to close its rolling mills for almost three weeks starting Monday.
	   A spokesman for the company said about 375 of the works' 400
staff agreed to take either annual or long-service leave while
those remaining had been allocated other duties.
	   The plant would remain closed until Oct. 16.
	   The spokesman said the widely reported Asian problems had
weakened demand in a number of BHP's traditional steel markets.
	   But he said the company had been successful over the past 12
months in opening new markets in other parts of the world and
efforts in that direction would continue.
	   Another shutdown of the mills was planned at the end of the year
when routine maintenance would be conducted.
	   The spokesman said the company had no plans to reduce the shift
levels in the rolling mills and no plans to close the plant
permanently. 	   
</TEXT>
