<SLUG> BC-SKorea-President </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Korean President predicts economic recovery next year
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By PAUL SHIN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ South Korea's president predicted
Monday that his country's contracting economy will resume growth in
the latter part of next year.
	   In a news conference devoted solely to economic matters, Kim
Dae-jung said tax cuts and other pump-priming measures will help
resuscitate the domestic economy.
	   ``In a word, there will be no second financial crisis,'' Kim
said. ``If we continue reform measures as we do now, the economy
will pick up later next year.''
	   Citing shrinking domestic consumption and exports _ the engine
of the country's economy _ some analysts have warned that South
Korea may be headed for a new financial crisis.
	   But Kim said the government, backed by a record foreign currency
reserve of dlrs 44 billion, will easily be able to repay dlrs 9
billion in external debt coming due this year and dlrs 36 billion
due next year.
	   ``Despite many uneasy international factors as shown in Japan,
Russia, Southeast Asia and South America, the value of our currency
has been stable and I believe the trend will continue,'' Kim said.
	   The president said his prediction of an economic turnaround next
year depends on how fast and effectively the economy can be
restructured, especially the financial and industrial sectors.
	   ``I know there is criticism that our reforms in these areas are
not fast enough, but significant progress so far has been made and
the prospects are good,'' he said.
	   Kim said his government will finish restructuring the banking
sector by the end of this month and make more low-interest loans
available for cash-strapped businesses.
	   So far this year, the government has shut down five troubled
commercial banks and 16 finance companies and ordered seven major
commercial banks to improve their financial structure or face
closure or merger.
	   The unions of the seven banks, which have a combined 30,000
members, threaten to go on strike Tuesday to protest the government
order, which would involve manpower cuts. 	   
</TEXT>
