<SLUG> BC-Japan-Bank Tie-up, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan's Asahi, Tokai banks announce alliance
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS; UPDATES with confirmation of agreement, details of
pact &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Preparing for increased competition in Japan's
liberalizing financial sector, two midsize Japanese city banks
announced Monday that they will form a broad business alliance.
	   Asahi Bank Ltd. and Tokai Bank Ltd. said in a statement that
they intend to cooperate in private banking, investment trusts and
the launch of financial products, such as derivatives.
	   The banks said they also hope to enter a cross-shareholding
agreement and eventually set up a joint holding company.
	   Asahi and Tokai said that the alliance would help them cope with
the stepped up competition expected to result from Japan's ``big
bang'' financial deregulation measures.
	   The two banks said they hope to cut costs by 50 billion yen
(dlrs 368 million) by consolidating redundant operations. The
tie-up is based on the condition that the banks will quickly write
off their non-performing assets.
	   The alliance announcement comes amid ongoing consolidation in
Japan's financial sector ahead of the introduction of the ``big
bang'' measures.
	   Earlier this month, four Mitsubishi group financial institutions
agreed to set up a securities company capitalized at about 200-300
billion yen (dlrs 1.46-2.19 billion).
	   In July, financial giants Sumitomo Bank and Daiwa Securities Co.
agreed on a partnership in the investment banking business.
	   Tokyo-based Asahi Bank has 429 offices worldwide, employs 12,688
people and has total deposits of 20.4 trillion yen (dlrs 150
billion).
	   Tokai Bank, based in Nagoya, western Japan, has 303 offices
worldwide, employs 11,407 people and has total deposits of 19.9
trillion yen (dlrs 146 billion).
	   Reports of the partnership sent shares of the banks sharply
higher Monday morning on the Tokyo Stock Exchange. Asahi shares
rose 1.6 percent to 391 yen (dlrs 2.86), while those of Tokai
gained 2.1 percent to 542 yen (dlrs 3.96).
 &UR; (js-apdj) 	   
</TEXT>
