<SLUG> BC-India-Kashmir,0175 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Daylong gunbattle leaves eight soldiers injured
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAMMU, India (AP) _ Indian soldiers traded fire with Kashmiri
separatists hidden in a forest for 24 hours over the weekend in a
battle that left eight soldiers injured, four of them seriously.
	   Indian army sources speaking on condition of anonymity Monday
said no casualties were reported among the guerrillas, who held
strategic hilltop positions during the clash. The sources said more
troops were being brought in Monday to launch a new attack.
	   The battle began late Saturday after soldiers acting on a tip
cordoned off a Fatehpur Mountains forest district 200 kilometers
(125 miles) north of Jammu, the winter capital of Indian-held
Kashmir.
	   A heavy exchange of fire lasted until late Sunday, the sources
said.
	   Muslim militants have been fighting since 1989 in Kashmir, which
is the only Muslim-majority state in predominately Hindu India.
Some of the militants want independence, while others want to merge
with neighboring and officially Islamic Pakistan. 	   
