<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Indonesia-Opposition </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Opposition leader says Bali party congress will proceed
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JAKARTA, Indonesia (AP) _ Indonesian opposition figure Megawati
Sukarnoputri said Monday a planned mass gathering of her political
faction will go ahead on the island of Bali next month, despite
fears that it could endanger the lucrative tourism industry.
	   Police have threatened to ban the gathering. However, organizers
said the meeting will go ahead with or without a permit from
authorities.
	   Thousands are expected to attend the congress of Megawati's
faction of the Indonesian Democratic Party, or PDI, at a beach
resort hotel between Oct. 8 and 10.
	   Many are coming from the neighboring main island of Java, which
was hit by deadly riots this year.
	   The government has called on her to move the location of the
congress amid fears that it might turn violent and scare away
foreign tourists.
	   Bali is a Hindu enclave in otherwise Muslim-dominated Indonesia,
now enduring its worst economic downturn in decades.
	   The so-called ``Island of the Gods'' is Indonesia's biggest
international tourist destination and a major source of badly
needed foreign exchange.
	   Until now, it's been untouched by the civil unrest that has
caused havoc in many other parts of Indonesia, climaxing with the
resignation in May of President Suharto after 1,200 people were
killed in rioting.
	   Megawati downplayed the prospect of trouble in Bali.
	   ``The congress must go ahead,'' Megawati told about 1,000
supporters at a policy seminar in Jakarta on Monday.
	   ``We are not wild and we are not rioters just because we support
the common people,'' she said.
	   Over the weekend, newspapers quoted Megawati as saying only
officials of the party would be invited to attend. She called on
other supporters to stay away.
	   Megawati is the eldest daughter of Sukarno, Indonesia's founding
president. With that pedigree she is regarded as a strong contender
for the presidency to be decided after parliamentary elections next
year.
	   Many of her supporters are workers and poor people hit hard by
soaring prices and mass unemployment.
	   One of the key objects of the planned congress is to try to grab
back control of the PDI, which has been wracked by political
squabbling and violence for years.
	   Megawati maintains she was deposed illegally as party chairwoman
in 1996, when dozens of her supporters were later killed or injured
in a clash with police and troops in the capital, Jakarta.
	   She has accused Suharto of being behind her ouster by a rival
party faction.
	   Suharto's successor, President B.J. Habibie still refuses to
recognize Megawati as the true PDI chief. 	   
</TEXT>
