<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Aborigines </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Aborigines threaten to take genocide case to World Court
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ALAN THORNHILL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CANBERRA, Australia (AP) _ Aboriginal elders who want to charge
Prime Minister John Howard with genocide said Monday they will take
their case to the World Court if necessary.
	   Their lawyer Len Lindon made the threat as he pressed their case
before Judge Ken Crispin of the Australian capital territory's
Supreme Court.
	   The International Court of Justice, as the World Court is
formally known, sits in The Hague and decides cases between nations
and involving treaties. States have to consent to its authority for
its ruling to be binding.
	   It is not clear how the Aboriginal elders would have the
authority to file a case with the International Court of Justice,
though they could contend that Australia is violating the U.N.
Convention against Genocide, which it has signed.
	   Lindon said genocide started with British colonization in 1788,
``It is continuing and will get worse.''
	   Aboriginal lawyer Michael Anderson, who also represented the
elders, said a British assumption that Aborigines had no culture of
their own had led to vicious policies of assimilation that had left
many Aboriginal communities ``spiritually sterile.''
	   ``People who are spiritually sterile depend on the grog
(alcohol) and other drugs to get them through the hardships of
life,'' he said.
	   Anderson said Australian law is still based on British
tradition.
	   Colonial authorities in Australia had ignored the instructions
of the British government, which had recognized that Aboriginal
life could be destroyed in Australia and wanted to prevent that
happening, he said.
	   But the colonial authorities had simply expected Aborigines to
die out.
	   That was made clear at a conference the Australian government
called in 1937 to deal with Aboriginal issues, when the
commissioner of native affairs in Western Australia, A.O. Neville,
said: ``We should forget that there were any Aborigines in this
country in 50 years' time.''
	   Anderson said successive Australian governments had not only
pursued policies of apartheid and genocide since colonization but
they had also kept their actions hidden from international
scrutiny.
	   The case is based specifically on Howard's successful move in
Parliament earlier this year to restrict Aboriginal land rights on
lands leased from the government.
	   Howard said then that this was necessary to give the country's
miners and ranchers the certainty of title to land they need to
conduct their businesses.
	   The case was adjourned for eight weeks, so that written
submissions on legal aspects can be made.
	   Howard was not represented in court.
	   at-pjs
</TEXT>
