<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Kia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With BC-South Korea-President
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Third auction to be called for bankrupt Kia Motors

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ After two previous attempts to sell
bankrupt Kia Motors Corp. failed, President Kim Dae-jung on Monday
ordered a new auction for the troubled South Korean auto firm.
	   ``A third auction will be called and various measures are being
considered to prevent it from being aborted,'' Kim said at a news
conference outlining his government's economic policies.
	   The first attempt to auction off the country's second-largest
automaker and its commercial vehicle arm, Asia Motors Co., was
scuttled by creditors Sept. 1 when bidders demanded bigger debt
write-offs.
	   The creditor banks said then that they would write off dlrs 2.1
billion of Kia's dlrs 8.4 billion debt and put the company back on
the auction block.
	   But that effort failed to impress the three South Korean
automakers who submitted new bids for Kia last week. Ford Motor Co.
of the United States withdrew from the second round of bidding.
	   Hyundai Motor Co., Samsung Motors Corp. and Daewoo Motor Co. all
said Kia's debt load was still too heavy, Kia officials said.
	   The president did not say what new conditions would be for the
third auction but local media quoted government officials they did
not identify as saying the amount of debts to be written off may be
increased to dlrs 3.2 billion.
	   The move to sell Kia is part of the government's effort to
restructure its battered economy under a dlrs 58 billion bailout
from the International Monetary Fund. Kia's collapse last year
helped erode investor confidence in South Korea's industries,
leading to a flight of capital.
	   Kia produced 780,000 cars in 1997. Asia Motors can turn out
250,000 vehicles, mostly trucks and buses, annually. The two
companies employ more than 18,000 workers. 	   
</TEXT>
