<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Gas Shortage, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Victoria state faces up to two weeks without gas as industry shuts
</HEADLINE>
down
 &UR; Eds: CORRECTS in lead to 1.4 million households affected &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) _ Industry in Australia's Victoria
state began massive shutdowns Monday as businesses and 1.4 million
households are without natural gas after a series of explosions and
a two-day fire crippled an Esso refinery.
	   Up to 100,000 workers may be sent home in the coming days, The
Age newspaper cited industry sources as saying, and the gas cutoff
could last two weeks, state Premier Jeff Kennett said after meeting
with Esso officials.
	   Hundreds of thousands of state residents are taking cold
showers, and are looking for electric griddles and fry pans to cook
their food. Many restaurants said they plan to close until the
weekend due to the gas shortage.
	   Victoria's largest crematorium has had to suspend cremations
until he crisis is resolved.
	   Car manufacturers Ford and Toyota have already announced
shutdowns, totaling 4,600 workers Monday. Another 3,000 workers
could be affected Tuesday.
	   Australian Industry Group director David Whiting said the range
of industries hit was massive, from car makers, breweries and dairy
and meat producers to small companies using heat to make ceramics,
office equipment or cement. There are about 100,000 businesses in
the state.
	   ``It is too early to put any real price on it, but we are
talking hundreds of millions'' of dollars in losses, Whiting said.
	   Law firm Slater and Gordon is considering what it says could be
the largest class action in Australian legal history, joining every
Victorian gas consumer in suing the gas provider and supplier.
	   Another firm, Maurice Blackburn and Co., will decide Monday if
it will take legal action on behalf of hospitality and union
clients.
	   At least five explosions and several fires ripped through Esso's
Longford gas plant near Sale about 110 miles (180 km) east of
Melbourne, on Friday, killing two men and injuring eight, one
critically.
	   The blaze was extinguished Sunday, but not before it had
extensively damaged the 29-year-old plant and some systems and
piping. The plant had supplied some 80 percent of Victoria's gas.
	   About 1 million Victorian residents, facing fines of 500
Australian dollars (U.S. dlrs 290), were forced to turn off their
gas meters Saturday after the state's supply authority, VENCorp.,
ordered the shutdown of the state's system.
	   Esso chairman and managing director Robert Olsen said experts,
including 12 from overseas, would try to get the plant running to
restore gas supplies.
	   He said it was a coincidence the plant had caught fire so soon
after production was halted by an ice plug in June and rejected
union suggestions maintenance standards had been lax.
	   The explosion and shutdown mark the third major infrastructure
collapse this year in this part of the world.
	   Auckland, New Zealand's central business district was blacked
out and suffered electricity shortages for some six weeks earlier
this year.
	   And Sydney, Australia's largest city, has just gone through a
series of drinking-water alerts after dangerous parasites were
found in high numbers in the water system.
	   Kennett raised the possibility of a judicial inquiry into what
caused the explosion, and was waiting for a report from Esso due
Monday.
	   ``This is going to effect this state dramatically for at least a
week,'' he said. 	   
</TEXT>
