</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Dissidents </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chinese police detain dissident over opposition party tactics
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Chinese police will keep a democracy campaigner
in custody for 13 days for trying to form an opposition political
party, a dissident monitoring group reported Monday.
	   In a detention notice sent to his family, police charged Liu
Lianjun with ``disturbing social order'' by filing an application
to register the would-be China Democracy Party, the Hong Kong-based
Information Center of Human Rights and Democratic Movement in China
said.
	   The notice, sent Friday, accused Liu of distorting remarks by
civil affairs officials in eastern Shandong province who examined
the application, the group said.
	   News from Liu and fellow campaigner Xie Wanjun that their
application was not rejected outright encouraged dissidents that
the Communist Party might be ready to end a virtual 49-year ban on
opposition politics.
	   Within days, dissidents in at least eight provinces and cities
applied or prepared applications to set up China Democracy Party
branches.
	   A crackdown started two weeks ago has signaled the party's
determination to hold on to its political monopoly. Police have
detained at least a dozen democracy campaigners, often for short
periods of time. Most have connections to the China Democracy
Party.
	   Police detained Xie Sept. 21 and two days later took Liu Lianjun
away. Xie's family was notified Thursday Xie would be detained for
15 days, also for disturbing social order, the Information Center
previously reported.
	   Police in southeastern Fujian province since Thursday have also
hauled in for questioning four dissidents about plans to set up a
China Democracy Party branch, the Information Center said.
	   Police are required by law to file detention notices if they
plan to hold a suspect without charge.
	   Although such detentions are supposed to be limited to 30 days,
loopholes and other regulations allow for lengthy stays in custody
without any public filings.
	   Police also have the authority to send suspects to labor camps
for up to three years without trial. 	   
</TEXT>
