w2364 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Malaysia-DefiantWife     09-28 0559
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Defiant Wife </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Anwar's wife says she won't be intimidated
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Malaysia-Politics
 &UR; AP Photos KL101-103
 &UR; By RANJAN ROY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ For someone who clung to her
husband before armed riot police wearing masks tore him away from
her, Azizah Ismail looks very composed. And determined.
	   If anything, adversity is exposing the steel concealed in the
fragile frame of ousted deputy prime minister Anwar Ibrahim's wife,
who exhibits the image of a pious Malay Muslim housewife with her
head draped in a white scarf.
	   ``I have to speak. They think the movement is dead,'' the
46-year-old eye surgeon said in an interview Monday, given despite
stern warnings from police that she could be arrested like her
husband was on Sept. 20.
	   ``I ask for my right as a Malaysian citizen to speak for my
husband who has no voice ... to clear the family's honor,'' she
told The Associated Press and AP Television News.
	   Anwar, 51, has disappeared. Police have ignored Azizah's pleas
for a glimpse of her husband, who is fast becoming the symbol of
reform in this Southeast Asian nation ruled by Prime Minister
Mahathir Mohamad for 17 years.
	   She says she fears for her husband's life because ``he knows a
lot of government secrets.''
	   ``I have not heard from him. I am worried. There are so many
rumors. I do not want to believe them.''
	   Anwar was arrested hours after he organized a mammoth public
rally, the largest in Kuala Lumpur in a decade. He has been
detained under the Internal Security Act, a law that allows for
detention without trial.
	   Promises by police and Mahathir himself of a speedy trial on
charges ranging from illegal homosexual acts to treason have yet to
be met.
	   ``I would like him to be charged in an open and fair court. So
we know what the charges against him are,'' Azizah said.
	   Azizah described the charges of homosexuality as ``absurd.''
	   She said she had been married for 18 years and Anwar ``is very
normal to me. Kind, loving.''
	   He has also been a ``A very caring father and very responsible''
to the couple's six children, aged between 19 and six. ``He is a
very family man.''
	   One of the daughters, Nurul Nuha, 14, wanted the media to carry
a message to her father. ``Papa, we know you are innocent. We are
behind you ... We really love you,'' she said before a television
camera.
	   Azizah said the family wasn't prepared for this fate and neither
she nor Anwar expected Mahathir to be so harsh.
	   ``I believed in him. He was my leader. I thought of him as my
father,'' she said, refusing to criticize the 72-year-old leader
who has publicly described her husband as a ``sodomist'' unfit for
politics.
	   ``I thought the vision of Dr. Mahathir worked well with Anwar's
fight for the poor.''
	   She said that all that Anwar was trying to do was bring change
from within the system. ``My husband was just trying to protect the
rights of the people who don't have a big say in the working of the
government.''
	   Azizah has been thrust into the forefront of the movement that
has convulsed Malaysian politics with regular street protests and
huge rallies reverberating with cries for Mahathir's resignation.
	   And she says she is ready to fill the role of a leader.
	   ``When he is not here, I have to continue.'' 	   
</TEXT>
