<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tokyo stocks, dollar, higher at mid-afternoon
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with mid-afternoon trading

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japanese stocks ended higher Monday, shrugging off
the failure of an affiliate of the troubled Long-Term Credit Bank
of Japan. The U.S. dollar rose against the yen.
	   The benchmark No. 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 185.53
points, or 1.35 percent, to 13,909.37. On Friday, the Nikkei shed
481.94 points, or 3.39 percent.
	   Traders said stocks were buoyed by an advance on the futures
market and buying by public funds.
	   ``Ahead of the September book-closing, public funds may be
buying on the futures market,'' said Masaru Arai, general manager
of the stock division at Ryoko Securities.
	   Also supporting the market was news that Japan's ruling and main
opposition parties had reached an agreement on key banking reform
measures over the weekend, paving the way for passage of
legislation in Parliament by early next month, traders said.
	   Shares of the Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan dived to an
all-time low of 13 yen (9.5 cents) per share, before closing at 15
yen (11 cents), down from Friday's finish of 24 yen (18 cents). The
bank's previous record low of 18 yen (13 cents) was recorded on
Sept. 18.
	   The plunge came after a non-bank affiliate of LTCB, Japan
Leasing Corp., applied late Sunday for court protection in Japan's
largest ever corporate bankruptcy.
	   Teikoku Data Bank Ltd., a Tokyo-based credit research firm, said
Japan Leasing is estimated to have debts exceeding 2.44 trillion
yen (dlrs 18.24 billion), making it Japan's biggest corporate
bankruptcy.
	   LTCB, one of Japan's largest banks, has been unable to shake off
speculation it may collapse under the weight of failed real estate
loans.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was up 13.59 yen, or 1.29 percent, to 1,063.52. On
Friday, the TOPIX closed down 28.08, or 2.6 percent.
	   In currency trading, the U.S. dollar remained higher against the
yen at mid-afternoon Monday from late Friday in Tokyo. But
unexpected gains in Tokyo stocks caused the U.S. currency to tumble
from its levels earlier in the session.
	   The dollar bought 135.71 yen at 3 p.m. (0600 GMT), up 1.07 yen
from late Friday in Tokyo, but below its late New York level of
136.25 yen Friday.
	   The dollar had surged 2.10 yen to 136.74 yen in early trading.
	   Traders attributed the dollar's slide to the rise on the Tokyo
Stock Exchange despite the failure of Japan Leasing. Many players
rushed to cover short, or oversold, yen positions following the
surprise rally in the stock market, they said.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond slipped to 0.800 percent from Friday's finish of
0.815 percent, driving its price up to 109.01 yen from 108.87 yen.
 &UR; (km-may) 	   
</TEXT>
