<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Bankruptcy, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan Leasing goes bust in Japan's biggest corporate bankruptcy
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: PMS. RECASTS and UPDATES throughout with fresh quotes,
background &QL; 
 &UR; TOK101-102 &QC; 
 &UR; By TODD ZAUN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ A leasing company saddled with over 2 trillion yen
(dlrs 16 billion) in debt announced Monday it has filed for
protection in Japan's biggest bankruptcy ever.
	   Instead of starting a market meltdown, however, stocks rose and
analysts said the megafailure might actually be good for Japan's
ailing banking sector.
	   Japan Leasing Corp., an affiliate of the ailing Long-Term Credit
Bank of Japan, filed for protection from creditors late Sunday,
said Hiroaki Okamoto, the company's president.
	   Okamoto said he did not know how much of the company's 2.18
trillion yen (dlrs 16 billion) in debts it would be able to pay
back.
	   ``Our efforts to restructure the company proved to be
impossible,'' Okamoto said. ``I deeply apologize to our creditors
and for the effects this will have on the financial system.''
	   The failure was the latest in a series of bankruptcies as Japan
struggles through its deepest recession in decades.
	   Teikoku Data Bank Ltd., a Tokyo-based credit research firm
generally regarded as authoritative on bankruptcies, said it would
be the biggest ever in Japan.
	   But instead of inspiring more gloom, the company's collapse was
seen by many as elminating a potential sticking point in government
efforts to pass a series of banking bills to clean up the country's
bad-loan mess.
	   ``This is a step forward, and is very positive in regard to
passing the bank bills,'' said Koyo Ozeki, a bank analyst at
Merrill Lynch Japan Inc.
	   Japan Leasing owed 250 billion yen (dlrs 1.8 billion) to LTCB,
which is at the center of the banking reform debate, and what to do
with that debt had been a contentious issue.
	   The ruling party had supported an LTCB plan to simply forgive
its loans to Japan Leasing. Opposition parties said they wouldn't
support using taxpayer's money to bail out LTCB if it let its
creditors off the hook so easily.
	   Ruling and opposition parties reached an agreement over the
weekend on key financial reform bills, including a plan to
temporarily nationalize LTCB.
	   That would make it impossible for LTCB to write off debts owed
by affiliates, including Japan Leasing, which thus had no choice
but to file for bankruptcy.
	   Japan Leasing, which leased a variety of equipment, including
airplanes and computers, will be taken over by court-appointed
managers within the next few days, a company lawyer said.
	   Its board of directors will resign.
	   Hoping to keep the failure from setting off a market meltdown,
Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi urged traders to be calm as financial
markets opened Monday.
	   His call was hardly needed.
	   Tokyo's stock market started higher and continued climbing
throughout the day. The benchmark Nikkei 225 stock average rose
185.53 points to close at 13,903.37 points, up 1.35 percent.
	   Analysts noted, however, that while the fall of Japan Leasing
wasn't necessarily bad for the larger financial picture, it will
likely affect reconstruction plans for two other LTCB affiliates _
Japan Landic Corp. and Nippon Enterprise Development Corp.
	   And LTCB's share price opened sharply lower Monday, briefly
hitting an all-time low of 13 yen (9.5 cents) a share before
rebounding slightly to 14 yen (10 cents). LTCB closed at 24 yen (18
cents) a share on Friday.
	   The worst previous bankruptcy was of Crown Leasing, a lender
with debts of 1.18 trillion yen (dlrs 8.86 billion) that went under
in April 1997, according to the Teikoku Data Bank.
	   The figures cited by Teikoku do not take into account failures
which occurred without formal bankruptcy filings, such as the
collapse of Yamaichi Securities Co.
	   Yamaichi announced last in November it was throwing in the
towel, leaving debts of more than 3 trillion yen (dlrs 22.38
billion) and 8,000 people without work.
	   Japan Leasing was established in 1963 as Japan's first leasing
firm.
 &UR; (dj-et)	   
</TEXT>
