<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Tropical Weather,0383 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Three hurricanes, one extra-tropical system still swirling
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: At 0300 GMT, Jeanne was centered near 29.3 north latitude and
41.1 west longitude, Karl was centered near 40.9 north latitude and
32.4 west longitude &QL; 
 &UR; With US-Hurricane Georges &QL; 
 &UR; By RACHEL LA CORTE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MIAMI (AP) _ Traffic is finally starting to slow after a busy
few days in the hurricane-crowded Atlantic Ocean.
	   This past week, for the first time since 1893, the Atlantic
played host to four hurricanes at once _ Georges, Jeanne, Ivan and
Karl.
	   Georges has been the most dangerous hurricane of the year,
killing at least 300 in the Caribbean before crashing over Key West
and heading into the Gulf of Mexico toward New Orleans and
surrounding areas late Sunday.
	   But the others have begun to weaken and stall out.
	   Late Sunday, Jeanne had top sustained winds of 75 mph (120 kph)
and was centered about 1,090 miles (1,745 kilometers) southwest of
the mid-Atlantic Azores Islands. Jeanne was moving north-northwest
at near 18 mph (29 kph), with tropical storm force winds spread out
up to 115 miles (184 kph).
	   ``She's holding her own,'' said meteorologist Michelle Huber.
``She could threaten the Azores in a day or two.''
	   By Saturday, Ivan had weakened to tropical storm strength once
its top sustained winds dropped below 74 mph (118 kph), the speed
that classifies it as a hurricane. By Sunday, the system located
over the east-central Atlantic was no longer even a tropical storm.
	   Late Sunday, Karl also was downgraded to an extra-tropical storm
after seeing its top winds drop to about 70 mph (112 kph). It was
about 310 miles (500 kilometers) west of the Azores and racing
northeast at near 41 mph (66 kph).
	   Even with the decrease of active hurricanes in the Atlantic, the
immediate focus remained on Georges, a deadly hurricane still
producing top sustained winds of 110 mph (176 kph) late Sunday as
it approached the north Gulf coast.
	   And, with more than two months left in the hurricane season,
there's still time for more hurricanes to form.
	   ``Hopefully, it's going to quiet down for a little bit,'' Huber
said. ``But, I'm not writing off the hurricane season by any
means.''
</TEXT>
