<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Election-Hanson </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ban continues on song satirizing Hanson using her own voice
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Australia-Election &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BRISBANE, Australia (AP) _ An appeal court Monday backed a radio
ban on a song which lampoons right-wing Australian politician
Pauline Hanson by using her voice to claim she is homosexual, a
prostitute, a transvestite and a member of the Klu Klux Klan.
	   Chief Justice Paul De Jersey upheld an injunction on the song
which prevents it being played on radio, saying it was clearly
defamatory and a ``mindless effort at cheap denigration.''
	   Hanson is suing a branch of the Australian Broadcasting Corp.
for playing the song, called ``Back Door Man,'' by Pauline
Pantsdown. The song uses rearranged excerpts from Hanson's speeches
as its lyrics.
	   The corporation claimed the song was satirical nonsense which
could not be taken seriously and was thereby incapable of being
defamatory.
	   De Jersey disagreed and dismissed the corporation's appeal
against the injunction.
	   The song contains ``grossly offensive imputations relating to
the sexual orientation and preference of a federal politician,''
that are plainly defamatory, De Jersey said in his ruling.
	   ``I consider there's no real room for debate that an ordinary
listener, not avid for scandal, would find one of the imputations
defamatory.''
	   During a brief hearing, Hanson wept as the song was played in
court.
	   ``I was very upset by it,'' she told reporters later.
	   ``The (court's) message is that freedom of speech does not
extend (to) allowing people the right to defame others and tell
lies.''
	   Pantsdown, formerly known as arts lecturer Simon Hunt, changed
his name to run in Australia's Oct. 3 national election and is
campaigning on an anti-Hanson ticket.
	   Dressed in Hanson-like garb and makeup, Pantsdown said outside
the court that the ruling was a blow to freedom of speech.
	   He said her role was that of a satirist, performing the same
role as German satirists did against Adolf Hitler.
	   The song rearranged Hanson's words into comments that Hanson had
already made by imputation, in particular on race and
homosexuality, Pantsdown said.
	   ``She has defamed me as one of the 10 percent of people in this
country who are homosexual.
	   ``I have turned those views around and satirized them. My
actions, my songs were trivial, it was a joke.''
	   Another Pantsdown song using Hanson's voice, ``I Don't Like
It,'' and another song parodying Hanson by two other comedians, are
still in circulation. 	   
</TEXT>
