<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinians </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Settlers rush to U.S. to head off Israel-Palestinian accord
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MARK LAVIE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Two Jewish settler leaders hurried to New York
on Monday to try to persuade Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu not
to conclude an agreement with the Palestinians on an Israeli troop
withdrawal from 13 percent of the West Bank.
	   The settlers threatened to topple Netanyahu if he went ahead
with such a deal which they fear will isolate many of the
settlements in the West Bank and Gaza Strips.
	   However, Israeli Cabinet Secretary Danny Naveh indicated Monday
that an agreement between Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser
Arafat was not near.
	   Speaking after a three-way meeting between U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright, Arafat and Netanyahu early Monday, Naveh
told Israel radio that the obstacle remains Palestinian refusal to
carry out its commitments, especially stopping extremists from
attacking Israel. ``We are not in the position of being able to say
that an agreement has been reached in these areas,'' he said.
	   Palestinians say they have done all they can to control
extremists. Arafat told a Jewish gathering in New York on Sunday
that his policy is ``zero tolerance for terror and violence.'' The
Palestinians charge that Israel is responsible for the stalemate.
	   Despite the remaining gaps, Naveh said a meeting at the White
House on Monday between U.S. President Bill Clinton, Netanyahu and
Arafat is a ``possibility.''
	   He said final arrangements have not yet been made. But he did
not expect an agreement to emerge from a White House meeting.
Netanyahu is scheduled to meet Clinton on Monday. Arafat is to see
the president Tuesday.
	   In a related development, Israel TV reported late Sunday that
once an agreement on a troop pullback is signed, Netanyahu plans to
appoint Cabinet hardliner Ariel Sharon as foreign minister in
charge of negotiating a final peace accord with the Palestinians.
	   Sharon's office would not confirm or deny the report.
	   Sharon, the most experienced member of Netanyahu's Cabinet,
could lead a right-wing revolt against the prime minister over the
upcoming troop withdrawal. Netanyahu apparently hopes to coopt
Sharon by giving him a crucial say over a future peace accord.
	   Sharon seeks to retain as much war-captured land as possible and
opposes full Palestinian statehood.
	   Amid radio reports that progress was being made on a West Bank
pullback, the mayors of two Jewish settlements, Uri Ariel of Beit
El and Benny Kashriel of Maaleh Adumim, jumped on a Sunday midnight
flight to New York to meet Netanyahu there. The two are leaders of
the Council of Jewish Settlements that represents 144 settlements
in the West Bank and Gaza Strip. Settlers say they received
information that an agreement with the Palestinians is near.
	   Israeli officials say that the size of the Israeli pullback is
no longer a matter of contention. Under interim peace agreements,
Israel was to withdraw troops in the West Bank in three stages by
the summer of this year. The Palestinians already control seven
West Bank cities and two-thirds of the Gaza Strip. According to a
U.S. compromise proposal, Israel is to hand over another 13 percent
of the West Bank in the first of two pullbacks.
	   Before leaving for the United States, Ariel warned that signing
an agreement could spell the end of the Netanyahu government.
	   Explaining why he decided to hurry to New York, he said: ``We
want to tell him, `Mr. Prime Minister, don't take this horrible and
terrible step, and don't lead us into situations that could cause
you and your government to be deposed.'''
	   Naveh did not promise that the settlers would meet Netanyahu. He
said it depends on whether they arrive before Netanyahu is to leave
for Israel. ``They can rest assured that the Prime Minister is
standing firm on Israel's vital interests,'' he added.
 &UR; ml-kl
</TEXT>
