<SLUG> BC-Russia-Vladivostok Vote </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Majority in Vladivostok vote against all candidates
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   VLADIVOSTOK, Russia (AP) _ The majority of voters in the Far
Eastern port of Vladivostok have rejected all the candidates for
mayor, according to preliminary results released Monday by the city
electoral commission.
	   Sunday's vote capped a scandal-ridden campaign. The leading
candidate, incumbent Mayor Viktor Cherepkov, was struck from the
ballot at the last minute for violating election laws.
	   According to the preliminary count on Monday morning, 53.6
percent of registered voters had voted against all 12 candidates
remaining on the ballot after Cherepkov and another candidate were
removed.
	   Some 13.3 percent voted for Vladimir Shakhov, a deputy in the
lower house of the Russian parliament and chairman of the
Dalrosso-Group insurance company.
	   Turnout was 38 percent, more than the 25 percent necessary to
make the vote valid. Still, the election will probably be
invalidated because of the massive no-vote, city election chairman
Ilya Grinchenko said, according to the Interfax news agency.
	   A city court ruled Thursday that Cherepkov could not run because
he had illegally paid for his campaign with city money, while city
official Vladimir Murashov was barred because of anti-Semitic
statements.
	   The commission instructed polling stations to strike both names
from the ballots just hours before polls were to open.
	   Vladivostok's mayoral election had been delayed for months as
Cherepkov has feuded with regional governor Yevgeny Nazdratenko.
Cherepkov's term expired on July 5.
	   (str/ji)
</TEXT>
