<SLUG> BC-Japan-Earthquake </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fairly strong earthquake shakes southern Japan
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ A fairly strong earthquake with a preliminary
magnitude of 5.1 rocked southern Japan Monday, but there were no
immediate reports of damage or injuries.
	   The quake was centered about 50 kilometers (30 miles) under the
Pacific ocean floor, off Amami Oshima island, about 1,300
kilometers (800 miles) southwest of Tokyo, the Meteorological
Agency said.
	   There was no danger of tsunami, seismic waves caused by undersea
disturbances such as earthquakes, as a result of the temblor, which
struck at 3:19 p.m. (0619 GMT), it said.
	   A magnitude 5-level quake can cause damage to homes if it occurs
in a residential area. Japan is one of the world's most
earthquake-prone countries.
