<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yeltsin meets with officials to complete cabinet formation
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ President Boris Yeltsin met Monday with top
officials in an effort to wrap up formation of the new Cabinet _ a
painful process that has stretched into a third week amid Russia's
raging economic crisis.
	   Yeltsin first met with Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov, who is
still struggling to fill more than 10 Cabinet seats.
	   Confusion over the Cabinet's makeup has contributed to the
uncertainty surrounding the future course of the new government,
which is saddled with the worst economic turmoil since the Soviet
collapse.
	   The Kremlin has had difficulty finding people willing to tackle
the job. Parliamentary deputy Vladimir Ryzhkov, who was appointed a
deputy premier while on a trip abroad, said he couldn't accept the
job because he lacks the necessary experience.
	   Alexander Shokhin, a centrist who was named to the key post of
deputy prime minister in charge of financial policy, resigned
Friday after just 10 days on the job.
	   He said he was quitting to protest the reappointment of Mikhail
Zadornov as finance minister. Shokhin held Zadornov responsible for
the previous Cabinet's decision on Aug. 17 to devalue the ruble and
freeze domestic debt _ a controversial move that many blame for
fueling Russia's crisis.
	   Zadornov, a liberal reformer, defended himself over the weekend,
saying the former government had few viable alternatives. He
pledged to improve the terms of the government's debt repayment.
	   A government team is to meet Tuesday with representatives of
Russian and foreign banks that suffered multibillion dollar losses
when the old Cabinet defaulted on its debt on treasury bills.
	   Several previous meetings have brought no result, and foreign
investors have assailed the Cabinet for allegedly favoring Russian
banks.
	   Yeltsin is also scheduled to meet Monday with three newly
appointed ministers: Economy Minister Andrei Shapovalyants, Trade
Minister Georgy Gabunia, and Science and Technology Minister
Mikhail Kirpichnikov.
	   (vi/ji/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
