<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cambodian opposition leaders postpone return to Cambodia
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ Two Cambodian opposition leaders
decided on Monday to postpone their return from Thailand amid
government threats of legal action against its critics.
	   Prince Norodom Ranariddh and Sam Rainsy left Friday for a
weekend trip to Bangkok after a controversial travel ban on newly
elected members of parliament and most other opposition figures was
lifted.
	   They were initially scheduled to return Monday, but they have
delayed their return by a few days, said officials from Ranariddh's
FUNCINPEC and the Sam Rainsy Party.
	   They denied the decision was linked to renewed threats of
arrests and court summons against members of the opposition who
were involved in massive street protests calling for the ouster of
the nation's leader, Hun Sen.
	   ``But of course, we are very concerned,'' said FUNCINPEC
spokesman Kong Vibol. ``If they are going to threaten arrests, they
have to tell us on what grounds. What have we done wrong?''
	   Government spokesman Khieu Kanharith said Monday that ``people
involved in organizing the demonstrations'' after the July 26
parliamentary elections will be called in for questioning this
week.
	   ``If they refuse to go or we cannot find them, the court will
issue an order for them to appear,'' he said.
	   Hun Sen has accused opposition leaders of provoking a Sept. 7
grenade attack on his home in the capital of Phnom Penh. No one was
injured in the attack.
	   His political rivals maintain the attack was staged by Hun Sen
as a pretext for cracking down on the street rallies, which
demanded the ouster of Hun Sen and alleged fraud in the elections.
	   A second alleged attempt on Hun Sen's life last week _ also
immediately blamed on the opposition _ has only added to the
tensions.
	   A 12-year-old boy was killed when a rocket exploded by Hun Sen's
motorcade in Siem Reap province. Three bystanders were injured.
	   Sam Rainsy, whom Hun Sen accused in the Sept. 7 attack, said by
telephone from Bangkok he would ``follow the developments very
closely.''
	   ``But I hope the government will refrain from issuing any
warrants or decisions to summons any opposition officials for
questioning, which can lead to detentions and so on,'' he said.
	   The July 26 elections were held one year after Hun Sen ousted
Ranariddh as his co-premier in a violent coup.
	   Hun Sen hoped to win back legitimacy and aid lost after his
takeover.
	   His Cambodian People's Party won a slight majority in the
parliamentary polls, but not the two-thirds needed to form a
government on its own.
	   The Cambodian People's Party and FUNCINPEC will head to the
negotiating table this week to try to diffuse tensions and perhaps
hammer out an agreement so that a coalition government can be
formed.
	   The Sam Rainsy Party, which won only 15 of 122 seats in
parliament, has been excluded from those talks. 	   
</TEXT>
