<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-PAL, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine Airlines union, management reach breakthrough agreement
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with President Estrada announcing
agreement; trims
 &UR; AP Photos Available
 &UR; By JIM GOMEZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Five days after the airline's
closure, the management and main union of Philippine Airlines
agreed Monday on a management-proposed rehabilitation plan that
could lead to its reopening.
	   Philippine President Joseph Estrada said union officials agreed
to accept a key management demand _ a 10-year suspension of their
collective bargaining agreement.
	   If approved by union members, regulators and PAL creditors, the
agreement could lead to the reopening of Asia's oldest airline,
officials said.
	   Opposition within the union, which represents ground personnel,
to that decision is high. Thousands of workers protested at the
union's office and at the Senate Monday, calling instead for the
government to take over the airline.
	   Union president Alex Barrientos said the agreement was PAL's
``last, last, last possible hope.''
	   ``If this fails, it's closed,'' he added.
	   PAL shut down last Wednesday after the ground crew union earlier
rejected the management plan, which would give workers 20 percent
of the company's stock in exchange for a 10-year suspension of
their collective bargaining agreement.
	   The union has been split over the proposal, with its radical
wing saying a 10-year suspension would violate workers' rights and
destroy the union.
	   PAL, which owes creditors dlrs 2.1 billion, has been ravaged by
strikes and Asia's currency crisis.
	   It says creditors and potential new investors have insisted on
the suspension of the collective bargaining agreement before they
will accept a restructuring of the company's finances.
	   Earlier Monday, Estrada flew to the central Philippines aboard
the first domestic flight by Hong Kong's Cathay Pacific Airways,
which he enlisted to help fill the vacuum left by PAL's closure.
	   Initially, two Cathay Pacific planes and crews will be leased to
PNB Holdings, a subsidiary of Philippine National Bank, which is 47
percent owned by the government.
	   The flights will nominally be operated by PNB Holdings since
Philippine law prohibits foreign carriers from servicing domestic
routes.
	   Presidential Executive Secretary Ronaldo Zamora said up to six
Cathay Pacific planes may be leased with accompanying crews.
	   At least three smaller Philippine domestic carriers have said
they plan to expand their operations in response to PAL's closure,
and air force planes are helping carry vital cargo, including mail,
medicine and newspapers, officials said.
	   A committee formed by Manila's Securities and Exchange
Commission is also studying whether there is a chance of reopening
the carrier.
	   Estrada says the government is unable to take over PAL because
there is no money in public coffers to underwrite daily losses of
up to 45 million pesos (dlrs 1 million) incurred by the airline.
	   Both PAL and Cathay Pacific have been hit hard by Asia's
currency crisis, which has reduced passenger volume. PAL had
launched a dlrs 4 billion modernization and refleeting program
shortly before the crisis hit.
	   The Philippine flag carrier also was badly crippled by a 22-day
pilots' strike in June.
</TEXT>
