<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Rice Exports </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Contingency plan calls for halts in rice export
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ As part of a contingency plan in event
of a world economic depression, Thailand may halt rice exports to
prevent shortages in domestic market, a Thai newspaper said Monday.
	   Thailand, the world's largest rice exporter, has not taken such
a measure since World War II.
	   The possible move was raised at a recent meeting as part of the
government's worst-scenario contingency plan to counter a global
slump, The Nation newspaper reported.
	   The newspaper quoted two unidentified government sources as
saying the contingency would be ``like preparing for war,'' and
also include controls on foreign borrowing and steps to protect the
country's export share from competitors.
	   The plan is being drafted by Commerce Minister Supachai
Panichapakdi and Finance Minister Tarrin Nimmanahaeminda. They will
submit it to the Cabinet in two weeks, the newspaper said.
	   Thailand is concerned that if the world economy continues to
deteriorate it could plunge into social unrest and political
turmoil like Indonesia and Malaysia, it said.
	   Thailand exports an average of 5 millions tons of rice each
year, or a third of its total production.
	   The government has been closely monitoring the international
rice trade as natural disasters in rice-producing countries have
cut short the world supply. 	   
</TEXT>
