<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Euro </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Poll: majority of British businesses favor joining European
</HEADLINE>
currency &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ A majority of British business executives want
their nation to join the European single currency, but most are
doing nothing to prepare for that day, according to a poll
published Monday by the Financial Times.
	   The survey of chairmen, managing directors and board members
found that 26 percent wanted to join the Euro as soon as possible,
and another 37 percent favored entry after the next election, which
must be held by 2002. Twenty-three percent said they wanted Britain
to stay out of the European currency.
	   Eleven members of the European Union are committed to launching
the currency on Jan. 1. British Prime Minister Tony Blair says he
is prepared to join the Euro when it is in Britain's interest to do
so, but has set no deadline.
	   The Financial Times' survey found that 22 percent of the
respondents were taking some steps to prepare for the single
currency but 77 percent were not. One percent didn't know.
	   The poll was carried out by the MORI polling organization, which
interviewed 753 executives by telephone between Sept. 9 and Sept.
25. The survey had a margin of error of about three percentage
points.
	   (rb)
</TEXT>
