<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Kia, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Creditors to propose new conditions to sell Kia Motors
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS throughout to eliminate reference to President Kim
Dae-jung ordering new auction

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Creditor banks said Monday they would
sweeten the terms of a third auction to sell off bankrupt Kia
Motors Corp., presumably by swallowing more of its debt.
	   An official at Kia's largest creditor, state-run Korea
Development Bank, said various measures were under study but
declined to elaborate.
	   But various South Korean media reported that the banks had
agreed to write off up to dlrs 3.2 billion of Kia's dlrs 8.4
billion debt.
	   They earlier had agreed to write off dlrs 2.1 billion, but that
didn't satisfy potential buyers who demanded further debt
reductions in two previous failed auctions.
	   The creditor banks said they would conduct a third auction on an
unspecified date in October. New bidding schedules are expected to
be announced this week.
	   Previous bidders were Ford Motor Co. of the United States and
Hyundai Motor Co., Samsung Motors Corp. and Daewoo Motor Co. of
South Korea.
	   The move to sell Kia is part of the government's effort to
restructure its battered economy under a dlrs 58 billion bailout
from the International Monetary Fund.
	   Kia's collapse last year helped erode investor confidence in
South Korea's industries, leading to a flight of capital. 	   
</TEXT>
