<HEADLINE>
Japan's home run king ``astonished'' by McGwire's 70th homer
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITS to correct slug &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Sports-Baseball-McGwire's Homers

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ After St. Louis Cardinals slugger Mark McGwire
whacked his 70th home run of the season this weekend, even Japan's
all-time home run king was overawed.
	   ``There's no other way to say it but that it's astonishing that
he hit the 70th homer with the world's attention focused on him,''
Sadaharu Oh told Kyodo News.
	   ``The world takes its hat off in respect,'' Oh was quoted as
saying.
	   Oh hit 868 home runs over his 22-year career _ 113 more than
Hank Aaron, America's all-time home run leader. Oh also holds
Japan's single season home run record, with 55 roundtrippers in the
140-game 1964 season.
	   Oh is now manager of the Pacific League's Fukuoka Daiei Hawks.
	   McGwire blasted his 70th homer against Montreal Expos pitcher
Mike Thurman at Busch Stadium in St. Louis on Sunday.
