</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Pakistan-Australia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Austalia warms up for test series with a huge victory
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RIZWAN ALI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 
 &UR; AP Photos KAR101-KAR102

<TEXT>
	   KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) _ Stuart MacGill's six-wicket haul,
including last five scalps off 19 deliveries, helped Australia post
a huge 333 runs victory over Karachi on the last day Monday of the
four-day tour opener.
	   MacGill, the rookie leg-spinner, coming in place of Shane Warne,
quickly wrapped up Karachi's second innings at 123 at lunch.
	   The victory comes as a big morale booster ahead of the first
test against Pakistan beginning Oct. 1 at Rawalpindi. The visitors
will play a three-test series.
	   Warne stayed back in Australia to recover from a shoulder
operation and MacGill's performance Monday could pose problems for
the Pakistani batsmen.
	   ``Of course the team's morale goes up when one goes into a Test
match with a victory behind them,'' said skipper Mark Taylor.
	   ``All the players performed outstandingly, batsmen got enough
runs while the bowlers did a splendid job,'' Taylor said after the
match.
	   Australia piled up 540 for nine in its first innings and then
dismissed Karachi for 278 in the first outing. The visitors
followed their first innings performance in the second innings and
made 194 for two before skipper Mark Taylor declared late on Sunday
and set up a challenging target of 457 for the home team.
	   Karachi, reeling at 11 for 2 overnight, started off cautiously
with Saeed Azad and Suleman Huda negotiating the opening overs of
Glenn McGrath and Michael Kasprowicz.
	   However, once Gavin Robertson removed both batsmen, Karachi
batsmen struggled to stay at the crease in front of MacGill. Huda
(21) gave an easy bat and pad catch to Justin Langer at forward
short leg and Azad (44) followed soon giving a return catch to the
off-spinner.
	   Thereafter, Karachi batsmen were devoured by MacGill who
polished off the middle-order and the tail in quick time, claiming
five wickets in space of 19 balls.
	   Azam Khan, highest scorer with 57 in Karachi's first innings
total of 278 in reply to Australians mammoth 540 for nine declared,
was the next to go, holing out in the deep to McGrath off MacGill's
full toss delivery.
	   Hasan Raza and Faisal Iqbal, nephew of Pakistan national team
coach Javed Miandad, halted the collapse briefly with the home team
struggling at 81 for five.
	   However, MacGill had Raza (24 off 27 balls) caught by skipper
Mark Taylor in the first slip while Iqbal was trapped leg before.
Skipper Aamir Sohail, who will be leading the Pakistan team in the
coming Test series, was smartly stumped by Ian Healy off MacGill
after hammering a solitary boundary.
	   MacGill then wrapped up the innings claiming the last two
wickets off successive deliveries with Ali Hussain Rizvi falling
leg before and last man Ali Gohar giving Healy his second stumping
of the innings.
	   MacGill finished with an impressive figures of 6 for 34 off 8.4
overs. McGrath (2-9) and Robertson (2-48) were the other successful
Australian bowlers.
	   (str/aks)
</TEXT>
