<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANALYSIS-Slovakia-Back to the Future,0612 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Slovak vote is watershed for democracy in Central Europe
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; An AP News Analysis &QL; 
 &UR; By DAVE CARPENTER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRATISLAVA, Slovakia (AP) _ An apparent victory by Slovakia's
opposition in the young country's second nationwide election has
opened a new door for the West into Eastern Europe.
	   It also sets the stage for the departure from power of one of
Europe's few remaining autocrats _ Prime Minister Vladimir Meciar _
although some doubts remain that he will go quietly.
	   If Meciar's ruling party doesn't challenge or overturn results
that show opposition parties winning more than 60 percent of the
seats in Parliament, a new leadership that is eager to please the
West is set to take over.
	   The leaders of the top four opposition parties met Sunday and
declared their formal intent to unite after results indicated they
had won 93 of the 150 seats. But weeks of political friction are
likely since Meciar's party would remain the largest in Parliament.
	   Barring a stunning change when the official vote count is
released Monday night or Tuesday, Meciar's likeliest options would
be to serve as minority leader or resign.
	   Mikulas Dzurinda, head of the Slovak Democratic Coalition, is
the prospective new prime minister. The 43-year-old economist and
former transport specialist rose to prominence due in part to his
plain-spoken style.
	   On Sunday, he avoided specific plans for change and said it was
important for Slovakia that the new government be formed swiftly.
	   Since Czechoslovakia dissolved six years ago, its two
ex-communist parts have gone in different directions. While the
Czech Republic swiftly adopted free-market and democratic reforms
and became a darling of Western tourists and investors, Slovakia
fell into diplomatic isolation under Meciar's heavy-handed rule.
	   The 56-year-old Meciar blocked dissent, reined in the media,
cracked down on the opposition and ethnic minorities, and was
censured by foreign governments.
	   Foreign investors fled or waited for change in the nation of 5.5
million. Relations with neighboring countries grew tense, and a
leery West bypassed the Slovaks while embracing the neighboring
Czechs and Hungarians for early entry into NATO and the European
Union.
	   Now, Slovakia appears to have rejected old-style leadership and
is poised to join its neighbors in integrating with the West.
	   Opposition parties campaigned heavily on the theme of reversing
``Meciarism'' and getting the nation into the EU and NATO, saying
they will pass laws aimed at establishing fairness and meeting
Western standards.
	   Meciar built highways and dams and provided strong and
relatively stable rule in Slovakia. He retained a loyal enough
following for his party to finish ahead of all 16 competitors.
	   But he wound up alienating not only the West but more and more
Slovaks with his increasing extremism.
	   In the end, he was outpolled by an unlikely alliance of
opposition parties _ ranging from rightists to ex-communists to
free-marketeers _ who united only out of a determination to drive
Meciar from power.
	   If it manages to form the new government, the opposition faces
daunting economic problems that may require harsh budget cuts.
	   But as the West's best chance in years to establish deeper
democratic roots in the region, they are counting on significant
foreign financial assistance to help Slovakia make the transition _
and are likely to get it.
	   ___
	   EDITOR'S NOTE: Dave Carpenter is East Europe news editor for The
Associated Press.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
