<SLUG> BC-Mideast-Summit, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Radio: Netanyahu, Arafat agree to three-way summit with Clinton
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPGRADES attribution throughout &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ U.S. President Bill Clinton will host the
Israeli and Palestinian leaders in a three-way summit at the White
House on Monday in hopes of concluding agreement on a West Bank
troop pullback, an Israeli official said.
	   The summit comes amid reports that the two sides have made some
progress toward an agreement on an Israeli pullback from 13 percent
of the West Bank.
	   Late Sunday, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
Palestinian Authority President Yasser Arafat met for the first
time in months. They were hosted in New York by U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright.
	   Albright said that much work remained to be done.
	   Palestinian negotiators said the talks focused on the scope of
the pullback, as well as the opening of a Palestinian airport and
industrial zone in the Gaza Strip.
	   An Israeli official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
Netanyahu and Arafat were to meet later Monday with Clinton. From
there, Arafat was to return to New York to address the U.N. General
Assembly and Netanyahu was to fly to Israel, Israel radio said.
