<SLUG> BC-Russia-Forest Fires </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Siberian blazes out of control, Sakhalin fires slowed by snow
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Fires are blazing out of control across up to
40,000 hectares (98,800 acres) of Siberian woodland, while snowfall
has slowed the spread of forest fires on Sakhalin Island in
Russia's Far East, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported Monday.
	   A funding shortage that has severely hampered fire-fighters is
to blame for the unprecedented scale of forest fires this year,
ITAR-Tass said. Fire-spotting planes and helicopters had been
unable to fly for lack of fuel.
	   Alexander Lyubakin, chief of the Far Eastern fire air base, said
that the federal government had provided just one-quarter of the
funds needed to put out the fires in the huge Khabarovsk territory
in Russia's Far East, ITAR-Tass reported.
	   In all, about 547,000 hectares (1.4 million acres) are on fire
in the territory.
	   On nearby Sakhalin Island, forest fires have calmed due to an
early snow. ITAR-Tass said that the fires no longer threaten
inhabited areas.
	   (ji) 	   
</TEXT>
