<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Bank Bills, BOX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Outline of Japan's proposed banking industry reform bills
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   Here are the key points of a compromise accord between Japan's
ruling and opposition parties over a set of banking industry reform
bills:
	   _BANK BAILOUTS. The government will effectively nationalize
failed financial institutions by purchasing shares to provide
capital needed to write off bad loans.
	   _LTCB RESCUE. The government will buy all outstanding stock in
the ailing Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan Ltd. and place the bank
under state control. Private sector suitors such as Sumitomo Trust
and Banking Co. may then submit bids for the bank.
	   _FINANCE MINISTRY. Regulatory authority for dealing with
financial industry crises will be shared by the powerful Finance
Ministry and a new independent oversight committee.
	   _JAPANESE RTC. Two existing entities established to buy up bad
loans from banks and failed housing lenders will be merged into a
more powerful body, creating a Japanese version of the Resolution
Trust Corp. created in the United States to deal with the savings
and loan crisis of the 1980s.
 &UR; (cd-et)	   
</TEXT>
