w2460 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  Bc-Sports-Tennis-DavisCu     09-28 0694
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> Bc-Sports-Tennis-Davis Cup-US,0693 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Torch passed to new generation
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ARNIE STAPLETON &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MILWAUKEE (AP) _ Rather than mourn America's Davis Cup debacle,
team captain Tom Gullikson is focusing on the future.
	   At least 21-year-old rookies Jan-Michael Gambill, whose victory
Sunday helped the United States avoid a shutout by the Italians,
and Justin Gimelstob got their Davis Cup debuts out of the way.
	   ``Hopefully, the next time they play, nerves won't be a big
factor,'' Gullikson said. ``You have to start sometime.''
	   Gambill and Gimelstob represented a sneak peak at the future of
U.S. Davis Cup, which will likely include practice partners Bob and
Mike Bryan, 20-year-old twins who just turned pro after winning
NCAA titles at Stanford.
	   The passing of the torch occurred earlier than anybody expected.
	   Playing without Pete Sampras, Andre Agassi, Michael Chang and
Jim Courier, the starless but still favored U.S. team was upset by
Italy 4-1.
	   ``Well, certainly you want the best players to play,'' Gullikson
said. ``It is not easy. I can certainly only worry about the
players who are here, who are really committed. And I think it was
a great opportunity this week for Jan-Michael and Justin to gain
some great experience.''
	   Gimelstob, who lost the doubles match on Saturday and Sunday's
``dead rubber'' singles match, said he found a silver lining in the
loss.
	   ``I don't think anything will sour me on Davis Cup,'' he said.
``I think it will test my resilience possibly, but it won't sour
me. My desire to represent my country and the pride that I feel in
doing so will always be strong.''
	   Gimelstob said he couldn't fathom stars skipping the Davis Cup
for any reason.
	   ``But different people have different views,'' he said. ``I am
also 21 years old and I don't know what it feels like to be 27 and
have 100 million miles on your body.''
	   Not only did the U.S. team fail to win, but the Americans didn't
even get the fast court they were counting on. The hard surface
inside the Milwaukee Arena was chosen by the Americans because it
was supposed to favor their fast games. But it played more like the
clay courts the Italians grew up on.
	   ``It's a perfect court for them,'' said Gimelstob, who lost to
Italy's Gianluca Pozzi 7-6 (7-4), 7-5 on Sunday.
	   Gullikson said his players chose a ``medium-paced court with a
high bounce and we ended up getting a slow court with a low
bounce.''
	   Something else that greatly aided the Italians, who will face
Sweden, a 4-1 winner over Spain, in the final in December, was the
makeup of the U.S. team.
	   Agassi, Sampras and Chang all decided against coming to
Milwaukee, and Courier was withheld by Gullikson because of an arm
injury.
	   That left Gambill and Gimelstob to make their Davis Cup debuts,
and Martin, who played like a rookie, getting dumped in both
singles and doubles.
	   ``I was very impressed with a lot of the tennis that our rookies
played this weekend,'' said Gullikson, who refused to disparage the
players who bypassed Milwaukee.
	   ``Recruiting is very difficult,'' he said. ``It really has to
come from their heart more than anywhere.''
	   The Italians won all six tiebreakers and dropped just three sets
all weekend before Gambill beat Davide Sanguinetti (4-6, 6-3, 6-3)
in the final, meaningless match.
	   ``I am going out there and thinking about next year,'' Gambill
said. ``Now I have two matches under my belt. I am no longer the
rookie when I come out next year.''
	   Gullikson's own future with the team will be decided in early
November when the U.S. Tennis Association changes presidents.
	   He said he wants to stay despite the turmoil of the past year as
stars such as Agassi and Sampras bowed out, criticizing such issues
as site selection and fan support.
	   ``Things don't always go smoothly,'' Gullikson said. ``Sometimes
you lose when you think you are going to win. Sometimes players who
we think should be playing aren't playing.
	   ``That is why when we get back to it maybe and win it the next
time, it will make it all that much sweeter remembering the harder
times.''
</TEXT>
