<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 09/28/1998 04:58:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
w2470 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 1stLdWritethru   09-28 0577
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 1st Ld Writethru,0577 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Serbian parliament to support Milosevic policies in Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; PRECEDE Pristina
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS to UPDATE with Serbian parliament convening, fighting
continuing in Kosovo; CHANGES changes dateline and byline. no
pickup &QL; 
 &UR; By JOVANA GEC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ In a show of unity and defiance
against NATO threats over Kosovo, Serbia's parliament convened
Monday to back the tough policies of its leader, Slobodan
Milosevic.
	   Parliament is expected to pass a resolution, proposed by the
government last week, which declares that stamping out ethnic
Albanian resistance in Kosovo is the nation's top priority. It will
blast the West for pressuring Serbia.
	   The strongly-worded resolution indicated that Serbia has no
intention of stopping its campaign against independence-minded
ethnic Albanians in the southern Kosovo province, despite new
warnings that time is running out to avoid NATO intervention.
	   The resolution is also aimed at strengthening Yugoslav President
Milosevic's position at home and rallying Serbs behind his policies
as he faces increased world pressure.
	   ``The main problem in Kosovo is separatism,'' declared Premier
Mirko Marjanovic as he submitted the government report about Kosovo
to the parliament.
	   Kosovo is part of Serbia, the dominant republic in Yugoslavia.
Most of Kosovo's majority ethnic Albanians want independence.
	   Milosevic's crackdown against militant separatists in Kosovo
started seven months ago. Some 275,000 people have been displaced
by the fighting and hundreds killed.
	   Serbia was defying the world on the ground, too.
	   Government forces launched a new offensive late Saturday in an
area about 50 kilometers (30 miles) southwest of the Kosovo capital
Pristina.
	   Serb sources in Pristina said Monday that fighting continued
overnight, in the region where rebel Kosovo Liberation Army
fighters seemed to have regrouped following a rout earlier this
year.
	   On Sunday, the Albanian-run Kosovo Information Center said Serb
forces were attacking from three directions near the towns of Suva
Reka, Urosevac and Stimlje. The attack reportedly focused on 11
villages, and three were on fire. An estimated 15,000 civilians
have begun leaving the area.
	   Police sources said the rebels recently kidnapped two Serbs,
which prompted the new action.
	   A U.N. Security Council demanded last week an end to all Serb
attacks in Kosovo and NATO finalized plans for air strikes unless
the fighting stops. The alliance has finalized plans to hit
strategic targets throughout Serbia.
	   In nearby Bosnia-Herzegovina, U.S. Defense Secretary William
Cohen said Milosevic has only ``a short period of time'' to comply
with international demands.
	   ``A failure to do so presents the possibility that a military
operation against Mr. Milosevic would be necessary,'' Cohen said.
``A failure to do so on his part will be met with very strong NATO
action in my judgment.''
	   The Serbian government resolution said pressure on Serbia would
be counter-effective. It called for negotiations on the future of
Kosovo and offered a degree of self-rule for the province.
	   The Serbian troops are by far stronger militarily than the
rebels but are stretched thin in Kosovo's rugged countryside. The
Serbs have had trouble maintaining control over the areas while
driving out rebels, mostly local farmers recruited by the KLA. 	   
</TEXT>
