<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asia Business Briefs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Korea. Some of these stories also moved earlier today as
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Contains items from China, Japan, the Philippines and South
separates. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Philippine Airlines' management and
its largest union reached agreement on a management-proposed
rehabilitation plan Monday, five days after the ailing airline's
closure, President Joseph Estrada announced.
	   Asia's oldest airline could reopen as early as next week if the
agreement is approved by union members, regulators and PAL's
creditors, officials said.
	   Estrada said union leaders agreed to accept a contentious
management demand _ a 10-year suspension of their collective
bargaining agreement.
	   The union has been split over the proposal, with its radical
wing saying a 10-year suspension would violate workers' rights and
destroy the union.
	   Hundreds of workers protested the agreement at the union's
office and at the Senate Monday, calling instead for the government
to take over the airline.
	   PAL shut down last Wednesday after the ground crew union earlier
rejected the management plan, which would give workers 20 percent
of the company's stock in exchange for a 10-year suspension of
their collective bargaining agreement.
	   ___
	   TOKYO (AP) _ A leasing company saddled with over 2 trillion yen
(dlrs 16 billion) in debt announced Monday it has filed for
protection in Japan's biggest bankruptcy ever.
	   Instead of starting a market meltdown, however, stocks rose and
analysts said the megafailure might actually be good for Japan's
ailing banking sector.
	   Japan Leasing Corp., an affiliate of the ailing Long-Term Credit
Bank of Japan, filed for protection from creditors late Sunday,
said Hiroaki Okamoto, the company's president.
	   Okamoto said he did not know how much of the company's 2.18
trillion yen (dlrs 16 billion) in debts it would be able to pay
back.
	   ``Our efforts to restructure the company proved to be
impossible,'' Okamoto said. ``I deeply apologize to our creditors
and for the effects this will have on the financial system.''
	   The failure was the latest in a series of bankruptcies as Japan
struggles through its deepest recession in decades.
	   Teikoku Data Bank Ltd., a Tokyo-based credit research firm
generally regarded as authoritative on bankruptcies, said it would
be the biggest ever in Japan.
	   But instead of inspiring more gloom, the company's collapse was
seen by many as eliminating a potential sticking point in
government efforts to pass a series of banking bills to clean up
the country's bad-loan mess.
	   ___
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan's ruling party announced Monday it had
reached a final agreement with the major opposition parties on a
key set of bills to clean up this country's troubled financial
system.
	   The announcement raised hopes that the bills, aimed at cleaning
up about dlrs 1 trillion of bad debt in the banking sector, would
be approved early next month, during the current session of
Parliament.
	   ``We'd like to bring the process to a conclusion as soon as
possible,'' Yoshiro Mori, secretary-general of the governing
Liberal Democratic Party, said after a set of marathon talks with
the opposition that went through the weekend.
	   Last week, the LDP and opposition reached a basic accord on the
bills, which incorporated the key parts of the opposition's rival
version of the legislation.
	   But the agreement was vague, and began to unravel almost as soon
as it was announced.
	   The breakthrough Monday, however, centered on a compromise over
how much power to give a new independent body that will be charged
with regulating the finance sector.
	   ___
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ South Korea's president predicted
Monday that his country's contracting economy will resume growth in
the latter part of next year.
	   In a news conference devoted solely to economic matters, Kim
Dae-jung said tax cuts and other pump-priming measures will help
resuscitate the domestic economy.
	   ``In a word, there will be no second financial crisis,'' Kim
said. ``If we continue reform measures as we do now, the economy
will pick up later next year.''
	   Citing shrinking domestic consumption and exports _ the engine
of the country's economy _ some analysts have warned that South
Korea may be headed for a new financial crisis.
	   But Kim said the government, backed by a record foreign currency
reserve of dlrs 44 billion, will easily be able to repay dlrs 9
billion in external debt coming due this year and dlrs 36 billion
due next year.
	   ``Despite many uneasy international factors as shown in Japan,
Russia, Southeast Asia and South America, the value of our currency
has been stable and I believe the trend will continue,'' Kim said.
	   The president said his prediction of an economic turnaround next
year depends on how fast and effectively the economy can be
restructured, especially the financial and industrial sectors.
	   ___
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Creditor banks said Monday they would
sweeten the terms of a third auction to sell off bankrupt Kia
Motors Corp., presumably by swallowing more of its debt.
	   ``Various attractive measures are being considered to sell Kia
without fail in a third auction,'' said one official at Kia's
largest creditor, state-run Korea Development Bank.
	   The official, speaking only on condition of anonymity, declined
to elaborate, but various news media said the banks had agreed to
write off up to dlrs 3.2 billion of Kia's dlrs 8.4 billion debt.
	   They earlier had agreed to write off dlrs 2.1 billion, but that
didn't satisfy potential buyers who demanded further debt
reductions in two previous failed auctions.
	   The creditor banks said they would conduct a third auction on an
unspecified date in October. New bidding schedules are expected to
be announced this week.
	   Previous bidders were Ford Motor Co. of the United States and
Hyundai Motor Co., Samsung Motors Corp. and Daewoo Motor Co. of
South Korea.
	   ___
	   BEIJING (AP) _ In a campaign to shore up the value of its
currency, China's government has warned businesses not to
circumvent foreign exchange controls, state media reported Monday.
	   The State Council, China's Cabinet, issued a recent directive,
threatening businesses with loss of licenses and other unspecified
punishment if they exploited legal loopholes, forged documents or
turned to the black market to trade hard currency.
	   Government policies confining conversion of the Chinese yuan to
international trade have largely protected it from the batterings
many Asian currencies have taken over the past 15 months.
	   Despite the policies and repeated pledges by Chinese leaders not
to devalue the yuan, however, back-door pressures on the currency
are mounting.
	   The government's dlrs 140 billion in foreign exchange reserves
has stopped growing this year as exporters hold on to more of their
hard currency earnings instead of remitting them to Beijing.
	   A black market exchange rate for the dollar that is 10 percent
above official rates suggests many Chinese fell less confident
about the yuan and government policies. 	   
</TEXT>
