r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Chechnya     09-28 0319
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Chechnya </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chechen leader pledges to fight kidnappings, faces challenge
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov said his
government would publicly execute kidnappers to stop a crime wave
that has swept the breakaway republic, a news agency reported on
Monday.
	   Speaking on national television, Maskhadov claimed foreign
secret services were behind the Chechen gangs responsible for
frequent kidnappings in the region, the ITAR-Tass news agency
reported. He did not identify the secret services.
	   Chechnya has seen an increase in kidnappings, theft, and
violence among armed gangs, Muslim sects and ethnic groups since
its 1994-96 independence war with Russia. Maskhadov's attempts to
rein in crime have brought little result.
	   Chechnya carried out several public executions, but they were
met with strong criticism from Russia and abroad, and no one has
been publicly put to death in recent months.
	   Maskhadov's government has also encountered growing opposition
from Chechen warlords, who have refused to obey his orders.
	   Shamil Basayev, who served as Maskhadov's prime minister earlier
this year, has recently joined others pushing for the president's
ouster.
	   The warlords will gather later this week to demand that
Maskhadov take a tougher line in relations with Russia and fulfill
other demands, or resign, the Interfax news agency reported.
	   Maskhadov turned down these demands over the weekend, saying
that he ``rejects the language of ultimatums and doesn't intend to
respond to letters of people who are guilty of breaking the law,''
the report said.
	   Chechnya claims to be a sovereign nation, but Moscow says it
remains a part of Russia. No country has recognized Chechnya's
independence bid.
	   Despite his fight for independence, Russia considers Maskhadov a
moderate and has been willing to negotiate with him.
	   (vi/ji/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
