<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Caribbean-Summary,1520 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
An overnight summary of Caribbean news
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 
 &UR; UNITED STATES: Finished with Caribbean, Georges targets New
Orleans &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW ORLEANS (AP) _ The Big Easy was decidedly uneasy Sunday as
New Orleans prepared for its worst nightmare hurricane _ a massive
storm that could sit overhead for days, driving Lake Pontchartrain
over its levees and submerging the city.
	   ``We're just waiting for the trigger to be pulled,'' said Lt.
Col. Ronnie Jones of the Louisiana State Police.
	   Thousands didn't wait for Hurricane Georges to arrive. They
fled, turning Interstates 10 and 55 into bumper-to-bumper
processions. More than 1.5 million people were ordered or urged to
leave New Orleans and coastal areas.
	   The storm, with sustained wind of 110 mph (177 kph), was
expected to smash the Gulf Coast late Sunday or early Monday.
	   Intermittent downpours started Saturday night. Waves crossed
beachfront roads in Mississippi, including four-lane U.S. 90.
Twenty-five-foot (Eight-meter) waves clipped off fishing piers
along Alabama's coast. High surf on top of a 5-foot (1 1/2-meter)
storm surge threatened to undermine the foundations of beachfront
homes on barrier islands along the Florida Panhandle.
 &UR; CUBA: Castro says speedy hurricane evacuation saved many from
death
	   HAVANA (AP) _ President Fidel Castro said in comments broadcast
Sunday that the speedy evacuation of hundreds of thousands of
people probably saved many from dying during Hurricane Georges'
march across Cuba last week.
	   ``The first victory was to reduce the losses,'' Castro said in
government broadcasts of a Friday night ceremony honoring
neighborhood block leaders.
	   According to the government, five people died when Georges cut
across Cuba on Thursday and Friday. The hurricane killed more than
300 people in its rampage through the Caribbean.
	   In Havana, activities were back to normal on Sunday, two days
after schools and the airport were closed and public transportation
was suspended while heavy rains and winds lashed the capital. By
Sunday afternoon, skies were sunny and the winds were gone.
	   Castro told leaders of the Committees for the Defense of the
Revolution that the government must help the thousands left
homeless and assess agricultural damage.
 &UR; HAITI: Destitute farmers say flooding could have been avoided
	   BOURDETTE TI-PLACE, Haiti (AP) _ The floodwaters are receding in
Haiti's breadbasket, the Artibonite Valley, but the anger is
mounting.
	   Impoverished farmers in the central rice-growing valley long
warned of disaster if the government didn't clear silt-clogged
irrigation canals. Haiti's officials listened and did nothing, and
disaster struck.
	   Hurricane Georges dumped 20 inches (50 cm) of rain into Haiti's
central mountains last week, unleashing a terrestrial tidal wave
across the valley that swamped villages, killed dozens and left
untold numbers missing.
	   Haiti's official death toll stood at 87 but was all but certain
to rise, the government said Sunday.
	   Some 250,000 acres (100,000 hectares) of tomato, onion, eggplant
and rice fields disappeared under chest-high water _ leaving the
Western Hemisphere's poorest nation more dependent than ever on
foreign emergency aid.
	   ``I personally warned government authorities that this would
happen,'' an angry Oreste Jean-Baptiste, 40, said as he churned
through the muddy lanes of the delta hamlet of Bourdette Ti-Place.
 &UR; HAITI: Grenade explodes outside Haitian legislature building
	   PORT-AU-PRINCE, Haiti (AP) _ A hand grenade exploded in the
parking lot of the Haitian legislature Saturday night, damaging
some vehicles but causing no injuries, the head of the body's lower
house said Sunday.
	   The explosion occurred around midnight, and there was no damage
to the building, said chamber of deputies president Vasco
Thernelan.
	   ``The political situation is tense, but it doesn't seem the
terrorists were really determined to wreak havoc,'' he said.
	   Haiti has been without fully effective government since June
1997, when then-Premier Rosny Smarth resigned to protest elections
he alleges were rigged in favor of the political party of former
President Jean-Bertrand Aristide.
	   The deadlock caused by Smarth's majority party and Aristide's
parliamentary allies has prevented the installation of a new
government since then.
 &UR; DOMINICAN REPUBLIC: Relief supplies, U.S. delegation arrive
	   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) _ The U.S. hurricane
relief effort for the Dominican Republic gained steam Sunday,
including tons of bottled water and plastic tarps for thousands of
struggling storm victims.
	   The United States shipped about dlrs 500,000 worth of supplies,
including enough plastic sheeting to roof 15,000 homes. More was
coming, said Hugh Parmer, head of disaster relief for the U.S.
Agency for International Development.
	   At least six U.S. military helicopters were due Monday to carry
relief supplies and help rescuers reach towns cut off by flooding,
downed bridges and debris-choked roads, Parmer said.
	   Chopper crews planned to fly rescuers to San Juan de Maguana,
120 miles (192 kilometers) west of the capital, where 76 bodies
were recovered on Thursday. Half the town, Parmer said, was
underwater or buried in mud.
	   ``These people aren't getting much of anything as of now,'' he
said.
	   More than 200 people were killed and 100,000 made homeless when
Hurricane Georges struck the Dominican Republic on Tuesday.
 &UR; UNITED STATES: Hurricane leaves houseboat community in question
	   KEY WEST, Florida (AP) _ Hurricane Georges may have settled a
persistent debate about whether the small island at the southern
tip of the continental United States should have a neighborhood of
houseboats.
	   When the hurricane tore through the Florida Keys Friday, it
spared little of what used to be known as Houseboat Row, a flotilla
of 26 houseboats moored on Key West's southeast end.
	   A day later, all but four of the boats had sunk, were sinking,
or had been smashed apart.
	   ``What the politicians couldn't do in 10 years, Georges did in
10 hours,'' said Larry Tinkler, who returned after the hurricane to
the Tenacity, a peach-colored floating home he shared with a
roommate.
	   City officials have conducted an on-and-off effort to abolish
Houseboat Row for years. The first houseboat moored there in 1957.
Others followed, and eventually the Row had electricity, garbage
pickup and phone service.
	   In the 1970s, the Outlaws motorcycle gang took over one boat in
the floating neighborhood, named it the Proud Mary, and held wild
parties that helped prompt the city's crusade against the houseboat
dwellers.
 &UR; UNITED STATES: New Englanders from Caribbean help hurricane
victims
	   NEW HAVEN, Connecticut (AP) _ Connecticut's Hispanic community
banded together this weekend to raise money, food and clothing to
aid people in Puerto Rico, the Dominican Republic and other
Caribbean islands ravaged by Hurricane Georges.
	   Hispanics living in the New Haven area collected money, food and
other supplies, in some cases going door-to-door in search of aid.
They raised about dlrs 10,000 Saturday and planned to continue
their efforts for the next few weeks.
	   Two rooms at the Latino Youth Development offices were packed
with food, water and clothing for the hurricane victims. Some of
the donations came from food drives at city schools.
	   ``There is so much food here it is unbelievable,'' said
organizer Daniel Diaz.
	   Organizers are making arrangements with the Connecticut-based
AmeriCares relief organization to fly the goods to Puerto Rico and
the Dominican Republic within the next two weeks.
 &UR; DOMINICAN REPUBLIC: All eyes on Sosa in his hurricane-battered
hometown
	   SAN PEDRO DE MACORIS, Dominican Republic (AP) _ Christian
Vallenilla, 11, picked up a wooden stick Sunday, said, ``This one's
for Sammy,'' and smacked his third home run of the day in the
stadium where Sammy Sosa used to play.
	   No matter that Sosa, the Chicago Cubs slugger, failed to homer
in the Cubs' 4-3 loss to Houston Sunday. Sosa's hurricane-ravaged
hometown of San Pedro de Macoris celebrated his remarkable regular
season, one that produced 66 home runs, just short of Mark
McGwire's mind-boggling 70.
	   ``We can't ask for any more, because he's done a lot already.
He's broken a lot of records,'' said Arizmendi Nunez, a 22-year-old
San Pedro bartender. ``I feel proud because now our flag is raised
high.''
	   Georges nearly destroyed the stadium where Christian was playing
his his friends Sunday. Lighting towers twisted to the ground,
girders stretched skyward where the roof used to be, and people
draped their soiled laundry over the bleachers to dry.
	   The outfield wall is gone, and Christian's house, itself
half-flattened by the hurricane, now has a direct view of home
plate.
</TEXT>
