<SLUG> BC-Uganda-Congo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Newspaper: Congolese planes drop bombs on Ugandan village
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KAMPALA, Ugand (AP) _ Congolese military planes bombed a village
in western Uganda, and Ugandan army troops were sent immediately to
the area, a newspaper reported Monday.
	   The government-owned New Vision said several high-flying
aircraft Sunday hit Bukaka village outside Bundibugyo, about 380
kilometers (235 miles) west of Kampala.
	   It was not immediately possible to obtain comment from Ugandan
military authorities.
	   ``After dropping the bombs, the planes retreated to the Congo. I
think such attacks are intended to provoke us into action, but we
have to study the situation,'' the newspaper quoted an unnamed
military official as saying.
	   Congo accuses Uganda and Rwanda of backing rebels who are trying
to unseat President Laurent Kabila.
	   Uganda acknowledges that under an agreement signed earlier this
year between Kabila and President Yoweri Museveni it has at least
two batallions in eastern Congo to ward off attacks on Uganda by
Ugandan rebels of the Allied Democratic Forces.
	   There have been unconfirmed reports that ADF rebels and former
Rwandan Hutu militimen and soldiers are being trained by Congo.
	   Budibugyo is about 20 kilometers (12 miles) from the Congolese
border on a spur of the Rwenzori Mountains that juts into Congo.
	   (hw/sl)	   
