<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine stocks rise on U.S. rate cut hopes; index up 1.2 percent
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with peso closing lower

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Philippine stocks rose Monday as
hopes of a cut in U.S. interest rates overpowered concerns over
Philippine Airlines' closure, traders said.
	   The 30-share Philippine Stock Exchange Index rose 15.04 points,
or 1.2 percent, to 1,230.50 after falling 4.79 points Friday.
	   Dealers said the market reacted positively to news that Cathay
Pacific Airways has begun flying domestic routes in the Philippines
to fill a vacuum left by the closure of national carrier Philippine
Airlines last Wednesday.
	   ``The main concern last week was the impact of the airline's
closure on domestic growth. Cathay's entry eases this concern,''
said Ricardo Puig, research head at Kim Eng Securities.
	   Puig said expectations that U.S. interest rates may be cut
Tuesday also helped support Philippine share prices.
	   Takeover speculation continued to bolster Philippine Long
Distance Telephone, which once again was the day's most actively
traded stock.
	   Traders attribute the stock's gains to bargain hunting on recent
losses related to a delay in the company's shareholders' rights
plan to deter a hostile takeover.
	   The stock is expected to remain volatile until the Securities
and Exchange Commission rules on whether the company can implement
the plan.
	   Although the possibility of a U.S. interest rate cut has been
discounted by many participants, traders expect an actual cut will
help the market improve.
	   ``We will see a further uptick when foreign funds come in as a
result of the rate cut,'' said Joey Roxas, president of Eagle
Securities.
	   Gainers outpaced losers 52 to 20, while 41 issues remained
unchanged.
	   Among the losers were Air Philippines, which succumbed to
profit-taking after more than tripling its share price in recent
days following improved earnings prospects with the closure of
Philippine Airlines.
	   In currency trading, the peso closed lower against the dollar on
brisk corporate demand for the U.S. currency, traders said.
	   The dollar averaged 43.890 pesos for the day, up from Friday's
average of 43.669 pesos. It was last traded at 43.940 pesos, close
to its intraday high of 43.960 pesos.
	   Traders said the peso didn't break the psychologically important
level of 44 pesos to the dollar because there were no buyers at
this rate.
	   Traders said the possibility of a U.S. interest rate cut
prevented the peso from weakening further, as some participants
expect a cut would bring more foreign funds to the Philippines and
other countries in the region.
</TEXT>
