<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Netherlands-Violence </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dutch police hunt hooligans after post-match riot
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   UTRECHT, Netherlands (AP) _ Police were Monday hunting the
leaders of a gang of hooligans responsible for the worst outbreak
of violence at a Dutch soccer match this season.
	   About 800 fans of FC Utrecht went on the rampage Sunday night
after their team slumped to a 3-0 home defeat at the hands of FC
Twente Enschede.
	   A police press release described the rioting as ``a low point in
the soccer history of Utrecht.''
	   Seven police officers and six Twente fans were injured in
post-match fighting. Two of the injured police had to be treated in
hospital _ one for a broken jaw and the other for a back injury.
	   One fan was hospitalized with a serious head injury after
Utrecht fans stoned the bus he was travelling in.
	   The hooligans also wrecked five police cars and tore down street
lights and traffic signs during the rioting. Police made no arrests
on the night because of the intensity of the violence.
	   In recent seasons Utrecht fans have shed their image of being
among the most violent of Dutch supporters and Sunday's outburst
took police by surprise.
	   ``This was totally unexpected,'' spokeswoman Liesbeth Tettero
said. Police had deployed 90 officers to control crowds at the
match, which was not considered a high-risk encounter meriting
beefed-up security.
	   Dutch police and soccer authorities are working hard to stamp
out hooliganism ahead of the Euro 2000 soccer championships which
are being co-hosted by the Netherlands and Belgium.
	   (mc)	   
</TEXT>
