r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HongKong-Hotels     09-28 0236
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Hotels </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
August hotel occupancy edges higher
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ In an encouraging sign for the territory's
tourism industry, hotel occupancy rose in August compared with the
same month last year, tourism officials said Monday.
	   Hotel occupancy increased to 79 percent, compared with 66
percent last August, a report by the Hong Kong Tourist Association
said. Occupancy in August also was slightly higher than July's 76
percent.
	   Although the rates are high by international standards, Hong
Kong hotels' occupancy rates were as high as 91 percent before the
handover.
	   ``It's good that hotel rates are coming down to competitive
levels, that is good for tourism,'' said association spokesman
Peter Randall.
	   After tourists flocked to Hong Kong to get a last glimpse of the
British colony before it reverted to Chinese rule last July,
arrivals fell sharply and steadily through June this year.
	   Occupancy in the first eight months averaged 73 percent,
compared with 78 percent in the same period last year.
	   Hotels have slashed rates by up to 50 percent to attract
tourists to the territory, which has become expensive compared to
other Asian destinations, where local currencies have depreciated
by up to 70 percent.
	   The Hong Kong dollar is the only fully convertible Asian
currency not to have lost value since the Asian financial crisis
unfolded last July.
</TEXT>
