<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Italy-Cohen-Kosovo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S., Italian defense ministers urge Serbs end violence in Kosovo
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen on Monday
renewed threats of a NATO airstrike unless Serb forces end their
offensive in the embattled province of Kosovo.
	   At a joint news conference with Italian Defense Minister
Beniamino Andreatta, Cohen said the planning for airstrikes was
completed.
	   Both he and Andreatta urged Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic yet again to seek a peaceful solution to the conflict
with ethnic Albania rebels in Kosovo.
	   Cohen said that ``a very strong, credible threat must be made to
Mr. Milosevic to back away from what he is currently doing, that he
should pull his military back, his police back to
allow...humanitarian missions...and to sit down at the bargaining
table to peacefully resolve the issue of Kosovo.''
	   NATO has set no deadline, but Cohen and Andreatta spoke of the
onset of winter and the hardships it would mean for refugees hiding
out in Kosovo's countryside.
	   Cohen said some 50,000 people ``run the risk of either starving
to death or freezing to death.''
	   ``Winter is coming and we are pressed for time,'' Andreatta
said.
	   Later Monday, the Serb government appeared to set the stage for
bowing to NATO demands. It said the rebels had been defeated and
special police units would return to barracks _ a condition
demanded by the Americans and Europeans to avoid NATO attack.
	   (cph/vls) 	   
</TEXT>
