<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Slovakia-Elections, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Slovak opposition agrees to unite, confident of forming new
</HEADLINE>
government &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with more opposition talks expected Monday, Meciar
reportedly at spa with back problem, Hungarian official hails
result; Budapest newspaper comment; no pickup &QL; 
 &UR; By ANDREA LORINCZOVA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRATISLAVA, Slovakia (AP) _ Opposition parties plan more talks
Monday aimed at forming a new government after sealing an apparent
victory in Slovak national elections by declaring their intent to
unite.
	   But weeks of political friction and uncertainty are likely
following results that also would keep Prime Minister Vladimir
Meciar's hard-line ruling party as the single biggest party in
Parliament.
	   ``It's going to be a tough month,'' Milan Ftacnik, deputy
chairman of the opposition Party of the Democratic Left,
acknowledged Sunday after the release of unofficial results touched
off immediate dickering over the makeup of the new government.
	   Meciar, who has ruled Slovakia in strong-handed fashion for six
years, has remained conspicuously absent from view since voting
Friday at the start of two-day parliamentary elections. Barring a
stunning change in figures when the official vote count is released
Monday night or Tuesday, his likeliest options now are to serve as
minority leader in Parliament or resign.
	   His spokesman, Marian Kardos, said Monday that Meciar was at a
spa outside Bratislava for a back problem that required intravenous
treatment. He did not elaborate.
	   Officials of his Movement for a Democratic Slovakia, or HZDS,
denied the 56-year-old premier would quit, and maintained they
still hope to form a majority coalition in Parliament.
	   The leaders of the top four opposition parties met Sunday and
reiterated their intent to form a governing coalition after results
indicated they won 93 of the 150 seats in Parliament. They said
more negotiations are needed to firm it up.
	   The Slovak Democratic Coalition won 26 percent, good for 42
parliament seats, according to the unofficial results. The other
three opposition parties _ the Party of the Democratic Left, the
Hungarian Coalition Party and the Party of Civic Understanding,
reflecting a wide variety of positions _ got another 32 percent to
earn 51 seats.
	   Finishing ahead of all 16 other parties will give Meciar the
first crack at forming a governing coalition. But the HZDS' sharp
decline in support since 1994 elections, coupled with that of its
current coalition partners, leaves it with slim hopes to form a
majority.
	   ``Slovakia has voted for change,'' top opposition leader Mikulas
Dzurinda, head of the Slovak Democratic Coalition, said Sunday.
``The opposition has won a constitutional majority.''
	   The country's neighbors in Central Europe were happy with the
result _ particularly Hungary, which has complained of
discrimination against Slovakia's 550,000-strong ethnic Hungarian
minority.
	   Referring to Meciar. the Budapest daily Nepszabadsag said ``the
man who failed in the ... elections has left an ugly legacy for
Slovakia.''
	   ``If `Vlado' remains in power, the semi-democracy and the
unbridled crony-privatization will continue, Slovakia will never
get into NATO and the EU, and will become a pariah just like
Yugoslavia,'' the newspaper said.
	   Hungarian Foreign Minister Janos Martonyi told the MTI news
agency that the new government will be a step forward for
Slovakia's democratic development and commitment to Western
integration.
	   (al/dc/reid)
</TEXT>
