<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Stocks </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Share prices surge
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) - Share prices in Hong Kong surged Monday on
expectations of a cut in U.S. interest rates.
	   The Hang Seng Index, the market's key indicator of blue chips,
rose 244.43 points, or 3.2 percent, closing at 7,946.04. On Friday,
the index had slumped 133.00 points.
	   Turnover amounted to 5.16 billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs
661 million), up from Friday's 4.41 billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S.
dlrs 565 million).
	   Brokers said investors expect the U.S. Federal Reserve Open
Market Committee to cut interest rates at its meeting on Tuesday.
	   A cut would ease pressure on Hong Kong interest rates, because
the Hong Kong dollar's peg to the U.S. currency means interest
rates here usually track U.S. rates.
	   A rate cut in Hong Kong will help slow the shrinkage of the
economy, brokers said.
	   Among properties, Cheung Kong rose 1.20 Hong Kong dollars to
27.10, and Cheung Kong rose 1.10 dollars to 35.50.
	   In the banking sector, HSBC Holdings rose 5.50 dollars to
145.00, and Hang Seng Bank rose 1.60 dollars to 48.80.
	   Elsewhere, Swire Pacific ``A'' rose 1.75 dollars to 24.80, and
Cathay Pacific rose 70 cents to 7.55. 	   
</TEXT>
