<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Thailand-Corruption </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Pricey vegetable seeds deal puts government in hot water
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BANGKOK, Thailand (AP) _ A Ministry of Agriculture poverty
alleviation program has turned into a political battle as the
leading opposition party questioned the government over its costs,
a party spokesman said Monday.
	   Chief spokesman for the New Aspiration Party Suraporn
Danaitangtrakool said his party will demand to know why vegetable
seeds were purchased from Taiwan and Japan at four times the local
prices.
	   ``We will hit the government hard if allegations (of corruption)
are proved true,'' the party's leader Chavalit Yonchaiyudh was
quoted in The Nation newspaper Monday as saying.
	   The 254 million baht (dlrs 6.2 million) project was designed to
help 2 million villagers, many suffering from the economic crisis,
grow their own vegetables from seeds distributed by the government.
	   Deputy Agriculture Minister Wirat Rattanaset told reporters
Monday he was prepared to defend the deal against any charges from
the opposition. He denied any wrongdoing.
	   Prime Minister Chuan Leekpai has ordered the minister of
agriculture to investigate the allegations, according to The
Nation.
	   The questionable purchases came to public attention after
unsigned leaflets were distributed at the ministry alleging
corruption.
	   The allegation has threatened to become a new scandal for the
government of Chuan, who in the past week witnessed resignations of
the public health minister and his deputy over corruption scandals
at government hospitals.
</TEXT>
