<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Austria-Hong Kong </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Austria's Lauda Air plans service to Hong Kong
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   VIENNA, Austria (AP) _ Austria's Lauda Air plans three flights a
week next year between Vienna and Hong Kong, the firm announced
Monday. The service will begin next summer.
	   The company said it has not decided whether to use a Boeing 767
or Boeing 777 aircraft for the service. If the former is used, the
flight will stop in Bangkok, Thailand before heading on to the
former British colony.
	   If the firm decides to use the Boeing 777, the flight will be
non-stop between Vienna and Hong Kong with an onward connection to
Manila, Philippines.
	   The company said its founder, former race car driver Niki Lauda,
has long wanted to initiate service to the Philippines.
