<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Kia Trial </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Prosecutors demand heavy prison terms for former Kia officials
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Prosecutors requested a 12-year prison
term Monday for a former head of bankrupt Kia Motors Co. on charges
of embezzling 52.3 billion won (dlrs 37 million) in company funds.
	   Prosecutors also sought prison terms of up to seven years for
four other top Kia officials for alleged involvement in the
bribes-for-loan scandal.
	   Kim Sun-hong, who headed the nation's second largest carmaker
until last October, was accused of embezzling company money to
bribe politicians and government officials to take out bank loans
and keep the financially shaky company afloat.
	   Kim also was accused of illegally arranging for Kia to guarantee
350 billion won (dlrs 250 million) in debt incurred by several of
its financially troubled subsidiaries and illegally to lend 1.1
trillion won (dlrs 814 million) to other units.
	   Kia collapsed under 11 trillion won (dlrs 8 billion) in bad bank
loans in the summer of last year. Its failure eroded foreign
investor confidence, fueling a flight of foreign capital.
	   ``Heavy punishment is needed as the defendants weakened the
finance of Kia by taking out large loans through forged accounting
books and caused a huge damage to the economy,'' senior prosecutor
Lee Myong-jae said.
	   Prosecutors earlier said South Korea's troubles spun out of
control when the government failed to unload Kia quickly after its
collapse.
	   South Korea was forced to call in the International Monetary
Fund to bail out its battered economy in December. 	   
</TEXT>
