<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cambodia-Resistance </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cambodian resistance general waits for political settlement
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PHNOM PENH, Cambodia (AP) _ The leader of Cambodian resistance
forces lodged in the jungles along the Thai-Cambodian border said
Monday his troops will remain patient while talks for a new
government continue.
	   Speaking by telephone from Bangkok, Gen. Nhek Bunchhay said he
met Sunday with opposition party leader Prince Norodom Ranariddh
and agreed that no new military actions would be instigated by his
heavily outgunned resistance fighters.
	   ``We want to wait and see if there is a political solution,''
said the general. ``We don't want to resort to military means.''
	   Nhek Bunchhay fled the capital of Phnom Penh last year after
Cambodian leader Hun Sen's ousted Ranariddh as his co-premier in a
violent coup.
	   He formed an armed resistance in northern Cambodia to oppose Hun
Sen's more powerful army.
	   Under a barrage of artillery, his forces managed stubbornly to
cling to a northern border post for eight months. It is unclear how
many troops he still has under his command.
	   Nhek Bunchhay agreed early this year to a cease-fire with the
government, paving the way for Ranariddh's return to Phnom Penh to
participate in July 26 parliamentary elections.
	   Hun Sen's Cambodian People's Party won a slight majority in the
July polls, but not the two-thirds needed to form a government on
his own.
	   Hun Sen's party will enter negotiations with Ranariddh's
FUNCINPEC _ which won 43 of 122 seats in the National Assembly _ on
Tuesday. He hopes to form a bipartite coalition with his former
battlefield foe.
	   Nhek Bunchhay's future was briefly discussed at a Monday meeting
of FUNCINPEC party in Phnom Penh, according to a party spokesman.
	   FUNCINPEC officials reaffirmed their commitment to seek a pardon
for Nhek Bunchhay, said spokesman Noranaridh Ananda Yath.
	   Nhek Bunchhay, along with Ranariddh and fellow resistance
commander Serey Kosal, was convicted in absentia at a show trial
earlier this year on charges of conspiring to overthrow the
government.
	   The prince was given a pardon by his father King Norodom
Sihanouk a few months before the election, but Nhek Bunchhay and
Serey Kosal were not.
</TEXT>
