r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Economy 1stLd-Writethru   09-28 0553
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yeltsin meets with officials to complete Cabinet formation
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS, UPDATES with Primakov saying government has paid debt
to military, details of debt restructuring plan in new three final
grafs. Trims. &QL; 
 &UR; By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The government has paid off its debt in back
salaries to the armed forces, and will be able to pay students
their stipends within days, Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov told
President Boris Yeltsin on Monday.
	   Since his appointment nearly three weeks ago, Primakov has
stressed that payment of salaries and pensions will be his
government's priority as it grapples with Russia's grave economic
crisis.
	   According to estimates published in the Kommersant earlier this
month, Russia owed a total of 36 billion rubles (dlrs 2.4 billion)
in back salaries and social payments. Of that sum, 3.5 billion
rubles (dlrs 233 million) was owed to the military.
	   Primakov's meeting with Yeltsin also focused on efforts to wrap
up formation of the new Cabinet _ a painful process that has
stretched into a third week as 10 Cabinet seats remain unfilled.
	   The Kremlin has had difficulty finding willing candidates.
Parliamentary deputy Vladimir Ryzhkov, who was appointed a deputy
premier while on a trip abroad, said he couldn't accept the job
because he lacks the necessary experience.
	   Alexander Shokhin, a centrist who was named to the key post of
deputy prime minister in charge of financial policy, resigned
Friday after just 10 days on the job.
	   He said he was quitting to protest the reappointment of Mikhail
Zadornov as finance minister. Shokhin held Zadornov responsible for
the previous Cabinet's decision on Aug. 17 to devalue the ruble and
freeze domestic debt _ a controversial move that many blame for
fueling Russia's crisis.
	   Zadornov, a liberal reformer, defended himself over the weekend,
saying the former government had few viable alternatives. He
pledged to improve the terms of the government's debt repayment.
	   A government team is to meet Tuesday with representatives of
Russian and foreign banks that suffered multibillion dollar losses
when the old Cabinet defaulted on its debt on treasury bills.
	   Several previous meetings have brought no result, and foreign
investors have assailed the Cabinet for allegedly favoring Russian
banks.
	   No details of the restructuring plan have yet been released
officially. Shokhin said that under the plan, investors would be
able to redeem their defaulted treasury bills in rubles but the
proceeds would be frozen in special accounts for six months.
	   In other economic news:
	   _ Economics Minister Andrei Shapovalyants left for meetings in
London with his counterparts from the Group of Seven industrialized
countries, who are discussing problems related to Russia's
financial crisis.
	   _ The Russian ruble on Monday remained stable, with banks
trading it at around 16 to the dollar _ the same level as last
week. The Russian currency stood at around 6 rubles a dollar before
the crisis.
	   _ The amount of private bank deposits fell by 6.5 percent to
about 151 billion rubles (currently dlrs 10 billion) last month as
people scrambled to pull their money out of failing banks.
	   (vi/ji/gm) 	   
</TEXT>
