<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Hong Kong-Trade </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
August trade deficit at five-year low
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Hong Kong's trade deficit in August fell to a
five-year low as demand in Asia fell because of the regional
financial crisis, the government said Monday.
	   The trade deficit in August fell to 700 million Hong Kong
dollars (U.S. dlrs 89.7 million), equivalent to 0.6 percent of the
value of imports, it said.
	   The deficit in August last year was 10.3 billion Hong Kong
dollars (U.S. dlrs 1.32 billion), or 7.4 percent of the value of
imports.
	   The value of exports fell by 8 percent last month to 119.1
billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs 15.27 billion) from the same
month last year, while imports decreased by 14.2 percent to 119.9
billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs 15.37 billion).
	   A partial air cargo ban imposed after the new airport opened
here in early July also exacerbated the trade decline, the
government statement said.
	   Computer and mechanical problems at the cargo terminal
jeopardized air cargo transport, which returned to full speed in
late August.
	   For the first eight months of 1998, exports fell 4.1 percent and
imports fell 8.6 percent, compared with the same period in 1997,
the statement said.
	   The trade deficit for the first eight months this year totaled
71.9 billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs 9.22 billion), compared
with last year's 121.1 billion Hong Kong dollars (U.S. dlrs 15.5
billion).
</TEXT>
