<HEADER>
w2581 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 3rdLd-Writethru   09-28 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Serb premier says Albanian `terrorism' has been defeated
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS to UPDATE with new material; COMBINES urgent series; no
pickup &QL; 
 &UR; By JOVANA GEC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Seeking to head off NATO attack,
Serbia's premier declared an end Monday to ``anti-terrorist
activities'' in Kosovo but warned the crackdown will resume if
Albanian separatists resume attacks.
	   Premier Mirko Marjanovic told the Serbian parliament that
special police units will return to their barracks _ a condition
demanded by both American and European diplomats to avoid a NATO
attack.
	   ``With this day, anti-terrorist activities have finished and can
be renewed only if some new terrorist bandit-terrorist activity
appears again,'' Marjanovic said. ``I wish to declare that with
this day ... the armed terrorist groups have been defeated.''
	   He said the government will grant amnesty to Kosovo Albanians
who surrender weapons within the next 10 days as long as they have
not committed ``war crimes.''
	   Marjanovic also said the government would appoint a Temporary
Executive Council to ``strengthen civilian structures'' in the
province, where Albanians form 90 percent of the estimated 2
million population.
	   ``The forces that will be decreased by this move will stay ready
in their barracks for a while, just in case that creation of a
terrorist organization in any part of Kosovo is renewed,'' he said.
	   Marjanovic made his remarks as he introduced a resolution
declaring that stamping out ethnic Albanian resistance in Kosovo is
the nation's top priority _ a move that bolsters the position of
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic.
	   Hundreds of people in the southern province of Kosovo have been
killed and some 275,000 forced to flee their homes since
Milosevic's crackdown on ethnic Albanians began seven months ago.
	   Marjanovic said Serb and Yugoslav forces would withdraw to their
barracks and remain there for a while. He gave no timetable but
said the move was in accordance with an agreement Milosevic signed
in June with Russian President Boris Yeltsin.
	   ``Armed terrorist groups have been defeated,'' Marjanovic told
Serbia's assembly today. ``Conditions have been made ... to
decrease engagement of anti-terrorist forces.''
	   The U.N. Security Council has been insisting since March that
Serbs withdraw special police units and other forces from the
province and begin talks with ethnic Albanians on the future of the
majority Albanian province.
	   On Wednesday, the council threatened additional action if
Milosevic did not stop the offensive against militant separatists
in Kosovo and allow for the safe return of refugees.
	   NATO defense chiefs then stepped up plans for airstrikes if
Milosevic failed to comply.
	   U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen added his voice to the
chorus Sunday, warning that Milosevic had only ``a short period of
time'' to comply with international demands to end the conflict.
	   ``A failure to do so presents the possibility that a military
operation against Mr. Milosevic would be necessary,'' Cohen said.
``A failure to do so on his part will be met with very strong NATO
action.''
	   There was no immediate comment from Kosovo Albanian leaders on
Marjanovic's statement. His comments appeared to give in to the
international community while at the same time maintaining an image
of defiance.
	   ``Terrorist gangs have been defeated and a great number of
terrorists have been arrested and disarmed and territory of Serbia
has been saved,'' Marjanovic said. ``We have showed decisively that
there is ... no compromise with those who want to create a new
state on Serbia's territory by terror and force.''
	   Kosovo is part of Serbia, the dominant republic in Yugoslavia.
Most of Kosovo's majority ethnic Albanians want independence.
	   Serb force launched a new offensive late Saturday 50 kilometers
(30 miles) southwest of Kosovo's provincial capital, Pristina. Serb
sources in Pristina said Monday that fighting continued overnight.
	   The Albanian-run Kosovo Information Center said Serb forces
attacked from three directions Sunday near the towns of Suva Reka,
Urosevac and Stimlje. The attack reportedly focused on 11 villages,
and three were on fire. An estimated 15,000 civilians were forced
to flee.
	   Police sources said the rebels recently kidnapped two Serbs,
which prompted the latest retaliation from Serb troops, which are
far stronger militarily than the rebels.
	   rr/jg/av
</TEXT>
