<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-German Election Reax </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Schroeder to visit France first, amid concern over ties
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER BURNS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Germany's future chancellor, Gerhard Schroeder,
said Monday he will make his first foreign trip to France in the
next 10 days to reassure a wary Paris he strongly backs the
Franco-German engine driving European unification.
	   ``The Franco-German axis has historic importance,'' Schroeder
said the day after his Social Democrats defeated Chancellor Helmut
Kohl's conservatives. ``And it will remain the most important for
Europe.''
	   France and Germany are each other's biggest trading partners and
are the main forces behind the euro single currency that takes
effect in January among 11 European nations.
	   But as Germany's first leader not to have lived through the
horrors of World War II, some French were concerned whether the
54-year-old Schroeder and the new German capital in Berlin will be
as committed as Kohl in rooting Germany into the European Union to
avoid future wars.
	   ``It's another generation coming to power, less sensitive to the
weight of the horrors of the past, because they didn't live them,''
said a front-page editorial in the conservative daily Le Figaro,
titled ``The Republic of Berlin.''
	   Schroeder insisted to French-based Europe 1 radio that his
personal ties with France were ``much better'' than the French
media think.
	   ``I would like the contacts between Germany and France, which at
the governmental level work very well and will remain very good, to
expand and reach the societies,'' Schroeder said.
	   The Social Democrat said he would respond quickly to an
invitation by President Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel
Jospin to visit Paris ``before the Bundestag election,'' meaning in
10 days ``at the latest.''
	   Schroeder rejected any possibility of renewed German
nationalism. ``There is no contradiction between the Germans and
the Europeans,'' he said. ``We will be very good Europeans, and
that's why we will be good Germans.''
	   The leader said he wanted the euro to be ``a success.'' He also
said he favored greater international financial cooperation as
proposed by U.S., British and French leaders.
	   (cb-parf-ip)
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
