<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Taiwan-Indonesia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Indonesian trade delegation visits Taiwan
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) _ Ilhan Habibie, son of Indonesian President
B.J. Habibie, arrived in Taiwan Monday as head of a delegation to
promote trade and investment, Taiwan's official news agency
reported.
	   The visit is sensitive because it risks angering China, which
views Taiwan as a renegade province. Indonesia has extended
diplomatic recognition to Beijing and has no formal ties with
Taiwan.
	   Taiwan's Foreign Ministry declined to provide any details on the
younger Habibie's trip. But the official Central News Agency said
he was to brief government officials on recent economic and
political reforms in Indonesia.
	   The elder Habibie came to power after street riots forced former
President Suharto to step down in May.
	   In Jakarta, an official of Taiwan's representative office said
the Indonesian delegation was scheduled to meet Taiwanese President
Lee Teng-hui and visit the state-run Aerospace Industrial
Development Corp. to discuss possible cooperation.
	   Members of the delegation include James Riady, head of the
powerful Lippo Group, and other business executives, officials
said. 	   
</TEXT>
