w2611 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Algeria-Economy     09-28 0249
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Algeria-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Algerian prime minister pledges more privatizations
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) _ Algeria's prime minister said Monday the
government was sticking to privatizations plans, assuring
disgruntled unions that they would be consulted along the way.
	   ``We will continue to implement reforms,'' Ahmed Ouyahia said
after marathon 19-hour talks with Abdelmadjid Sidi-Said, the head
of The General Union of Algerian Workers (UGTA).
	   ``We will continue privatizations within the framework of the
law, transparently and with dialogue,'' he added.
	   Unemployment is growing in Algeria and many workers are not
happy about the government's plans to privatize state industries,
which will mean the loss of more jobs.
	   The UGTA, opposed to privatizations, had boycotted a meeting
with government officials on Sept. 9 and had threatened to call a
general strike.
	   It claims some 200,000 people have lost their jobs in three
years.
	   The UGTA, Algeria's only significant union, has worked
hand-in-hand with the government since 1992, so the strike threat
loomed as a rupture.
	   Sidi-Said said Monday he was ``globally satisfied'' with the
talks with the prime minister, but insisted they did not support
privatization. He did not mention the strike threats.
	   Earlier this year, more than 100,000 Algerian metal and steel
workers, mechanics and customs employees went on strike to protest
government plans to cut public jobs.
	   (parf-ip)
</TEXT>
