<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Myanmar-Ne Win </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Former strongman leaves Myanmar for medical check-up
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   YANGON, Myanmar (AP) _ Ne Win, who ruled the Southeast Asian
nation now known as Myanmar with an iron fist for nearly three
decades, has left the country for a medical check-up in Singapore,
diplomatic sources said Monday.
	   The country's longest ruling leader in modern times, Ne Win
served as head of state from 1962 to 1981, and as chairman of the
then ruling socialist party from 1981 to 1988.
	   Although still said to be powerful, the reins of military rule
were seized by a group of officers who brutally put down a
student-led uprising in 1988. The nation, formerly called Burma,
then became known as Myanmar.
	   Ne Win, 87, had his last examination a year ago after his visit
to Indonesia as guest of then President Suharto. Although
frequently reported to suffer various ailments, the secretive Ne
Win has proved resilient.
	   He first came to power in a military coup and managed to stay in
power for years despite the country's steady economic deterioration
and political isolation. 	   
</TEXT>
