<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Jordan-Israel </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Phone company cuts direct line to Israel in bill dispute
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ Jordan's phone company said Monday it cut
its direct link with a subsidiary of Israel's state-owned Bezek
Telecom Co. because of a financial dispute.
	   Telephone service between the two countries continues, however,
via other carriers.
	   Ali Shukri, chairman of the Jordanian Telecommunications Co.,
said JTC earlier this month stopped the service provided to Bezek
International Ltd., a unit of BTC, because it had not paid a bill
of dlrs 5 million for 1997.
	   ``It has refused to pay the bill,'' Shukri said. He did not
elaborate.
	   Shukri added that Jordan now was routing phone calls to Israel
through a private Israeli firm, Golden Lines.
	   There was no immediate comment from Bezek, which apparently is
using a third country to connect calls to Jordan since it remains
possible to dial between the two countries.
	   The Jordanian Telecommunications Co. had been providing service
to Bezek _ including links not only to the Jewish state but to the
West Bank and Gaza Strip _ since Israel and Jordan signed a peace
treaty in 1994.
	   A phone call to Israel costs dlrs 1 per minute during working
hours, about the same amount as a call to neighboring Gulf states
and North Africa.
 &UR; jjh-eap
</TEXT>
