w2636 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Baseball-NLRou     09-28 0854
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-NL Roundup,0854 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Cardinals win 7-6 over Expos
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ST. LOUIS (AP) _ Mark McGwire ended his spectacular season as
mightily as he started it, hitting his record 69th and 70th homers
in the St. Louis Cardinals' final game, a 7-6 victory Sunday over
the Montreal Expos.
	   McGwire, who hit five homers on the final weekend, connected
against rookie Mike Thurman in the third inning, then broke a 3-all
tie in the seventh with a three-run shot off Carl Pavano (6-9).
	   McGwire moved four ahead of Sammy Sosa and ended nine in front
of Roger Maris' old record. McGwire also got his 162nd walk, tying
Ted Williams (1947 and '49) for the second-highest total ever
behind Babe Ruth's 170 in 1923.
	   John Frascatore (3-4) was the winner and Juan Acevedo got his
15th save.
 &UR; Astros 4, Cubs 3
	   In Houston, moments after another heartbreaking loss, Chicago
won a reprieve when San Francisco lost at Colorado, forcing a
tiebreaking wild-card playoff between the Cubs and Giants on Monday
night at Wrigley Field.
	   Carl Everett tripled off Rod Beck (3-4) leading off the 11th
when a retreating Sammy Sosa shied away from the ball as he reached
the warning track in right, and Richard Hidalgo hit a sacrifice
fly.
	   Sosa, who didn't homer, singled for his 158th RBI, fourth-best
in NL history. He also struck out, flied out twice and singled in
the eighth, finishing 2-for-5.
	   Scott Elarton (2-1) pitched two perfect innings.
 &UR; Rockies 9, Giants 8
	   In Denver, San Francisco wasted a 7-0 lead, watched Neifi Perez
hit a game-winning homer off Robb Nen (7-7) in the ninth inning
about a minute after the Cubs lost.
	   San Francisco and Chicago are both 89-73 heading into Monday's
tiebreaker.
	   The Giants, who trailed the Cubs by five games with 10 days left
in the season but closed with nine wins in 10 games, led 7-6 in the
seventh before Vinny Castilla hit a two-run homer off Julian
Tavarez. But the Giants came right back in the eighth and tied it
on Jeff Kent's solo homer off Pedro Astacio.
	   Colorado's Larry Walker went 2-for-4 and won his first batting
title with a .363 average, nine points ahead of New York's John
Olerud. Jerry Dipoto (3-4) pitched a scoreless ninth for the win.
 &UR; Braves 7, Mets 2
	   In Atlanta, New York, which had a one-game lead in the NL
wild-card race going into their final five games and were still in
a three-way tie with two games to go, fell behind 5-0 and was
eliminated.
	   Contending for their first postseason appearance since 1988, the
Mets lost their final five games, scoring just seven runs in their
last 44 innings.
	   During three days in Atlanta, the Mets stranded 32 runners _ 11
on Sunday _ and left the bases loaded four times.
	   Greg Maddux (18-9) helped Atlanta to its 106 win, the most in
the NL since the Mets had 108 in 1986. Armando Reynosa (7-3) was
pounded for five runs and six hits in 1 2-3 innings.
 &UR; Marlins 6, Phillies 5
 &UR; Phillies 7, Marlins 3
	   In Miami, Ruben Amaro Jr., playing his final major league game
before becoming the Phillies' assistant general manager, singled
home the go-ahead run in the second game. Kevin Sefcik drove in a
career-high four runs for the Phillies in the opener.
	   The Marlins, who swept the Phillies on Saturday, finished at
54-108, the worst record in the majors since 1979, when Oakland
also dropped 108 and Toronto lost 109. The Marlins had the worst
record ever for a defending World Series champion, breaking the
previous low (74-88) set by the 1991 Cincinnati Reds.
	   Brian Meadows (11-13) allowed three runs and seven hits in five
innings in the opener and Antonio Alfonseca got one out for his
eighth save. Tyler Green (6-12) was the loser. Carlton Loewer (7-8)
won the second game and Rafael Medina (2-6) lost.
 &UR; Reds 4, Pirates 1
	   In Cincinnati, the Cincinnati Reds ended their season by putting
together the majors' first all-brother infield _ Barry and Stephen
Larkin, and Bret and Aaron Boone _ and won on Aaron Boone's
three-run homer.
	   Roberto Petagine hit a solo homer and Boone had a three-run shot
off Jose Silva (6-7) as Pittsburgh finished with an eight-game
losing streak.
	   Brett Tomko (13-14) gave up five hits and struck out seven in
his first complete game in 53 career starts.
 &UR; Dodgers 2, Brewers 1
	   In Los Angeles, Chan Ho Park (15-9) allowed one run and eight
hits in six innings for his career-high 15th win, and Mark
Grudzielanek drove in the go-ahead run with a sacrifice fly off
Bill Pulsipher (3-4). Jeff Shaw got three outs for his 48th save.
 &UR; Padres 3, Diamondbacks 2
	   In Phoenix, Greg Vaughn became the fourth player to hit 50
homers this season and Trevor Hoffman got his major league-leading
53rd save.
	   Vaughn broke a 1-all tie in the eighth with a two-run shot off
Aaron Small (3-1). Before this year, there had never been more than
two 50-homer players in a single season.
	   Hoffman got three straight outs for his 53rd save in 54 chances,
tying the NL saves record set by current teammate Randy Myers, who
did it for the Cubs in 1993. Matt Clement (2-0) got the win in
relief.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Baseball-NL Roundup; CT:s; 
(REG:EURO;)
(REG:BRIT;)
(REG:SCAN;)
