<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Asian Markets, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Asian markets close higher on U.S. rate cut hopes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: RECASTS; UPDATES with closing figures for all markets.

<TEXT>
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Most Asian stock markets closed higher Monday
on growing expectations for an interest rate cut in the United
States and hopes that Japan is finally prepared to deal with its
banking problems.
	   In Hong Kong, the blue chip Hang Seng Index surged 244.43
points, or 3.2 percent, closing at 7,946.04. On Friday, the index
had slumped 133.00 points.
	   Tokyo share prices also rose as investors welcomed news that
Japan's ruling party and opposition had reached an agreement on
banking reform measures.
	   The benchmark No. 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average gained 185.53
points, or 1.35 percent, to 13,909.37. On Friday, the Nikkei shed
481.94 points, or 3.39 percent.
	   The compromise deal paves the way for passage next month of
legislation aimed at cleaning up Japan's troubled financial system,
which has been burdened by roughly dlrs 1 trillion in bad loans.
	   Investors in Tokyo shrugged off the failure of Japan Leasing
Corp., a non-bank affiliate of the troubled Long-Term Credit Bank
of Japan.
	   The leasing company, estimated to have debts exceeding 2.44
trillion yen (U.S. dlrs 18.24 billion), applied late Sunday for
court protection in Japan's largest ever corporate bankruptcy.
	   Meanwhile, the U.S. dollar was quoted at 135.72 yen in late
afternoon trading, up 1.08 yen from late Friday in Tokyo, but below
its late New York level of 136.25 yen Friday.
	   Hong Kong brokers said investors expect the U.S. Federal Reserve
Open Market Committee to cut interest rates at its meeting on
Tuesday.
	   A cut would ease pressure on Hong Kong interest rates, because
the Hong Kong dollar's peg to the U.S. currency means interest
rates in the territory usually track U.S. rates.
	   In Bangkok, share prices closed sharply higher on growing
perception that the Thai market, which had been hovering at 11-year
lows for weeks, has begun to recover.
	   The Stock Exchange of Thailand index rose 6.60 points, or 2.7
percent, to 255.53.
	   The market was closed for a holiday in Malaysia.
	   Elsewhere:
	   MANILA: Philippine shares closed higher as concerns over the
economic impact of Philippine Airlines' closure receded and on
hopes of a cut in U.S. interest rates. The 30-share Philippine
Stock Exchange Index rose 15.04 points, or 1.2 percent, to
1,230.50.
	   TAIPEI: Share prices closed lower because of continued worries
over last week's bailout of hedge fund Long-Term Capital Management
LP in the United States. The market's key Weighted Stock Price
Index fell 69.28 points, or 1 percent, to 6,910.61.
	   WELLINGTON: New Zealand share prices closed higher on
expectation of a cut in U.S. interest rates. The NZSE-40 Capital
Index fell 7.42 points, or 0.4 percent, to 1,716.61.
	   SYDNEY: Australian share prices closed higher. The All
Ordinaries Index rose 28.2 points, or 1.1 percent, to 2,591.6.
	   SEOUL: Share prices closed slightly lower on worries over
Tuesday's planned strike by bank workers. The Korea Composite Stock
Price Index slipped 0.57 point to 305.73.
	   SINGAPORE: Shares prices closed mixed, with the key index rising
on wide expectations that the U.S. will make a significant cut in
interest rates. The Straits Times Index rose 6.61 points, or 0.7
percent, to 930.55.
	   JAKARTA: Share prices closed generally higher, but continued
selling in telecommunication stocks forced the benchmark index to
stay in negative territory. The Composite Index slipped 0.223 point
to 275.001.
 &UR; (ks) 	   
</TEXT>
