w2647 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-France-GermanElection 1stLd-Writethru   09-28 0591
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-German Election Reax, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Schroeder to visit France first, amid concern over ties
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS Chirac, Jospin, Giscard, other comment, background
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER BURNS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Germany's future chancellor Gerhard Schroeder said
Monday he will make his first foreign trip to France in the next 10
days, to reassure a somewhat wary Paris that he strongly backs the
Franco-German engine driving European unification.
	   ``The Franco-German axis has historic importance,'' Schroeder
said the day after his Social Democrats defeated Chancellor Helmut
Kohl's conservatives. ``And it will remain the most important for
Europe.''
	   Schroeder said he would respond quickly to an invitation by
President Jacques Chirac and Prime Minister Lionel Jospin to visit
Paris in the next 10 days ``at the latest.''
	   France and Germany are each other's biggest trading partners and
are the main forces behind the euro single currency that takes
effect in January among 11 of the 15 European Union nations.
	   But as Germany's first leader not to have experienced World War
II, some French were concerned whether the 54-year-old Schroeder
and the coming new German capital in Berlin will be as committed as
Kohl in rooting Germany into the European Union to avoid future
wars.
	   ``It's another generation coming to power, less sensitive to the
weight of the horrors of the past, because they didn't live them,''
said a front-page editorial in the conservative daily Le Figaro,
titled ``The Republic of Berlin.''
	   On the left, the daily Liberation said that for Schroeder, ``the
war is over, well over, as well as the time of repentance. And if
he says he's European, as he likes to repeat, it's not by moral
obligation but by national interest. An interest that is not
necessarily eternal.''
	   Schroeder insisted to French-based Europe 1 radio that his
personal ties with France were ``much better'' than the French
media think.
	   ``I would like the contacts between Germany and France, which at
the governmental level work very well and will remain very good, to
expand and reach the societies,'' Schroeder said, referring to a
lack of cultural exchange between the two countries.
	   While Paris media raised questions about Schroeder, and noted he
speaks only English and German, French leaders publicly voiced
support for the new leader. Kohl spoke no foreign language, but was
seen as far more Francophile than Schroeder.
	   Both conservative Chirac and Socialist Jospin congratulated
Schroeder, though Chirac also thanked Kohl ``for the immense
contribution to Europe-building for 16 years and said Europe
``still needs him.''
	   Jospin hailed Kohl's ``role in the history of his country,'' and
he said he was ``certain that the new team in Germany will have the
heart to further reinforce, enrich and renew relations with
France.''
	   Former President Valery Giscard d'Estaing asked whether today's
French and German leaders ``will be capable of elaborating an
important and significant plan to advance the European Union.''
	   Schroeder rejected any possibility of renewed German
nationalism. ``There is no contradiction between the Germans and
the Europeans,'' he said. ``We will be very good Europeans, and
that's why we will be good Germans.''
	   The leader said he wanted the euro to be ``a success.'' He also
said he favored greater international financial cooperation as
proposed by U.S., British and French leaders.
	   (cb-parf-ip)
</TEXT>
