<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Kiribati </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Korean tuna ship released by Kiribati authorities
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ A South Korean tuna ship and its 25
crewmen were released Monday after being detained by the central
Pacific island nation of Kiribati for four days, its owner said.
	   The tuna boat, owned by Dongwon Industry Co. of Seoul, was
seized while operating in waters close to Kiribati last Thursday,
Dongwon officials said.
	   A Kiribati patrol boat ordered the ship to stop for questioning.
When the ship continued to sail, the patrol boat opened fire,
killing a Vietnamese crewman, Dongwon officials said.
	   The ship and the rest of the crew have been detained in Canton
since. The ship was operating with official permission from
Kiribati authorities when the incident occurred, Dongwon officials
said.
	   ``A funeral for the dead crewman was held in Canton,'' said Lee
Hwa-shin, a Dongwon official. ``We're not legally responsible for
the incident but are willing to pay some compensation for the dead
sailor's family.''
	   Kiribati straddles the equator between Hawaii and Australia. Its
60,000 people inhabit 33 small atolls and are among the poorest in
the Pacific. 	   
</TEXT>
