</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Uganda-Embassy Bombing </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Police holding 15 after house-to-house search
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KAMPALA, Uganda (AP) _ Police were holding 15 people Monday
after some 200 people were picked up in a weekend house-to-house
search, a spokesman said.
	   Bob Ngobi said the 15 picked up in neighborhoods east of the
Ugandan capital would be charged ``with being idle and
disorderly.'' He said no other crime was involved.
	   He did not explain why the extensive search was necessary to
locate idle and disorderly people.
	   Ugandan authorities are now holding between 17 and 20 people in
connection with an alleged plan to bomb the U.S. Embassy in Kampala
as well as Ugandan targets.
	   Simultaneous bombings of the U.S. embassies in neighboring Kenya
and Tanzania Aug. 7 that were allegedly organized and carried out
by people associated with Saudi exile Osama bin Laden killed 248
people in Nairobi and 11 in Dar es Salaam.
	   A report Monday in the Nairobi East African Standard said three
of the 20 had been released, but Ngobi was not able to confirm
this. The report also identified two in the group of 20 as Kenyans
who were said to be organizers of the foiled bombing.
	   Earlier reports had said the group was made up of Ugandans and
Somalis, and that the identities two men arrested at the
Kenyan-Ugandan border two weeks ago were not known.
	   The government-owned New Vision newspaper said Monday one of the
20 being held is an Iranian. He was identified as Asghar Pishdar,
and the report said he was arrested by Ugandan police and FBI
agents as he was boarding a plane at Entebbe International Airport.
	   Iran Air has a weekly flight from Entebbe to Tehran on
Saturdays.
	   Ngobi refused to comment on the report.
	   (hw/sl)	   
</TEXT>
