<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP News Summary,0722 </SLUG>


<TEXT>
	   A summary of late news from The Associated Press. Some items
have moved on this circuit in expanded form with ``i'' or ``f''
category codes:
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ Gerhard Schroeder, Germany's designated new
chancellor, begans talks Monday on building a coalition government
after German voters ousted Chancellor Helmut Kohl after 16 years of
conservative rule. The Social Democratic victory marked the first
time in postwar Germany that voters rejected all the parties from
the previous government in favor of fresh faces and new ideas. Kohl
and his Christian Democrats won just 35 percent of the vote, which
translates to a loss of 49 of the 294 seats it held in the old
parliament. Now it's up to Schroeder _ whose Social Democrats won
41 percent of the vote _ to make good on pledges to end
unemployment, stuck above 10 percent, and to bring long-awaited tax
and economic reforms. (GERMANY-ELECTION)
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Seeking to head off NATO attack,
Serbia's premier declared an end Monday to ``anti-terrorist
activities'' in Kosovo but warned they will restart if there are
new attacks by Albanian separatists. Premier Mirko Marjanovic told
the Serbian parliament that special police units will return to
barracks _ a condition demanded by both American and European
diplomats to avoid a NATO attack. He said the government will grant
amnesty to Kosovo Albanians who surrender weapons within the next
10 days as long as they have not committed ``war crimes.''
Marjanovic made his remarks as he introduced a resolution declaring
that stamping out ethnic Albanian resistance in Kosovo is the
nation's top priority _ a move that bolsters the position of
Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic. (YUGOSLAVIA-KOSOVO)
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Two Jewish settler leaders hurried to New York
on Monday to try to persuade Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu not
to conclude an agreement with the Palestinians on an Israeli troop
withdrawal from 13 percent of the West Bank. The settlers
threatened to topple Netanyahu if he goes ahead with a deal they
fear will isolate many settlements in the West Bank and Gaza
Strips. However, Israeli Cabinet Secretary Danny Naveh indicated on
Monday that an agreement between Netanyahu and Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat was not near. Speaking after a three-way meeting
between U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, Arafat and
Netanyahu early Monday, Naveh told Israel radio that the obstacle
remains Palestinian refusal to carry out its commitments,
especially stopping extremists from attacking Israel. Palestinians
say they have done all they can to control extremists.
(ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS)
	   ISLAMABAD, Pakistan _ Pakistani opposition parties on Monday
demanded that Prime Minister Nawaz Sharif be investigated following
a newspaper report accusing him of tax evasion and siphoning
millions of dollars from his country's coffers into personal bank
accounts. The Observer, a British Sunday newspaper, quoted a report
prepared by the Pakistani Federal Investigation Agency that said
the Sharif family was involved in tax evasion, loan defaults and
has ``phantom'' bank accounts. It did not say what these accounts
were. In Islamabad, a government spokesman dismissed the
allegations as ``wild, incorrect and malicious,'' while Sharif's
son, Hasan Nawaz, said the report was baseless. Sharif had no
immediate comment. (PAKISTAN-SHARIF-CORRUPTION)
	   PASCAGOULA, Mississippi (AP) _ The U.S. Gulf Coast groaned under
the fury of Hurricane Georges, which moved ashore with 126 mph (203
kph) gusts early Monday as it spewed wind and rain from the Florida
Panhandle to Louisiana. Power outages were reported all along the
coast, airports and interstates closed, curfews were imposed and
flash-flood warnings abounded. Waves as tall as a house clipped off
fishing piers in Alabama and leapt across beachfront roads along
U.S. 90 in Mississippi. More than 1.5 million people were told to
leave the coast, spurring ``probably the largest evacuation we have
ever achieved,'' said Lt. Col. Ronnie Jones of the Louisiana State
Police. No deaths or injuries were directly attributed to Georges
during its odyssey across southern states, in contrast to the more
than 300 deaths reported in the Caribbean. (US-HURRICANE GEORGES)
</TEXT>
