<SLUG> BC-AP Top Financial News,0708 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 1100 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   HONG KONG (AP) _ Most Asian stock markets closed higher Monday
on growing expectations for an interest rate cut in the United
States and hopes that Japan is finally prepared to deal with its
banking problems. In Hong Kong, the blue chip Hang Seng Index
surged 244.43 points, or 3.2 percent, closing at 7,946.04. On
Friday, the index had slumped 133.00 points. Tokyo share prices
also rose as investors welcomed news that Japan's ruling party and
opposition had reached an agreement on banking reform measures.
Elsewhere, shares also closed higher in Thailand, the Philippines,
New Zealand and Australia. Shares were lower in Taiwan and South
Korea. They were mixed in Singapore and Indonesia. (ASIAN MARKETS)
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan's ruling party announced Monday it had
reached a final agreement with the major opposition parties on a
key set of bills to clean up this country's troubled financial
system. The announcement raised hopes that the bills, aimed at
cleaning up about dlrs 1 trillion of bad debt in the banking
sector, would be approved early next month, during the current
session of Parliament. Monday's breakthrough centered on a
compromise over how much power to give a new independent body that
will be charged with regulating the finance sector. The ruling
Liberal Democratic Party and the opposition agreed regulation of
the finance sector would be shared by the ministry and the
independent panel. They also agreed that any bank whose capital
falls precariously while purchasing an ailing bank that has been
nationalized will be eligible for an injection of public funds.
(JAPAN-BANK BILLS)
	   TOKYO (AP) _ A leasing company saddled with over 2 trillion yen
(dlrs 16 billion) in debt announced Monday it has filed for
protection in Japan's biggest bankruptcy ever. Japan Leasing Corp.,
an affiliate of the ailing Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan, filed
for protection from creditors late Sunday, said Hiroaki Okamoto,
the company's president. Okamoto said he did not know how much of
the company's 2.18 trillion yen (dlrs 16 billion) in debts it would
be able to pay back. But instead of sparking more gloom, the
company's collapse was seen by many as elminating a potential
sticking point in government efforts to pass a series of banking
bills to clean up the country's bad-loan mess. (JAPAN-BANKRUPTCY)
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The government has paid off its debt in back
salaries to the armed forces, and will be able to pay students
their stipends within days, Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov told
President Boris Yeltsin on Monday. Since his appointment nearly
three weeks ago, Primakov has stressed that payment of salaries and
pensions will be his government's priority as it grapples with
Russia's grave economic crisis. According to estimates published in
the Kommersant earlier this month, Russia owed a total of 36
billion rubles (dlrs 2.4 billion) in back salaries and social
payments. Of that sum, 3.5 billion rubles (dlrs 233 million) was
owed to the military. Primakov's meeting with Yeltsin also focused
on efforts to wrap up formation of the new Cabinet _ a painful
process that has stretched into a third week as 10 Cabinet seats
remain unfilled. (RUSSIA-ECONOMY)
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Prosecutors requested a 12-year prison
term Monday for a former head of bankrupt Kia Motors Co. on charges
of embezzling 52.3 billion won (dlrs 37 million) in company funds.
Prosecutors also sought prison terms of up to seven years for four
other top Kia officials for alleged involvement in the
bribes-for-loan scandal. Kim Sun-hong, who headed the nation's
second largest carmaker until last October, was accused of
embezzling company money to bribe politicians and government
officials to take out bank loans and keep the financially shaky
company afloat. Kia collapsed under 11 trillion won (dlrs 8
billion) in bad bank loans in the summer of last year. Its failure
eroded foreign investor confidence, fueling a flight of foreign
capital. (SKOREA-KIA TRIAL)
</TEXT>
