<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinians, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede JERUSALEM
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Hebron settlers attack Palestinians after shots are fired &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: INCORPORATES BC-Israel-Shooting, UPDATES with details of
three-way summit at White House; changes byline
 &UR; By LAURIE COPANS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HEBRON, West Bank (AP) _ Shots were fired Monday at a group of
young Israelis by assailants in the Palestinian-run part of this
divided town, and a female Israeli student was wounded in the leg.
	   In response, Jewish settlers beat several Palestinians passing
by the Jewish enclave of Beit Hadassah, and witnesses said one
Palestinian woman was injured. An Israeli woman was detained.
	   The violence came as the Israeli and Palestinian leaders were to
meet in Washington with U.S. President Bill Clinton on Monday in
hopes of concluding an agreement on a West Bank troop pullback,
said an Israeli official who spoke on condition of anonymity.
	   Late Sunday, Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu had met in New York, with U.S.
Secretary of State Madeleine Albright as host. It was their first
face-to-face meeting in nearly a year.
	   Violence in the volatile city of Hebron could cast a shadow on a
three-way summit in Washington.
	   Monday's incident began shortly before noon. A group of visiting
Israeli students was walking from on the road between two Jewish
enclaves, Beit Hadassah and Tel Romeida, when shots were fired at
them from the Palestinian-controlled part of town.
	   A female student was hit in the leg by two or three bullets,
Israel army radio said. A companion fainted. The wounded Israeli,
whose name and age were not immediately available, was taken to a
hospital in Jerusalem.
	   In response, several settlers beat Palestinian passers-by
outside Beit Hadassah.
	   Israeli soldiers closed off the Israeli enclaves, keeping
Israelis from reaching the open-air Palestinian market. In the
past, settlers have responded to attacks by rampaging through the
market, overturning stalls and attacking Palestinians.
	   Tensions between Jewish settlers and Palestinians in Hebron rose
considerably last month after a settler rabbi was stabbed to death
in his home in Tel Romeida, a cluster of several trailers in the
heart of a Palestinian neighborhood. The assailant, presumably a
Palestinian militant, was never caught.
	   Hebron is home to 130,000 Palestinians and 450 Jewish settlers.
In January 1997, Israeli troops handed 80 percent of the city to
Palestinian control, but remained in the downtown area to protect
the settler enclaves.
 &UR; ml-kl
</TEXT>
