<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sudan-Mobilization </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Government mobilizes citizens to fight in south
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MOHAMED OSMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KHARTOUM, Sudan (AP) _ Sudan has declared a general mobilization
and has called up retired army officers to counter expected
assaults by southern rebel forces, a state-run newspaper reported
Monday.
	   Al-Anba daily said Sudan was under threat from the rebels and
two neighboring states ``aided by the United States.''
	   The government has been warning for several days that it expects
a major battle with the rebels for the provincial capital of Juba
in southern Equatoria state. There also have been reports of
shelling along the Sudanese border with Eritrea.
	   Al-Anba said the Sudanese Cabinet adopted the mobilization
decision in a meeting Sunday night to counter ``Ugandan aggression
against the southern region and an Eritrean offensive in the
east.''
	   In a statement read over state-run Omdurman radio, the army's
spokesman, Gen. Abdul-Rahman Sirul-Khatim, accused the United
States of aiding the attackers.
	   ``The two simultaneous attacks are coordinated by the Americans,
who have been providing materiel, political and media support for
the rebels and the Ugandan-Eritrean aggression,'' he said.
	   The government has long accused Uganda of sending troops to
fight with southern Sudanese rebels and Eritrea of aiding
rebel-allied opposition groups intent on overthrowing the Islamic
government of Lt. Gen. Omar el-Bashir.
	   Both Uganda and Eritrea have repeatedly denied the accusations.
	   The Cabinet statement called on all Sudanese who are able to
carry arms and all senior government officials to ``take part in
the honor of defending the homeland.''
	   It also ordered all retired army officers and non-commissioned
officers to report to the nearest army unit to move to the war
zones.
	   On Saturday, el-Bashir paid a surprise visit to Juba and called
on the nation to be ready for the ``final battle'' to defend the
town, which is 1,200 kilometers (740 miles) south of the capital
Khartoum.
	   The higher education ministry suspended classes at Sudanese
universities for one month to enable the students to take part in
any fighting.
	   El-Bashir had ordered a general mobilization in June after the
rebel Sudan Peoples' Liberation Army captured the garrison town of
Ulu, 455 kilometers (280 miles) southeast of Khartoum.
	   The SPLA has announced advances around Juba in recent weeks.
	   SPLA rebels have been fighting since 1983 for more autonomy for
the south's Christians and animists from the Islamic North.
	   More than 1.5 million people have died in the fighting and
accompanying famines. Millions more have been forced to flee their
homes.
 &UR; mo-my/eap
</TEXT>
