w2668 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GermanElectionReax     09-28 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-German Election Reax </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With Kohl defeated, concern shifts to new leader's policies
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Germany Election &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Politicians of the left on Monday welcomed Gerhard
Schroeder's election triumph which ended 16 years of conservative
government under Helmut Kohl, claiming the result as fresh evidence
that the political tide was running their way.
	   ``It's a very positive result,'' said Deputy Prime Minister
Walter Veltroni, who said Schroeder was in the same center-left
mold as British Prime Minister Tony Blair and French Prime Minister
Lionel Jospin.
	   ``With Schroeder, Blair and Jospin, it gets easier ... for the
unemployment issue to enter full force in Europe's political
discussion,'' Veltroni said.
	   ``A new epoch is coming. Many countries have become much more
leftist in nature,'' said Russian Communist Party leader Gennady
Zyuganov.
	   ``A different Germany is born, but also a different Europe, full
of question marks,'' said the Italian daily newspaper Corriere
della Sera.
	   The Wall Street Journal Europe agreed on Schroeder's place in
the political spectrum but with a negative spin, calling him ``a
split-the-difference pragmatist'' in the mold of Blair and U.S.
President Bill Clinton.
	   ``When it comes time to jump off the fence on actual policy
questions, on which side Mr. Schroeder will land is anyone's
guess,'' the Wall Street Journal Europe said in an editorial
Monday.
	   Schroeder declared that one thing wouldn't change: the
partnership between Germany and France as leaders of the European
Union.
	   ``The Franco-German axis has historic importance, and it will
remain the most important for Europe,'' said Schroeder, who said he
would make an official visit to France within 10 days.
	   In Australia, the end of 16 years of conservative government in
Germany was hailed by opposition leader Kim Beazley as evidence the
rest of the world was abandoning policies like those pursued by
Australia's conservative Prime Minister John Howard.
	   Beazley, who is campaigning to unseat Howard in an Oct. 3
national election, said Europeans were now looking to parties, like
his own, that were prepared to do something about unemployment.
	   ``Since the mid 1990s the people in Europe have been turning to
interventionist government policies,'' he said in a radio
interview. ``These days we've recognized that there are benefits
from a globalized economy and benefits from the free market, but
there are also casualties.''
	   Kohl, who had governed for 16 years, won warm praises.
	   Japanese Prime Minister Keizo Obuchi said Kohl ``has attained
historic achievements, such as the realization of German
unification and promotion of European integration.''
	   The Irish Times of Dublin said the election ``was notable for
the basic agreement on foreign policy matters between the main
parties, which is nonetheless important for that. Dr. Kohl's main
legacy will probably be seen as having successfully anchored German
national interests in such a European framework, making this seem a
normal state of affairs at a time when events could readily have
forged a different outcome.''
	   The Daily Telegraph of London, which has opposed Kohl's drive
for European unification and a single currency, delivered a mixed
verdict.
	   ``His vision of Europe may have been fundamentally flawed,
undemocratic and dangerous... But of his vision of Germany, and his
triumphant enactment of it, history will surely be kind.''
	   (rb)
</TEXT>
