<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Election-Waigel </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Leader of Kohl's Bavarian ally party steps down
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MUNICH, Germany (AP) _ Chancellor Helmut Kohl's election defeat
claimed another victim Monday. The chairman of the conservative
Bavarian party that has been part of Kohl's coalition in Bonn
announced he would step down.
	   Theo Waigel, who also is the outgoing government's finance
minister, has headed the Bavaria-only Christian Social Union for 10
years.
	   He told a party meeting that he will not run for re-election as
party chairman at a January convention, said a party official,
Georg von Waldenfels.
	   Waigel, who was re-elected to parliament in Sunday's election,
told his party peers he wants to concentrate on helping the
conservative camp mount a strong opposition to the new Social
Democrat-led government.
	   Bavarian governor Edmund Stoiber, who led the party to a strong
victory in state elections two weeks ago, is considered Waigel's
likely successor.
	   Many thought the CSU victory would boost Kohl in the national
election, but instead the party recorded significant losses in
Bavaria, a traditional stronghold.
	   Kohl announced Sunday night he would not run again as party
chairman.
