<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Volcano </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Volcano erupts on Kamchatka Peninsula
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A volcano has erupted on Russia's Kamchatka
Peninsula, sending 100-meter (328-foot) columns of ash into the
sky, the ITAR-Tass news agency reported Monday.
	   At night, the 1,537-meter (5,043 mile) high Karymsky volcano
sends out a glow from top to bottom, ITAR-Tass said.
	   There are 29 active volcanoes on the Kamchatka Peninsula,
located eight time zones east of Moscow along the Pacific Rim's
``ring of fire.'' In the last decade, eight of those volcanoes have
erupted repeatedly, sometimes sending up ash and smoke 12
kilometers (7 miles) high.
	   A Russo-Japanese expedition will travel to a site 3 kilometers
(2 miles) from the Karymsky volcano on Thursday to carry out
seismic research, ITAR-Tass said.
	   (ji) 	   
</TEXT>
