w2683 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Germany-Election 3rdLd-Writethru   09-28 0823
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Election, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Germany's future chancellor Schroeder must now form government
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS lead to CLARIFY Schroeder had informal talks with
Greens; UPDATES with Waigel resigning as chief of Christian Social
Union. NOTE: Schroeder expected to announce preferred coalition
partner in 3 p.m. (1300 GMT) news conference. &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Germany-Goodbye Kohl &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By ANNE THOMPSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ Gerhard Schroeder, Germany's designated new
chancellor, approached the environmental Greens party Monday about
joining his Social Democrats in a coalition government after
ousting Chancellor Helmut Kohl in sweeping vote for change.
	   The Social Democratic victory marked the first time in postwar
Germany that voters rejected all parties from the previous
government in favor of fresh faces and new ideas.
	   In a stinging humiliation for the West's longest-serving leader,
Kohl and his Christian Democrats won just 35 percent of the vote,
which translates to a loss of 49 of the 294 seats it held in the
old parliament.
	   Now it is up to Schroeder -- whose Social Democrats won 41
percent of the vote -- to make good on pledges to end unemployment,
stuck above 10 percent, and to bring long-awaited tax and economic
reforms.
	   With the Greens, a Social Democratic-led government would
command a 21-seat majority in the new 669-seat parliament. ``I
think 21 seats is enough of a majority to form a stable
government,'' Schroeder told national ZDF television on Monday.
	   The Social Democrats held informal talks overnight with the
Greens, which won 6.7 percent, and were to begin what could be
tough negotiations between two parties with some sharp policy
differences.
	   Though eager for their first shot at entering government, the
Greens warned the Social Democrats not to try to shore up a new
government by bringing in other parties, for example, the liberal
Free Democrats that were Kohl's junior coalition partners. They won
6.2 percent.
	   ``Our signal is clear: according to us there can only be
negotiations with one party,'' said Heide Ruehle, a Greens' party
leader.
	   Already, Schroeder has ruled out including the ex-communist
Party of Democratic Socialism, which won enough votes to stay in
parliament. Many in the west view the party as a troubling remnant
of the former communist East German state.
	   A Social Democrat-Greens alliance would be postwar Germany's
most radical government as well as a test of the Greens' ability to
curb their sometimes eccentric ideals in cooperation with a more
mainstream party.
	   The Greens have proposed reforms that outrage some Germans and
amuse others: tripling gas prices to 5 marks (dlrs 3) per liter
over 10 years and introducing a 100-kilometer (60-mile) speed limit
on the autobahn.
	   These ideas, off-the-wall even for some Greens, were unlikely to
rock a future government, but the two parties might still have a
struggle agreeing on nuclear energy, immigration and defense
policy.
	   Schroeder will be the first of his generation, rooted in the
1960s leftist movement, to lead Europe's biggest nation.
	   Besides tackling nitty-gritty reforms, Schroeder, 54, will lead
Germany through two enormous changes next year: the return of the
government to Berlin, its prewar capital, and the exchange of the
trusted German mark for Europe's common currency, the euro.
	   His party's strong showing ruled out, at least for the moment,
sharing power with the Christian Democrats in a so-called ``grand
coalition.''
	   The Christian Democrats general secretary, Peter Hintze, said
voters put his party in opposition, and that it could play more
active role as a conservative counterweight to the Social Democrats
center-left leanings.
	   The Social Democrats and Greens have won ``their turn'' at
government, he said. ``We can only hope that a large part of what
they're planning to do will not be achieved. That would be a big
problem for Germany.''
	   Kohl, 68, had sought an unprecedented fifth term on the strength
of his image of stability and clout with world powers at a time of
economic turmoil in Russia and ongoing conflict in the Balkans.
	   But Germans voted for a fresh face of government, and Kohl
conceded the race by announcing he would step down as the leader of
the party he has ruled with an iron fist since 1973.
	   The Christian Democrats said they would elect a new leader in
early November. Hintze declined to speculate on a successor, but
Kohl has indicated a preference for his protege, Wolfgang
Schaeuble.
	   The party lost support in all of Germany's 16 states _ even
Bavaria, a conservative stronghold ruled by Kohl's allies, the
Christian Social Union.
	   Following Kohl's example, CSU party chief Theo Waigel said
Monday he would step down. Waigel, also Germany's outgoing finance
minister, has led the Christian Social Union for 10 years.
	   (aet/cb) 	   
</TEXT>
