<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Politics, 1st-Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Anwar's supporters continue protests on national holiday
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RANJAN ROY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with new protests; CHANGES byline.

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Undaunted by police batons, tear
gas and more than 150 arrests, several thousand supporters of
ousted Deputy Prime Minister Anwar Ibrahim continued protests
Monday, a national holiday, for the fourth straight day.
	   Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad's decision to fire and arrest
Anwar, his former heir apparent, has stirred anger on the streets
of downtown Kuala Lumpur, the capital.
	   Chanting ``Reformasi'' or ``Reforms,'' the demonstrators marched
from a courthouse, carrying banners that said, ``Free Anwar.''
	   Several truckloads of riot police arrived at the lush green park
where the marchers had gathered, to quell the demonstrations.
	   Witnesses saw several protesters being grabbed and pushed into
red police buses. There were no immediate reports of injuries.
Police also turned their wrath on reporters and cameramen, shouting
``Go, go, go!''
	   On Sunday, more than 10,000 supporters trudged for several
kilometers (miles) to attend a gathering organized by Malaysia's
opposition Islamic party. Police had blocked cars from entering a
village road leading to the rally.
	   Although authorities have banned all public meetings, police
allowed the meeting at the headquarters of the Parti Islam
Se-Malaysia, or PAS, on condition that it would end by midnight.
	   The rally was held just hours after the cancellation of a
planned launch of a coalition of opposition parties and
non-governmental groups promoting political reform.
	   The organizers of The Coalition for People's Democracy said the
launch had to be called off because the hotel where the event was
to be held was pressured by police not to allow its use.
	   Former deputy leader Anwar and 16 of his associates have been
held under a harsh security law that allows indefinite imprisonment
without trial. Neither Anwar, arrested last Sunday, nor any of his
detained allies have been formally arraigned in a court.
	   Anwar has been accused of crimes that include unlawful sex acts
and leaking state secrets. He has denied the charges, saying they
were politically motivated.
	   His Sept. 20 arrest has drawn strong support from Lim Kit Siang,
his one-time political foe and the opposition leader of Parliament,
who has called for the Parliament to investigate allegations of
corruption leveled against both Anwar and Mahathir.
	   ``What Malaysians want to know are all the full facts about
corruption, cronyism and nepotism _ regardless of whether they
affect Mahathir or Anwar,'' said Lim in a statement.
	   In a home videotape made on the night of his arrest, Anwar
accused his former boss of allowing his commercial interests and
those of his family and cronies to sway his judgment on public
spending and controls.
	   Mahathir, in turn, has said his designated heir didn't know how
to manage the economy.
	   On Saturday, police beat demonstrators and used a water cannon
to disperse a rally of more than 3,000 people. Twenty-nine
Malaysians were arrested for gathering illegally, police said.
	   Even small public gatherings and outdoor assemblies in Malaysia
require police permits.
</TEXT>
