<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Harford Quits </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ray Harford steps down as QPR manager
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Ray Harford resigned Monday as manager of Queens
Park Rangers after guding the struggling first division club to
just one win in nine games this season.
	   In a statement, the club said Harford felt it was in QPR's
``best interest'' to step down following Saturday's 4-1 defeat at
Oxford United.
	   Harford left West Bromwich Albion in the middle of last season
to join QPR, which lies second from bottom in the first division.
	   The club appointed player/coach Ian Dowie as caretaker manager.
He will be in charge for Tuesday's game at Wolverhampton and
Saturday's home match against Grimsby Town.
	   The QPR board will interview a short list of candidates over the
next two weeks and hopes to have a new manager installed in time
for the Oct. 17 game at Huddersfield Town.
	   The board said it considered appointing player/assistant manager
Vinnie Jones as Harford's replacement but decided to formulate a
short list of candidates instead. The statement said Jones, the
former Wimbledon star, would still be considered for the job.
	   (sw) 	   
</TEXT>
