r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Britain-Politics 1stLd-Writethru   09-28 0576
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Politics, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Britain's chancellor tells party he'll stick with strict policies
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS with Brown comments; trims, adds byline &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By MAUREEN JOHNSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BLACKPOOL, England (AP) _ With leftists flexing muscles at the
Labor Party's annual conference, Treasury chief Gordon Brown warned
Monday he will stick by strict economic policies that are angering
many trade unions.
	   Brown wants to keep Britain on track for his target of 2.5
percent inflation _ a goal that prompted him last year to take the
power to set interest rates away from politicians and give it to
the Bank of England.
	   The bank has tightened monetary policy, drawing fierce protests
from British manufacturers and workers who say the resulting high
value of the British pound makes it hard to sell their products
overseas at a time when inflation wasn't much of a threat anyway.
	   But Brown told the Labor delegates that any short-term pains
will be worth the long-term gains of stable growth with few
inflationary pressures.
	   ``It is because of our commitment to long-term stability, even
more essential at a time of world instability, that from this
government there will be no U-turns. No left turns. No right
turns,'' Brown told delegates.
	   ``No return to Tory boom and bust,'' Brown said. ``We have not
come this far as a party, we have not come this far as a country,
to turn back now.''
	   Brown added: ``I tell this conference there is no other way, no
solution, or even comfort, in soft options, no magic wand solution,
no quick-fix alternative to these long-term policies for achieving
the goals we share.''
	   Although applause during Brown's speech was subdued, most of the
delegates gave him a standing ovation at the end.
	   Sunday's opening of the conference brought Prime Minister Tony
Blair his first setback _ albeit largely symbolic in terms of power
_ from within the party since he ended a generation of Conservative
Party rule in May 1997 elections.
	   Leftists won four of the six seats on the party's governing
National Executive Committee that are chosen by the party
rank-and-file. Blair loyalists still command a lopsided majority on
the 32-member body.
	   But he warned the party against returning to the internal
wrangling that helped keep Labor long in opposition.
	   ``We have got to trust each other,'' Blair told the 1,400
delegates gathered in the Winter Gardens conference center in this
north England seaside resort.
	   ``But I make no apology for saying to you that at the same time
as we make our society fairer, we are a party, happy, proud to say
we are pro-enterprise and pro-business,'' he added.
	   Leftists, long sidelined by the centrist ``New Labor'' policies
of Blair, declared they had begun to reassert influence.
	   ``It shows the party members don't care about the smears,'' said
Liz Davies, a candidate elected to the executive committee from the
left-wing's ``Grassroots Alliance'' slate.
	   ``They care about the politics we stood for _ redistribution of
wealth and power from the rich to the poor, and democracy and
diversity in the Labor Party,'' added Ms. Davies.
	   Moderate trade union leaders _ whose organized labor is still a
prime funder of the party _ said they would press for a lowering in
interests rates, now at 7.5 percent. They also urge further boosts
in state spending.
	   (mj-db-rb)
</TEXT>
