<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Flood Heroes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chinese leaders extol flood-fighting to rally nation
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos BEJ103-104
 &UR; By CHARLES HUTZLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Combining genuine gratitude with pure politics,
Chinese leaders commended soldiers and officials Monday for
combating summer floods and tried to use their heroics to rally the
nation behind the communist government.
	   In 95 minutes of speechmaking broadcast live nationwide from the
Great Hall of the People, an array of national, provincial and
military figures touted the ``victory'' over the flooding as proof
of the Communist Party's right to rule.
	   Such propaganda displays underscore the leadership's growing
worries about public anger over corruption and the slowing economy.
	   While floods raged this summer, the People's Liberation Army _
the ultimate defender of party rule _ was accused of rampant
smuggling and a former party power-broker was tried in a graft case
that symbolized corruption's spread.
	   Chinese President and Communist Party chief Jiang Zemin, in a
45-minute speech, acknowledged people's doubts about the party and
military but said, ``The great victory in the fight against the
floods is another most telling answer to their question.''
	   ``The extremely hard and bitter struggle against the floods, the
severe test of life and death, and the experience of braving wind
and storm together have strengthened the flesh-and-blood ties
between the party and the masses and the fish-and-water
relationship between the army and the people,'' Jiang said.
	   With party elders and Politburo members seated behind him, Jiang
spoke to a mostly military crowd of 10,000 inside the Great Hall's
main auditorium. Soldiers roared chants that echoed off the
ceiling's electrically lit red star and lent the event a martial
air.
	   Aside from the moment of silence Jiang called to remember the
dead, the meeting glossed over the disaster's human toll. More than
3,000 people were killed and millions made homeless in the worst
flooding in decades.
	   Likewise, Jiang never mentioned the decades of rapacious logging
and only briefly noted other environmentally disastrous policies
that exacerbated the flooding.
	   Instead heroism took center stage. Applause filled the hall when
about 100 soldiers and officials marched in wearing red sashes _
signs of their status as national heroes in the flood-fighting.
	   ``The victory shows that our socialist system has tremendous
advantages,'' Jiang said.
	   Jiang's speech displayed all the flair of the centrist tactics
he has used to stay atop the party hierarchy. He praised ordinary
people who sacrificed family interests for the nation and thanked
the tightly controlled state media for popularizing ``the heroic
deeds.''
	   His most lavish praise went to the army, saying the military
proved it ``deserves the complete trust of the party and the
people.''
	   Jiang cast the flood-fighting as the latest in a series of
victories: the revolution a half-century ago and against Western
bullying after the military quelled democracy demonstrations in
Tiananmen Square in 1989.
	   ``We have a bright future, but the road ahead will not be
smooth,'' Jiang said.
</TEXT>
