<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-PAL, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippine Airlines union, management reach agreement on rescue
</HEADLINE>
plan
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES and RECASTS throughout with additional quotes, union
to seek workers' approval through signatures; other details
 &UR; AP Photos Available
 &UR; By JIM GOMEZ &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ Philippine Airlines may reopen next
week after a decision by its largest union Monday to accept a key
element of a management-proposed recovery plan, President Joseph
Estrada said.
	   ``Everybody's happy, not only me but the whole country,''
Estrada said. ``Finally there is an agreement.''
	   Asia's oldest airline, which owes creditors dlrs 2.1 billion,
closed last Wednesday after failing to convince its ground crew
union to accept the rescue plan. Its closure left much of the
Philippines without air service.
	   After Monday's agreement, PAL chairman Lucio Tan and union
president Alex Barrientos beamed and shook hands. A pleased Estrada
stood behind them.
	   ``I'm very sure that labor and management can achieve very
harmonious cooperation,'' Tan said.
	   Barrientos called the agreement PAL's ``last, last, last
possible hope.''
	   ``If this fails, it's closed,'' he said.
	   The breakthrough came when union leaders agreed to accept a
10-year suspension of their collective bargaining agreement in
exchange for continued management recognition of the union and a
guarantee of no cuts in salaries or health benefits.
	   The union has been split over the proposal, with its radical
wing saying the 10-year suspension would violate workers' rights
and destroy the union.
	   Hundreds of workers protested the agreement at the union's
office and at the Senate Monday, calling instead for the government
to take over the airline.
	   Estrada said PAL may reopen by next week even though the
agreement must still be formally approved by workers, regulators
and PAL's creditors.
	   The union will hold a simple signature campaign in which workers
will be asked to sign their names if they support the plan,
Barrientos said.
	   The recovery plan would give workers 20 percent of the company's
stock in exchange for the 10-year suspension of their collective
bargaining agreement.
	   PAL has been ravaged by strikes and Asia's currency crisis. It
says creditors have insisted on the suspension before they will
accept a restructuring of the company's finances.
	   Earlier Monday, Estrada flew to the central Philippines aboard
the inaugural domestic flight by Hong Kong's Cathay Pacific
Airways, which he enlisted to help fill the vacuum left by PAL's
closure.
	   Initially, two Cathay Pacific planes and crews will be leased to
PNB Holdings, a subsidiary of Philippine National Bank, which is 47
percent owned by the government.
	   The flights will nominally be operated by PNB Holdings since
Philippine law prohibits foreign carriers from servicing domestic
routes.
	   Estrada says the government is unable to take over PAL because
there is no money in public coffers to underwrite daily losses of
up to 45 million pesos (dlrs 1 million) incurred by the airline.
	   Asia's currency crisis hit shortly after PAL launched a dlrs 4
billion modernization and refleeting program, greatly inflating the
amounts of money it must repay to overseas creditors.
	   The Philippine flag carrier also was badly crippled by a 22-day
pilots' strike in June.
</TEXT>
