<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sudan-Hospital Bombed </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sudanese planes reportedly bomb hospital in southern Sudan
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By CHEGE MBITIRU
 &UR; Associated Press Writer

<TEXT>
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ Sudanese air force planes have dropped
cluster bombs on a hospital in a rebel-controlled town controlled
in southern Sudan, a humanitarian organization said Monday.
	   A patient was seriously wounded and a ward was damaged in the
bombing of the hospital in Yei, about 120 kilometers (74 miles)
southwest of Juba, said Dan Effie of Norwegian People's Aid, which
runs the hospital.
	   The hospital has been bombed four times since April 1997, Effie
said.
	   There was no independent confirmation of the bombing, but NPA
has in the past provided reliable reports.
	   Juba, a provincial capital about 1,200 kilometers (744
milesJuba) south of the Sudanese capital, Khartoum, is the largest
town in southern Sudan still under government control.
	   The Sudan People's Liberation Army has been fighting since 1983
for autonomy from the Muslim and Arab-dominated north for southern
Sudan where Christians and followers of tradtional religion form
the majority. The rebels have never been able to capture Juba, a
strategic goal in their campaign.
	   Government forces and rebels are fighting 72 kilometers (45
miles) east of Juba. The bombing came a day after Sudanese
President Omar el-Bashir paid a surprise visit Saturday to the
provincial capital.
	   El-Bashir warned of ``a final battle'' to keep Juba in
government hands.
	   He said Ugandan troops were fighting alongside the SPLA rebels
and ``have brought the best they have to this battlefield. They
wanted it to be final, and they will have it.''
	   Uganda denies it has troops in southern Sudan, but few believe
the denial.
	   SPLA Nairobi spokesman Justin Arop Yaac denied Monday the SPLA
had launched an offensive, saying recent government bombings of two
smaller rebel-held towns provoked the current fighting.
	   ``They are bombing targets where there are no troops,'' Arop
said. ``It is just wanton destruction of civilian facilities, and
we will not allow it.''
	   He accused the government of escalating the war by reinforcing
Juba.
	   On Saturday, Sudanese education minister Ibrahim Ahmed Omar
suspended classes at Sudanese universities for one month to enable
the students to take part in the fighting. An exception was made
for all-women universities.
	   Early last year, the SPLA launched a major offensive and have
captured most of the territory in southern Sudan in a region the
size of France.
	   Another round of peace talks between the government and rebels,
mediated by the regional Intergovernmental Authority on
Development, is scheduled to begin in Nairobi Oct. 5.
	   Previous rounds have resulted in deadlock.
	    &UR; (CM-sl)	   
</TEXT>
