<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Germany-Roster </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A Turkish native gets picked in Germany's roster for Turkey game
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NESHA STARCEVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   FRANKFURT, Germany (AP) _ Mustafa Dogan, a Turkish native with
German citizenship, was named Monday in a 26-man roster for
Germany's upcoming Euro 2000 qualifying match against Turkey.
	   Dogan, a 22-year-old defender, has never played for Germany
although he was on the roster of the German team earlier this month
for the ill-fated trip to Malta.
	   The trip's two games _ a slim 2-1 victory over lowly Malta and a
1-1 draw with Romania _ doomed coach Berti Vogts, who stepped down
under growing public pressure.
	   His successor Erich Ribbeck took over the job of rebuilding a
team badly shaken by its quarterfinal ouster at the World Cup.
	   But the new team looks very much like the old one, with 16
players who had already played under Vogts.
	   Germany is the defending European champion and Ribbeck's first
games as coach will be against Turkey Oct. 10 and Moldova Oct. 14,
both away from home.
	   The Germans regard the game in Turkey as the most important in
their Euro 2000 campaign.
	   Ribbeck's roster, which will be reduced to 20 or 21 men shortly
before the trip, included eight players from Bayern Munich, the
Bundesliga leader which has notched six victories in six league
games this season.
	   They include Lothar Matthaeus, the 37-year-old veteran who
retired after the World Cup only to be summoned again by Ribbeck.
	   The roster included five players with no national team
experience: Dogan, reserve goalkeeper Stefan Klos of Borussia
Dortmund, defender Yves Eigenrauch of Schalke, midfielder Carsten
Ramelow of Bayer Leverkusen and striker Carsten Jancker of Bayern
Munich.
	   Dogan has played in the Bundesliga but is now with Fenerbahce
Istanbul.
	   The squad includes another foreign-born player, Hansa Rostock
forward Oliver Neuville, a former Swiss.
	   Two players return after long absences, midfielders Dariusz Wosz
of Hertha Berlin and Ralf Weber of Eintracht Frankfurt.
	   The two Borussia Dortmund midfielders and national team
veterans, Andreas Moeller and Thomas Haessler, are missing,
however. Moeller retired after the World Cup, only to announce last
week that he was ready to return.
	   But after a conversation between Ribbeck and Moeller, the two
agreed to leave Moeller's comeback for another date. Haessler's
future is uncertain and he is struggling in Dortmund, often being
left on the bench.
	   The roster:
	   Goalkeepers: Oliver Kahn (Bayern Munich), Stefan Klos (Borussia
Dortmund), Jens Lehmann (AC Milan).
	   Defenders: Markus Babbel (Bayern Munich), Mustafa Dogan
(Fenerbahce Istanbul), Yves Eigenrauch (Schalke), Lothar Matthaeus
(Bayern Munich), Jens Nowotny (Bayer Leverkusen), Marko Rehmer
(Hansa Rostock)
	   Midfielders: Mario Basler (Bayern Munich), Stefan Beinlich
(Bayer Leverkusen), Marco Bode (Werder Bremen), Joerg Heinrich
(Fiorentina), Jens Jeremies (Bayern Munich), Christian Nerlinger
(Borussia Dortmund), Carsten Ramelow (Bayer Leverkusen), Lars
Ricken (Borussia Dortmund), Thomas Strunz (Bayern Munich), Michael
Tarnat (Bayern Munich), Ralf Weber (Eintracht Frankfurt), Dariusz
Wosz (Hertha Berlin)
	   Forwards: Oliver Bierhoff (AC Milan), Carsten Jancker (Bayern
Munich), Ulf Kirsten (Bayer Leverkusen), Olaf Marschall (FC
Kaiserslautern), Oliver Neuville (Hansa Rostock).
	   (ns)	   
</TEXT>
