<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-Water Conference </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. conference on water resources opens
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ The Middle East must increase efforts to
improve the management of declining water resources, a U.N.
conference was told Monday.
	   The five-day conference is being held at the Economic and Social
Commission for Western Asia, a regional U.N. agency based in
Beirut.
	   ``We are pressed to double our efforts toward enhancing the
management of water resources ... to rise to the challenges facing
most of the developing countries,'' said ESCWA's executive
secretary Hazem el-Beblawi in his opening statement.
	   He said this was particularly true for the Middle East, which is
burdened with arid and semi-arid zones.
	   El-Beblawi described water as a ``strategic element in forging
the political environment of the future.''
	   In the Middle East, water figures in disputes _ and peace
negotiations _ between countries.
	   Water rights have been a source of tension between Turkey and
neighboring Syria. Damascus has accused Turkey of taking more than
its fair share of water from the Euphrates River through a series
of new dams.
	   Lebanon has accused Israel of trying to divert rivers in a zone
it occupies in southern Lebanon.
	   In the 1994 peace treaty between Jordan and Israel, Israel
promised Jordan additional water.
	   States and territories under ESCWA's jurisdiction are Bahrain,
Egypt, Iraq, Jordan, Kuwait, Lebanon, Oman, the Palestinian
territories, Qatar, Saudi Arabia, Syria, the United Arab Emirates
and Yemen.
 &UR; sfg-eap
