<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy-Box </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Changes in Russia's evolving Cabinet
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With BC-Russia-Economy &QL; 
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   Changes announced Monday in Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov's
evolving Cabinet:
	   OUT:
	   Boris Fyodorov, acting deputy prime minister and tax chief,
strongly supported market-oriented reforms and opposed printing
money. He was point man on the government's recent get-tough
campaign against tax evaders.
	   Fyodorov wasn't popular among the country's big industries _
most of which are chronic tax delinquents _ or among those who
feared he'd make good on his repeated pledges to seize assets from
companies that didn't pay their taxes.
	   Viktor Khristenko, acting deputy prime minister in charge of
state finances and macroeconomics, was a proponent of cutting
government spending to ease the financial crisis. Before his
appointment, he had worked in the Finance Ministry, as well as in
Russia's Chelyabinsk region, where he tried to tighten control over
local spending and cut waste.
	   IN:
	   Farit Gazizullin, newly reappointed state property minister, has
long worked in the area of privatizing Russia's state-owned
enterprises. Before his entry into national politics in 1996,
Gazizullin was deputy head of the semi-autonomous Tatarstan
republic and chairman of the republic's privatization committee.
	   (nw/ji/gm) 	   
