w2751 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Philippines-WorldExpo     09-28 0342
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Philippines-World Expo </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Estrada may reconsider withdrawal of Philippines as World Expo 2002
</HEADLINE>
host

<TEXT>
	   MANILA, Philippines (AP) _ President Joseph Estrada said Monday
he would reconsider a decision to withdraw the Philippines as host
of World Expo 2002, if private firms shoulder all the costs.
	   Estrada said he doubts if the government could recover even half
of the 6 billion pesos (dlrs 135 million) needed to host the event,
adding it would be better if the money goes to projects that would
ease poverty.
	   ``I am agreeable provided they spend for everything. The
government will not spend a single cent,'' Estrada told reporters.
	   Estrada said Friday he has decided to withdraw the Philippines
as host of the exposition due to the country's economic
difficulties.
	   Former Tourism Secretary Mina Gabor said withdrawing as host
could damage the image of the Philippines to the international
community and potential investors. Gabor lobbied for the
Philippines to win in June over Australia to host the exposition.
	   Gabor said she and private corporate backers would brief Estrada
soon on the benefits of the project in an effort to convince him to
reverse his decision.
	   She said at least 3.7 million tourists would be expected to
attend the exposition. About 60 countries were expected to
participate.
	   Former President Fidel Ramos also urged Estrada to reconsider
and offered to help raise funds, officials said.
	   Estrada was concerned that the private sector may be unable to
cover half the costs as it reportedly promised because of the
economic downturn.
	   He said he preferred if the money would be used for agriculture,
like building roads and irrigation needed by poor farmers.
	   He said the event may result in what he saw as useless edifices
like costly structures that were put up at a special economic zone
north of Manila for a trade exposition last June.
	   ``It's there lying like a white elephant. I don't like to
experience the same thing. We must learn from that mistake,''
Estrada said. 	   
</TEXT>
