<HEADLINE>
REPEATING TO CORRECT LEAD SEQUENCE
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Serb premier says Albanian `terrorism' has been defeated
 &UR; Eds: LEADS to UPDATE with KLA statement; no visible withdrawal of
special police
 &UR; By JOVANA GEC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Seeking to head off a NATO attack,
Serbia's premier declared an end Monday to ``anti-terrorist
activities'' in Kosovo but warned they will resume if there are new
attacks by Albanian separatists.
	   Premier Mirko Marjanovic told the Serbian parliament that
special police units will return to barracks _ a condition demanded
by both American and European diplomats to avoid a NATO attack. By
early afternoon Monday, however, there was no visible withdrawal of
the units.
	   ``With this day, anti-terrorist activities have finished and can
be renewed only if some new terrorist bandit-terrorist activity
appears again,'' Marjanovic said. ``I wish to declare that with
this day ... the armed terrorist groups have been defeated.''
	   But the separatist Kosovo Liberation Army issued a statement
Monday, pledging to continue ``the holy war'' against Serbia and
demanding an urgent NATO action in Kosovo. The statement also
criticized pacifist Kosovo Albanian leaders ``whose actions are
hindering this holy war.''
	   Marjanovic said the government will grant amnesty to Kosovo
Albanians who surrender weapons within the next 10 days as long as
they have not committed ``war crimes,'' which was another demand to
Serbia by world officials.
	   Marjanovic also said the government would appoint a Temporary
Executive Council _ previously unknown body _ to ``strengthen
civilian structures'' in the province, where Albanians form 90
percent of the estimated 2 million population.
