<SLUG> BC-Germany-Election-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German markets slightly up after Social Democratic victory
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ The Frankfurt stock exchange was trading
higher Monday contrary to expectations that a Social Democratic
victory in Germany's national elections would drive the market
down,
	   The Xetra DAX electronic index was up 53.13 points at midday, or
1.2 percent.
	   However, analysts said the market was reacting primarily to an
agreement on banking reform in Japan, and not to the German
elections.
	   They had predicted that news of a Social Democratic victory,
bringing the likelihood of a government coalition with the liberal
Greens party, would hurt the markets, as well as the German mark
and German bonds.
	   ``The Greens will be particularly worrisome,'' said Karl-Rudolf
Korte, head of a University of Munich political research group.
``For the markets and foreign companies a period of observation
will start now. They will wait to see what kind of policies the new
government will introduce.''
	   (cb-pfg) 	   
