w2762 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Lesotho     09-28 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lesotho </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Public offices reopen, many Lesotho troops turn themselves in
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo MAS101 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MASERU, Lesotho (AP) _ Thousands of public employees returned to
work Monday as government offices opened for the first time since
last week's South Africa-led intervention to forestall a coup.
	   Meanwhile, about 1,000 members of the Lesotho Defense Force
turned themselves in, as ordered, for review of their roles in
events of recent weeks. Rebels face possible punishment. Others
would be reinstated in the 2,000-member force.
	   Those who did not surrender by the end of the day would be
presumed to be rebels, officials said, and tracked down by the
South Africa and Botswana force of somewhat more than 1,000 troops.
	   ``Under the circumstances, I am very pleased,'' government
secretary Ken Tsekoa said.
	   The capital city of 50,000 was mostly calm for a third day, but
_ because of the widespread devastation caused by arson and looting
_ it won't be ``normal'' for a long time. Possibly years.
	   Hundreds of businesses were burnt down or pillaged. Several
thousand jobs disappeared in a country of 2 million that is one of
the poorest in the world. About eight of every 10 job-holders is a
public employee.
	   The security situation was largely under control, despite
incidents of sniping. Nevertheless, businessmen are uneasy about
reopening undamaged stores. Aid groups haven't restored food
distribution to rural, subsistence farming communities where most
of the people live.
	   The intervention, and political and military unrest in general
in this mountain kingdom that is surrounded by South Africa,
remained a priority for governments in the region.
	   The defense ministers of South Africa, Botswana and Zimbabwe
were scheduled to meet Monday in Maseru. King Letsie III was
scheduled to travel Tuesday to Cape Town for talks with South
Africa President Nelson Mandela.
	   Political instability in Lesotho underlies almost all the other
problems, analysts said.
	   Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili, whose Lesotho Congress Party
won 79 of the 80 seats in parliament in elections last May, is
bitterly opposed by parties that garnered 39 percent of the vote _
but just a single seat.
	   They claim, without providing convincing evidence, that the vote
was rigged. The government and international observers say there
was little or no fraud. Balloting was via the first-past-the-post
system rather than proportional representation.
	   The two sides refuse to meet. Mosisili, whose Cabinet ministers
went into hiding following a Lesotho Defense Force insurrection
earlier this month that attempted to topple the high command,
claims the opposition intended to assassinate him.
	   (ewm)
</TEXT>
