<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-EBRD </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EBRD to continue lending to Ukraine despite its financial crisis
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ The European Bank for Reconstruction and
Development is determined to continue long-term cooperation with
Ukraine despite the country's shaky financial situation, a senior
bank official said Monday.
	   The EBRD will focus in particular on support for Ukraine's small
and medium businesses and the energy sector, and assistance in
privatization of the country's telecommunications and energy
companies, EBRD Vice President Charles Frank said.
	   Frank said that the situation in Ukraine was ``significantly''
different from that in Russia. Ukraine, unlike Russia, did not
default on its debt payments and has managed to restructure them on
a voluntary basis. Also, Ukraine did not permit an insolvency
crisis in the banking sector, Frank added.
	   Ukraine was badly hit by Russia's turmoil, which caused the
national currency to slide and sparked inflation. However, the
government so far has kept the situation in the financial market
under control and has prevented significant price rises.
	   The EBRD has recently expressed interest in financing the run-up
to privatizing Ukraine's telecommunications monopoly. The bank is
also considering participating in completion of a Black Sea oil
terminal and a pipeline in Ukraine, which could be used to
transport Caspian Sea oil to western Europe.
	   Frank said Ukraine could count on receiving up to dlrs 1 billion
from the EBRD for various projects currently under consideration.
	   Since Ukraine joined the EBRD in 1992, the bank has approved 27
projects for the country, which collectively amount to 660 million
ecus (dlrs 725 million).
	   (vl/ji) 	   
</TEXT>
