<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Di Canio-Referee </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FA to announce disciplinary sanction against Italian striker
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Already suspended by his club and now facing a
long ban by the Football Association, Italian striker Paolo Di
Canio has accused the referee he shoved to the ground of
play-acting.
	   An FA disciplinary panel was expected to announce sanctions
Monday against Di Canio, the Sheffield Wednesday player who pushed
referee Paul Alcock after being sent off during Saturday's 1-0 win
against Arsenal at Hillsborough.
	   Danny Wilson, Sheffield Wednesday's manager, announced an
immediate suspension of Di Canio pending sanctions from the FA.
	   The FA announced a charge of gross misconduct, which could
result in a six-month ban or even in an expulsion from the Premier
League.
	   While Di Canio's act was roundly criticized, the player took the
unusual step of accusing the referee of taking a dive.
	   ``I pushed (the ref) in the stomach,'' said Di Canio, who flew
to Italy on Sunday. ``He took 3-4 steps sideways and fell like a
player'' who dives for a penalty. ``This does not diminish the
gravity of my act, but when the sentence arrives I will raise, with
the best lawyers, the mitigating circumstances in my appeal.''
	   Di Canio claimed the ref would have received a yellow card if he
had been a player because ``it looked like soneone who was
acting.''
	   David Elleray, spokesman for English referees, described Di
Canio's claims as ``extraordinary.''
	   ``I can not imagine any referee doing anything like that,''
Elleray said. ``It is is quite clear that the one thing Paul was
trying not to do was fall down because he wanted to preserve his
dignity. He has no reason to go down because it is a very
undignified thing to happen.''
	   Alcock was pushed to the ground by the 30-year-old Italian after
he was shown a red card for his part in a brawl in the final
minutes of the first half.
	   Arsenal's Martin Keown was also sent off as a melee among a
dozen players broke out following a tussle between Arsenal's
Patrick Vieira and Wim Jonk.
	   ``I made a mistake, but the responsibility also belongs to
others,'' Di Canio said. ``Everything started when Vieira brought
Jonk down. I ran towards Vieira, with whom I played at Milan, to
say to him, `Why the heck did you do that?' Keown was nearby and he
stopped me with a very painful elbow to the nose. I kicked him and
we came to blows. The referee, instead of calling both of us,
showed me a red card. An atrocious injustice.''
	   Di Canio, a former Lazio, Milan and Juventus forward,
transferred last year from Celtic to Sheffield Wednesday. His
13-year career has been marked by disciplinary problems and
controversy.
	   (sw)	   
</TEXT>
