<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinians, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hebron settlers attack Palestinians after shots are fired
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with information about shooting victim, settler
rampage in Palestinian market, Palestinians confirming White House
summit, restores quotes from Israeli negotiator &QL; 
 &UR; By LAURIE COPANS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HEBRON, West Bank (AP) _ Assailants firing shots from the
Palestinian sector of Hebron wounded an Israeli woman Monday, and
in retaliation Jewish settlers beat Palestinian passers-by and
overturned tables in an outdoor Arab market.
	   Several settler women, including Miriam Levinger, one of the
founders of the Jewish enclave in Hebron, sat down on the ground in
the market, refusing to be moved.
	   The violence came as the Israeli and Palestinian leaders were en
route to Washington for a three-way summit with U.S. President Bill
Clinton at the White House later in the day.
	   Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat said Palestinian leader
Yasser Arafat agreed to meet with Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu at the White House even though no progress had been made
toward agreement on a West Bank troop withdrawal.
	   Late Sunday, Arafat and Netanyahu had met for the first time in
nearly a year at the insistence of Clinton, with U.S. Secretary of
State Madeleine Albright hosting the talks in New York.
	   Monday's incident in Hebron, a divided city of 130,000
Palestinians and 450 Jewish settlers, began at about 11:30 a.m.
(0930 gmt) when members of an Israeli family _ in Hebron to
celebrate a bar mitzvah _ walked on the road between two Jewish
enclaves, Beit Hadassah and Tel Romeida. The army said four shots
were fired at the group, and that one bullet hit a 52-year-old
woman in the leg.
	   Israel radio said the woman was from Herzliya, north of Tel
Aviv, but her name was not given. The woman taken to a hospital in
Jerusalem.
	   In response, settlers beat several Palestinians passing by Beit
Hadassah, and witnesses said one Palestinian woman was injured. An
Israeli woman was detained in the confrontations.
	   A group of about 15 settler women and teen-age girls entered the
Palestinian open-air market and overturned several vegetable
stands, throwing cucumbers and tomatoes to the ground. Israeli
security forces initially did not interfere, but then began
ordering the women to leave.
	   Mrs. Levinger and two other settler women sat down on the
ground, refusing to be moved. They held on to each other as police
tried to drag them away. After one woman fainted and was taken away
by ambulance, Mrs. Levinger stood up.
	   Tensions between Jewish settlers and Palestinians in Hebron rose
considerably last month after a settler rabbi was stabbed to death
in his home in Tel Romeida, a cluster of several trailers in the
heart of a Palestinian neighborhood. The assailant, presumably a
Palestinian militant, was never caught.
	   Despite the preparations for a White House summit on Monday,
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators said they didn't see much of a
chance for a breakthrough.
	   Erekat, the Palestinian negotiator, said that while Netanyahu
and Arafat discussed the scope of an Israeli pullback on Sunday,
they did not discuss any of the other issues, such as the opening
of a Palestinian airport, an additional Israeli withdrawal and a
Palestinian crackdown on Islamic militants.
	   ``Until now, there isn't any real progress,'' Erekat said.
	   A similar assessment came from Danny Naveh, the Israeli Cabinet
secretary. Speaking after the Netanyahu-Arafat meeting in New York,
Naveh told Israel radio that the obstacle remains Palestinian
refusal to carry out its commitments, especially stopping
extremists from attacking Israel.
	   ``We are not in the position of being able to say that an
agreement has been reached in these areas,'' he said.
