w2784 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Poland-Church-Auschwi     09-28 0328
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Poland-Church-Auschwitz </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Parish priest resigns after putting up cross at Auschwitz
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ANDRZEJ STYLINSKI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WARSAW, Poland (AP) _ A parish priest in northern Poland has
resigned after putting up a cross next to the former Nazi death
camp Auschwitz, defying calls by church leaders for conservative
Catholics to stop the action.
	   Church officials indicated Monday that the decision by the Rev.
Ryszard Krol, from the village parish of Kepice, some 400
kilometers northwest of Warsaw, resulted primarily from his
deteriorating health condition.
	   The cross, which Krol's parishioners put up near Auschwitz, was
not a reason behind his resignation, or perhaps just one of
additional ``small drops,'' according to diocese chancellor, the
Rev. Leszek Wodz.
	   He would not elaborate on Krol's health, but said the priest
showed signs of ``depression'' for some time.
	   On Sept. 14, Krol's cross joined some 200 others planted by
conservative Catholics in support of an eight-meter (26-foot)
wooden cross erected in 1988 by Carmelite nuns on the site where
152 Poles were killed by the Nazis in 1941.
	   The crosses appeared after Jewish groups complained that the big
cross, used in a 1979 Mass celebrated by Polish-born Pope John Paul
II at the camp, disturbs the memory of the more than 1 million Jews
killed at Auschwitz and wanted it removed.
	   Polish bishops and Prime Minister Jerzy Buzek's government
called in late August for conservative Catholics to stop putting up
crosses.
	   Krol, in a letter to his superiors, explained he was ``led by
emotions'' and had ``no intention to do anything against the
bishops,'' Wodz said. He said the cross has been brought back from
Auschwitz.
	   Bishop Marian Golebiowski, of the Koszalin diocese, received a
request of a leave from Krol on Sept. 18, Wodz said.
	   Krol has left his parish and formally is on an unlimited leave
as of Oct. 1.
	    &UR; (ajs-gb)
</TEXT>
