<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 4th Ld-Writethru,0668 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Serb premier says Albanian `terrorism' has been defeated
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with new quotes, description from Kosovo;
DELETES outdated material; EDITS to conform and trim. &QL; 
 &UR; By JOVANA GEC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Seeking to head off a NATO attack,
Serbia's premier declared an end Monday to ``anti-terrorist
activities'' in Kosovo but warned they will resume if there are new
attacks by Albanian separatists.
	   Premier Mirko Marjanovic told the Serbian parliament that
special police units will return to their barracks _ a condition
demanded by both American and European diplomats to avoid a NATO
attack. By early afternoon Monday, however, there was no visible
withdrawal of the units.
	   ``With this day, anti-terrorist activities have finished and can
be renewed only if some new terrorist bandit-terrorist activity
appears again,'' Marjanovic said. ``I wish to declare that with
this day ... the armed terrorist groups have been defeated.''
	   But the separatist Kosovo Liberation Army issued a statement
Monday, pledging to continue ``the holy war'' against Serbia and
demanding an urgent NATO action in Kosovo. The statement also
criticized pacifist Kosovo Albanian leaders ``whose actions are
hindering this holy war.''
	   Marjanovic said Serb and Yugoslav forces would remain in their
barracks for an unspecified period to guard against any resumption
of attacks by the secessionist Kosovo Liberation Army, which has
been largely routed.
	   Marjanovic also said that the government will grant amnesty to
Kosovo Albanians who surrender weapons within the next 10 days as
long as they have not committed ``war crimes.''
	   He added that the government would appoint a Temporary Executive
Council _ previously unknown body _ to ``strengthen civilian
structures'' in the province, where Albanians form 90 percent of
the estimated 2 million population.
	   Hundreds of people in the southern province of Kosovo have been
killed and some 275,000 forced to flee their homes since
Milosevic's crackdown on ethnic Albanians began seven months ago.
Kosovo is part of Serbia, the dominant republic in Yugoslavia. Most
of Kosovo's majority ethnic Albanians want independence.
	   Marjanovic made his remarks as he introduced a resolution
declaring that stamping out ethnic Albanian resistance in Kosovo is
the nation's top priority.
	   He said the move was in accordance with an agreement Yugoslav
President Slobodan Milosevic signed in June with Russian President
Boris Yeltsin.
	   The U.N. Security Council has been insisting since March that
Serbs withdraw special police units and other forces from the
province and begin talks with ethnic Albanians on the future of the
majority Albanian province.
	   On Wednesday, the council threatened additional action if
Milosevic did not stop the offensive against militant separatists
in Kosovo and allow for the safe return of refugees.
	   NATO defense chiefs then stepped up plans for airstrikes if
Milosevic failed to comply.
	   Paddy Ashdown, leader of Britain's Liberal Democrat party who is
touring Kosovo, told reporters in Suva Reka that he had seen little
active fighting. ``We saw refugees being bumped around from one
place to another,'' he said, indicating Serbs were trying to
prevent large gatherings of refugees which draw international
attention.
	   During the parliamentary session, Gorica Gajevic, the general
secretary of Milosevic's Socialist Party, called on Kosovo
Albanians to open talks with the government. She denied the
government used excessive force in its clampdown.
	   ``It used as much force as was needed to stifle the evil of
terrorism, in the way other world democratic countries do when
faced with terrorism,'' she said.
	   Another member of Milosevic's party, Dusan Matkovic, said that
if the world wants to help Kosovo, it should invest ``several
hundred million dollars'' in Kosovo's mines and economy.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 4th Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
