w2797 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Baseball-Seaso     09-28 0817
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-Season Highs,0829 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Williams and Walker win first batting titles, Vaughn hits 50th
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By RONALD BLUM &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Bernie Williams, Larry Walker and Greg Vaughn
also managed breakthroughs in a North American baseball season
dominated by Mark McGwire.
	   Williams won his first American League batting title Sunday,
going 2-for-2 in another historic Yankees win. He finished at .339,
two points higher than Boston's Mo Vaughn but the lowest average
for an AL champion since George Brett hit .329 in 1990.
	   ``It feels great, absolutely, when you add your name to a list
of players that have accomplished this feat,'' Williams said.
``Coming into this season, I would have never imagined it with all
the distractions, trying to get my game going, missing six weeks
with an injury. It's just very satisfying.''
	   Walker also won his first batting crown, going 2-for-4 for
Colorado to wind up at .363, nine points ahead of the Mets' John
Olerud.
	   ``I've got the same feeling as I did last year when I won the
MVP,'' said Walker, who stopped Tony Gwynn's streak of four
straight National League titles. ``But I'm not greedy on all this
individual stuff. The bottom line for me is to win a
championship.''
	   McGwire, whose 70 homers shattered Roger Maris' mark of 61, and
Sammy Sosa, who had 66 going into his final regular-season game
Monday, also set other records.
	   Sosa, who will lead the major leagues in RBIs, has 158 for the
Cubs, the highest NL total since the Cubs' Hack Wilson set the
major league record with 190 in 1930. Sosa's 414 total bases are
the most in the majors since Stan Musial had 429 in 1948.
	   McGwire walked 162 times for the Cardinals, tying Ted Williams
(1947, 1949) for the second highest total in major league history
behind Babe Ruth's 170 in 1923. McGwire's .752 slugging percentage
was the highest in the majors since Ruth (.772) in 1927 and the
highest in the NL since Rogers Hornsby (.756) in 1925.
	   Juan Gonzalez of the Rangers had 157 RBIs, the most in the AL
since teammates Ted Williams and Vern Stephens had 159 in 1949.
	   When Greg Vaughn hit his 50th homer for San Diego at Arizona on
Sunday, he made it four 50-homer players in a single season _
double the previous high.
	   McGwire won his first NL home run title after leading AL twice
and topping the majors with 58 last season for Oakland and St.
Louis.
	   Ken Griffey Jr. won his third AL home run title, leading with 56
for the second straight season.
	   With 114 wins, the Yankees set an AL record and finished with
the second most ever, trailing only the 1906 Cubs, who went 116-36.
New York (114-48) had a .704 winning percentage, the highest in the
majors since the 1954 Cleveland Indians went 111-43 (.721).
	   Randy Johnson led the majors in strikeouts for the fifth time,
fanning 329, but didn't win the title in either league. Johnson
fanned 213 for Seattle, then got 116 more for Houston as he went
10-1 after the July 31 trade.
	   Philadelphia's Curt Shilling led the NL with 300 strikeouts, 19
fewer than last year. He became the fifth pitcher to reach 300 in
consecutive seasons, joining J.R. Richard (1978-79), Nolan Ryan
(1972-74, 1976-77), Sandy Koufax (1965-66) and Rube Waddell
(1903-04).
	   Toronto's Roger Clemens fanned 271 to win his fifth AL strikeout
title. Clemens ended the season unbeaten in his final 22 starts
after losing to Cleveland on May 29, the longest streak since
Baltimore's Dave McNally went 26 straight starts without a loss in
1969. Clemens won his final 15 decisions.
	   Clemens finished 20-6 with a 2.65 ERA. Last year, when he won
his fourth Cy Young Award, he went 21-7 with a 2.05 ERA and 292
strikeouts, becoming the first AL pitcher to lead in all three
categories since Detroit's Hal Newhouser in 1945. This year, he led
in ERA and strikeouts and tied Texas' Rick Helling (20-7) and New
York's David Cone (20-7) in wins.
	   Atlanta's Tom Glavine led the NL in wins, going 20-6. Braves
teammate Greg Maddux won his fourth ERA title, finishing at 2.22.
	   Atlanta pitchers had 1,232 strikeouts, tied with last year's
Dodgers for the second most in major league history behind the 1996
Braves (1,245). The Braves had five pitchers with 16 or more wins _
Glavine, Maddux (18-9), John Smoltz (17-3), Kevin Millwood (17-8)
and Denny Neagle (16-11). They joined the 1902 Pittsburgh Pirates
as the only teams to accomplish the feat.
	   San Diego's Trevor Hoffman got his 53rd save Sunday night, tying
the NL record set by current teammate Randy Myers, who did it for
the Cubs in 1993. Boston's Tom Gordon led the AL with 45 saves.
	   Oakland's Rickey Henderson won his record 12th stolen base
title, swiping 66 to lead the AL for the first time since 1991.
Tony Womack topped the NL with 58 and became the first Pittsburgh
player to lead the league since Omar Moreno in 1979.
</TEXT>
