<HEADLINE>
Canadian embassy grounds occupied by Kosovo-Albanian refugees
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS to UPDATE with police ready to clear embassy grounds,
refugees identified as Albanians from Kosovo &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) _ Police surrounded the Canadian embassy
Monday after 34 ethnic Albanian refugees pushed their way into the
building and demanded political ayslum.
	   Hungarian police said the group has been identified as ethnic
Albanians from Yugoslavia's war-torn Kosovo province.
	   ``The group entered the embassy grounds a few minutes after 10
a.m. (0800 GMT) and demanded to be granted political asylum,'' said
police spokesman Mihaly Dezsi in a telephone interview.
	   He added that the 18 adults and 16 children had been housed at a
refugee camp in Bicske, some 40 kilometers (25 miles) west of
Budapest, since they had escaped to Hungary from Yugoslavia.
	   It was not known what made them decide to go to the Canadian
embassy.
	   Dezsi said the embassy had asked police to be ready to clear the
embassy grounds.
	   Embassy officials, engaged in the negotiations, were not
available for comment.
	   Hungarian police have sealed off the area around the embassy,
which is a fenced-in compound of two larger buildings in the hills
of Buda, a quiet residential part of the city.
