<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Helicopter Crash </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Body of British navy officer recovered in South China Sea
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ The body of a British naval officer, killed in
a Lynx helicopter crash into the South China Sea last week, was
recovered Monday by divers.
	   The body of Lt. Toby Beale, 27, reportedly of Weymouth, England,
was found among the wreckage by Singapore salvage divers and was
being returned to shore by a Singapore naval vessel, the RSS
Valiant.
	   A ceremonial guard from the British frigate HMS Grafton prepared
to perform a parade of honor at the naval berths at Sembawang Wharf
just before midnight, when the Valiant was due to arrive, said a
statement from the Royal Navy.
	   Beale's body will be sent home after medical and legal
documentation is completed, said David Healy, a spokesman for the
Royal Navy. The salvage team will continue operations to recover
the wrecked helicopter, he said, and a Royal Navy Board of Inquiry
is investigating the cause of the Sept. 23 crash.
	   The helicopter pilot, Lt. Cmdr. Andy Hurry, 36, reportedly of
Torquay, England, survived the crash. It occurred in deep waters
about 90 miles (145 kilometers) northeast of Singapore. 	   
