<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-China-Protest </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
300 workers at Chinese paint factory hold protest
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIJING (AP) _ Three hundred workers at a paint factory in
northern China protested outside government offices on Monday,
calling for unpaid back wages and an investigation into corruption,
a human rights group reported.
	   Workers at the No. 2 Xi'an Paint Factory said management at the
state-owned factory had used it for their personal profit, piling
up losses to the factory until it had to close, the Hong Kong-based
Information Center of Human Rights and Democratic Movement in China
said in a statement.
	   Workers claimed they had not been paid wages for half a year,
the group said.
	   Three hours after the protest began, a government official told
the workers the government would pay part of their wages beginning
Tuesday and would investigate the managers, it said, adding that
the workers then dispersed and there were no arrests.
	   Similar protests have erupted throughout China as struggling
state factories lay off millions of workers. Many have ended
quietly when the government has met at least some of the workers'
demands. 	   
