<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Holocaust Claims </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yad Vashem: Generali insured more than 100,000 Holocaust victims
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ANN S. KIM &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ At least 100,000 Jews took out life insurance
policies with Italy's largest insurance company before they
perished in the Nazi Holocaust in World War II, the head of
Israel's Holocaust research center said Monday.
	   The estimate by Avner Shalev, chairman of the Yad Vashem
Holocaust Memorial, is based on information provided by the company
itself, Assicurazioni Generali. The Jerusalem Post daily said this
marked the first time an actual number of policy holders was cited.
	   Generali, which reneged last week on an agreement to pay dlrs
100 million to policyholders and their heirs, has come under
criticism for not making public information on wartime policies.
	   The company provided Yad Vashem about six months ago with
information on some 300,000 World War II policies. Yad Vashem
randomly sampled and cross-referenced that information with its own
data bases to reach its conclusion on the number of Jewish
policyholders, Shalev told The Associated Press.
	   Under the terms of its agreement with Generali, Yad Vashem is
not allowed to publish the information it received from the company
but only to use it for its own research.
	   ``We have reached an understanding with Generali that we should
not provide (publish) the names of individuals unless Generali will
change their minds,'' Shalev said. ``We are doing it for the sake
of research and enriching our lists.''
	   Generali is one of 16 European insurance companies named in a
federal class-action suit filed last year in New York. Another suit
was filed in February in a Los Angeles Superior Court by family
members of five Holocaust victims.
 &UR; ask-kl
</TEXT>
