<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Kuwait-Attempted Fraud </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Oil company acknowledges fraud attempt at London office
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ The state-run Kuwait Petroleum Corp. said Monday
that an attempt to defraud its London-based subsidiary, Kuwait
Petroleum International, had been foiled.
	   KPC did not say in its statement how much money was involved,
but press reports earlier put the amount at 300,000 British pounds
(dlrs 507,000).
	   The statement said that officials at the Kuwait Petroleum
International ``discovered an attempt to steal and forge signatures
on six company checks.'' It did not say when the incident took
place. The company manages Kuwait's refining and marketing
interests abroad.
	   KPC said that four of the checks were blocked before they were
cashed or deposited and that the accounts of the ``culprits where
the other two were deposited were frozen.''
	   It said the matter was under investigation by the company and
that KPI was cooperating with British police. It gave no other
details.
	   On Sunday, the independent Al-Qabas daily said that the incident
involved cleaners who worked at KPI.
	   The newspaper said that the cleaners allegedly took checks,
forged the signatures of KPI officials, cashed the checks and
disappeared.
	   Al-Qabas said they were from an African country, but did not
identify the country by name.
