r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Economy 4thLd-Writethru   09-28 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Economy, 4th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Primakov says Russia has paid off debts to soldiers; students next
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with official speaking about plans to nationalize
industries, banks, strengthen currency controls in new grafs
12-13. &QL; 
 &UR; By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The government has paid off its debt in back
salaries to the armed forces, and will be able to pay students
their stipends within days, Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov told
President Boris Yeltsin on Monday.
	   Since his appointment nearly three weeks ago, Primakov has
stressed that payment of salaries and pensions will be his
government's priority as it grapples with Russia's grave economic
crisis.
	   The stark conditions for soldiers have made the debt to the
military a potent political issue for the government's critics.
	   According to estimates published in the Kommersant daily earlier
this month, Russia owed a total of 36 billion rubles (dlrs 2.4
billion) in back salaries and social payments. Of that sum, roughly
10 percent was owed to the military.
	   Primakov's meeting with Yeltsin also focused on efforts to wrap
up the formation of the new Cabinet _ a painful process that has
stretched into a third week as 10 Cabinet seats remain unfilled.
	   In a blow to the proponents of market-oriented reform, Boris
Fyodorov was dismissed from his posts of acting deputy prime
minister and tax chief, Russian news agencies reported. His exit
leaves Mikhail Zadornov, whom Yeltsin reappointed to the post of
finance minister on Friday, as the strongest supporter of reform in
the evolving Cabinet.
	   Zadornov is associated with the previous Cabinet's decision on
Aug. 17 to devalue the ruble and freeze domestic debt _ a
controversial move that many blame for fueling Russia's crisis.
	   Zadornov defended himself over the weekend, saying the former
government had few viable alternatives. He pledged to improve the
terms of the government's debt repayment.
	   A government team is to meet Tuesday with representatives of
Russian and foreign banks that suffered multibillion dollar losses
when the old Cabinet defaulted on its debt on treasury bills.
	   Several previous meetings have brought no result, and foreign
investors have assailed the government for favoring Russian banks.
	   No details of the restructuring plan have yet been released
officially. Shokhin said that under the plan, investors would be
able to redeem their defaulted treasury bills in rubles but the
proceeds would be frozen in special accounts for six months.
	   Dmitry Vasilyev, the head of the Federal Commission on
Securities and Capital Markets, said he had submitted his
resignation in protest over unfair treatment of investors and what
he described as plans to nationalize industries and banks and
tighten controls over the currency market.
	   ``These are recipes from the old Soviet past,'' he said.
Vasilyev, who spoke at a news conference, claimed that the
government and the Central Bank were planning to take controlling
stakes in bankrupt industrial enterprises and banks. He provided no
specifics.
	   In other economic news:
	   _ The Russian ruble on Monday remained stable, with banks
trading it at around 16 to the dollar _ the same level as last
week. The Russian currency stood at around 6 rubles a dollar before
the crisis.
	   _ The amount of private bank deposits fell by 6.5 percent to
about 151 billion rubles (currently dlrs 10 billion) last month as
people scrambled to pull their money out of failing banks.
	   _ Russia's foreign trade turnover shrank by 4.3 percent in the
first eight months of the year, totaling 83.7 billion dollars, said
the State Statistics Committee.
	   _ Revenues from privatization amounted to 1.3 billion rubles
(dlrs 87 million) in January-August, only 16 percent of the 8.12
billion rubles (dlrs 541 million) planned for this year.
	   (vi/ml)
</TEXT>
