<SLUG> BC-Georgia-Abkhazia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Three peacekeepers wounded in mine blast in Abkhazia
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TBILISI, Georgia (AP) _ Three peacekeepers were wounded on
Monday when their armored vehicle struck a mine in Georgia's
breakaway region of Abkhazia.
	   The blast occurred in the village of Otoboya, in the Gali
district, which is patrolled by peacekeepers from the Commonwealth
of Independent States, a group of former Soviet republics.
	   Georgia lost Abkhazia, a region on the Black Sea, to
secessionist forces in 1993 after 13 months of fighting. Around
250,000 Georgians were forced to flee their homes.
	   Russian peacekeepers, ostensibly a Commonwealth of Independent
States force with the blessing of the United Nations, have kept the
two sides apart since June 1994, enforcing a security zone between
Abkhazia and the rest of Georgia.
