<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinians, 1st Ld-Writethru,0650 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Precede JERUSALEM
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Hebron settlers attack Palestinians after shots are fired
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with details of three-way summit at White
House, information about shooting victim, settler rampage in
Palestinian market, Palestinians confirming White House summit;
INCORPORATES Israel-Shooting and CHANGES byline; Talks expected to
begin at about 1445 GMT &QL; 
 &UR; By LAURIE COPANS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HEBRON, West Bank (AP) _ Shots fired from the Palestinian sector
of Hebron injured an Israeli woman, and Jewish settlers responded
by beating Palestinian passers-by and overturning tables in an
outdoor Arab market.
	   Several female Jewish settlers, including Miriam Levinger, one
of the founders of the Jewish enclave in Hebron, sat on the ground
in the market, refusing to be moved.
	   The violence came as Israeli and Palestinian leaders scheduled a
meeting in Washington with U.S. President Bill Clinton later Monday
in hopes of concluding an agreement on a West Bank troop pullback.
	   Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and Israeli Prime Minister
Benjamin Netanyahu met with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright in New York late Sunday. It was their first face-to-face
meeting in nearly a year.
	   Palestinian negotiator Saeb Erekat said Arafat had agreed to
meet with Netanyahu at the White House even though no progress had
been made toward agreement on a West Bank troop withdrawal.
	   Monday's incident in Hebron, a divided city of 130,000
Palestinians and 450 Jewish settlers, began Monday morning when
members of an Israeli family _ in Hebron to celebrate a bar mitzvah
_ walked on the road between two Jewish enclaves, Beit Hadassah and
Tel Romeida. The army said four shots were fired at the group, and
that one bullet hit a 52-year-old woman in the leg.
	   Israel radio said the woman was from Herzliya, north of Tel
Aviv, but her name was not given. The woman taken to a hospital in
Jerusalem.
	   In response, settlers beat several Palestinians passing by Beit
Hadassah, and witnesses said one Palestinian woman was injured. An
Israeli woman was detained in the confrontations.
	   A group of about 15 settler women and teen-age girls entered the
Palestinian open-air market and overturned several vegetable
stands, throwing cucumbers and tomatoes to the ground. Israeli
security forces initially did not interfere, but then began
ordering the women to leave.
	   Mrs. Levinger and two other settler women sat on the ground,
refusing to be moved. They held on to each other as police tried to
drag them away. After one woman fainted and was taken away by
ambulance, Mrs. Levinger stood up.
	   Tensions between Jewish settlers and Palestinians in Hebron rose
considerably last month after a settler rabbi was stabbed to death
in his home in Tel Romeida, a cluster of several trailers in the
heart of a Palestinian neighborhood. The assailant was never
caught.
	   Despite the preparations for a White House summit on Monday,
Israeli and Palestinian negotiators said they didn't see much of a
chance for a breakthrough.
	   Erekat, the Palestinian negotiator, said that while Netanyahu
and Arafat discussed the scope of an Israeli pullback on Sunday,
they did not discuss any of the other issues, such as the opening
of a Palestinian airport, an additional Israeli withdrawal and a
Palestinian crackdown on Islamic militants.
	   ``Until now, there isn't any real progress,'' Erekat said.
	   A similar assessment came from Danny Naveh, the Israeli Cabinet
secretary. Speaking after the Netanyahu-Arafat meeting in New York,
Naveh told Israel radio that the obstacle remains Palestinian
refusal to carry out its commitments, especially stopping
extremists from attacking Israel.
	   ``We are not in the position of being able to say that an
agreement has been reached in these areas,'' he said.
</TEXT>
