<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Germany </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia hopes new German government won't abandon strong ties
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The Russian government said Gerhard Schroeder's
election as German chancellor was an opening for closer ties
between the two countries, while Russian leftists cheered the
victory as ``a sign of our times.''
	   The two countries should ``avoid pauses in Russian-German
cooperation,'' Russian Foreign Ministry Spokesman Vladimir
Rakhmanin said, according to the Interfax news agency.
	   Rakhmanin said that Russia wants to establish ``direct and
regular contacts'' with Schroeder and the Social Democratic Party,
hoping the new government will ``continue to strengthen relations
of good-neighborliness, partnership, and mutual trust,'' Interfax
reported.
	   Germany is Russia's main trading partner outside the former
Soviet Union, and Russia is eager for German help as it weathers
its worst financial crisis in years.
	   Communist leader and parliament deputy Gennady Zyuganov was more
ebullient, calling the outcome ``a sign of our times'' that
indicates leftist governments are gaining popularity across Europe.
	   ``A new epoch is coming. Many countries have become much more
leftist in nature. It is symptomatic that leftist forces have come
to power in 12 of the 15 major European states, including France,
Italy and Germany,'' he said.
	   Meanwhile, the Foreign Ministry paid tribute to former
Chancellor Helmut Kohl, whose friendship with President Boris
Yeltsin is well known in Russia.
	   Germany's outgoing leader ``without a doubt has played an
outstanding role in the history of Germany and the whole of Europe
at one of the most crucial stages of their history,'' Rakhmanin
said, according to Interfax.
	   (nw/ji/ml)
</TEXT>
