<HEADLINE>
Islamic Jihad leader released from Palestinian prison
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   GAZA CITY, Gaza Strip (AP) _ The leader of the Palestinian
militant group Islamic Jihad has been released from a Palestinian
jail after six weeks.
	   Abdallah Shami said Monday he was held for writing an article in
which he criticized Yasser Arafat's Palestinian Authority. The
article appeared in the Gaza City weekly Al Istiqlal.
	   Shami was released Sunday. He said he was treated well in
prison.
	   Islamic Jihad and its larger sister group, Hamas, oppose the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process, and have claimed responsibility
for attacks that have killed scores of Israelis since the
Israel-Palestinian peace accords in 1993.
	   Israel and the United States have demanded that Arafat crack
down on the militant groups and arrest senior figures. Israel has
complained that Arafat was engaged in a revolving-door policy,
detaining militants for show and then releasing them.
