<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Singapore-Economy </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Singapore's prime minister lowers growth forecast again
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SINGAPORE (AP) _ Prime Minister Goh Chok Tong has predicted
almost no economic growth for Singapore this year, warning that his
people must be prepared for a possible recession next year.
	   ``We have been telling our people to exercise restraint in wage
increase and we are talking about wage freeze now,'' Goh said in a
Sept. 11 interview with Chilean journalists, without elaborating.
	   The government released a transcript of the interview Monday to
coincide with Goh's visit to Chile Wednesday and Thursday.
	   ``This year, the growth will be minimal, at around zero to 1
percent at most, which means we have been affected by about 7
percentage points in growth as a result of the crisis in the
region,'' Goh said.
	   Goh's forecast was the government's third downward revision for
economic growth for this year. The official forecast for the gross
domestic product is between 0.5 percent to 1.5 percent.
	   The Singapore economy grew 7.8 percent last year but growth has
since slowed sharply. The economy grew 6.1 percent in the first
quarter but slowed further to register a rise of only 1.6 percent
in the second quarter.
	   ``We are still up there and could be dragged down by those who
fell,'' Goh said of the Asian economic crisis that has seen near
financial collapse in Indonesia, Malaysia, Thailand and South
Korea.
	   ``Indonesia and Malaysia, for example, are our major trading
partners.
shape because their government was not like others in the region,
Goh told the Chileans the government is now preparing the
island-state's 3.2 million people for a letdown.
	   ``We are preparing our people for a possible recession next year
so that if it comes, Singaporeans would not be taken by surprise,''
Goh said. 	   
</TEXT>
