 &UR; U.S. defense minister urges Serbs to end violence in Kosovo
 &UR; Eds: Stands for BC-Italy-Cohen-Kosovo. Will be updated after
scheduled 17:15 GMT news conference.
 &UR; AP Photo planned &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   RABAT, Morocco (AP) _ U.S. Defense Secretary William Cohen
arrived in Morroco on Monday after renewing threats of a NATO
airstrike unless Serb forces end their offensive in Kosovo.
	   Cohen was to meet Monday afternoon with King Hassan II, as well
as the Moroccan prime minister and other senior officials in the
North African kingdom.
	   Earlier Monday in Rome, Cohen and Italian Defense Minister
Beniamino Andreatta said the planning for airstrikes was completed.
	   Both Cohen and Andreatta urged Yugoslav President Slobodan
Milosevic yet again to seek a peaceful solution to the conflict
with ethnic Albanian rebels in the embattled province of Kosovo.
	   Cohen said ``a very strong, credible threat must be made to Mr.
Milosevic to back away from what he is currently doing.''
	   He said Milosevic should pull his military and police forces
back to allow for humanitarian missions, ``and sit down at the
bargaining table to peacefully resolve the issue of Kosovo.''
	   NATO has set no deadline, but Cohen and Andreatta spoke of the
onset of winter and the hardships it would mean for refugees hiding
out in Kosovo's countryside.
	   Cohen said some 50,000 people ``run the risk of either starving
to death or freezing to death.''
	   ``Winter is coming and we are pressed for time,'' Andreatta
said.
	   Later Monday, the Serb government appeared to set the stage for
bowing to NATO demands. It said the rebels had been defeated and
special police units would return to barracks _ a condition
demanded by the Americans and Europeans to avoid NATO attack.
	   Cohen's visit to Morocco was the final stop on a trip that has
taken him to Portugal, Macedonia, Bosnia and Italy. He is scheduled
to returned to Washington on Tuesday.
	   (pvs/dgs/ip)
</TEXT>
