<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Hoddle-Drugs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
England coach dismisses claims of doping
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ England coach Glenn Hoddle has dismissed
suggestions by Manchester United manager Alex Ferguson that
England's World Cup players were given potentially dangerous
performance-enhancing substances.
	   ``I'm afraid some people must have their heads in the sand,''
Hoddle said in an interview in Monday's Daily Telegraph. ``To
suggest there is anything wrong or that the players are on drugs is
outrageous. It is so far from the truth.''
	   Hoddle said each member of the England squad had his blood
tested before the World Cup and was given vitamin and mineral
supplements. Two players were prescribed boosters, administered
voluntarily by injection, before the match against Colombia, he
said.
	   Ferguson, whose players made up the bulk of the England team,
has written to the Football Association questioning the practice
and demanding to know details of the pre-game injections.
	   ``You wonder about the long-term effects on players,'' Ferguson
said. ``I have looked into all of this but when you use these
methods you have to also remember there is a side effect.
	   ``There is another aspect when you punish your body with
chemicals and things like that _ you are putting things in the body
that aren't normally there.''
	   Hoddle said all the pills and inections were legal and
prescribed by Dr. Yann Rougier, who worked with Arsenal last
season.
	   ``Dr. Rougier has worked with the best in the world in the last
15 years, with AC Milan and Monaco and individual athletes,''
Hoddle said.
	   Among the products taken by England players was creatine, a
legal muscle-building compound that is widely used by soccer
players and other athletes throughout the world.
	   On another issue, Hoddle said he expects to sign a new two-year
contract as England coach by Friday. He said he is not interested,
for now, in extending his contract for four years through the 2002
World Cup.
	   ``I'm not looking for a new four-year deal, not from this
distance,'' he said. ``If we qualify for the (2000) European
Championship, that might be the time to look further ahead for
myself and the FA.''
	   A large section of the British media has been pushing for Hoddle
to resign or be fired. Newspapers, particularly tabloids, have
attacked Hoddle over his World Cup memoirs and his ties with faith
healer Eileen Drewery.
	   But Hoddle insisted he could cope with the media pressure.
	   ``People will push and push and push on different elements
because they have got to sell papers,'' he said. ``If I have to
take that, I'll take it. Up to a point.''
	   On Friday, Hoddle will name the England squad for the upcoming
Euro 2000 qualifier against Bulgaria. Even though midfielders David
Beckham and Paul Ince are suspended, Hoddle dismissed speculation
that he will bring Middlesbrough's Paul Gascoigne back into the
fold.
	   ``He has got to get ultra-fit and back to his very best form,''
Hoddle said. ``He hasn't had the opportuntiy to do that yet. He has
missed too many games. But we are keeping a close eye on the
situation though.''
	   (sw) 	   
</TEXT>
