<SLUG> Africa Briefs </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Princess Anne in Kenya; Burkina election blues; dull Botswana
</HEADLINE>
bourse &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) _ Britain's Princess Anne laid a wreath
Monday at the site of the Aug. 7 bombing of the U.S. embassy in
which 248 people, 12 of them Americans, lost their lives.
	   Most of the dead were killed when an adjacent building, housing
a teachers' cooperative, collapsed.
	   The British government has pledged 150 million shillings (dlrs
2.5 million) to help replace teaching equipment destroyed in the
blast.
	   Queen Elizabeth's only daughter is in Africa on an 11-day tour
of charity projects she supports in Uganda, Tanzania, Kenya and
Mauritius.
	   In Kenya, she was scheduled to visit a refugee camp near the
Sudanese border, schools in Nairobi and a women lawyers' center in
the western town of Kisumu.
	   -----
	   MOGADISHU, Somalia (AP) _ The capital was tense Monday following
clashes between rival militiamen. Five people were killed and seven
others wounded.
	   In two separate incidents Sunday, militiamen fought street
battles in the northern and southern parts of the city, and the
wife of Abdelaziz Ahmed Mahdi, a well-known businessman and soccer
coach, was kidnapped.
	   At one point, sources said, her abductors held a gun to her head
and told those trying to rescue her they would kill her on the spot
of the shooting did not stop. Elders were then sent to negotiate
with the captors, but the woman was not released.
	   Since the announcement two months ago of a joint administration
for the war-torn capital to allow the reopening of the airport and
port, security has worsened as militiamen marked for demobilization
attempt to exort as much money as possible.
	   -----
	   OUAGADOUGOU, Burkina (AP) _ The main opposition party said it
will boycott presidential elections scheduled for November.
	   Speaking at a party meeting, Joseph Ki Zerbo, head of the Party
for Democracy and Progress, said Sunday, ``The boycott aims at
ensuing a minimum of democracy before it is too late.''
	   The Nov. 15 balloting is the second since President Blaise
Campaore took power in a bloody 1987 coup. He won the 1991
elections as the sole candidate. Other parties boycotted.
	   Opposition members accuse the government of setting up a sham
national electoral commission to oversee this year's vote.
	   Although civic and opposition groups will be represented on the
27-member commission, the top two posts are reserved for appointees
of the government.
	   -----
	   GABORONE, Botswana (AP) _ The stock market that soared 100
percent last year has risen just 0.2 percent in the last three
months. Analysts predict tough times lie ahead.
	   ``We are in for a year of stagnation. There will be little
movement in share prices until the price earnings ratios improve --
and that will take 12 months,'' Botswana Insurance Fund manager
Alan Norrie said on Monday.
	   The chief executive of Stockbrokers Botswana, Rupert McCammon,
said after years of sustained growth, there would be a longer
cooling off period before the situation improved.
	   ``In the short to medium term we are unlikely to see any
increase in prices. In the longer term it will depend on sentiment
towards the emerging markets,'' he was quoted as telling the South
African Press Association.
	   -----
	   LUANDA, Angola (AP) _ Former rebel group UNITA staged several
attacks in two rural provinces last week, killing an army officer,
a policeman and injuring four others, news reports said Monday.
	   UNITA troops Saturday attacked and occupied Calandula, in the
central Malanje province, some 250 miles (400 kilometers) east of
Luanda, state weekly Actual Fax quoted an unnamed army officer as
saying.
	   Also in Malanje, an anti-tank mine killed an army officer and
injured four others last week, according to the report. In the
far-eastern province of LundaSul, gunmen staged an ambush last
week, killing a policeman, the army officer told the weekly.
	   General lawlessness in the sprawling southwest African country
have made it difficult for foreign observers to reach outlying
areas and help determine the perpetrators of the attacks.
	   The government has said remnants of UNITA's 70,000-strong
guerilla army are responsible. The former rebels have angrily
rejected the accusations and blame roaming gangs of bandits for the
incidents.
	   UNITA fought a two-decade civil war against the government
before signing a 1994 U.N.-sponsored peace deal in Lusaka, Zambia,
which remains to be fully implemented.
	   -----
	   ABIDJAN, Ivory Coast (AP) _ Cheick Mohammed Cherif, one of the
Ivory Coast's most popular jazz musicians, has died, newspapers
reported Monday.
	   Cherif, popularly called Cheick Smith, after American jazz
musician Jimmy Smith, died Friday night in a car accident in the
commercial capital Abidjan, on the way to a concert,
Fraternite-Matin newspaper reported. He was 44.
	   The Guinea-born musician settled in the Ivory Coast at the age
of 16 and became an integral part of the national jazz scene. He
was famous for blending traditional instruments and rhythms with
modern instruments.
	   (sl/nai-var/ad/ids-bh/lis-sapa/ewm)
</TEXT>
