<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-India-Madonna,0269 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sanskrit scholars defend Madonna
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NEW DELHI, India (AP) _ Those who have criticized Madonna for
mixing her sexy image with her new interest in Hinduism are giving
the religion a bad name, several scholars say.
	   ``Hinduism is a religion of tolerance,'' Acharya Vageesh
Shastri, one of the most respected scholars in the Hindu holy city
of Varanasi, told The Associated Press Sunday. ``One should have
the vision to look beyond her transparent tops. Her interior is
more appealing than her exterior.''
	   The World Vaishnava Association had issued a statement
condemning Madonna for wearing a holy facial marking along with
``clothes through which her nipples were clearly visible and while
gyrating in a sexually suggestive manner'' during the Sept. 10 MTV
Video Music Awards.
	   B.N. Chaturvedi, another Varanasi scholar, was more interested
in what Madonna sang during the show than what she wore. He praised
her for improving her pronunciation of Sanskrit prayers she had
incorporated into a pop song, and dismissed the World Vaishnava
Association as an ``unknown organization run by people with
doubtful credentials.''
	   Vaishnavas are one of a bewildering array of branches of
Hinduism. Hindus range from fundamentalists to reformers often led
by a guru, or teacher. No central hierarchy has the final word on
doctrine.
	   Revered Hindu guru Pandit Shiv Kumar Upadhaya said the interest
of ``global celebrities'' like Madonna created welcome attention.
	   ``Madonna's newfound passion for Indian culture should be viewed
in the right perspective,'' Upadhaya said.
</TEXT>
