r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Yeltsin     09-28 0455
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Yeltsin </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Court to decide if Yeltsin may run for third term
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A parliamentary committee seeking to impeach Boris
Yeltsin resumed hearings on Monday, and Russia's highest court set
a date for deciding whether the president may run for a third term
in 2000.
	   The impeachment campaign by the Communist-led opposition began
long before the current crisis in Russia, but has made little
progress and appears likely to fail, as have several previous
efforts.
	   The impeachment committee's previous session, which was
scheduled for earlier this month, had to be postponed because
several key witnesses failed to show up. Most of the politicians
did not turn up again Monday, but lawmakers decided to go ahead
anyway with their review of Yeltsin's handling of the unsuccessful
war in Chechnya.
	   One of the witnesses who appeared at the hearings _ the former
commander of the North Caucasus Military District, Col. Gen. Alexei
Matyukhin _ said Chechnya's independence bid could have been
resolved without military intervention if the federal government
had been more willing to negotiate with separatist leaders, the
ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
	   If the committee manages to put an impeachment motion on the
agenda of the parliament's lower house, the State Duma, the motion
would need a two-thirds majority vote to pass. It would then need
to be approved by a two-thirds majority in three other bodies: the
upper house or Federation Council, and both the Constitutional and
Supreme Courts, which include many Yeltsin supporters.
	   Meanwhile, Russia's Constitutional Court announced that on Oct.
15 it would look into parliament's inquiry into whether Yeltsin may
run for a third term in the 2000 presidential election.
	   A constitutional limit of two terms would appear to rule out
another bid for Yeltsin. But the president's aides argue that his
first term began during Soviet times _ before the new constitution
was adopted _ and should not count toward the two-term limit.
	   Yeltsin has repeatedly said he does not plan to run. But
parliament still wants the Constitutional Court to formally ban
another bid.
	   Yeltsin representative in the court, Mikhail Mityukov, said
Monday that parliament's position ``does not make any sense,''
ITAR-Tass reported.
	   ``It is difficult to say what guided the deputies _ maybe
educational motives, or maybe they tried to over-protect,''
Mityukov said.
	   Potential candidates for the 2000 race include former Prime
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin, Moscow Mayor Yuri Luzhkov, Communist
Party leader Gennady Zyuganov, who came in second in the 1996
election, and former national security chief Alexander Lebed.
	   (ad/ml)
</TEXT>
