<SLUG> BC-Hungary-Canada-Refugees </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Canadian embassy grounds occupied by Kosovo-Albanian refugees
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with police asked to negotiate settlement or clear
grounds. Stands as 3rd Ld-Writethru for some points.
 &UR; By ALEX BANDY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) _ Canadian diplomats asked police to
negotiate a settlement Monday with 34 ethnic Albanian refugees
occupying the front steps of the embassy and demanding political
asylum, or else use force to clear the grounds.
	   Hungarian police spokesman Mihaly Dezsi said officers hoped to
negotiate a settlement with the refugees. ``We want to avoid any
rough stuff,'' he said.
	   Dozens of police dressed in riot gear surrounded the embassy
compound Monday afternoon.
	   Police said the group occupying the embassy's front steps in a
slight rain had been identified as ethnic Albanians from
Yugoslavia's war-torn Kosovo province.
	   ``The group entered the embassy grounds a few minutes after 10
a.m. (0800 GMT) and demanded to be granted political asylum,''
Mihaly Dezsi said.
	   He added that the 18 adults and 16 children, including one
infant, had been housed at a refugee camp in Bicske, some 40
kilometers (25 miles) west of Budapest, since they had escaped to
Hungary from Yugoslavia. Some had arrived in June.
	   It was not known what made them decide to go to the Canadian
embassy and request asylum.
	   ``We will die here if we have to,'' one refugee yelled from the
embassy steps.
	   Canadian officials broke off talks with the refugees and asked
police to take over negotiations, Dezsi said.
	   The embassy officials were unavailable for comment.
	   Hungarian police sealed off the area around the embassy, which
is a fenced-in compound of two larger buildings in the hills of
Buda, a quiet residential part of the city.
	   (ab/rr/scl)
</TEXT>
