<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Space, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
International space station faces new delay, Russia behind
</HEADLINE>
schedule &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with today's meeting over, final decision on launch
dates to be made on Friday, other details in new grafs 5, 10-11,
minor edit. &QL; 
 &UR; By VLADIMIR ISACHENKOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Participants in the dlrs 21 billion international
space station debated on Monday whether to again delay its
construction after Russia failed for the third time to deliver a
key segment.
	   The station, a joint project of Russia, the United States, the
European Space Agency, Canada and Japan, has already been pushed
back a year because the cash-strapped Russian space industry has
missed two previous target dates.
	   Despite repeated pledges, the Russian government has failed to
fund construction of the service module that would serve as living
quarters for the crew.
	   It seems certain that the module won't be completed in time to
meet an April launch date, Russian Space Agency chief Yuri Koptev
said, according to the ITAR-Tass news agency.
	   Mikhail Sinelshchikov, head of Russia's manned space program,
said the module could be launched some time next summer, provided
the government comes up with promised funds.
	   The delay also casts doubt on a plan to launch the station's
first module in less than two months, on Nov. 20. The cargo module,
built by the Russian Khrunichev company under contract with the
U.S. firm Boeing, has already been taken to the launch site at the
Baikonur cosmodrome in the former Soviet republic of Kazakstan.
	   NASA was expected to follow with a launch of the second part, a
connecting passageway, on Dec. 3.
	   Because of the probable delay in sending up a crew in the third
stage, the dates for the first two launches may be revised. Some
experts consider it too risky to leave the orbiting modules
unmanned for so long.
	   However, the Russian space agency is pushing for the first two
segments to be launched as previously scheduled, because that would
make it easier to lobby the government for delivery of the promised
funds, ITAR-Tass said.
	   Sinelshchikov said other participants in the project are likely
to agree to launch the first module as scheduled, since it's
capable of flying alone for more than 400 days.
	   All the countries involved in the international space station
took part in Monday's meeting. The final decision on the launch
dates is expected on Friday, ITAR-Tass said.
	   In an attempt to prevent new costly delays in the project, NASA
intends to ask Congress and the White House for approval to buy
additional goods and services from the Russian Space Agency worth
as much as dlrs 660 million over the next four years, according to
news reports last week.
	   However, Koptev bristled at the proposed bailout, saying the
U.S. aid would effectively deprive Russia of its current status as
a major stockholder in the project and turn it into a
subcontractor.
	   (vi/ml)
</TEXT>
