<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq-Malnutrition </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. says oil-for-food program reducing malnutrition in Iraq
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By LEON BARKHO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ The oil-for-food program has begun reducing
malnutrition among children in Iraq, a U.N. official said Monday.
	   Eric Falt, spokesman for U.N. humanitarian programs in Iraq,
said that a survey in the north showed that 25.3 percent of
children under the age of 5 were suffering from chronic
malnutrition, down from 33.3 percent.
	   He said U.N. agencies hoped for similar results in surveys to be
undertaken soon in central and southern areas.
	   A study conducted late last year by the U.N. Children's Fund
indicated that nearly one million Iraqi children _ or more than 30
percent under age 5 _ were suffering from chronic malnutrition.
	   ``Following the introduction of the food basket ... malnutrition
appears to be ebbing countrywide,'' Falt told The Associated Press.
	   Iraq began selling oil in December 1996 under the U.N.-approved
oil-for-food program to raise funds to provide needed food and
medicine to its 22 million people.
	   Oil earnings are used to purchase flour, sugar and other food
from abroad for distribution to the public as a ration each month.
	   The program is an exception to U.N. trade sanctions imposed
after Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait. The U.N. Security Council has
said the sanctions will not be lifted until Iraq has eliminated its
weapons of mass destruction.
	   In its initial phases, the oil-for-food program allowed Iraq to
sell dlrs 2 billion worth of oil every six months. The U.N. raised
the ceiling to dlrs 5.2 billion, but Iraq has said it will be able
to earn just dlrs 3 billion in the current phase.
	   Falt said this will allow Iraq to introduce protein into the
ration.
	   He said the Iraqi government has indicated that full cream milk
will be distributed to all citizens starting in November.
	   The monthly ration currently includes flour, rice, sugar, tea,
lentils, salt, cooking oil, soap and detergent. A special ration of
milk is provided for babies.
 &UR; lb-eap
</TEXT>
