<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Currency </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ukraine's central chief pledges to keep national currency under
</HEADLINE>
control &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ Ukraine's central bank remains committed to
keeping the national currency within the declared trading corridor
and will not let its rate float, the country's top banker said
Monday.
	   National Bank chief Viktor Yuschenko said the central bank has
no plans to let the hryvna float freely, despite its continuous
fall over the previous months.
	   ``If we lose control over the hryvna's rate, it will be a heavy
blow to Ukraine and its banking sector,'' Yuschenko was quoted by
the Interfax news agency as saying.
	   Ukraine's hryvna, which had remained practically stable until
mid-August, has slid about 45 percent since Russia's financial
turmoil began.
	   It fell to 3.37 to the U.S. dollar on Friday, dangerously close
to the upper limit of the government-set trading corridor of 2.5 to
3.5 to the dollar, which was introduced this month.
	   However, Yuschenko said he saw no reason for the hryvna's
further devaluation. He said public demand for dollars has
diminished in recent days, while people have mostly stopped
withdrawing their savings from commercial banks.
	   Yuschenko added that the National Bank would refrain from
spending its reserves to support the currency, although demand for
dollars at the currency exchange still exceeds supply.
	   He said the National Bank's reserves currently stand at dlrs
1.08 billion, up from about dlrs 850 million at the beginning of
September. The reserves were replenished largely by the first dlrs
257 million tranche of the dlrs 2.2 billion International Monetary
Fund loan approved to Ukraine this month.
	   (vl/ml)
</TEXT>
