w2941 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Caribbean-Hurricane 2ndLd-Writethru   09-28 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Caribbean-Hurricane, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0586 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Hurricane relief operation gains steam in Dominican Republic
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES number killed in Haiti to 94 in 11th graf with dead in
Haiti to 94. &QL; 
 &UR; With US-Hurricane Georges &QL; 
 &UR; By JARED KOTLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) _ Inside a squalid,
overcrowded disaster shelter in Santo Domingo, refugees from
Hurricane Georges seethed over life's latest indignity: the food.
	   Stabbing a fork into a bowl of cold, soggy rice mixed with
tomato sauce, Juanito Montero thrust the foul concoction in a
reporter's face. ``They're not giving us anything!'' shouted the
27-year-old father of two, whose zinc and plywood house was washed
away by floods.
	   Naked children played inside the darkened San Vicente church,
home to 500 storm victims for the past week. Others lay languidly
on the cement floor, not seeming to notice a humanitarian visit
Sunday by a group of U.S. congressmen.
	   ``It's a heartbreaking situation for everyone,'' said Rep. Elton
Gallegly, a California Republican. ``To call it pathetic would be a
gross understatement.''
	   Now, finally, help is on the way. The U.S. relief effort for the
Dominican Republic gained momentum Sunday, ferrying in tons of
bottled water and plastic tarps for thousands of struggling storm
victims.
	   More than 200 people were killed, hundreds are missing and
100,000 were left homeless when Georges struck the Dominican
Republic on Tuesday. Most victims died in flooding or mudslides as
substandard homes proved no match for the hurricane's destructive
power and the rivers it flooded.
	   Over the weekend, the U.S. Agency for International Development
said the hurricane death toll in the Dominican Republic ``is almost
certain to exceed 500.''
	   The United States has shipped dlrs 500,000 worth of supplies,
including enough plastic sheeting to roof 15,000 homes. More aid
was coming, said Hugh Parmer, head of disaster relief for the U.S.
Agency for International Development.
	   At least six U.S. military helicopters were to carry relief
supplies today and help rescuers reach towns cut off by flooding,
downed bridges and debris-choked roads.
	   Helicopter crews hoped to reach San Juan de la Maguana, 120
miles (200 kilometers) west of the capital of Santo Domingo, where
76 bodies were recovered on Thursday. Half the town was under water
or buried in mud, Parmer said.
	   In all, Georges killed more than 300 people throughout the
Caribbean, including at least 94 in Haiti, five in Cuba, three in
St. Kitts and two in Antigua. At least three were killed in Puerto
Rico, where the damage surpassed dlrs 2 billion.
	   In Cuba, President Fidel Castro said the speedy evacuation of
hundreds of thousands of people probably saved many more from dying
during Georges' march across that island on Thursday and Friday.
	   ``The first victory was to reduce the losses,'' Castro said in a
speech broadcast Sunday. He said Cuba now had to help thousands
left homeless and assess agricultural damage.
	   In Santo Domingo, U.S. Peace Corps workers loaded private planes
with bags of food and water to be dropped into villages isolated by
flooding. New York City sent search and rescue teams and Puerto
Rico sent search dogs.
	   At the city's military airport, soldiers used forklifts to
unload flashlights, pinto beans, diapers, graham crackers and chain
saws _ all donated by Houston-based Enron Corp., an investor in the
Dominican electrical power industry.
</TEXT>
