<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Middle East Business Briefs </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items on Jordan and Kuwait. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   AMMAN, Jordan (AP) _ The deficit in the balance of trade fell by
5.9 percent in the first six months of the year because of
increased exports to new markets worldwide.
	   A Trade Ministry report obtained Monday set the deficit at 763.9
million dinars (dlrs 1.075 billion) between January and June, down
from 812.1 million dinars (dlrs 1.143 billion) in the same period
last year.
	   It said more Jordanian output has found its way to new markets
in United States, Europe and Africa.
	   Imports, however, decreased because of the slackened demand in
the local market resulting from a cash crunch, uncertainty over a
settlement between neighboring Israel and the Palestinians and
sanctions on Iraq, it added.
	   The report said imports slipped by 5.4 percent this year to
1.344 billion dinars (dlrs 1.893 billion) compared with the same
period in 1997.
	   Total exports _ including re-exported goods _ were estimated at
580.8 million dinars (dlrs 818 million) between January and June
this year, it said.
	   ---
	   KUWAIT (AP) _ The Kuwait Stock Exchange announced it was
introducing futures trading as of Saturday, the beginning of the
next trading week.
	   Hisham al-Otaibi, the exchange's general manager, told the
Kuwait News Agency on Monday that futures will be traded for half
an hour in the afternoon for an experimental period of six months.
However, the futures option will not be open to all listed
companies during this period, he said.
	   A experiment will be evaluated in order to ``fill any loopholes
that appear'' during that half year, al-Otaibi told KUNA.
	   The exchange which lists 76 companies is considered one of the
most active in Arab companies. But trading is limited to Kuwaitis
and nationals of the other Arab states in the Gulf.
 &UR; vars-ggl
</TEXT>
