w2957 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Europe-WatchingGerman     09-28 0656
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Europe-Watching Germany </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EU nations expect Schroeder to continue pro-unity policies
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; with Germany-Election
 &UR; By PAUL AMES &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ With the towering figure of Helmut Kohl
removed from the European scene, Germany's neighbors are watching
how Chancellor-elect Gerhard Schroeder will affect the continental
balance of power.
	   For 16 years, Kohl used the economic and political strength of
the EU's largest nation to shape key EU policies _ from the
impending launch of a common currency to a planned expansion into
Eastern Europe.
	   Few expect any sudden, fundamental change in Germany's European
stance.
	   ``You don't change foreign policy as often as you change a
government,'' said Danish Foreign Minister Niels Helveg Pedersen.
``Germany will continue to have strong ties to the European Union,
the the United States, to NATO.''
	   Nevertheless, many wonder if Schroeder, who was born at the end
of World War II, shares Kohl's emotional commitment to a united
Europe which stemmed from childhood memories of a continent
ravished by war.
	   ``The new leadership will feel in a different way this
connection between Germany and Europe,'' said Italian Defense
Minister Beniamino Andreatta. ``But I hope that Mr. Kohl's legacy,
Germany's role toward the West, will not be changed.''
	   Schroeder's victory in Sunday's election means Socialists now
lead the governments of the EU's three biggest powers _ Germany,
France and Britain.
	   ``It's a new era opening up,'' said British Prime Minister Tony
Blair. ``It's a tremendous thing that we now have center-left
governments in the three countries ... I look forward to working
with them very much.''
	   Leaders of the other 14 EU nations are expected to meet
Schroeder Oct. 24 at a special summit in the Austrian lakeside
resort of Poertschach.
	   Many expect the new German leader to draw closer to Blair's
vision of a ``third way'' combining free market economics with a
commitment to social justice, than the more traditional socialist
approach of French Prime Minister Lionel Jospin.
	   ``He will look for closer relations with England,'' said Robert
Aspeslagh, senior researcher at the Netherlands Institute for
International Relations in The Hague.
	   ``Before, in the EU, there was Germany and France on one side
and then Britain. Now you will see Germany, France and Britain as
equal partners.''
	   However, Britain's decision to stay out of the inner-club of EU
nations that switch to the euro as their shared currency on Jan. 1,
means the relationship between Schroeder and Jospin remains
crucial.
	   ``The Franco-German axis has historic importance, and it will
remain the most important for Europe,'' said Schroeder after his
election win Sunday.
	   Schroeder once expressed doubts about ditching the Deutsche mark
for the euro, but since he has fallen in line with the single
currency plan.
	   However, Germany's European allies are expecting Schroeder to
follow Kohl's line in demanding pays a smaller share of the cost of
bringing the former-communist nations to the east into the EU fold
some time next decade.
	   ``Whoever is in power will have to do more on the contributions,
because Germany is not the rich country it was,'' said Anne-Marie
Le Gloannec, deputy director of the Paris-based Center for
International Studies and Research.
	   Germany paid almost one-third of the dlrs 86 billion budget this
year and wrangling over how to share the burden is expected to
dominate EU business over the coming months as Germany prepares to
take over the presidency of the Union for the first six months of
1999.
	   Despite the likely entry into the Schroeder government of
ministers from the pacifist Green Party, NATO official said they
expected no weakening of Germany's steadfast support for the
alliance, even if that means German planes going to war in Kosovo.
 &UR; (pa)
</TEXT>
