w2958 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Women     09-28 0355
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Women </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russia's women activists seek greater role to fight crisis
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ANNA DOLGOV &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ With Russia sinking deeper into economic crisis,
dozens of women's rights activists on Monday discussed ways to
improve the situation of women in Russia and raise their profile in
government.
	   ``Now is a time when the women's voice must be heard in all its
strength,'' said Natalya Berezhnaya, a leader of Equality and Peace
association.
	   ``We make up 53 percent of the country's population, yet we are
still shunted aside from political government, and that's one of
the factors in (the problems) we have in our country,'' she said.
	   Russian women, who suffer discrimination in the job market and
political life while carrying most of the workload at home, have
been badly hit by the economic turmoil.
	   Proposals at the discussion Monday ranged from helping one
another get through the crisis, to sending proposals to male
politicians, to fighting for raising the number of women in
government.
	   ``Men, as the male political club, have discredited
themselves,'' said Nadezhda Shvedova, a political analyst with the
USA and Canada Institute, a leading Russian think-tank.
	   ``We need parity in politics. ... A woman in politics is a new
resource that will allow people to trust the government again,''
Shvedova said.
	   Conference participants also voiced support for Valentina
Matviyenko, deputy prime minister for social affairs and the only
woman in the new Cabinet.
	   Others, however, called for women to rely on their own strength
and help others get through the crisis, without expecting help from
the government.
	   ``I appeal to everyone not to wait for help from the government
that is about to be formed now. ... We think about what we can do
now, today, while distancing ourselves from the various political
groups and factions,'' said Yevgenia Poplavskaya, a leader of the
Mercy and Social Protection Association.
	   ``If we don't unite for small things, we won't be able to
resolve big ones,'' Poplavskaya said.
	   (ad/ji/ml)
</TEXT>
