<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-UEFA-Euro 2004 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Portugal, Spain, and Austria/Hungary to bid for Euro 2004 finals
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   NYON, Switzerland (AP) _ Portugal, Spain, Austria and Hungary
have officially entered the race to host the finals of the European
soccer championships in 2004, European soccer's governing body UEFA
announced Monday.
	   Austria and Hungary will submit a joint bid, according to a UEFA
press release. Hungary's government voted Thursday to support it
despite initial concerns voiced by ministers about the country's
ability to fund the project, which is expected to cost up to dlrs
85 million.
	   Switzerland had also indicated interest in hosting the finals
but withdrew its bid earlier this year because it didn't fulfil
UEFA requirements, a UEFA spokeswoman said.
	   All the candidates will submit dossiers on their bids to UEFA at
a meeting on Thursday. UEFA is expected to announce the winner in
July next year.
	   Also Monday, UEFA said representatives of an extra six clubs
have been invited to attend the second meeting in Geneva on Friday
of its European Club Football 2000 task force.
	   The special group was set up to study options for reform of
European club competitions in response to plans by Italy's Media
Partners for a breakaway super league.
	   The clubs are Real Madrid and Barcelona of Spain, Lazio of
Italy, Bayer Leverkusen of Germany, Russia's Spartak Moscow and
Rosenborg, of Norway.
	   Six clubs have already taken part in the first meeting of the
task force, among them Ajax of Holland, Juventus of Italy,
England's Liverpool, Bayern Munich of Germany, FC Porto of Portugal
and France's Olympique Lyonnais.
 &UR; (pw)	   
</TEXT>
