<SLUG> BC-Greece-Hostage to Events </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Botched hostage raid has government under siege
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos ATH101-2 &QL; 
 &UR; By BRIAN MURPHY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ It started with a family taken hostage by
a career criminal making his last stand.
	   Now it's the government being held captive.
	   A succession of calamities _ including a blood-soaked police
raid and the death of the hostage-taker in a prison medical ward _
have officials backed into a corner by critics claiming gross
errors in judgment reaching all the way toward Premier Costas
Simitis.
	   The scandal, which began last week on an unprecedented live
television hook-up with the fugitive, has slapped the 2-year-old
government with its most delicate and embarrassing domestic crisis.
	   ``A madhouse,'' groaned the moderate newspaper Exousia in a
Monday commentary on the government's handling of the affair.
	   ``We have every right to question everything,'' said Aleka
Papariga, the head of the Greek Communist Party.
	   Simitis has been able to ride out labor protests of his painful
economic measures by saying it is vital to keep pace with European
Union partners. There is no such clarity in the web of missteps and
suspicions from the hostage drama and its aftermath.
	   Greek officials are left having to explain actions that,
according to media and government foes, exposed serious weaknesses
in security forces and the political leadership.
	   It does not appear Simitis' government is in danger of falling,
but calls are growing louder for high-level resignations following
the botched raid and the Saturday death of Greek-Romanian convict
Sorin Matei. Autopsy reports concluded Matei, 27, choked to death
on his own vomit while heavily sedated.
	   ``With the sudden death of (Matei), the portrait of political
and state brutality we witnessed is expanded,'' wrote the
conservative newspaper Vradini.
	   Matei, an escapee serving sentences for attempted murder and
armed robberies, had been on the run since July. On Sept. 6, he
managed to escape after taking a police officer hostage with a hand
grenade.
	   On Wednesday, he was again surrounded by police but slipped away
carrying a grenade. He burst into an apartment and took three
hostages. He made demands and rambled on about his drug problem in
calls to the anchorman of a private television station.
	   Police, wrongly concluding the grenade was fake, stormed the
building and were caught in the blast. Twelve people were injured,
including Matei, a hostage and the police chief who later resigned.
	   Police were harshly denounced for the bungled operation. But the
recriminations soon spread to Simitis' cabinet.
	   The criticism was particularly stinging after Greek authorities
insisted they do not need outside help to handle security for the
2004 Olympics in Athens.
	   Then the death of Matei in Athens' maximum-security prison
raised new questions: why he was left sedated with only superficial
injuries and why he was not under special watch?
	   ``It seems special measures were not taken to keep the witness
alive,'' said Costas Papanikolau, a commentator on the Antenna
radio network.
	   Government spokesman Dimitris Reppas insisted that everything
and everybody is being investigated ``from beginning to end.''
	   ``We want truth to shine,'' he told reporters Monday.
	   At Matei's funeral a few hours later, his body was dressed in a
white suit and his casket surrounded by white daisies and orange
and white tiger lillies. His mother, Tzenaka Kapsopoulou, sobbed:
``They shut your mouth so you couldn't talk.''
	   (bm-pq) 	   
</TEXT>
