<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Election, 7th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Germany's future chancellor Schroeder taps Greens for new
</HEADLINE>
coalition &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with more Schroeder quotes. Trims. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By ANNE THOMPSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ Gerhard Schroeder, Germany's future
chancellor, said Monday the center-left Social Democrats will begin
talks Friday on forming a government coalition with the
environmentalist Greens.
	   Schroeder said the coalition was ``the natural result'' of the
Social Democrat's sweeping 41 percent victory in elections Sunday
that ousted Chancellor Helmut Kohl after 16 years of conservative
rule.
	   The Social Democratic triumph marked the first time in postwar
Germany that voters rejected all parties from the previous
government in favor of fresh faces and new ideas.
	   The Greens, which won 6.7 percent, get their first shot at
governing if talks are successful. Schroeder said his party would
try to assemble a coalition as quickly as possible. But
negotiations could be tricky between two parties with some sharp
policy differences.
	   Schroeder was beaming and giddy during his first post-election
press conference, jokingly deferring tough economic questions to
his likely finance minister, party chief Oskar Lafontaine, who was
sitting next to him.
	   He became serious, though, in addressing concerns about what
concessions the Social Democrats might have to make to secure
cooperation with the pacifist wing of the Greens.
	   ``The Greens are going to have to prepare for a clear and tough
round of talks,'' Schroeder said.
	   The future chancellor offered assurances that his government
would maintain Germany's foreign and economic policies. Schroeder
said Germany's role in NATO was not in question, though he skirted
questions on participation in possible NATO intervention in Kosovo,
saying the Kohl government was still in power.
	   ``Nobody needs to be afraid. We will ensure continuity in
foreign policy,'' he said. ``The international community can rely
on Germans to remain good partners.''
	   Schroeder said the new government is committed to Europe's
single currency, the euro, which starts Jan. 1. Germany also takes
over the six-month rotating presidency of the European Union on
that day.
	   The Social Democrats will try to reach agreement with the Greens
within 30 days. Germany's consistition gives no deadline for
forming a government, but the new parliament must convene by Oct.
27. The parliament will then elect a chancellor, in this case
Schroeder, who will in turn designate his Cabinet and a coalition.
	   The Kohl government remains as a caretaker until the new
parliament convenes.
	   Kohl's defeat was a stinging humiliation for the West's
longest-serving leader. His Christian Democrats won just 35 percent
of the vote, which translates to a loss of 49 of the 294 seats it
held in the old parliament.
	   Now Schroeder must make good on pledges to end unemployment,
stuck above 10 percent, and to bring long-awaited tax and economic
reforms.
	   With the Greens, a Social Democratic-led government would
command a 21-seat majority in the new 669-seat parliament. ``I
think 21 seats is enough of a majority to form a stable
government,'' Schroeder told national ZDF television earlier
Monday.
	   A Social Democrat-Greens alliance would be postwar Germany's
most radical government as well as a test of the Greens' ability to
curb their sometimes eccentric ideals in cooperation with a more
mainstream party.
	   The Greens have proposed reforms that outrage some Germans and
amuse others: tripling gas prices to 5 marks (dlrs 3) per liter
over 10 years and introducing a 100-kilometer (60-mile) speed limit
on the autobahn.
	   These ideas, off-the-wall even for some Greens, were unlikely to
rock a future government, but the two parties might still have a
struggle agreeing on nuclear energy, immigration and defense
policy.
	   Schroeder, who has governed Lower Saxony state since 1990, will
be the first of a generation rooted in the 1960s leftist movement
to lead Europe's biggest nation.
	   Besides tackling nitty-gritty reforms, Schroeder, 54, will lead
Germany through two enormous changes next year: the return of the
government to Berlin, its prewar capital, and the exchange of the
trusted German mark for Europe's common currency, the euro.
	   Kohl, 68, had sought an unprecedented fifth term on the strength
of his image of stability and clout with world powers at a time of
economic turmoil in Russia and ongoing conflict in the Balkans.
	   But Germans voted for a fresh face of government, and when Kohl
conceded the race he also announced he would step down as the
leader of the Christian Democratic party he has ruled with an iron
fist since 1973.
	   Following Kohl's example, the leader of the Bavaria-only party
that governed with Kohl in Bonn said Monday he would step down.
Christian Social Union chief Theo Waigel, also Germany's outgoing
finance minister, has led his party for 10 years.
	   (aet/cb) 	   
</TEXT>
