<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-Secret Police </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Media accuse Muslim secret police of dirty deeds
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SRECKO LATAL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) _ Reports by Bosnia's two
leading independent magazines accused part of the country's Muslim
leadership of using the secret police to organize slayings and
terrorist attacks.
	   Weekend articles published by Slobodna Bosna (Free Bosnia) and
Dani (Days) stirred up public debate over a favorite Sarajevo topic
_ involvement of Muslim leaders in the activities of secret police
units during and after the Bosnian war.
	   Writing in the daily Oslobodjenje on Monday, columnist Sejad
Luckin said the articles showed the leadership ``didn't want to, or
was not capable of'' controlling some parts of the secret police.
	   But Alija Izetbegovic, the leader of Bosnian Muslims and their
representative in the joint three-member presidency, dismissed the
articles' claims.
	   ``It is obvious that there is a synchronized campaign ...
against the AID,'' Izetbegovic told reporters Saturday.
	   The Agency for Investigation and Documentation (AID) is
instrumental in gathering documentation against war crimes
suspects, which is then turned over to the U.N. war crimes
tribunal.
	   Izetbegovic said the articles were ``an unpatriotic act'' aimed
at helping war criminals escape punishment.
	   His response did little to satisfy the public. ``This reply will
not calm already raised dust, nor it will improve the image of the
leadership,'' Luckin wrote.
	   The magazines carried interviews with Edin Garaplija, an AID
member. He claimed some of the Muslim leadership organized killings
and drug trafficking through their secret services.
	   Garaplija spoke from Zenica prison, 50 kilometers (31 miles)
north of Sarajevo, where he is serving a 13-year sentence for the
torture and attempted murder of another secret service agent.
Garaplija claims he was framed.
	   Garaplija said that at the beginning of the war, some Muslim
leaders formed a secret terrorist unit, code-named ``skylarks.''
The unit allegedly committed at least one mass execution of Bosnian
Serbs, Croats and Muslims who opposed the leadership.
	   The skylarks were reportedly behind several other murders and an
attempted assassination of a Bosnian army commander.
	   When AID was formed in late 1995, a group of skylarks was
recruited and became a secret police unit within AID, he said.
	   A key figure behind the group is former Interior Minister Bakir
Alispahic, who financed his actions with drug trafficking,
Garaplija claimed.
	   Alispahic is linked to the president's son, Bakir Izetbegovic,
who has publicly denied involvement with any secret service.
	   In past years, several police sources have made comments to The
Associated Press that corroborate Garaplija's statements. But no
written evidence was ever provided.
	   For years, the West has been pressing Muslim leadership to
include Croat officers in AID.
	   The Dayton peace accord divided Bosnia into two entities _ the
Serb Republic and the Muslim-Croat federation _ and prohibited any
ethnically pure institutions.
	   The Muslims have refused to integrate this part of the police
because some top Croats are being investigated for war crimes.
	   (sl/acr/scl) 	   
</TEXT>
