<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Grand Slam Cup </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Grand Slam winners missing from Grand Slam Cup
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NESHA STARCEVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MUNICH, Germany (AP) _ The Grand Slam Cup doesn't live up to its
name this year _ at least on the men's side.
	   The lucrative tournament was nominally created to bring together
winners of the four Grand Slam tennis events.
	   But of the four Grand Slam men's champions this year, three have
elected not to come, including the two top players in the world,
Pete Sampras and Patrick Rafter.
	   But the women, competing in the dlrs 6.7 million event for the
first time, are here in full force, with only Monica Seles absent.
Seles has refused to play in Germany since her stabbing at a
tournament in Hamburg in 1993.
	   Martina Hingis, the No. 1 in the world and the Australian Open
champion, is joined by No. 2 Lindsay Davenport, who is in hot
pursuit of the top ranking. Davenport beat Hingis for the U.S. Open
title earlier this month.
	   The tournament, which gives out more prize money per head than
any other event, starts Tuesday in Munich's Olympic Hall, with 12
men and eight women in the field.
	   Hingis opens the event against Conchita Martinez, followed by
two men's matches, Tim Henman vs. Jonas Bjorkman and Nicolas Escude
vs. Felix Mantilla.
	   The tournament began in 1990, with the idea of bringing together
players with the best records in the four Grand Slam events of the
year _ the Australian, French and U.S. Open and Wimbledon.
	   But this year, only one Grand Slam male champion is here: Petr
Korda, who won the Australian Open. Seeded No. 2 is Marcelo Rios.
	   Wimbledon champion Sampras, U.S. Open champion Rafter and Carlos
Moya, the French Open winner, all declined to show up for the event
that has no bearing on the rankings.
	   So, the organizers turned to wild cards to spice up the
tournament that is likely to be upstaged by the Oktoberfest, not to
mention the Bayern Munich-Manchester United Champions League game
on Wednesday.
	   That's how Andre Agassi got into the field. But efforts to bring
in a crowd-pulling German failed. Semi-retired Boris Becker is
injured, just like Steffi Graf.
	   But if the men's side lacks stars, the women should provide the
fireworks.
	   Hingis and Davenport are joined by Wimbledon champion Jana
Novotna and French Open champion Arantxa Sanchez Vicario.
	   With Rafter absent, Australia is represented by Mark
Philippoussis, whom Rafter beat in the U.S. Open final.
Philippoussis missed Australia's Davis Cup victory over Uzbekistan
over the weekend in a dispute with Rafter and captain John
Newcombe.
	   The men's winner will receive dlrs 1.3 million, the women's
800,000.
	   (ns) 	   
</TEXT>
