<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sri Lanka-Civil War,0377 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Fighting in northern Sri Lanka continues, 237 combatants dead
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   EDITORS NOTE _ The following story was submitted to the Sri
Lankan military censor, who made no changes.
	   COLOMBO, Sri Lanka (AP) _ The Sri Lanka military said Monday
that 237 people have died in recent fighting between government
soldiers and Tamil Tiger rebels.
	   The fighting began early morning Sunday when Tamil Tiger rebels
attacked soldiers near the military-controlled town of Paranthan,
280 kilometers (175 miles) north of Colombo, the Sri Lankan
capital.
	   ``Liberation Tigers of Tamil Eelam has confirmed 194 of their
cadres (were) killed,'' according to a statement issued Monday by
the military. Forty-three soldiers also have died and 110 have been
injured in the fighting so far, the statement said.
	   The military on Sunday said only 40 rebels and nine soldiers
were killed but raised the figures Monday, saying the fighting was
on a much larger scale that earlier thought.
	   ``Sporadic confrontations are being reported at present,'' the
statement added.
	   Military-held Paranthan lies along the northernmost stretch of a
70-kilometer (45-mile) highway through rebel-held territory that
the military has been trying to capture for the past year.
	   A sustained campaign from the southern part of the highway has
taken the military two-thirds of the way. Gaining control of the
rest of the rebel-held road would open a supply line to the Jaffna
peninsula, a former rebel stronghold at the northern tip of Sri
Lanka that was captured by the military two years ago.
	   Jaffna's half-million people have had to rely on air and sea
deliveries for food and other supplies.
	   Independent reports of fighting were not available because the
government has barred journalists from battle zones.
	   The government also has imposed censorship on war reporting on
foreign and local reporters in June after fighting to capture the
road escalated.
	   The rebels are fighting for a separate homeland for minority
Tamils in the country's north and east, claiming that they are
discriminated by the majority Sinhalese who control the government
and the military.
	   More than 54,000 people have died in Sri Lanka's civil war since
1983.
</TEXT>
