<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Land Protests </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Protests by Israeli Arabs widen in scope
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By EYAL WARSHAVSKY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UMM AL FAHM, Israel (AP) _ In an escalating battle over land,
police fired rubber bullets for a second day Monday to break up
stone-throwing riots by Israeli Arab teen-agers and Arab
legislators called a general strike.
	   The clashes in Umm al Fahm, the largest Arab town in Israel,
were the most violent in recent years. Scenes of teen-agers hurling
stones from slingshots and burning tires were reminiscent of the
Palestinian uprising in the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
	   The intensity of the anger raised the question of whether the
protests would spread. Israel's 1 million Arab citizens, who make
up 20 percent of the population, have long complained of
discrimination at the hands of successive Israeli governments. The
confiscation of Arab land is an especially sore point.
	   In August, a report prepared by Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu's office recommended treating Israel's Arab citizens as a
strategic threat.
	   A general strike was set for Tuesday in Arab towns and villages
throughout Israel, with schools, businesses and municipal offices
to shut down. A strike was observed in Umm al Fahm on Monday.
	   Legislator Abdel Wahab Darawshe of the Arab Democratic Party
warned that protests would spread unless the government changed its
policies. ``The government has pushed the Arab population against a
wall, so this was the beginning of a larger flare-up,'' he said.
	   The protests began Sunday when Israeli police dismantled a tent
set up to protest the exproriation of a 125-acre olive grove that
is to be used for a military firing range. Israeli authorities said
the land owner was being compensated with about six times as much
land elsewhere.
	   In riots that lasted into the night Sunday, about 50 Umm al-Fahm
residents and 15 police officers were injured.
	   Clashes resumed Monday, with groups of Umm al-Fahm youths
throwing stones at police who responded with tear gas and rubber
bullets. At least five protesters were injured and four arrested.
 &UR; sb-kl
</TEXT>
