<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-Bankruptcy, 5th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan Leasing goes bust in Japan's biggest bankruptcy since WWII
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMS. RECASTS; UPDATES thruout with background, context,
quotes; CHANGES byline.
 &UR; With BC-Japan-Bank Bills
 &UR; AP Photos TOK101-102
 &UR; By CHESTER DAWSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ Japan's wobbly economy and shaky financial system
have claimed its latest victim _ a major leasing firm that declared
bankruptcy with debts totaling more than 2 trillion yen (dlrs 16
billion).
	   The collapse of Japan Leasing Corp. marked the country's biggest
bankruptcy since World War II, but it was just the latest in a
string of high-profile corporate failures.
	   ``Bigger failures are definitely out there somewhere,'' said
Chris Calderwood, chief economist at the Tokyo branch of Jardine
Fleming Securities Co. ``There will be more.''
	   Like many companies which borrowed heavily during an economic
boom in the 1980s, the leasing agent for computers, aircraft and
other equipment was burdened by a crushing load of debts which
soured with the onset of slower growth in the 1990s.
	   With little hope of restructuring itself, the 35-year old
company sought protection from its creditors late Sunday. The
immediate trigger for that decision, however, was the crisis faced
by its parent company, the Long-Term Credit Bank of Japan.
	   Japanese lawmakers had vowed last week to block the credit
bank's attempt to write off bad loans extended to Japan Leasing
Corp. and other affiliates.
	   The move paved the way for a legislative compromise to allow the
government to nationalize ailing lenders such as the LCTB.
	   But it was the death knell for Japan Leasing.
	   Teikoku Data Bank, a Tokyo-based credit research firm generally
regarded as authoritative on bankruptcies, said the failure was the
biggest so far since the end of World War II.
	   Investors appeared to shrug off the news, however. Instead of
starting a market meltdown, stocks rose and analysts said the
failure might actually be good for Japan's troubled banking sector.
	   ``This is a step forward and is very positive in regard to
passing the bank bills,'' said Koyo Ozeki, a bank analyst at
Merrill Lynch Japan Inc.
	   Tokyo's stock market started higher and continued climbing
throughout the day. The benchmark Nikkei rose 185.53 points to
close at 13,903.37 points, up 1.35 percent.
	   Japan Leasing will be taken over by court-appointed managers
within the next few days, a company lawyer said. Its board of
directors will resign.
	   Hiroaki Okamoto, the president of the failed leasing company,
said he did not know how much of his firm's 2.18 trillion yen (dlrs
16 billion) in debts it would be able to pay back.
	   ``Our efforts to restructure the company proved to be
impossible,'' Okamoto said. ``I deeply apologize to our creditors
and for the effects this will have on the financial system.''
	   The worst previous Japanese bankruptcy was of Crown Leasing, a
lender with debts of 1.18 trillion yen (dlrs 8.86 billion) that
went under in April 1997, according to Teikoku Data Bank.
	   The figures cited by Teikoku do not take into account failures
which occurred without formal bankruptcy filings, such as the
collapse of Yamaichi Securities Co.
	   Yamaichi announced last November it was throwing in the towel,
leaving debts of more than 3 trillion yen (dlrs 22.38 billion) and
8,000 people without work.
	   Earlier this month, Toa Steel Co., an affiliate of leading
Japanese steelmaker NKK Corp., collapsed under a massive debt load.
	   Daido Concrete Co. failed earlier this year, and major food
company Toshoku Ltd. went under late last year as did leading
commercial lender Hokkaido Takushoku Bank.
 &UR; (pvs-cd) 	   
</TEXT>
