<HEADLINE>
Yeltsin: Russia will keep financing An-70 contruction in Ukraine
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Despite the economic crisis, Russia will keep
financing its share of the joint construction of An-70 planes with
Ukraine, President Boris Yeltsin said Monday.
	   In an order to the government signed Monday, Yeltsin said the
project remains a ``priority direction in the development of
(Russia's) aircraft industry,'' the ITAR-Tass news agency reported.
	   Yeltsin also told the government to pay for the testing of the
Antonov An-70 craft that have already been manufactured and to keep
up financing in the future, ITAR-Tass and the Interfax news agency
said.
	   Yeltsin's aide in charge of the project, Yevgeny Shaposhnikov,
met with German and Ukrainian officials in Bonn last week to
discuss possible funding by Germany and other European countries,
Interfax reported.
	   Since the fall of communism, Germany has become Russia's most
important trade partner outside the former Soviet Union, and a key
source of aid and credit.
	   Ukraine has also been trying to enlist Germany and France to
help build a Ukrainian version of the Antonov An-70 military
transport plane.
	   (ad/ml)
