<SLUG> BC-Zimbabwe-Congo-Lesotho </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Catholic Church urges removal of foreign troops from Congo,
</HEADLINE>
Lesotho &QL; 
 &UR; By ANGUS SHAW &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HARARE, Zimbabwe (AP) _ The Roman Catholic Church of Zimbabwe
called Monday for the removal of foreign troops from the Congo and
Lesotho.
	   The church's Catholic Commission for Justice and Peace said the
deployment of Angolan, Namibian and Zimbabwean troops in Congo, and
South African and Botswanan troops in Lesotho, came with
``extraordinary haste.''
	   ``The consequences of these military interventions are
far-reaching, costly and devastating for the ordinary people of the
affected countries,'' the commission said in a statement.
	   More could have been done, it added, to find diplomatic and
negotiated solutions in broad consultation with the continent-wide
Organization of African Unity and the United Nations.
	   Zimbabwe has sent nearly 3,000 troops, backed by warplanes and
armored cars, to support Congolese president Laurent Kabila battle
an insurrection.
	   Zimbabwe argues it had to act swiftly to prevent Kinshasa, the
Congolese capital, from falling to the rebels.
	   Last week's intervention in the Lesotho mountain kingdom that is
completely surrounded by South Africa left at least 67 troops from
both sides dead, along with several dozen civilians, and led to
widespread looting and arson.
	   The action aimed to prevent a military mutiny from escalating
into a coup, and to bolster the civilian government elected last
May against bitter opposition by rival political parties.
	   Zimbabwe is estimated to be spending up to dlrs 1 million a day
in Congo. Defense Minister Moven Mahachi declined to specify the
cost, but defended the operation. ``When a friend's house is on
fire, you don't ask where the money is, you just go and help him,''
he said.
	   In South Africa, despite widespread criticism of the
intervention _ directed more to its flawed execution than to its
motives _ president Nelson Mandela repeatedly has noted it came at
the request of the elected government, and was necessary and right.
	   He was scheduled to meet Tuesday in Cape Town with Lesotho's
King Letsie III.
	   (as-ewm)
</TEXT>
