<HEADLINE>
Serbia's leader threatens taking hostages in case of NATO strikes
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Serbia's ultra-nationalist vice
premier threatened Monday to take pro-Western Serbs hostage in case
of NATO air strikes.
	   Vojislav Seselj told Serbia's parliament that if they decide to
strike against Serbia, the U.S. and other Western countries
``should better withdraw'' all Serb ``traitors'' from Yugoslavia
``before we grab them'' and take them ``hostage.''
	   Seselj's list of pro-Western ``traitors'' included journalists
of independent Nasa Borba, Blic and Glas Javnosti dailies and
members of independent human rights, intellectual and peace groups,
such as the Belgrade Circle, Serbia's Helsinki Committee and the
Women in Black.
	   Seselj's address was greeted with loud applause from Serbian
deputies who discussed the Kosovo crisis.
	   Seselj, the leader of the ultra-nationalist Radical Party, who
is allied with Socialists of Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic
in the Serbian government, also said that Serbia's armed forces
``should use all available means'' to counter eventual NATO strike.
	   On Wednesday, NATO threatened action if Milosevic did not stop
the offensive against Kosovos's separatists and allow for the safe
return of refugees.
