r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Poll     09-28 0379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Poll </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Poll: Most Russians say wage payments should be government
</HEADLINE>
priority &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ A majority of Russians believe the new government
should concentrate on paying off back wages and pensions, a poll
released Monday indicated. The new government has said that would
be its top priority.
	   Respondents in a poll conducted last week by the independent
All-Russian Public Opinion Center were asked to name the top three
priorities for the government. Paying off wage debts was the top
choice, mentioned by 55 percent of those polled.
	   It was followed by reducing prices, mentioned by 46 percent,
``improving'' the ruble's exchange rate, mentioned by 40 percent,
and establishing price controls, by 37 percent, according to
results carried by the Interfax news agency.
	   Since Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov was appointed three weeks
ago, he has repeatedly stressed that his government's top priority
would be the payment of salaries and pensions.
	   According to estimates published in the Kommersant daily earlier
this month, Russia owed a total of 36 billion rubles (dlrs 2.4
billion) in back salaries and social payments.
	   Primakov said Monday his government has paid off its debt in
back salaries to the armed forces and will be able to pay students
their stipends within days.
	   Other priorities suggested in the poll included raising wages,
pensions and bank deposits to compensate for price increases (25
percent), fighting corruption and theft of state assets (22
percent), financial support for state-run enterprises (18 percent).
	   Support for private business was the least favorite among the 15
possible choices, mentioned by only 6 percent. In post-Soviet
Russia, private businesses have largely accounted for the creation
of a small middle class, which was expected to become the backbone
of economic and political stability. But many impoverished Russians
resent private business people.
	   Improving tax collection _ which is demanded by the
International Monetary Fund and other foreign lenders _ was
advocated by only 9 percent of those polled.
	   The poll of 2,400 people had a margin of error of plus or minus
3 percentage points. The report did not say how the poll was
conducted.
	   (ad/ml)
</TEXT>
