w1061 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Lesotho 1stLd-Writethru   09-28 0516
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lesotho, 1st Ld-Writethru,0515 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Public offices reopen, many Lesotho troops return to their bases
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with more details to clarify for some
points; NEW to others. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos MAS101-103 &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MASERU, Lesotho (AP) _ Thousands of public employees returned to
work Monday, when government offices opened in Lesotho's capital
for the first time since last week's South Africa-led intervention
to forestall a coup.
	   Meanwhile, about 1,000 Lesotho soldiers returned to their bases
Monday in uniform and with their weapons, as ordered, for review of
their roles in events of recent weeks. Rebels face possible
punishment. Others could be reinstated in the 2,000-member Lesotho
Defense Force.
	   It was unclear how many members of the force actually
participated in the rebellion, and how many simply resisted when
foreign troops intervened. Officials said Monday that those who did
not surrender by the end of the day would be presumed to be rebels
and tracked down by the intervention force.
	   Last week, South Africa and neighboring Botswana sent about
1,000 troops into Lesotho, a poor country of 2 million people
surrounded by South Africa, after the government requested help
dealing with an army mutiny and crippling strikes.
	   South Africa's first peacekeeping mission since apartheid got
off to a rocky start when the force arrived last Tuesday without
advance warning. Believing they were being invaded, both loyalist
and mutinous Lesotho soldiers turned their guns on the South
Africans.
	   The political and military unrest in this mountain kingdom
remained a priority for governments in the region.
	   The defense ministers of South Africa, Botswana and Zimbabwe
were scheduled to meet Monday in Maseru, and King Letsie III was to
travel Tuesday to Cape Town for talks with South Africa President
Nelson Mandela.
	   The capital city of 50,000 was mostly calm for a third day
Monday, but officials have estimated that it could take years to
repair the widespread devastation caused by arson and looting.
	   The security situation was largely under control, despite
occasional sniper attacks. Nevertheless, businessmen were uneasy
about reopening undamaged stores. Aid groups haven't restored food
distribution to rural, subsistence farming communities where most
of the people live.
	   South Africa's involvement has been criticized by opposition
parties in Parliament who condemned the military move as
unnecessary and costly in lives and money.
	   At least 67 troops from both sides died in Tuesday's
intervention, as well as at least 10 South African soldiers.
Thousands of refugees also fled to towns in South Africa seeking
shelter and food.
	   Prime Minister Pakalitha Mosisili, whose Lesotho Congress Party
won 79 of the 80 seats in parliament in elections last May, is
bitterly opposed by parties that garnered 39 percent of the vote _
but just a single seat.
	   They claim, without providing convincing evidence, that the vote
was rigged. The government and international observers say there
was little or no fraud.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Lesotho, 1st Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
