w1085 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UN-Philippines     09-28 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Philippines,0391 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Philippines calls on wealthy to give poor markets access, aid
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ The Philippines urged wealthy nations to
remove export barriers for goods from the developing world and
called for more development aid to bring South Asian economies back
from collapse.
	   The Philippines' foreign affairs secretary, Domingo Siazon, told
the General Assembly's annual debate that the Asian financial
crisis was his country's ``immediate global concern.''
	   ``For in its wake, millions of lives have been afflicted with
untold suffering. For in its path, nations may fall,'' he said.
	   Although badly hobbled by the Asian financial crisis, the
Philippine economy is in better shape than many of its harder-hit
neighbors.
	   Last week the Philippine government and the International
Monetary Fund agreed on a 1.5 percent economic growth target this
year. If the target is achieved, the Philippines would be one of
the few countries in Southeast Asia to avoid an economic
contraction as a result of the region's crisis.
	   For the good of the region, Siazon called on the industrialized
world and the United Nations to fight off protectionism ``which is
a commonplace and desperate response during economic downturns.
	   ``The richer economies, aside from fully implementing their
multilateral commitments ... should act to remove or minimize
market access barriers, especially on export products from
developing countries,'' he said.
	   He also decried the decline in development assistance from donor
countries.
	   ``Now more than ever, social amelioration programs and safety
nets that directly benefit the most vulnerable sectors in many
countries must be enhanced,'' he said.
	   On another matter, Siazon urged more international efforts to
help Cambodia reach a settled and democratic solution to its
political turmoil. Opposition parties have been protesting the
electoral victory of Hun Sen, who staged a violent coup last year.
	   He said efforts by the Association of Southeast Asian Nations,
the Friends of Cambodia group and the United Nations have not been
in vain.
	   ``They have just not been enough. Much could be done, a lot
should be done. But so much more needs to be done by the Cambodians
themselves to pull their country from the brink.''
</TEXT>
