<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iran-Rushdie </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Senior clerics say edict against Rushdie must be upheld
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By AFSHIN VALINEJAD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ The Islamic edict that calls for British
author Salman Rushdie's death is irrevocable and must be
implemented, two senior Iranian clerics were quoted as saying
Monday.
	   ``I heard that England is under the illusion that the fatwa
(edict) against the apostate Rushdie will be revoked. This fatwa is
irrevocable and cannot be changed at any time. It is obligatory to
carry out the fatwa,'' Grand Ayatollah Mohammad Fazel Lankarani,
said in a statement published in the hard line Resalat daily.
	   He said the Iranian government should be among the first in the
world to support the edict even if it does not intend to carry it
out.
	   Nouri Hamedani, another Grand Ayatollah, said the fatwa must be
enforced and no high-ranking Muslim scholar can issue a fatwa to
reverse it.
	   The words of the two clerics, who have a big following among
Iranians, carry substantial weight in Iran.
	   The debate over the edict has intensified after Foreign Minister
Kamal Kharrazi on Thursday distanced his government from a dlrs 2.5
million reward for Rushdie's death.
	   Rushdie has spent nearly a decade in hiding since the late
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini called for his death on Feb. 14, 1989,
claiming his book, ``The Satanic Verses,'' blasphemed Islam.
	   ``The issue of Rushdie will only end with killing him and all
the elements associated with the publishing of the book. The fatwa
of killing Rushdie will be implemented,'' the Resalat daily said in
an editorial.
	   The Rushdie affair has been the main hurdle in Iran's efforts to
improve ties with the European Union. Britain has sought better
ties in order to benefit from lucrative projects in Iran, which
have gone to France and other European countries.
	   Iran has been trying to change its foreign policy ever since
Khatami, a moderate cleric, became president in August 1997.
Khatami has underscored the need to replace confrontation with
dialogue in Iran's relations with the West, including the United
States.
	   But powerful hard-liners inside the Islamic regime have always
supported the death sentence and are likely to continue to do so.
	   Another senior cleric, Ayatollah Hossein Mazaheri, said the
edict remains valid and could not be changed.
	   ``The execution of the divine death sentence remains a duty for
every Muslim until the day of resurrection,'' the Islamic Republic
News Agency quoted Mazaheri, who is a representative for Iran's
Supreme leader Ayatollah Ali Khamenei in the central province of
Isfahan, as saying.
 &UR; av-ti 	   
</TEXT>
