<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Russia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Russian Duma speaker calls for union among Russia, Ukraine and
</HEADLINE>
Belarus &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ Russia's parliamentary speaker called
Monday for creation of a union among Russia, Ukraine and Belarus as
a means of overcoming their common economic and political problems,
a news report said.
	   Gennady Seleznyov, a member of the Communist Party and speaker
of parliament's lower house, the State Duma, said the creation of
such a union would help solve ``a great deal of problems.''
	   ``It would be hailed by our peoples as the most important event
of the 20th century,'' Seleznyov said in comments cited by the
Interfax news agency.
	   Seleznyov brought a State Duma delegation to Kiev on Monday for
two days of talks with Ukraine's leaders.
	   During his meeting with Ukrainian parliament Speaker Oleksandr
Tkachenko, the two men said they shared common views on how Russia
and Ukraine should develop, and pledged to enhance cooperation to
overcome the economic crisis the two countries are enduring.
	   But Seleznyov's meeting with Ukraine's Foreign Minister Borys
Tarasyuk later in the day appeared to show that the two sides
remain at odds over their attitude towards NATO, which has long
been a thorny issue in the two countries' relations.
	   Seleznyov criticized Tarasyuk for his earlier characteristic of
NATO as a ``remarkable organization'' and said that Ukraine and
Russia should pursue a joint policy towards the alliance, according
to Interfax.
	   Tarasyuk, in turn, said integration into European institutions
remains a priority for Ukraine along with close cooperation with
Russia, adding that ``NATO serves to support peace in stability''
in Europe.
	   Ukraine has favored close relations with NATO, eagerly
participating and hosting military maneuvers under the alliance's
Partnership for Peace Program.
	   Such an approach has won sharp disapproval from Russia, with the
State Duma refusing to ratify a Ukrainian-Russian friendship and
cooperation treaty earlier this year because of Ukraine's links
with NATO.
	   Seleznyov said the Duma plans to debate the treaty by the end of
the year, but added that Russian lawmakers remain ``very worried''
over Ukraine's plans to cooperate with NATO.
	   Russian President Boris Yeltsin and his Ukrainian counterpart
Leonid Kuchma signed the bilateral friendship and cooperation
agreement in May 1997, and Ukraine's legislature overwhelmingly
ratified it last January.
	   (vl/ml)
</TEXT>
