<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bulgaria-Media </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
President asks lawmakers to review a law on radio, TV
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SOFIA, Bulgaria (AP) _ Bulgarian President Petar Stoyanov asked
lawmakers Monday to review a law on radio and TV the opposition
says allows too much government control of the media and ignores
minority rights.
	   Siding with opposition demands, Stoyanov spelled out four points
on which he disagrees with the law sponsored by the government of
his party colleague Premier Ivan Kostov.
	   His move only suspends ultimate passage of the law which
Parliament approved last week. It will take effect if the lawmakers
ignore his remarks. But Premier Ivan Kostov said his party was
ready to discuss a review.
	   Stoyanov called for:
	   _ greater political balance in a 7-member media council that is
to supervise state radio and TV. The opposition fears the council
will reflect government views as four of its members are elected by
Parliament and three by the president;
	   _ nationwide broadcasts on state TV in minority languages,
particularly in Turkish, which the law allows only on regional
channels, while requiring the main programs to be in Bulgarian;
	   _ exemption of people who don't own TV sets from a fee imposed
on virtually all citizens and aimed to fund the state radio and TV;
	   - reversing a ban on commercials in state TV prime time.
	   All three opposition parties _ the Socialists of renamed
Communists, the social-democratic Euroleft and an alliance led by
an ethnic Turk's party _ have most vigorously protested against the
fees and the commercials ban. They have threatened to challenge the
law before the Constitutional Court which is empowered to revoke
legislation.
	   The cabinet wants the fees to gradually phase out government
funding of state media and put them under public control. The
opposition says the fees are unfairly imposed on people who don't
have TV sets or who pay for receiving state TV through cable
operators.
	   The government has said the ban on commercials would encourage
competition on the advertising market where the state TV, currently
the only one with nationwide coverage, holds the lion's share. The
opposition argues that the government wants to free space for loyal
private nationwide broadcasters, which it is to license.
	   It replaces an old one adopted under the previous Socialist
government. The Constitutional Court has invalidated key articles
of that law for imposing too much government control on the media.
	   (vz/vt/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
