<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Liberia </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Liberian leader Charles Taylor says he's in control after rival
</HEADLINE>
evacuated &QL; 
 &UR; By CHRISTOPHER BURNS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Liberian President Charles Taylor said Monday his
government was fully in control after new clashes with the
followers of his rival Roosevelt Johnson, in a country devastated
by years of civil war.
	   Taylor also said he fully supported the arrangement for
Johnson's airlift evacuation out of the country Friday from the
U.S. Embassy in Monrovia, Liberia, bringing an end to a diplomatic
standoff with Washington.
	   ``There's no fighting in Liberia. There was an attempt to
destabilize the government'' from Friday evening to Saturday
morning, Taylor told reporters after an hour-long meeting with
French President Jacques Chirac.
	   ``My government forces went in, settled the problem and, with a
very respectable arrangement with the United States,'' Johnson was
airlifted out of the country from the U.S. Embassy, he said in the
courtyard of the presidential Elysee Palace.
	   Johnson, taken Friday to Sierra Leone, is to be tried in
absentia for rape, murder, kidnapping and treason, he said.
	   ``The fact that the government forces would surgically move in,
solve this problem,'' Taylor said, ``showed that the government is
capable, that peace has finally come to Liberia, and that the
government is able to do what it was elected to do. That is provide
security and stability.''
	   But Taylor's forces were criticized by Washington after Johnson
fled to the embassy Sept. 19 during gun battles between his
supporters and government forces seeking to arrest him.
	   Taylor has insisted all shooting had occurred on Liberian
territory _ not on the embassy's grounds. While the shooting did
begin just outside the embassy gate, American diplomats have said
the Liberians were on American soil when the attack began.
	   Taylor has also defended his actions against Johnson's
supporters, saying the former warlord had created his own
mini-state in his neighborhood stronghold, largely populated by his
ethnic Krahn followers.
	   Chirac and Taylor, who was on a trip to court aid and trade,
announced no new agreements after their meeting.
	   ``It was not about just asking for assistance,'' Taylor said.
``It's about future bilateral cooperation.''
	   Taylor, on his first trip to Europe since being elected Aug. 1
last year, was on a three-day official visit to France that ends
Wednesday. He was to meet with several Cabinet ministers and visit
the port and wine region of Bordeaux.
	   Liberia's seven-year civil war ended in 1996, leaving an
estimated 200,000 people dead and 600,000 refugees. But fighting
had broken out again in recent months with fighters loyal to
Johnson.
	   Liberia, a nation founded by freed American slaves, was for
years one of the largest U.S. aid recipients.
	   (cb-eg)
</TEXT>
