<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Ukraine-Belarus </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Ukraine, Belarus set up banking consortium to battle financial
</HEADLINE>
crisis &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   KIEV, Ukraine (AP) _ Under pressure from the financial crisis in
neighboring Russia, Ukraine and Belarus agreed Monday to set up a
banking consortium to help settle payments between the two
countries, a news report said.
	   The sides also agreed to invite a Russian bank to join the
consortium, which already includes Ukraine's Prominvestbank, its
largest, and Belarus' Promstroibank, the Interfax news agency
reported.
	   The agreement was reached during a meeting between Ukrainian
Prime Minister Valery Pustovoitenko and his Belarusian counterpart,
Sergei Ling, who arrived in Kiev on Monday.
	   The formation of the consortium would help stabilize banking
transactions and enliven cooperation between Ukrainian and
Belarusian banks, which was seriously hampered by Russia's turmoil,
Prominvestbank chairman Volodymyr Matvienko said.
	   Ukraine and Belarus, which maintain close trade links with
Russia, were hit hard by the ruble's fall and the following turmoil
on Russia's financial market.
	   The three countries' leaders have communicated intensely over
past weeks, trying to come up with a quick solution to the crisis.
	   Separately, Pustovoitenko and Ling also discussed preparation of
a 10-year bilateral economic cooperation program, which the
Ukrainian and Belarussian presidents are expected to sign by the
end of 1998, according to Interfax.
	   Ukraine's Foreign Trade Minister Serhiy Osyka said
implementation of the program, which is already 70 percent
complete, would boost Ukrainian-Belarussian trade by up to dlrs 700
million next year.
	   Trade between the two countries amounted to dlrs 1.4 billion in
1997, and may fall to dlrs 1.1 billion this year due to the Russian
crisis, Osyka said.
	   (vl/ml)
</TEXT>
