<SLUG> BC-UN-Malaysia,0335 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Malaysia warns of global depression
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) - Malaysia's foreign minister, whose country
is facing an economic and political crisis, warned of a global
depression Monday unless developing countries helped reform the
international financial system.
	   Blaming overseas currency speculators for the economic crisis
that has swept his country and much of Asia, Abdullah Badawi told
world leaders at the U.N. General Assembly that the turmoil had
given developing countries second thoughts about the benefits of
globalization.
	   Without reforms, ``the threat of a global depression, as
devastating as the one that hit the world in the thirties, could
confront us,'' Badawi said.
	   Malaysia's economic problems, spurred by the Asian financial
crisis, are its worst in more than three decades. The economy
contracted by almost 7 percent in the second quarter of 1998,
pushing it into full-blown recession.
	   The crisis and opposition to Prime Minister Mahathir Mohamad's
decision to fire and arrest Anwar Ibrahim, his former deputy and
heir apparent, has sparked a series of protests in Malaysia.
	   Badawi said the international community ``must find consensus to
formulate necessary ground rules to keep in check the rapacious
nature of financial speculators and manipulators whose only
motivation is profit-making and profit-taking.''
	   He said international financial markets lacked transparency, and
called for rules governing the buying and selling of currencies.
	   ``It is now most urgent that the international financial market
be reformed. More than that, significant changes should be made to
the international financial architecture.''
	   He said that globalization and free trade were impossible until
developing countries were given the time to strengthen their
economies.
	   Otherwise, ``it would be a continuing form of exploitation of
the weak and poor nations by those that are powerful and rich.''
</TEXT>
