<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Chechnya, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chechen leader pledges to fight kidnappings, faces challenge
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with new conditions for release of Russian envoy in
3rd graf, edits throughout to strengthen opposition angle.

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Chechen President Aslan Maskhadov, under
increasing pressure from opposition leaders to resign, said his
government would publicly execute kidnappers to stop a crime wave
that has swept the breakaway republic, news agencies reported on
Monday.
	   Speaking on national television, Maskhadov claimed foreign
secret services were behind the Chechen gangs responsible for
frequent kidnappings in the region, the ITAR-Tass news agency
reported. He did not identify the countries.
	   Meanwhile, the abductors of Russia's presidential envoy to
Chechnya, Valentin Vlasov, said Monday they are ready to release
him in exchange for Doku Zavgayev, who headed Chechnya's pro-Moscow
government during the republic's 1994-96 independence war, the
Interfax news agency said.
	   Chechnya has seen an increase in kidnappings, theft, and
violence among armed gangs, Muslim sects and ethnic groups since
its 1994-96 independence war with Russia. Maskhadov's attempts to
rein in crime have brought little result.
	   Maskhadov's government faces growing opposition from Chechen
warlords, who plan to gather later this week and demand that he
take a tougher line in relations with Russia and fulfill other
demands, or resign, Interfax reported.
	   The warlords have refused to obey Maskhadov's orders and accuse
him of maintaining too-close relations with the Russian government.
	   Shamil Basayev, who served as Maskhadov's prime minister earlier
this year, has recently joined the others pushing for the
president's ouster.
	   Maskhadov turned down the warlords' demands over the weekend,
saying that he ``rejects the language of ultimatums and doesn't
intend to respond to letters of people who are guilty of breaking
the law,'' the report said.
	   Chechnya claims to be a sovereign nation, but Moscow says it
remains a part of Russia. No country has recognized Chechnya's
independence bid.
	   Despite his fight for independence, Russia considers Maskhadov a
moderate and has been willing to negotiate with him.
	   (pvs/nw/ml)
</TEXT>
