<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Gulf War </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iraqi book on Gulf War says Saddam signaled invasion plans
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; SALAH NASRAWI &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CAIRO, Egypt (AP) _ The U.S envoy to Iraq during the 1990 Gulf
crisis should have grasped Iraqi President Saddam Hussein's plans
to attack Kuwait from a meeting she had with him a week beforehand,
says a book published by the Iraqi government.
	   The book renews an old argument since President Bush presents a
different picture of then-U.S. Ambassador April Glaspie in excerpts
from his new book on the Gulf war, ``A World Transformed,'' which
began appearing Monday in Arab newspapers.
	   ``The Grand Duel and its Leader,'' the Iraqi government's first
official account of the 1991 Gulf War, states that Saddam did not
explicitly say he was going to invade Kuwait.
	   But it said he clearly indicated that he wanted to punish
Kuwait, which he accused of deliberately trying to bring oil prices
down and harm Iraq's economy by flooding the market.
	   ``It was not difficult for Glaspie to realize the decisive tone
of Saddam Hussein, whom she knew as a man who sees his country
equal to any other nation,'' said the book, a copy of which was
obtained by The Associated Press ahead of its official debut.
	   ``We do not want war because we know what it means, but do not
push us to consider it as the only way for us to live in dignity,''
Saddam is quoted as telling Glaspie.
	   ``I hope this message will reach the president (Bush) and won't
be left in the hands of the State Department,'' Saddam told
Glaspie.
	   ``I clearly understand this message,'' Glaspie is quoted as
answering Saddam.
	   In Bush's book, co-authored with former National Security
Adviser Brent Scowcroft, the president defends Glaspie as ``a
trusted veteran diplomat'' and blames Saddam for underestimating
American interests in the Gulf.
	   After the invasion, Glaspie was blamed by some for not making
clear to Saddam that the United States would oppose Iraq's military
steps against Kuwait.
	   Iraqi media published the minutes of Saddam's meeting with
Glaspie a few days after the Aug. 2, 1990, invasion to try to
portray Washington as having endorsed the incursion. Glaspie was
quoted as saying the United States had no position on Iraqi
territorial claims to Kuwait.
	   President Bush, in his book, expresses his worries that the war
did not have a clean end and that Iraq already was claiming it won.
	   The Iraqi book maintains that Iraq essentially was victorious,
noting that it was not Iraq but leaders of the U.S.-led Gulf War
coalition that asked for the cease-fire ending the fighting. It
says Saddam first heard about it on a radio news broadcast.
	   ``The American President George Bush must have realized that his
calculations were wrong, he was trapped and the only way out was to
ask for a cease-fire,'' the book said.
	   ``The Grand Duel and its Leader'' was written by Saddam's press
secretary during the war, Abdel-Jabbar Muhsen, and Hamid Saeed, a
former editor of the ruling Baath Party newspaper Al-Thawra.
 &UR; sn-ggl
</TEXT>
