<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Flooding,0238 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report: one dead, three injured in Mexico flooding
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Heavy rains swelled rivers in central Mexico
and triggered a mud slide in Mexico City on Monday, killing one
girl and injuring three people, local media reported.
	   Rainstorms soaked squatter communities perched on the steep
slopes of hillsides south of the city, and television footage
showed a stream of mud roaring down a gully there, with the ruins
of two homes that had been swept away.
	   The television network Televisa reported that a 13-year-old girl
died in the mudslide in Tierra Colorada, a squatter community
perched on the slopes of the Ajusco mountain. Three members of her
family were injured.
	   Some neighborhoods in a low-lying former lakebed to the east of
Mexico City have been flooded for days, and to the west, the Lerma
river overflowed its banks and left some villages inundated in
sewage.
	   Separately, Televisa reported that one child and one adult had
been swept away by swollen rivers in neighboring Puebla state and
were feared drowned Sunday.
	   Elsewhere, rivers overflowed in the southern state of Chiapas,
which was hit by flooding earlier this month that killed 185 people
and left thousands of towns and villages cut off from the outside
world.
	   Two temporary bridges built to replace ones destroyed in that
flooding were washed away again Sunday, local media reported.
</TEXT>
