w1147 &Cx1f; wstm-
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Soccer-UEFACup     09-28 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-UEFA Cup Preview </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Parma, Betis threatened with quick exit from UEFA Cup
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By STEPHEN WADE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Italy's Parma and Spain's Betis, two of Europe's
big spenders, are in danger of being eliminated from the lucrative
UEFA Cup. And it's only the first round.
	   And Germany's Stuttgart, thrashed two weeks ago at home 3-1 by
Dutch leaders Feyenoord, is as good as gone entering the second leg
_ one of 31 matches Tuesday across Europe.
	   Parma spent about dlrs 60 million this summer on transfers.
Seville-based Betis spent half that much on one player _ dlrs 35
million for Brazilian Denilson.
	   So far, the investments haven't paid off as both clubs return
home trailing 1-0.
	   Parma, 1995 UEFA champions and '93 Cup Winners Cup titlists, is
in big trouble. The Italians are injury-hit, struggling on offense
and, in Turkey's Fenerbache, face a club that's due to advance.
	   Parma's top striker Enrico Chiesa is out with an ankle injury,
and Croatian winger Mario Stanic is also hurt. Midfielder Dino
Baggio and defender Fabio Cannavaro are suspended on red cards.
	   History this time is either with _ or against _ Fenerbache. No
Turkish team in 16 tries has eliminated an Italian side from
European competition. Parma's last lost at home in cup play was
five years ago. Since then Parma is 15-1-0 at Tardini Stadium.
	   ``We want to write history by eliminating Parma,'' said
Fenerbache spokesman Ali Yildirim. ``We have the power to do
that.''
	   Fenerbache players are getting a substantial bonus _ reported
earlier at dlrs 18,000 _ for eliminating the Italians.
	   Betis, facing Danish side Vejle, is having what coach Manual
Ruiz de Lopera calls a ``cursed September,'' which includes four
league games without a victory, good for 19th in the 20-team
Spanish league.
	   ``The league (season) is long and there is still time to
recover,'' the coach said. ``But fouling up the UEFA Cup would have
no remedy and serious consequences for Betis.''
	   As for Denilson, he's yet to score in league play and newspapers
are ripping him for his non-team style. To make matters worse,
Betis' other striker _ Spanish international striker Alfonso Perez
_ may miss the game with an injury.
	   If you needed an early favorite, it would be Feyenoord.
	   The Rotterdam side has won all six of its league games and
defends a 3-1 lead against Stuttgart. Brazilian attacker Tininho is
injured, but Argentine striker Julio Cruz and Jon Dahl Tomasson
should provide the scoring.
	   Despite crowd disturbances in the first leg in Germany,
Rotterdam police are not expecting problems. ``We do not think this
is a high-risk match,'' police spokeswoman Laurie 't Hart said.
	   Fellow German side Bayern Leverkusen _ quarterfinalist last year
in the European Champions Cup _ is also in jeopardy of exiting
after a first-leg 1-1 draw at Udinese. The club is coming off a 1-0
league win over Schalke.
	   ``We had a good start at Schalke, so we hope to win against
Udinese,'' said coach Christoph Daum, who will be missing injured
Brazilian midfielder Emerson.
	   Udinese is tied for second in Italy's Serie A and has five goals
from Brazilian striker Marcio Amoroso _ the same number he scored
last season.
	   Udinese has never won away in the UEFA Cup.
	   In other key games on a crowded day:
	   _ English Premier League leader Aston Villa takes a 3-2 lead to
Norway's Stromsgodset, with disappointing 7-million-pound (dlrs
11.5 million) transfer Stan Collymore expected to get a last-ditch
start in his bid to stay with the team.
	   _ Atletico Madrid, semifinalists last year in the European
Champions Cup, takes a 2-0 lead to Obilic, Yugoslavia. The Yugoslav
team is owned by Serbia's notorious warlord Zeljko
Raznatovic-Arkan. Players have been banned from talking to
reporters and their cellular phones have been confiscated.
	   _ Italian league leader Fiorentina is up 2-1 in a tough match at
Croatia's Hadjuk Split. Fiorentina, alone in first place for the
first time in 16 years, is rolling with six wins in six league and
cup games. Gabriel Batistuta will have to play without suspended
strike partners Rue Costa and Luis Oliveira. Hajduk has played
three home games with Italian clubs and has won all three by 3-1
scores.
	   _ Red Star Belgrade goes to France's Metz with a 2-1 lead but
will be without top striker Perica Ognjenovic, who is suspended.
	   _ Germany's Schalke, 1997 UEFA champion, takes a 1-0 lead to
Slavia Prague. Slavia has scored only once in its last four
matches.
	   _ Rapid Vienna hosts French league leaders Bordeaux after a 1-1
draw in France with the French needing a precious away goal to
survive.
	   _ Olympique Marseille, playing its first European competition
after a four-year absence, is 2-2 and playing at home to Sigma
Olomouc of the Czech Republic. Marseille, No. 2 in the French
standings, won the European Champions Cup in 1993 but was ousted
from European play in a match-fixing scandal.
	   _ England's Leeds is up 1-0 going to Portugal's Maritimo. It is
likely to be the last match for coach George Graham, who is
reported moving to London club Tottenham.
	   (scw) 	   
</TEXT>
