<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Islamic Mayor </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
United States, European Union criticize jail term for Istanbul's
</HEADLINE>
Islamic mayor &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ The United States and the European Union
criticized the jail sentence given Istanbul's strongly pro-Islamic
mayor, saying Monday that the move heightened doubts about Turkey's
democracy.
	   Recep Tayyip Erdogan was sentenced to 10 months in prison for
reading a strident religious poem at a rally in December. The
sentence, upheld by an appeals court last week, means a lifetime
ban from public office for a man who was seen as a future leader of
Turkey's Islamic movement.
	   On Monday in Istanbul, Erdogan held talks with U.S.
Consul-General Carolyn R. Huggins, who expressed concern about his
sentencing, according to Turkey's semiofficial Anatolia news
agency.
	   The U.S. Embassy in Ankara decried the jailing.
	   ``It is a serious matter when democratically elected leaders are
subject to criminal prosecution by courts for statements they made
as political figures. Such developments weaken confidence in
Turkish democracy,'' a U.S. Embassy spokesman said, speaking on
condition of anonymity.
	   Adding to the international criticism, the 15-member European
Union expressed ``concern at the implications for democratic
pluralism and freedom of expression, which prosecution of
democratically elected politicians for nonviolent expression of
their views is bound to have.''
	   The EU rejected Turkey's application for membership in December,
saying then it was politically and economically unprepared and
still had serious human rights problems.
	   Turkey is a predominantly Muslim country governed by staunchly
secular laws, which the Islamic movement describes as undemocratic.
	   The courts convicted Erdogan of inciting racial hatred with a
two-line poem: ``Minarets are our bayonets, domes are our helmets,
mosques are our barracks, believers are our soldiers.''
	   On Thursday, 30,000 people gathered in front of Istanbul's city
hall to protest the appeals court's decision.
	   Monday, prosecutors launched an investigation into the mass
protest to determine whether the demonstration incited divisions in
society _ a crime under Turkish law.
	   (ht-ek)
</TEXT>
