<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Bosnia-War Crimes </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Bosnian Serb arrested by NATO to enter pleas Wednesday
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) _ A Bosnian Serb arrested by NATO
forces will Wednesday enter pleas to charges that he murdered,
raped and tortured Muslims and Croats in 1992, the Yugoslav war
crimes tribunal announced Monday.
	   Stevan Todorovic was snatched over the weekend by troops serving
in the NATO peace stabilization force in Bosnia. He was transferred
Sunday to U.N. cells in The Hague to await trial.
	   Todorovic, 41, is charged with atrocities allegedly committed
after he was appointed police chief of the northern Bosnian town of
Bosanski Samac following a Serb takeover of the area in early 1992.
	   In the year that followed, Bosanski Samac was the scene of a
ruthless campaign of terror and discrimination by Serb forces that
drove all but a handful of non-Serbs from the municipality.
	   Todorovic, the ninth suspect arrested by NATO forces in Bosnia,
is charged with five war crimes, five grave breaches of the Geneva
Conventions and five crimes against humanity. Each charge carries a
maximum sentence of life imprisonment.
	   Todorovic's July 1995 indictment alleges that he murdered one
Muslim, beat or tortured six others and forced two unidentified
prisoners to perform sexual acts on each other while other
prisoners and Serb guards watched _ an allegation that warrants a
rape charge under the tribunal's rules.
	   Set up in 1993 to bring to justice those responsible for
atrocities during conflicts in the former Yugoslavia, the tribunal
has indicted 58 suspects and has 26 in custody.
	   (mc) 	   
</TEXT>
