<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Netherlands-Mondrian Theft </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Painting by abstract pioneer Piet Mondrian stolen from museum
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MIDDELBURG, Netherlands (AP) _ A small oil painting by abstract
pioneer Piet Mondrian has been stolen from a Dutch museum, a
spokesman said Monday.
	   The painting titled ``The Tree'' was snatched from the Zeeuws
Museum in this southwestern Dutch city sometime between Thursday
night and Saturday morning, said museum director Ineke Spaander.
	   The museum bought ``The Tree'' in 1994 for 260,000 guilders
(dlrs 130,000), said Spaander.
	   She declined to give details surrounding the theft, but said
police have launched an investigation.
	   The 27-by-38-centimeter (10.8-by-15.2 inch) painting was created
by the Dutch master between 1908 and 1909. It was neither signed
nor dated.
	   The painting shows a black apple tree against a dark blue
background. The oil-on-paper was attached to cloth.
	   Spaander said the painting came ahead of Mondrian's modern
masterpieces which showed his signature brightly colored lines and
squares.
	   One such abstract work, ``Victory Boogie Woogie,'' was recently
purchased by the Dutch state for dlrs 40 million.
	   (jc/mc)
</TEXT>
