<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-Mercosur Cup-Gremio-Vasco,0307 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rehabilitated Gremio faces Vasco in Mercosur Cup
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) _ Gremio is slowly returning to its
old, winning form. And that could be bad news for Vasco, which
visits Gremio on Tuesday for a game for Group E of the Mercosur
Cup.
	   Gremio needs to win to maintain a realistic chance of qualifying
for the next round. The team is in third place in Group E with four
points, two behind co-leaders Vasco and River Plate of Argentina.
	   With its final game against powerful River Plate in Buenos
Aires, Gremio has to make the most of its home advantage in Porto
Alegre, in far southern Brazil.
	   A victory on Tuesday would give Gremio at least second place.
And if River loses to Universidad Catolica in Chile, the
``gauchos'' could take sole possession of first place.
	   Gremio, the 1996 Libertadores Cup champion, is gradually
recovering its winning ways after a shaky start in the Mercosur Cup
and the Brazilian national championship.
	   After two quick losses to River and Vasco, Gremio pounded U.
Catolica 5-1 at home and tied the Chileans in Santiago.
	   In the Brazilian championship, Gremio has won its last two games
and is in ninth place among the 32 first-division teams.
	   Vasco, the defending Brazilian and Libertadores Cup champion,
has coasted through the Mercosur Cup using its reserve team.
	   The second-string squad, nicknamed ``the little express,'' added
three ties, including two with River Plate, to the victory over
Gremio.
	   And it's the reserve team that will face Gremio on Tuesday, as
Vasco coach Antonio Lopes saves his starters for the national
championship and for the world inter-club championship against
Spain's Real Madrid in December.
	   The game starts at 9:40 p.m. (0040 GMT Wednesday) in Olimpico
Stadium.
</TEXT>
