<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Romania-Corruption </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Opposition accuses Romania's president of meddling in judicial
</HEADLINE>
affairs

<TEXT>
	   BUCHAREST, Romania (AP) _ Romania's opposition Monday accused
President Emil Constantinescu of unlawfully interfering in the
country's judicial system in his battle against corruption.
	   ``For some time, in the context of the struggle against
organized crime, he (the president) subordinated the state's
institutions,'' former Interior Minister Doru Ioan Taracila read in
a statement in front of parliament.
	   When Constantinescu came to power in November 1996, he made the
eradication of corruption one of his main priorities. He set up
special committees in each county to deal with corruption cases.
	   But there has been an uproar over these bodies, which answer to
a national board comprised of the president, intelligence and
government officials.
	   Most opposition politicians argue that the Justice and Interior
ministries are the only organizations authorized to deal with
financial crimes.
	   They claim Constantinescu has interfered with the authority of
the Justice and Interior ministries by staffing his anti-corruption
board with employees from these ministries.
	   Despite several anti-corruption campaigns, Constantinescu
acknowledged Friday that the economy has lost 3,500 billion lei
(almost dlrs 389 million) in the past 18 months because of
financial irregularities.
	   Taracila, a prominent member of the leftist Social Democracy
Party serving in parliament's upper chamber, said his party was
studying Constantinescu's possible impeachment for
``unconstitutional acts.''
	   (ma/am/scl)
</TEXT>
