<HEADLINE>
FA lodges misconduct charge against player for shoving ref
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with comments from sports minister &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ Italian striker Paolo Di Canio of Sheffield
Wednesday was charged with misconduct Monday by the Football
Association for shoving a referee to the ground _ an act which
could result in a lengthy ban from the English game.
	   The FA gave Di Canio 14 days to respond to the charge and
request a personal hearing over what was described as a ``reported
assault'' on referee Paul Alcock.
	   Di Canio pushed Alcock after being sent off during Saturday's
1-0 win against Arsenal at Hillsborough. He later accused the ref
of play-acting, comparing him to a player diving to win a penalty.
	   Danny Wilson, Sheffield Wednesday's manager, announced an
immediate suspension of Di Canio pending sanctions from the FA.
	   The FA's misconduct charge could result in a six-month ban or
even in an expulsion from the Premier League.
	   British Sports Minister Tony Banks condemned Di Canio and urged
the FA to ``chuck the book at him.''
	   ``This was an incident too far,'' Banks said. ``All of us
involved in football, whether as supporters or players, have
shouted at the referee as passions run high. But you cannot assault
the referee. There has to be a limit _ the referee stands between
us and chaos, and this was totally unacceptable.
	   ``This is a matter for the FA, and I think they should chuck the
book at him. This is so serious that an example has to be made of
the player.
	   ``To say that the referee `took a dive' is just compounding what
he has done.''
