<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Politics, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Union leaders sour over tight economic policies
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMs. RECASTS and UPDATES with Trade Secretary quote;
background; recaps &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By MAUREEN JOHNSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BLACKPOOL, England (AP) _ Trade union leaders on Monday accused
the Labor Party _ which they help bankroll _ of following
unnecessarily stringent economic policies.
	   But Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon Brown, addressing Labor's
annual conference in this northern town, insisted ``there is no
other way.''
	   ``Don't just give us a vision of the promised land, give us a
place in it,'' declared Rodney Bickerstaffe, leader of Britain's
biggest union, UNISON.
	   Bickerstaffe, whose union represents hundreds of thousands of
low-paid government workers, such as hospital cleaners, was greeted
with thunderous applause by delegates.
	   It underlined a change in atmosphere at this year's convention
compared with a year ago when the conference was largely an
ebullient celebration of Labor's landslide election victory in May
1997, which ended 18 years of Conservative Party rule.
	   Labor remains well ahead _ some 25 points _ of the
still-battered Conservatives in opinion polls.
	   But the strict economic polices, aimed at holding inflation to
2.5 percent, are angering both trade unions and manufacturers
because the resulting high value of the British pound makes it hard
to sell exports and encourages relatively cheap imports.
	   Brown said any short-term pains will be worth the long-term
gains of stable growth with few inflationary pressures.
	   ``It is because of our commitment to long-term stability, even
more essential at a time of world instability, that from this
government there will be no U-turns. No left turns. No right
turns,'' said Brown.
	   ``I tell this conference there is no other way, no solution, or
even comfort, in soft options, no magic wand solution, no quick-fix
alternative to these long-term policies for achieving the goals we
share.''
	   Although applause during Brown's speech was subdued, most of the
delegates gave him a standing ovation at the end.
	   Ken Jackson, head of the engineering workers' union, a moderate
union that has been a prime supporter of Blair's centrist ``New
Labor'' policies, said he would continue to campaign for the
government to take back control of interest rates.
	   ``We have to reflect the views of our members who see the future
in manufacturing as under threat,'' said Jackson. ``Both sides of
industry are now saying that we are facing problems.''
	   As a key to keeping Britain on track for his inflation target,
Brown last year took the power to set interest rates away from
politicians and gave it to the Bank of England, which has tightened
monetary policy.
	   Blair, who has a huge parliamentary majority and thus enormous
power, argues that the tight policies will end what Labor calls the
``boom and bust'' cycle of the British economy.
	   (mj-acw)
</TEXT>
