<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Hand Transplant </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Good weekend for man with grafted right hand
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LYON, France (AP) _ A man who received a new forearm and hand in
a rare operation last week is eating and drinking normally, four
days after the 13-hour surgery, the hospital administration said
Monday.
	   The grafted right hand, it added, is ``well colored'' --
apparently a good sign.
	   The five-line statement identified the patient for the first
time by name: Clint Hallam. Hospital personnel said Hallam hails
from New Zealand but lives in Perth, Australia.
	   ``Clint Hallam ... had a very good weekend ..., the statement
said.
	   It added that the dressing was changed and ``he will be able to
get up today.''
	   Neither the press service for the Lyon public hospital system
nor doctors at Edouard Herriot Hospital could confirm whether
Hallam did, indeed, leave his bed.
	   At the hospital, his condition was described simply as
``satisfactory.''
	   Dr. Jean-Michel Dubernard, co-head of the transplant team, was
not immediately available for comment.
	   Hallam, 48, had his right hand amputated in 1989 after an
accident.
	   In Thursday's painstaking operation to give Hallam the forearm
and hand of an anonymous donor, arteries, veins, nerves, tendons,
muscles and skin were attached after the two bones of the forearm
were set.
	   The surgery represented a breakthrough that was hailed by the
University of Louisville Medical Center, where such a transplant is
planned before the end of the year.
	   ``It gives hope to all those who are victims of domestic or work
accidents, anti-personnel mines, or have congenital deformations,''
Dubernard told French television after Thursday's surgery.
	   Among the risks ahead for Hallam are how well he will accept
anti-rejection drugs that can be potentially fatal. The drugs
suppress the immune system to keep the body from trying to destroy
the foreign tissue. That could also raise the risk of infection,
cancer and even death.
	   Other problems include nerve regeneration to allow sensation. A
transplant patient may never regain feeling of hot and cold in
their new hand.
	   Doctors in Ecuador tried in the 1960s, but the patient's body
rejected the hand after two weeks.
	   (eg)
</TEXT>
