<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-San Marino,0233 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
San Marino seeks to promote human rights in short speech
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ The republic of San Marino highlighted its
efforts to strengthen human rights in a speech to the General
Assembly, which is celebrating the 50th anniversary of the U.N.
Universal Declaration on Human Rights.
	   Gabriele Gatti, the foreign minister of San Marino, noted that
his tiny country paid for a project to translate the declaration
into 250 languages.
	   ``The principles contained in the declaration represent today,
more than ever before, the essence of a civilized way of living
together in a modern society,'' Gatti said.
	   He called for the abolition _ or at least limitation of _ the
death penalty, which he said was abolished in San Marino in 1865.
	   ``The government and the people of San Marino deeply believe
that death imposed by law cannot represent a valid protection for
society nor a deterrent for crime,'' he said.
	   San Marino, a mountainous, 23-square-mile (60-square-kilometer)
landlocked republic, is situated in northeast Italy, 150 miles (240
kilometers) south of Venice. It depends on tourism, postage stamps
and financial services for income.
	   Founded in the year 301, San Marino calls itself the world's
oldest republic, with an unbroken line of elected government
officials since at least the year 1244.
</TEXT>
