<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Cape Verde-Plane Crash </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Commuter plane crashes in Cape Verde islands; 1 killed, 19 injured
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ A commuter plane with 20 people on board
crash-landed Monday in the Cape Verde islands off West Africa,
killing one passenger and injuring the others, including the
country's Prime Minister Carlos Veiga, according to news reports.
	   Veiga was under observation at Agostinho Neto Hospital in Praia,
the capital of the island group 480 kilometers (300 miles) off the
coast of Senegal, the Portuguese news agency Lusa reported. He
suffered bruises but his life was not in danger.
	   One of Veiga's bodyguards was killed in the crash and two other
members of his staff had ``worrying'' injuries, Lusa quoted a
government source as saying.
	   Others on board the plane suffered slight injuries, the report
said, but gave no details.
	   The names of the injured were not immediately available.
	   The Twin Otter two-engine plane, belonging to the state-owned
Cape Verde Air Transport company, crashed as it landed at Praia
airport during a storm.
	   The cause of the crash was not immediately known, according to
Lusa. The airline declined to comment.
	   The plane was on a regularly scheduled flight between two of the
former Portuguese colony's 10 islands, Lusa said.
	   Veiga has been prime minister of Cape Verde since its first
democratic elections, held in 1991. He was reelected in 1996.
	   Cape Verde gained independence from Portugal in 1975.
	   (bh/dw)
</TEXT>
