r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Russia-Prisons     09-28 0185
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-Prisons </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Justice minister: Russian prisons spend less than half-cent per
</HEADLINE>
inmate &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ Russia spends just 70 kopeks a day _ the
equivalent of less than half a U.S. cent _ for each prisoner in its
vast prison system, the justice minister said Monday.
	   Pavel Krasheninnikov said the amount was enough to buy 300 grams
(10 ounces) of bread for each prisoner, according to the Interfax
news agency.
	   Russia has the world's highest incarceration rate, and a long
history of brutal prisons and labor camps that date to czarist
times but were expanded under the Soviet regime.
	   The prison system holds over 1 million prisoners in 13 prisons
and hundreds of other facilities, according to government
statistics released last year.
	   In July, President Boris Yeltsin transferred authority over
prisons from the Interior Ministry to the Justice Ministry, saying
the prison system badly needed reform.
	   Krasheninnikov said the situation might be improved by
increasing the number of prisoners released in one of the
government's periodic amnesties.
	   (ml)
</TEXT>
