<HEADER>
w1188 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Turkey-Italy-Kurds     09-28 0239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-Italy-Kurds </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Turkey protests Kurdish meeting in Rome's parliament building
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ Turkey protested a planned meeting of the
Kurdish parliament-in-exile in Rome, saying Monday it was
especially galling that the meeting would be in Italy's own
parliament building.
	   A group of Italian lawmakers invited the self-proclaimed Kurdish
parliament, whose earlier meetings in Russia, the Netherlands,
Norway, Austria and Denmark also triggered protests from Turkey.
	   Its Rome meeting is set for Tuesday. Turkey objected in a note
to Italy's Foreign Ministry.
	   ``We informed them of our displeasure and expressed our
expectations that the meeting should not be held in Rome,
especially not in the parliament's building,'' said Haldun Otman, a
Foreign Ministry spokesman.
	   The Italian Embassy in Ankara said it was a personal invitation
from the Italian lawmakers.
	   The Kurdish group includes some former Kurdish members of
Turkey's parliament, who fled the country when their party was shut
down in 1994 for ties with Kurdish rebels.
	   The rebels are fighting for greater autonomy for Turkey's Kurds;
the 14-year-old war has killed more than 37,000 people.
	   The first meeting of the parliament-in-exile caused a diplomatic
clash between the Netherlands and Turkey, which recalled its
ambassador for two months and suspended arms purchases from the
Dutch.
	   (ht-ek)
</TEXT>
