<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Greece-Turkey </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Greece, Turkey both to take part in NATO exercises for fist time
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   ATHENS, Greece (AP) _ For the first time in 13 years, Greece and
Turkey will jointly take part in a NATO exercise in the Aegean Sea.
	   An announcement issued by the general defense staff said Greece
will take part in the annual ``Dynamic Mix,'' a large 21-day air,
land and sea exercise held in the region.
	   More than 17,000 troops and forces from Britain, Canada, France,
Greece, Germany, Holland, Italy, Portugal, Spain, Turkey and the
United States will take part in the exercise. It will include 62
ships and 170 aircraft.
	   In April, Greece did not participate in NATO's ``Distant
Thunder'' maneuvers because of its longstanding disputes with
Turkey over the Aegean Sea.
	   Last year, Athens took part in ``Dynamic Mix,'' but Ankara
boycotted the maneuvers because NATO forces based in Turkey were
not included in the exercise's Aegean Sea part.
	   Greece's participation in ``Dynamic Mix'' last year was its
first in 13 years.
	   NATO allies Greece and Turkey have nearly gone to war twice in
the past 11 years over disputes on air, sea and seabed mineral
rights in the Aegean.
	    &UR; pq
</TEXT>
