<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Lebanon-UNRWA </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. agency's Beirut office at heart of corruption allegations
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) _ Already beset by financial burdens, the
U.N. agency that cares for 3.5 million Palestinian refugees faces a
new problem _ corruption allegations.
	   Wolfgang Plasa, Beirut director of the United Nations Relief and
Works Agency, was dismissed earlier this month as allegations of
wrongdoing at the agency's Lebanon offices became public.
	   Sources close to Plasa told the leading Beirut daily An-Nahar
Saturday that the former director was on the offensive to clear his
name.
	   An Amman-based UNRWA liaison officer said Plasa was trying to
uncover ``issues relating to building some schools.''
	   ``So far, such allegations were not proved,'' the liaison
officer, Maher Nasser, told The Associated Press in Amman. He did
not elaborate.
	   An-Nahar quoted sources as saying Plasa may have been dismissed
when he began to investigate wrongdoings or that he blew the
whistle after UNRWA did not renew his contract, which expires Oct.
14.
	   One source said that Plasa ``found problems'' in UNRWA's work in
Lebanon and started a probe, ``discovering what could form a good
basis for a large investigation.'' The source did not elaborate.
	   ``There is a problem and money spent, but we don't know exactly
whether it was stolen or not,'' the source told An-Nahar.
	   Nasser said the corruption allegations were ``briefly
discussed'' in Amman on Monday by UNRWA's 10-member Advisory
Commission, which reviewed the agency's overall performance.
	   He said UNRWA's Commissioner-General Peter Hansen had dispatched
officials to Lebanon to ``investigate the allegations.''
	   ``If it is proven that there was embezzlement or corruption in
UNRWA, whether in Lebanon or elsewhere, we will pursue the policy
of hitting with an iron hand those who touch money allocated for
the 3.5 million refugees we serve,'' Nasser said.
	   UNRWA, which is headquartered in the Palestinian Gaza Strip, has
been facing financial difficulties because of limited funding from
donor countries.
	   For the past 18 months, UNRWA's management has repeatedly warned
that its growing budget shortfall was forcing it to implement
austerity cuts. Hansen said in March that donor nations had given
the agency dlrs 237 million to meet a budget of dlrs 314 million
this year.
	   Earlier this month, thousands of UNRWA employees staged a
one-day strike, closing schools and clinics across the Middle East.
The workers were demanding pay raises and other benefits that had
been delayed for years by the agency's tight finances.
	   The agency, which has a staff of 22,000, provides education,
health and relief services to refugees. It was set up in 1948 after
the creation of the state of Israel.
	   Some 3.5 million refugees in the West Bank, the Gaza Strip,
Lebanon, Syria and Jordan are now registered with UNRWA, and that
population is growing at around 4 percent annually.
 &UR; sfg-jjh-sf 	   
</TEXT>
