<SLUG> BC-Cape Verde-Plane Crash,0239 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Commuter plane crashes in Cape Verde islands
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   LISBON, Portugal (AP) _ A commuter plane crashed Monday in the
Cape Verde islands off West Africa, killing one passenger and
injuring the other 19 people on board, including the country's
prime minister, according to news reports.
	   Prime Minister Carlos Veiga was under observation at Agostinho
Neto Hospital in Praia, the capital of the island group 480
kilometers (300 miles) off the coast of Senegal, the Portuguese
news agency Lusa reported. He suffered bruises, but his injuries
were not life threatening.
	   One of Veiga's bodyguards died in the crash, Lusa quoted a
government source as saying. Others on board the plane suffered
slight injuries, the report said, but no details were available.
	   The names of those injured were not immediately available.
	   The Twin Otter two-engine plane, belonging to the state-owned
Cape Verde Air Transport company, crashed as it landed at Praia
airport during a storm.
	   The cause of the crash was not immediately known, according to
Lusa. The airline declined to comment.
	   The plane was on a regularly scheduled flight between two of the
former Portuguese colony's 10 islands, Lusa said.
	   Veiga has been prime minister of Cape Verde since its first
democratic elections, held in 1991. He was re-elected in 1996.
	   Cape Verde gained independence from Portugal in 1975.
</TEXT>
