<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Macedonia-Arrests </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
With BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Four Macedonian Albanians arrested, two sentenced in Serbia &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   SKOPJE, Macedonia (AP) _ Two ethnic Albanians were sentenced in
Serbia Monday, and police in neighboring Macedonia said four more
suspected bombers were arrested.
	   The Belgrade-based state news agency Tanjug said two Kosovo
Albanians were sentenced to eight years in jail each for
``terrorist activities'' in Serbia's embattled Kosovo province.
	   Over 1,000 Kosovo Albanians, of whom over 500 have been
arrested, are suspected of an armed uprising in order to secede the
Kosovo province from Serbia.
	   In Macedonia, which has its own restive ethnic Albanian
minority, four people were arrested over the past weekend on
suspicion of belonging to a group which planted bombs that went off
in six different Macedonian towns in the last 10 months.
	   Ethnic Albanians make up 23 per cent of the 2-million Macedonian
population.
	   Four other alleged group members were arrested earlier this
month, and one was killed in a police raid.
	   Responsibility for two of the explosions was claimed by the
Kosovo Liberation Army, a militant organization fighting for
Kosovo's independence.
	   Police said Monday they discovered ``large quantities of
automatic and other firearms smuggled from Albania, as well as
ammunition and explosive devices ... intended for terrorist
actions.''
	   Three suspects escaped the raids, while terrorism charges will
be brought against the eight arrested, the report said.
	   The bombings attributed to the suspects injured none but caused
major damage: targets were courts, police stations, army barracks
and railroad stations.
	   (kt/ds) 	   
</TEXT>
