<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Slovakia-Elections, 3rd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Slovak opposition works on forming new government
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with Merciar holding coalition talks; ADDS byline &QL; 
 &UR; By ANDREA LORINCZOVA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRATISLAVA, Slovakia (AP) _ Opposition parties held private
consultations Monday at forming a new government after sealing an
apparent victory in Slovak national elections by declaring their
intent to unite.
	   But weeks of political friction and uncertainty are likely
following results that also would keep Prime Minister Vladimir
Meciar's hard-line ruling party as the single biggest party in
Parliament.
	   Meciar's Movement for a Democratic Slovakia, began sounding out
several opposition groups Monday to see if they were interested in
joining a new government.
	   Only one -- the far-rightwing Slovak National Party -- showed
any interest. Party Chairman Jan Slota, who was in the previous
government, said he was interested in any coalition which did not
include the minority Hungarians.
	   Two other groups sounded out by Meciar's movement -- the Party
of Civic Understanding and the Party of the Democratic Left --
ruled out any coalition with him.
	   ``It's going to be a tough month,'' Milan Ftacnik, deputy
chairman of the Party of the Democratic Left, acknowledged Sunday
after the release of unofficial results touched off immediate
dickering over the makeup of the new government.
	   Official results are expected Tuesday morning, the Central
Election Commission said.
	   Meciar, who has ruled Slovakia in strong-handed fashion for six
years, has remained conspicuously absent from view since voting
Friday at the start of two-day parliamentary elections. Barring a
stunning change in figures when the official vote count is released
Monday night or Tuesday, his likeliest options now are to serve as
minority leader in Parliament or resign.
	   His spokesman, Marian Kardos, said Monday that Meciar was at a
spa outside Bratislava for a back problem that required intravenous
treatment. He did not elaborate.
	   The leaders of the top four opposition parties, headed by the
Slovak Democratic Coalition, have reiterated their intent to form a
governing coalition after results indicated they won 93 of the 150
seats in Parliament.
	   Finishing ahead of all 16 other parties will give Meciar the
first crack at forming a governing coalition, but his chances
appear bleak.
	   The country's neighbors in Central Europe were happy with the
result _ particularly Hungary, which has complained of
discrimination against Slovakia's 550,000-strong ethnic Hungarian
minority.
	   Referring to Meciar, the Budapest daily Nepszabadsag said ``the
man who failed in the ... elections has left an ugly legacy for
Slovakia.''
	   ``If `Vlado' remains in power, the semi-democracy and the
unbridled crony-privatization will continue, Slovakia will never
get into NATO and the EU, and will become a pariah just like
Yugoslavia,'' the newspaper said.
	   (al/dc/reid)
</TEXT>
