<SLUG> BC-UN-Iraq, 4th Ld-Writethru,0617 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Aziz meets with Annan, U.N. inspection stalemate looms
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; URGENT &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: COMBINES pvs, REORGANIZES top 5 graphs, RAISES background. &QL; 
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Iraqi's deputy prime minister said Monday
that Baghdad won't make concessions to end the standoff over arms
inspections, saying his country had complied fully with U.N.
resolutions demanding that it destroy its banned weapons.
	   The Security Council should make the first move and conduct a
comprehensive review of sanctions and Iraq's efforts over seven
years to disarm itself, Tariq Aziz said, adding that the council
was legally and morally bound by its own resolutions to do so.
	   ``The idea that Iraq should do this or that concession before
the comprehensive review takes place is not legal,'' Aziz said.
	   Aziz spoke to reporters after meeting with Secretary-General
Kofi Annan on the standoff and the U.N. chief's proposal of a
``comprehensive review'' to break the logjam.
	   The Security Council asked Annan to formulate such a proposal
earlier this month, hoping that Iraq would back down from the
standoff knowing that a comprehensive review could highlight Iraq's
work to destroy its banned weapons.
	   The council stressed that no such review would take place until
Iraq rescinds its Aug. 5 decision to stop cooperating with U.N.
inspectors.
	   U.N. arms experts must report that Iraq has destroyed its
chemical, biological and nuclear weapons _ and the long-range
missiles to deliver them _ before the council will lift sanctions
imposed after Iraq invaded Kuwait in 1990.
	   Iraq stopped cooperating with inspectors after the chief U.N.
weapons inspector, Richard Butler, refused to certify that it had
destroyed its banned weapons.
	   Aziz was instructed to insist that the United Nations take the
first step in ending the stalemate, Iraq's vice president, Taha
Yassin Ramadan, said in a statement carried Friday by the official
al-Iraq newspaper.
	   Aziz told reporters: ``I would like to say that the idea of a
comprehensive review is not a reward to be given to Iraq and then
Iraq has to make concessions before such a review takes place. The
review is an obligation _ a legal and moral obligation by the
Security Council itself.''
	   Aziz said his meeting with Annan was professional, cordial and
constructive, and that he thanked the U.N. chief for trying to put
together a comprehensive review.
	   Another meeting with Annan was planned before the week was out,
Aziz said, adding that he would be meeting with Security Council
members as well.
	   Monday's meeting comes as chemical weapons experts have been
meeting at U.N. headquarters to discuss the findings of Swiss and
French laboratories testing missile fragments for suspected traces
of the deadly VX gas.
	   Preliminary results from the European labs have been
inconclusive, diplomats have said.
	   A U.S. Army lab reported finding traces of the gas in June but
Baghdad disputed the findings.
	   Butler agreed to send other samples to European labs, though he
has said Saddam Hussein still must answer for the positive U.S.
tests.
	   In a related matter, Annan appointed a German official with the
U.N. Development Program, Hans von Sponeck, as the new humanitarian
coordinator for Iraq.
	   He replaces Dennis J. Halliday, who bowed out after criticizing
U.N. sanctions against Iraq and pushing to get more aid for Iraqis.
	   Von Sponeck will take over the distribution network of the U.N.
oil-for-food program, which allows Iraq to sell limited amounts of
oil to buy food, medicine and other humanitarian goods.
</TEXT>
