<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Election, 8th Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Germany's new government takes form: Schroeder taps the Greens
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: AMS; Recasts throughout. &QL; 
 &UR; With BC-Germany-Election-Industry &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By COLLEEN BARRY &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) -- After ousting Chancellor Helmut Kohl in
national elections, a beaming Gerhard Schroeder declared Monday he
will try to forge a coalition with the Social Democrats he led to
power and a small environmentalist party that has never before been
in government.
	   While Germans voted for sweeping political change after 16 years
of conservative rule, pairing the pragmatic Social Democrats with
the sometimes pacifist Greens presents unique challenges for
Europe's largest nation.
	   At his first post-election news conference, Schroeder kept his
message broad, offering reassurances to his country and the world
that his government would continue the stability Kohl, the West's
longest-serving leader, secured during his four terms.
	   ``Nobody needs to be afraid. We will ensure continuity in
foreign policy,'' Schroeder said. ``The international community can
rely on Germans to remain good partners.''
	   Commitment to NATO was not in question, Schroeder said,
addressing concerns that the Greens' anti-militaristic tendencies
might jeopardize Germany's role in European security. More radical
Greens call for the dissolution of the security alliance.
	   One of the first tests of the new government could be German
participation in proposed NATO strikes to quell bloodshed in the
Serb-led Yugoslav province of Kosovo. Schroeder skirted that issue
by saying Kohl technically was still in power.
	   With party chief Oskar Lafontaine at his side on the dais,
Schroeder grinned and cracked jokes while fielding questions about
his plans. Tensions from months of tough campaigning clearly melted
away with the Social Democrat's sweeping 41 percent victory.
	   The future chancellor avoided committing his government to
specific plans before opening negotiations Friday with his
potential partners. The Social Democrats and Greens have some sharp
policy differences in key areas such as defense and energy
policies.
	   On one point Schroeder was emphatic: Drawing the Greens into
government would not compromise any of the Social Democrats'
center-left policies and campaign pledges. ``The Greens are going
to have to prepare for a clear and tough round of talks,'' he said.
	   Eager to enter government for the first time, the Greens
emphasized ideas the parties share: combating unemployment,
scrapping nuclear energy and giving long-time foreign residents of
Germany dual nationality.
	   Party leaders, new to the center stage of national politics,
appeared amused and bewildered by the throngs of international
journalists pelting them with questions Monday and blinding them
with TV lights.
	   Joining government would be a test of whether the Greens can
curb some of its idealism to cooperate with a more mainstream
party. A Social Democrat-Greens alliance would be postwar Germany's
most radical government, drawing in a party whose environmentalist
zeal has alienated and drawn ridicule from some Germans.
	   The standard Greens platform calls for raising the price of gas
to 5 marks (dlrs 3) a liter and setting a 100 kilometer (60 mile)
an hour speed limit on the autobahn. Greens even oppose Germany's
new high-speed magnetic levitation train scheduled to open in 2005,
on the principle that it will harm animals along the route.
	   Proposals such as these are completely out of the question,
Schroeder's party made clear even during the campaign. It is up to
the Greens to work out their internal problems, Schroeder said
Monday, emphasizing that his party will call the shots. The Social
Democrats have 298 seats in the 669-seat parliament; the Greens
have 47.
	   Even when the parties agree in principle, on issues such as
nuclear power, the Social Democrats are far more pragmatic.
Recognizing Germany's energy needs, they commit themselves vaguely
to shutting down nuclear plants ``as soon as possible.'' The Greens
say right away.
	   The Social Democrats will try to reach agreement with the Greens
within 30 days. Germany's constitution gives no deadline for
forming a government, but the new parliament must convene by Oct.
27. The parliament will then elect a chancellor, in this case
Schroeder, who will in turn designate his Cabinet and a coalition.
	   The Kohl government remains as a caretaker until the new
parliament convenes.
	   (cb-aet) 	   
</TEXT>
