<SLUG> BC-India-Rebel Ambush,0204 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Five soldiers, two civilians killed in rebel ambush
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   GAUHATI, India (AP) _ Separatist rebels armed with automatic
weapons ambushed government troops passing through a thick forest
in Eastern India Thursday, killing five soldiers and wounding seven
others, police said.
	   Two civilians were caught in the shooting and died on the spot.
The five soldiers died as they were being rushed to the hospital.
	   The attack occurred Monday morning near the town of Goalpara,
1,350 kilometers (800 miles) east of the Indian capital, New Delhi,
police said.
	   The rebels belonged to the United Liberation Front of Assam, an
outlawed group fighting for an independent homeland for the ethnic
Assamese people in India's northeast. A spokesman for the group
called newspaper offices and claimed responsibility for the attack.
	   Troops have been deployed in strength in large parts of Assam
state to prevent possible rebel strikes against civilians during a
five-day festival that began Sunday.
	   Already 100 people have been killed in the last three weeks in
fresh fighting between rival ethnic groups in Assam where
separatist insurgency and tribal clashes have claimed hundreds of
lives.
</TEXT>
