w1263 &Cx1f; wstm-
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Germany-Election-Indu     09-28 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Election-Industry </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
German industry wary of left's election victory
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With Germany-Election &QL; 
 &UR; By KAREN CARSTENS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ German industry leaders voiced concern
Monday that the left's election victory threatened the economy, but
the stock market welcomed the prospect of a stable government under
future chancellor Gerhard Schroeder.
	   Schroeder, a Social Democrat, said Monday he would seek a
coalition with the environmentalist Greens as junior partner _ a
shock for organized industry, which strongly backed defeated
Chancellor Helmut Kohl.
	   ``I believe, as I always have, that the Greens are an
anti-industry party,'' said Hans Peter Stihl, head of the German
Chamber of Industry and Commerce.
	   The Frankfurt Stock Exchange took a more favorable view, though,
ending the day 2 percent higher.
	   ``At the end of the day, even investors abroad understood that
Schroeder isn't a threat or someone who wants to convert everything
into public-sector entities,'' said a trader at M.M. Warburg.
	   With unemployment stuck above 10 percent, Schroeder has called
for talks between government, labor and industry on solving the
jobs crisis.
	   He stressed Monday that his goal was ``economic stability.''
	   But industry leaders warned the Social Democrats against pumping
up social welfare programs that industry fears will push up
Germany's already high labor costs.
	   Hans-Olaf Henkel, head of the German Federation of Industry,
rejected one of the Social Democrats' campaign planks _ scrapping
cuts in sick pay and easing firing rules pushed through by Kohl's
government.
	   ``I will do everything in my power to prevent these rollbacks in
the reforms,'' said Dieter Hundt, head of the German Employers'
Association.
	   While the lobbyists talked tough, individual companies were more
relaxed about the new government.
	   German chemical giant BASF sees ``no reason to panic'' after the
election, company spokesman Frank Halder said.
	   And Hermann Franzen, head of a retailer lobby, voiced hope that
tax reforms will help merchants by putting more money in consumers'
pockets.
	   Henkel was among the first to congratulate Schroeder at the
Social Democrats' victory bash in Bonn Sunday night.
	   He and other industry leaders left the door open for round-table
talks on fighting unemployment and suggested the Social Democrats'
promises to rescind the modest social welfare cuts be included in
the bargaining.
	   ``There are campaign promises, and then there's reality,'' he
told a Berlin radio station.
	   Industry wants the talks to yield tax cuts and reforms of
Germany's increasingly stretched social security system, Henkel
said.
 &UR; (kc-tc-cb)	   
</TEXT>
