r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Netherlands-Srebrenic     09-28 0370
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Netherlands-Srebrenica Investigation,0370 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report clears Dutch military of Bosnia cover-up
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By MIKE CORDER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) _ An independent inquiry Monday
cleared the Dutch military of trying to cover up its troops'
failings in the 1995 fall of the Bosnian Muslim enclave of
Srebrenica.
	   But the inquiry, ordered last month by Defense Minister Frank de
Grave, did find ``many shortcomings and much carelessness in the
information process'' following one of the worst debacles in Dutch
military history.
	   Charged by the United Nations with protecting the Muslim enclave
of Srebrenica, a group of 300 Dutch soldiers could only look on
helplessly as rebel Serbs overran the area in July 1995.
	   More than 6,000 Muslims are believed to have been massacred in
the aftermath of the takeover.
	   In the face of international criticism at their lack of action,
Dutch top brass insisted the troops were outnumbered and outgunned
and also barred by their U.N. mandate from engaging in combat.
	   But in the three years since the humiliation, Dutch media have
reported a string of embarrassing allegations linked to the
Srebrenica fall.
	   In addition to the destruction of film said to show peacekeepers
helping Serbs separate Muslim men from women for deportation, Dutch
troops are alleged to have driven a tank through a crowd of fleeing
Muslims, killing up to 30. Four medics also claim that they were
ordered not to treat wounded Muslims.
	   Although military authorities knew about all of the alleged
incidents, there was a suspicion that they were not always
immediately or fully reported to the Defense Ministry, prompting
Minister De Grave to order the inquiry.
	   The inquiry's author, senior civil servant Jos van Kemenade, was
charged with investigating whether the lack of information was a
deliberate attempt to hide the truth.
	   He said it was not.
	   ``There is no question of this being swept under the carpet,''
concluded inquiry leader Jos van Kemenade. ``But the gathering,
distribution and use of information about peacekeeping missions
can, in possible future operations, be considerably better than it
was in this case.''
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Netherlands-Srebrenica Investigation; CT:i; 
