<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Russia-IMF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMF: Russia program hinges on actions, not personalities
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ The International Monetary Fund will decide
whether to loan more money to Russia on the basis of programs, not
personalities, the fund's Moscow representative was quoted as
saying Monday.
	   ``We will work with anyone whom the Russian government names ...
and the results will depend on the fulfillment by the Russian side
of the obligations that it takes on,'' the IMF's Martin Gilman
said, according to ITAR-Tass.
	   ``In Russia, there is a tendency to run relations with the IMF
at a personal level,'' he added.
	   Last week, Vice Premier Alexander Shokhin, who was in charge of
the government's relations with the IMF, resigned after a 10-day
tenure at the post. Before Shokhin, Russia's talks with the IMF
were coordinated by Anatoly Chubais, who was fired from the post
during the latest government reshuffle.
	   The IMF's lending program to Russia has been on hold since
August, when the government defaulted on its domestic debt and
imposed a moratorium on commercial foreign debt.
	   Last week, a mission from the fund left Moscow without a word
about any further loan installments.
	   The most serious problem in the Russian economy is the budget
deficit, Gilman said.
	   ``This has been going on for so long that at the moment Russia
isn't able to borrow, which has led to the payments crisis,''
Gilman said.
	   The fund's work is hampered by the government's lack of a
consistent economic program, Gilman added.
	   Yevgeny Primakov has faced an uphill struggle to form his
government, and infighting between Cabinet members over economic
policy already led to Shokhin's resignation last week.
	   (apdj/ml)
</TEXT>
