w1300 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Somalia-Fighting     09-28 0394
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Somalia-Fighting </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Rival militiamen in standoff after Sunday fighting
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By OSMAN WEHELEYE &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MOGADISHU, Somalia (AP) _ Rival militiamen in the war-torn
Somali capital faced each other Monday in an armed standoff that
threatened to erupt again into violence following clashes that
killed seven people.
	   In two separate incidents Sunday, militiamen fought street
battles in central and southern parts of the city in which five
people were killed and seven were wounded.
	   In a third battle, militiamen loyal to faction leader Hassan
Osman Ali, known by the nickname Atto, attacked a World Food
Programme convoy as it returned from delivering food aid to south
central Somalia. Two rival militamen guarding the convoy were
killed.
	   The convoy was guarded by fighters loyal to warlord Hussein
Mohamed Aidid, who controls most of south Mogadishu, and who has
worked out an agreement with Ali Mahdi Mohamed, warlord in the
northern sector, for a joint administration to run the seaside
capital.
	   Atto's militamen have not been included in the agreement that
would allow the international airport and port to open after being
closed for nearly four years, and violence has increased as they
attempt to block the implementation.
	   In one of the battles Sunday in the central Bermuda neighborhood
in which two people were killed, the wife of well-known businessman
and soccer coach Abdelaziz Ahmed Mahdi was kidnapped. Elders failed
again Monday to secure her release.
	   On Monday, several dozen militiamen loyal to Aidid and Atto
aimed heavy machine guns and mortars at each other across an empty
300-meter (yard) stretch of road in the southern Medina
neighborhood where fighting Sunday killed three people and wounded
three others, two of them children.
	   Last December in Cairo, most of the Somali warlords agreed to an
Egyptian-brokered peace deal that established an interim government
and called for an international reconciliation conference.
	   But the conference has been postponed several times, reportedly
for lack of funds.
	   Somalia has not had a central government since 1991 when Ali
Mahdi and Aidid's late father, Mohamed Farah Aidid, joined forces
to oust longtime dictator Mohamed Siad Barre, then turned on each
other and plunged the country into a civil war and famine.
	   (ow/dc/sl)	   
</TEXT>
