<HEADLINE>
EU ambassadors urge compliance with Dayton agreement
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SARAJEVO, Bosnia-Herzegovina (AP) _ The European Union said
Monday it will not tolerate any attempts by ethnic groups or people
to jeopardize the sovereignty of Bosnia, the Bosnian news agency
Onasa reported.
	   The ambassadors of Britain, Austria and Germany _ forming the
so-called EU troika _ said they hoped that leaders newly elected in
nationwide balloting earlier this months would cooperate with the
international community and assist in the development of pluralism
and democracy in the country.
	   The diplomats reportedly singled out ultranationalist Nikola
Poplasen, who beat Biljana Plavsic for president of the Bosnian
Serb republic.
	   Valentin Inzko, the ambassador of Austria, which currently holds
the rotating EU presidency, said assistance from the international
community would hinge on implementation of the Dayton agreement.
	   He said special efforts would be made to ensure the functioning
of Bosnia and its entities, economic reforms, improvement of human
rights and the return of refugees and displaced persons.
