<HEADLINE>
Opposition resumes cooperation with Tajik government
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   DUSHANBE, Tajikistan (AP) _ The Tajik opposition agreed Monday
to resume cooperation with the Tajik government and participation
in reconciliation efforts, the government's press secretary said.
	   The leader of the Unified Tajik Opposition, Said Abdullo Nuri,
signed an agreement with President Emomali Rakhmonov designed to
speed up the peace process in this poor, mountainous country that
has been torn by civil strife since breaking away from the Soviet
Union seven years ago.
	   Opposition members will resume its work in the National
Reconciliation Commission and the cabinet on Tuesday, Press
Secretary Zafar Saidov said.
	   The opposition halted cooperation after the killing of Otakhon
Latifi, who had returned to Tajikistan a year ago following peace
accords that ended the five-year civil war between the hard-line
government and the opposition.
	   They protested what they saw as a lack of protection for
opposition leaders, and were also angry at government statements
accusing several opposition field commanders of violating terms of
the peace treaty.
	   The new program signed by both sides calls for, among other
things, the protection of opposition workers in the government, the
creation of a commission to investigate Latifi's death, and
organizing a joint unit to combat crime, the Interfax news agency
said.
	   (str/nw/ml)
