<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinians, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0592 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tensions high in Hebron after Israeli woman shot
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with new details on shooting, color;
Clinton invitation to Arafat and Netanyahu; ADDS photo numbers. &QL; 
 &UR; With US-Mideast &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos JRL101-105 &QL; 
 &UR; By LAURIE COPANS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HEBRON, West Bank (AP) _ Tempers flared in this divided West
Bank city on Monday when an Israeli woman was shot, apparently by
Palestinian assailants, and Jewish settlers beat Arab neighbors in
retaliation.
	   The violence came as Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat and
Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu headed into a meeting
with U.S. President Bill Clinton in Washington to try to end months
of impasse in Israeli-Palestinian peace making.
	   Monday morning, a 52-year-old Israeli woman, in Hebron with her
family to celebrate her son's bar mitzvah, was shot once in the leg
while touring the city's Jewish settlement.
	   The bullet that hit her was one of four fired by assailants from
a Palestinian-controlled area of the city that surrounds the
settlement's trailer homes. The army sealed the area and searched
for suspects but made no arrests.
	   Shortly afterward, angry settlers from the 450-strong Jewish
community took to the city's dusty streets and beat Palestinian
passersby, injuring one.
	   And in the city's Arab-run vegetable market, some 15 settlers
including one founder of the Hebron settlement, Miriam Levinger,
overturned tomato and cucumber stands, spitted toward Palestinian
merchants and shouted ``dogs,'' at them.
	   The women, dressed in long skirts and head scarves and clutching
their children, planted themselves in the center of the busy
Palestinian shopping area until soldiers forcibly dragged them,
some of through garbage and barbed wire, to extract them from the
area.
	   Two policemen were hurt in the incident, spokeswoman Linda
Menuhin said. One woman settler was arrested in the confrontation
and one Palestinian man was detained for beating a Jewish girl,
Menuhin said.
	   Yasser Arafat's Palestinian Authority gained control of 80
percent of the Hebron, where the majority of the city's 130,000
Palestinians live, as part of a 1997 peace deal. Israel still
controls the tense downtown area, home to the settlers and 15,000
Palestinians.
	   A few hours later the blood stains from the wounded Israeli
woman still smeared the white limestone walk near the settler home,
The woman, from the Tel Aviv suburb of Herziliya, remained in a
Jerusalem hospital being treated for a bullet wound to the knee.
	   Col. Yigal Sharon, the commander of the Israeli army's forces in
Hebron, said Monday's shooting represented a further escalation in
tensions in the city since a rabbi was murdered there last month.
	   Israel has insisted that the Palestinians do more to counter
violence against Jews and rein in militant groups. No peace deal
between the sides to end an 18-month stalemate in negotiations
would be possible with Palestinian security guarantees, Netanyahu
said.
	   At the end of Monday's three-way summit in Washington, Clinton
said work remained to be completed before an agreement was reached
and invited Netanyahu and Arafat back to the White House in
October.
	   Meanwhile, some 2,500 members of the Islamic militant group
Hamas, which opposes the peace talks, rallied against Israel in the
West Bank city of Nablus on Monday.
	   The demonstrators burned Israeli flags in protest of the killing
earlier this month by Israeli soldiers of two Hamas leaders.
</TEXT>
