<SLUG> BC-Algeria-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Algerian prime minister pledges to continue privatization program
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES thruout with background on privatization plan; shows
policeman reported killed in new violence &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) _ Algeria's prime minister said Monday the
government would stick to its massive program of privatization,
assuring that the nation's disgruntled main union would be
consulted along the way.
	   ``We will continue to implement reforms,'' Ahmed Ouyahia said
after marathon 19-hour talks with Abdelmadjid Sidi-Said, head of
the General Union of Algerian Workers (UGTA), Algeria's largest
union.
	   ``We will continue privatization within the framework of the
law, transparently and with dialogue,'' he added.
	   Unemployment is already around 30 percent of the active
population, and the government's program of privatizing state
industries, under the pressure of the International Monetary Fund,
is translating into further job losses.
	   The UGTA, opposed to the program, had boycotted a meeting with
government officials on Sept. 9 and threatened to call a general
strike.
	   The union claims some 200,000 people have lost their jobs in
three years.
	   The UGTA has worked hand-in-hand with the military-backed
government since 1992, when this North African nation began a
spiral into violence following an army decision to cancel
legislative elections a Muslim fundamentalist party was winning.
	   An estimated 75,000 people have been killed in the violence that
took the life of an Algiers policeman on Sunday, the daily
newspaper Liberte reported Monday. Authorities blame such attacks
on Islamic extremists fighting to topple the government.
	   Discord between authorities and the UGTA loomed as another
rupture.
	   But Sidi-Said said he was ``globally satisfied'' with the talks
with the prime minister, while insisting the union ``neither
supports nor adheres to privatization.'' He did not mention the
earlier strike threat.
	   Earlier this year, more than 100,000 Algerian metal and steel
workers, mechanics and customs employees went on strike to protest
government plans to cut public jobs.
	   (parf-ip-eg)
</TEXT>
