<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-French Open Sponsor </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sponsor Peugeot pulls out of French Open after 15 years
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PARIS (AP) _ Organizers of the French Open golf tournament lost
their main sponsor Monday when car manufacturer Peugeot announced
that it would no longer support the 92-year-old event.
	   In a statement, Peugeot, which has sponsored the dlrs 800,000
competition for 15 years, said that it would concentrate its future
golf sponsorship in France on the amateur game.
	   ``After 15 years of support for professional golf, we feel we
have achieved our objectives in France,'' the statement said.
	   The French company said that it will continue to sponsor the
Spanish Open.
	   Launched in 1906, the French Open is Europe's second oldest open
golf tournament, but its prize money has not enabled it to maintain
a place among the top echelons of the European circuit.
	   The Lancome Trophy, also held in France, offers prize money of
dlrs 1.32 million.
	   The inability of the French Golf Federation to boost the money
on offer has resulted in the Open losing its late-June slot in next
year's European calendar.
	   It is tentatively re-scheduled for the second week of May.
	   (ap-ae)
</TEXT>
