<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cycling-Drugs,0334 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Belgian team doctor claims two-thirds of cycling doctors in bad
</HEADLINE>
faith
 &UR; By RAF CASERT &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) _ Two-thirds of the doctors involved in
cycling are giving athletes performance-enhancing drugs, the
medical chief of the sport's Belgian federation said Monday.
	   ``I'm afraid we're talking about two out of three. There are too
many people operating in bad faith and they drag down the others,''
Dr. Joost De Maeseneer said.
	   He hopes the Oct. 5 Congress of the International Cycling Union
in Maastricht, the Netherlands, would start cleaning up the sport,
which was hit hard by a drugs scandal at its premier event, the
Tour de France, over the summer.
	   ``We have to make sure we can start turning things around,'' he
told The Associated Press in an interview.
	   His comments came after the Brussels daily Het Nieuwsblad
reported that the Belgian cycling federation issued a formal
complaint against Festina team doctor Eric Ryckaert for his
involvement in the Tour scandal.
	   Ryckaert was imprisoned during the Tour after more than 400
doping products, including the endurance enhancing drug EPO, were
found in a Festina team car. The team was expelled from the Tour.
Rumors and accusations involving several other teams have since
cast a shadow over the sport.
	   ``We were in a relatively quiet period until five years ago,''
said De Maeseneer. ``Then came the excesses. The rise of EPO
certainly played its role, and so did the increased pressure of
sponsors.''
	   The discovery of EPO in the Festina car was the first time the
drug could be linked so clearly to cycling.
	   Apart from doctors handing out illegal drugs on the professional
circuit, De Maeseneer was also alarmed by the increasing use of
doping in cycling's youth divisions. ``We are seeing that certain
people are giving illegal drugs to youngsters now,'' he said.
	   De Maeseneer has been involved in cycling for 17 years.
</TEXT>
