w1360 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo 7thLd-Writethru   09-28 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 7th Ld-Writethru,0833 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Serb premier says special police units will be pulled out of Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS and UPDATES with ethnic Albanian reaction; fighting in
Kosovo; unofficial NATO reaction, Serbs saying action near Suva
Reka over; inserts new ethnic Albanian reaction. CHANGES byline. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo BEL103 &QL; 
 &UR; By DUSAN STOJANOVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Trying to avert a NATO attack,
Serbia's premier declared that Kosovo's separatists have been
defeated and promised Monday to withdraw special police units from
the province _ as demanded by the United States and Europe.
	   But Premier Mirko Marjanovic said the Serb crackdown will resume
if the rebels stage new attacks, and his deputy threatened to take
hostage all Serbs who work for independent media, peace and human
rights groups in case of NATO strikes.
	   The Kosovo Liberation Army, which is fighting for Kosovo's
independence, pledged to continue what it called ``the holy war''
against Serbia and demanded NATO action. The statement also
criticized pacifist Kosovo Albanian leaders ``whose actions are
hindering this holy war.''
	   Hundreds of people have been killed and about 275,000 have fled
their homes since Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's forces
began cracking down on Kosovo's ethnic Albanians in February.
	   Kosovo is part of Serbia, the dominant republic in Yugoslavia.
Most of Kosovo's ethnic Albanians _ who make up the vast majority
of the 2 million inhabitants _ favor independence.
	   Marjanovic said the government will grant amnesty to Kosovo
Albanians who surrender weapons within the next 10 days unless they
have committed ``war crimes.''
	   ``With this day, anti-terrorist activities have finished and can
be renewed only if some new bandit-terrorist activity appears
again,'' he said. ``I wish to declare that with this day ... the
armed terrorist groups have been defeated.''
	   A NATO spokesman in Brussels, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, repeated the alliance's official position that Milosevic
has to fulfill all the conditions laid down in Wednesday's U.N.
resolution that called for an immediate cease-fire.
	   ``Words are nifty, but we want to see action,'' he said.
	   There was no visible withdrawal Monday of the police units.
Marjanovic said Serb and Yugoslav forces would remain in their
barracks for an unspecified period to guard against any resumption
of attacks by the KLA, which has been largely routed.
	   ``Conditions have been made ... to decrease engagement of
anti-terrorist forces,'' the premier said.
	   But the leading ethnic Albanian Democratic League of Kosovo
party stated the premier's claims were a ``manipulation of the
world public by the Belgrade regime,'' and urged ``immediate NATO
action in Kosovo to stop the humanitarian catastrophe.''
	   Despite word of special forces' imminent pullout, sporadic
fighting was reported Monday in Kosovo. The Kosovo Information
Center, which is close to the ethnic Albanian leadership, reported
Serbian shelling in the region of the Suva Reka village and
Urosevac town south of Pristina.
	   Reporters saw thick columns of smoke blurring the horizon of
Suva Reka where open flames consumed at least four villages
sprawling over nearby hills Monday. Police and the Yugoslav army,
backed by tanks and heavy artillery, had surrounded several
villages in the area and denied entry to journalists and foreign
diplomatic observers.
	   ``There are still many KLA,'' said one Serb police officer in
Suva Reka, which sits at the foot of the hills where Sunday's
police offensive devastated several villages.
	   The state Tanjug news agency later said that ``all strongholds
of terrorists'' in the region of Suva Reka were ``destroyed''
Monday, and that dozens of ``terrorists'' were killed and hundreds
were arrested.
	   The Kosovo Information Center also claimed that two ethnic
Albanian families, including 15 members, were ``massacred'' by
withdrawing Serb troops in the central Drenica region on Sunday.
The report could not be independently confirmed.
	   The U.N. Security Council has insisted since March that Serbs
withdraw special police units and other forces from Kosovo and
begin talks with ethnic Albanians on the province's future.
	   On Wednesday, the council threatened additional action if
Milosevic did not stop the offensive against Kosovo's separatists
and allow the safe return of refugees.
	   NATO defense chiefs then stepped up plans for airstrikes in the
event that Milosevic failed to comply.
	   The premier made his remarks hours before the Serbian parliament
adopted a resolution declaring that stamping out ethnic Albanian
resistance in Kosovo was Serbia's top priority.
	   During the session, vice premier Vojislav Seselj threatened to
take pro-Western Serbs as hostage in case of NATO strikes. His list
of ``traitors'' included independent journalists, and members of
human rights, intellectual and peace groups.
</TEXT>
