<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Israel-Smoking </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Israeli health insurer sues tobacco companies for dlrs 2 billion
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING to restore cycle designator &QL; 
 &UR; By GREG LANGLOIS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Israel's largest health insurer filed a dlrs
two billion lawsuit Monday against American and Israeli tobacco
manufacturers, claiming compensation for the costs to treat smokers
who were misled about the effects of cigarettes.
	   The lawsuit, filed in Jerusalem's District Court, also seeks
punitive damages and unspecified future damages.
	   Those named in the suit include Phillip Morris, R.J. Reynolds,
Brown &AMP; Williamson, Liggett &AMP; Meyers, and Lorillard. Israel's only
cigarette manufacturer, Dubek, its former chief executive officer
and its sister company were also named in the suit.
	   The 28-page complaint accuses the companies of withholding
evidence of the harmful effects of smoking, target advertising of
minors, deceptive advertising and altering nicotine levels to
encourage addiction.
	   The plaintiff, the Kupat Holim Klalit health fund, insures about
70 percent of Israel's citizens, said Amos Hausner, one of two
attorneys behind the lawsuit.
	   In addition to monetary damages, the suit seeks injunctions to
halt the alleged false advertising and the removal of harmful
substances from cigarettes.
	   The Dubek cigarette manufacturer is currently fighting two other
suits in Israeli courts. One was filed by a similar health provider
for dlrs 486 million, and another suit was on behalf of 15 Israelis
allegedly sickened or killed from smoking.
	   Hausner, a legal adviser for the Israeli Forum for the
Prevention of Smoking, said the other suits would not affect the
filed Monday. Spokesmen for Dubek were not immediately available
for comment.
	   Last year Liggett executives broke ranks from the tobacco
industry by acknowledging that nicotine is addictive, that tobacco
causes cancer and that cigarette companies targeted children.
Liggett agreed to turn over documents that contained more than 30
years of industry secrets.
	   Israel's health ministry says 28 percent of thr country's 5.9
million citizens smoke and 5,000 die from smoking-related diseases
every year.
 &UR; gl-dl 	   
</TEXT>
