w1378 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Iraq-Oil     09-28 0404
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iraq-Oil </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iraq says U.S. holding up 28 oil spare part contracts
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photos BAG-105 &QL; 
 &UR; By LEON BARKHO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BAGHDAD, Iraq (AP) _ The United States is holding up 28
contracts for the purchase of spare part needed to revamp Iraq's
oil industry, Trade Minister Mohammed Mehdi Saleh said Monday.
	   He said out of the dlrs 300 million earmarked to repair Iraqi
oil installations, only dlrs 21.1 million have so far been
released.
	   The delay in the approval of the contracts has prevented Iraq
from exporting enough oil needed to raise its revenues, Saleh said
at a news conference.
	   Iraq says it will only be able to sell dlrs 3 billion worth of
crude during the current, six-month phase of the U.N. oil-for-food
program, or about dlrs 1 billion below target.
	   This will give Iraq dlrs 2 billion for food and other
humanitarian goods. The balance will go to war reparations and the
cost of the U.N. weapons monitoring program.
	   The United Nations agreed to increase the oil-for-food program
to dlrs 5.2 billion from the previous dlrs 2 billion every six
months. The program, an exception from U.N. trade sanctions imposed
after Iraq's 1990 invasion of Kuwait, allows Iraq to sell oil to
buy food and medicine for its 22 million people.
	   Iraq had said it could not meet the dlrs 5.2 billion total and
had set a target of dlrs 4 billion for the current six month
period. But even that ceiling is not attainable now.
	   Saleh said of the dlrs 2 billion that will be available to Iraq
under the fourth oil phase, contracts worth dlrs 1.1 billion have
so far been approved by the United Nations.
	   He said money from the oil program was not enough and was not
improving the condition of the Iraqi people.
	   But a U.N. official in Baghdad said Monday that the deal was
reducing malnutrition among Iraqi children.
	   Eric Falt, spokesman for U.N. humanitarian programs in Iraq,
said a survey in the north of the country showed that 25.3 percent
of children under the age of 5 were suffering from chronic
malnutrition, down from 33.3 percent.
	   He said U.N. agencies hoped for similar results in surveys to be
undertaken soon in central and southern parts of the country.
	   Meanwhile, Saleh said his ministry was negotiating with Saudi
businessmen and firms and deals worth more than dlrs 100 million
have been signed with them under the oil program.
 &UR; lb-sf
</TEXT>
