w1384 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Mexico-Flooding 1stLdWritethru   09-28 0495
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Flooding, 1st Ld Writethru ,0495 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Three dead in Mexico mudslides, flooding
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with death toll increased, details
of mudslides. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Heavy rains swelled rivers in central Mexico
and triggered mudslides Monday in Mexico City which killed three
people and injured five others, a local official reported.
	   Rainstorms soaked squatter communities perched on the steep
slopes of hillsides south of the city, and television footage
showed a stream of mud roaring down a gully over the ruins of two
homes that had been swept away.
	   It was a disaster city officials had been predicting for months,
as they launched a campaign to relocate shanty towns that ring the
city's hillsides.
	   Officials had warned the squatters that their houses _ often
perched on hillsides so steep that the dwellings are supported only
by sandbags _ were in danger during Mexico's rainy season.
	   ``It's very difficult to convince them, they don't want to leave
their houses,'' said Aurelio Garcia, spokesman for the Magdalena
Contreras precinct where the deaths occured.
	   The first death came when a house was swept away by a mudslide,
killing a 13-year-old girl and injuring her two brothers and
mother. One of the injured boys was evacuated by helicopter to a
hospital in the city's center, after he was nearly choked by the
mud.
	   Another family of four in a nearby neighborhood was buried in
their home when mud came streaming down on top of it. Two
teen-agers were pulled from the house alive by local police, but
their parents died, apparently of suffocation.
	   Two other people were killed when a muddy hillside collapsed on
top of a containment wall, crushing their house, local media
reported. However, Garcia said his office could confirm only three
deaths.
	   Garcia said a shelter had been established at a local gymnasium
to house 700 residents threatened by mudslides, but that no one had
yet gone there.
	   Some neighborhoods in a low-lying former lake bed to the east of
Mexico City have been flooded for days, and to the west, the Lerma
river overflowed its banks and left some villages inundated in
sewage.
	   Mexico City's main highway to the western part of the country
was also blocked Monday by a mudslide. Rains are expected to
continue here, the National Meteorological service predicted.
	   The television network Televisa reported that one child and one
adult had been swept away by swollen rivers in neighboring Puebla
state and were feared drowned Sunday. State officials were
unavailable to comment on that report.
	   Elsewhere in the country, the rains caused rivers to overflow in
the southern state of Chiapas, hit by flooding earlier this month
that killed 185 people and left thousands of towns and villages cut
off from the outside world.
	   Two temporary bridges built to replace ones destroyed in that
flooding were washed away again Sunday, local media reported.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Mexico-Flooding, 1st Ld Writethru; CT:i; 
