w1402 &Cx1f; wstm-
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Italy-OlympicC 1stLd-Writethru   09-28 0269
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Italy-Olympic Chief, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Italian Olympic Committee head resigns amid scandal over doping
</HEADLINE>
tests &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with more quotes, ADDS background.
No pickup. &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   ROME (AP) _ Mario Pescante resigned Monday as president of the
Italian National Olympic Committee amid a scandal over testing for
banned, performance-enhancing substances.
	   Pescante had come under growing criticism from sports and
government officials after news reports that some required doping
tests were not being conducted properly.
	   ``I've made this decision to restore calm to the atmosphere and
not because I believe I have responsibility,'' Pescante said in
announcing his resignation.
	   The committee oversees all sports _ amateur and professional _
in Italy. As head of the committee, Pescante became a target for
blame when Italian media reported that sports authorities were
failing to run all the required doping tests on pro soccer league
players.
	   Pescante has served as president of the committee since June
1993. His resignation is to become official after an Oct. 13
meeting of sports officials.
	   This year has seen a series of investigations into alleged
doping by Italian athletes. The probes were prompted by comments
from AS Roma coach Zdenek Zeman, who said he was amazed by the
quick muscular development of some players.
	   One investigation, for the Italian Olympic Committee's doping
commission, ended in August without finding evidence of illegal
drug use, but did find that the use of legal muscle-builders is
widespread.
	   (ek)
</TEXT>
