<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-France-Le Pen, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Le Pen begins appeal against political ban
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES thruout with quotes, color, Le Pen files complaint;
Verdict in November; FIXES to show Versailles west of Paris &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   VERSAILLES, Paris (AP) _ Far-right National Front leader
Jean-Marie Le Pen on Monday began his appeal against a two-year
political ban for physically attacking a Socialist politician,
claiming the incident was a setup.
	   Addressing the court, Le Pen denied attacking anyone at the May
30, 1997, election rally in the working class town of
Mantes-La-Jolie west of Paris.
	   A court has convicted the 70-year-old leader of attacking
Annette Peulvast-Bergeal, a parliamentary candidate running against
Le Pen's daughter, Marie-Caroline. Le Pen was on hand to support
his daughter's candidacy.
	   ``There was no pushing against Madame Peulvast-Bergeal,'' Le Pen
told the court. Instead, he said, he and National Front members are
``harrassed endlessly.''
	   ``They didn't want Jean-Marie Le Pen to shake hands. They came
looking for a confrontation,'' he said of the crowd.
	   The hearing at the appeals court in Versailles, west of Paris,
was expected to last two days with the verdict due Nov. 17. Dozens
of supporters, some holding banners saying ``Justice for Le Pen,''
and ``Le Pen targeted, the French hit,'' stood outside the
courtroom.
	   Le Pen's lawyer, Georges Wagner, alleged that Peulvast-Bergeal
had hurt her leg two weeks earlier and ``hid'' that from the court
at the time.
	   She ``tried to blame her injuries on Jean-Marie Le Pen,'' the
attorney said, adding that he is filing a complaint against her for
``fraud in judgment.''
	   On Wednesday, the court is to view television footage of the
scuffle.
	   A court stripped Le Pen of his civil rights for two years, in
effect banning him from holding office, running for office, or
voting in that time. He was also fined 20,000 francs (dlrs 3,333).
	   If upheld, the conviction would make Le Pen ineligible to run in
the June 1999 European Parliament elections. He has said that in
that case his wife, Jany, would run in his place.
	   The National Front, which has won about 15 percent in recent
elections, blames immigrants, particularly from North Africa, for
high unemployment and rising urban violence. It has also been
accused of anti-Semitism.
	   On Sunday, it suffered a setback, losing its only remaining
parliamentary seat in a by-election in the southern port city of
Toulon. But it remains a powerful force at regional level.
	   Le Pen holds a seat in the European Parliament and is a regional
counselor in the Provence-Alpes-Cotes d'Azur region of southern
France.
	   (ip-parf-eg)
</TEXT>
