r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Brazil-IMF     09-28 0501
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Brazil-IMF,0509 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Battered Brazil hopes for relief at IMF meeting
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By PETER MUELLO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) _ Battered by a never-ending Asian
crisis, Brazil is looking for some good news this week at the
annual meeting of the International Monetary Fund in Washington
D.C.
	   The government's economic team heads to Washington on Tuesday
amid rumors that a major loan package is in the works to avert a
possibly disastrous devaluation of the Brazilian real.
	   One estimate puts the loan package for Brazil at dlrs 30
billion. Another says dlrs 50 billion will be earmarked for all of
Latin America.
	   But after a costly bailout for Russia, it's not clear how much
the IMF can come up with, or whether the Group of Seven
industrialized countries will pitch in.
	   Also uncertain is what terms Brazil will accept to get the
money, and how much more belt-tightening it can exact with a
stagnant economy, record unemployment, and national elections days
away.
	   As much as the cash itself, Brazil needs the credibility that
would come with a mega-loan.
	   With the world's ninth-largest economy, Brazil is in trouble
mainly because of its huge budget deficit: nearly dlrs 60 billion,
more than 7 percent of the gross domestic product.
	   As the Asian market turmoil sent investors scurrying to safer
havens, it looked harder for Brazil to get financing for its
deficit. An estimated dlrs 25 billion left the country in two
months. Cash reserves, which reached a record dlrs 74 billion in
April, had shrunk to dlrs 49 billion by mid-September.
	   It got so bad that President Fernando Henrique Cardoso, who is
up for re-election on Sunday, went on television to give a speech
that was a candidate's nightmare.
	   The government will cut spending to the bone, he said. If that's
not enough, it may raise taxes.
	   The speech got high marks from U.S. Treasury Secretary Robert
Rubin. IMF chief Michel Camdessus said the Fund was prepared to
help, if Brazil presents a ``strong and credible'' program.
	   Enrique Iglesias, president of the Inter-American Development
Bank, said Cardoso's speech ``opens the door for contingency lines
of credit ... if the government asks for them.''
	   That seems unlikely, especially before elections.
	   The IMF is believed to have between dlrs 5 billion and dlrs 9
billion in normal capital plus about dlrs 15 billion in the special
credit line known as General Arrangements to Borrow. More might be
needed from private lenders or even the Federal Reserve.
	   Some analysts think even money alone won't be enough without a
devaluation of the real, which would boost exports and allow the
government to reduce interest rates, now a scorching 49.75 percent.
	   But Brazil may be too important to go under. U.S. banks have an
estimated dlrs 27 billion in this country, more than quadruple
their exposure in Russia. And a tumble by Latin America's biggest
domino would almost surely take much of the region with it.
</TEXT>
