w1430 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Britain-FashionWeek     09-28 0532
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Fashion Week </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. designer Betsey Johnson in London Fashion Week debut
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SUE LEEMAN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ To pounding rap and swirling Latino rhythms, New
York designer Betsey Johnson made her London Fashion Week debut
Monday with a colorful collection whose exotic touches drew gasps
from her audience.
	   Johnson's designs for the spring and summer of 1999 mixed Latino
influences with New York attitude: tulle skirts in hot yellow,
lilac and green, pink and blue baby doll minidresses with stretch
cotton black bandeaus.
	   Some of the large contingent of photographers drawn by Johnson's
reputation for daring jeered as three male models sporting skimpy
pants with revealing cutouts on the buttocks sashayed down the
catwalk.
	   British model Erin O'Connor was stunning in a gothic outfit from
Johnson's Morticia Line (named for the mother in the Addams Family)
_ skin tight red trousers and bra scattered with black spiders.
	   The grand finale was a black Spanish wedding outfit with a long
inky gauze veil that flowed to the floor from a traditional Spanish
headdress.
	   To end of the show, Johnson danced down the ramp in a bright
pink tutu, before executing her trademark cartwheel.
	   Married to a Briton, she opened her first store outside the
United States in London's tony Chelsea neighborhood earlier this
year.
	   She is one of more than 50 designers who are holding catwalk
shows during the five days of London Fashion Week, which made an
upbeat start Friday with news that the government plans a
conference in November to boost British designers' earning power.
	   In contrast to 1993, when just 15 exhibitors showed their
accessories, some 140 others are showing shoes, bags, scarves and
other fashion items at the Natural History Museum, headquarters of
Fashion Week.
	   Also Monday, British designer Bella Freud showed tailored suits
reminiscent of the 1980s, but with a sharp modern edge.
	   Ms. Freud, who is known for her sexy silhouettes, said she drew
her inspiration from the feline beauty of model and singer Grave
Jones and the kind of pants suits favored by model turned activist
Bianca Jagger.
	   Dresses featured geometric stripes and the ruffles seen at many
of this season's shows; three-quarter length trousers were teamed
with strappy mules.
	   Model Jodie Kidd provided the high point, wearing a sheer body
sheath splashed with irregular patches of color _ a tribute to the
work of the painter Matisse, Ms. Freud said.
	   Newcomer Andrew Groves, whose fabrics have included surgical
latex and who once introduced a swarm of wasps to a show, will show
his work Tuesday, the final day of London Fashion Week.
	   The first British Fashion Designer Conference will be held in
London on Nov. 25. Sponsored by the Labor Party government and the
British Fashion Council, it will look at designers' access to
finance, their relationship with manufacturers and how they can
develop new products.
	   The British Fashion Council says the country's fashion industry
is now worth more than 16 billion pounds (dlrs 27 billion) a year
and employs some 350,000 people.
	   (scl-acw)
</TEXT>
