<SLUG> BC-Yemen-Maneuvers </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Yemeni troops conduct maneuvers near Saudi border
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SAN`A, Yemen (AP) _ Yemen on Monday completed a week of military
maneuvers near the Saudi border, state television said.
	   Air force squadrons, artillery and infantry units participated
in the war games, code named Victory-2, in Saywun, in the
southeastern Hadramawt province, about 300 kilometers (187 miles)
south of the Saudi border.
	   Troops made simulated air attacks on imaginary enemy targets,
the television broadcast said.
	   It said the maneuvers began early last week.
	   Fighting has occasionally erupted along the 2,000-kilometer
(1,300-mile) frontier between Yemen and Saudi Arabia over a
decades-old border dispute.
	   Yemen, on the tip of the Arabian Peninsula, has long contested
Saudi Arabia's claim to three Red Sea islands and parts of the
Empty Quarter, a vast desert region with potentially lucrative oil
fields. The two nations have yet to demarcate a mountainous border
in the east.
	   In 1995, Saudi Arabia sent 20,000 troops and hundreds of tanks
across the border before Syrian mediation secured a cease-fire and
an eventual withdrawal.
	   The maneuvers are Yemen's second such exercises this year.
 &UR; str-mae-sf
</TEXT>
