w1476 &Cx1f; wstm-
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UN-Iraq 6thLd-Writethru   09-28 0680
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Iraq, 6th Ld-Writethru,0679 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Aziz says Baghdad won't make concessions over arms stalemate
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with new quotes, council appearing to
reject any review without Iraqi compliance, UN spokesman saying
Aziz showed a less hard-line side during meeting. &QL; 
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Insisting that Baghdad will not make
concessions to end the standoff over U.N. arms inspections, Iraqi
Deputy Prime Minister Tariq Aziz said Monday that the U.N. Security
Council should make the first move.
	   Aziz responded positively to Secretary-General Kofi Annan's
proposal for a comprehensive review of sanctions and Iraq's efforts
over seven years to disarm itself. But he balked at the council's
insistence that no such review take place until Iraq rescinds its
Aug. 5 decision to stop cooperating with U.N. inspectors.
	   ``The idea that Iraq should do this or that concession before
the comprehensive review takes place is not legal,'' Aziz said.
	   U.N. arms experts must report that Iraq has destroyed its
chemical, biological and nuclear weapons _ and the long-range
missiles to deliver them _ before the council will lift sanctions
imposed after Iraq invaded Kuwait in 1990. Iraq claims it has fully
disarmed.
	   Aziz said even after its Aug. 5 decision, Iraq was cooperating
with inspectors from the U.N. Special Commission, or UNSCOM, who
are conducting long-term, less intrusive monitoring of already
searched sites.
	   ``What we are not allowing them to do is just provocations,'' he
said.
	   Aziz spoke to reporters after an hourlong meeting with Annan on
the standoff and the U.N. chief's proposal of a ``comprehensive
review'' to break the logjam. He welcomed the U.N. chief's
proposal, calling the session professional, cordial and
constructive.
	   A U.N. spokesman said, however, that Annan told Aziz that Iraq
must make the first move and reverse the Aug. 5 decision to freeze
cooperation with weapons inspectors before a comprehensive review
can get under way.
	   ``The position of the council is clear and the secretary-general
cannot go above what the council has decided,'' the spokesman said,
speaking on condition of anonymity. ``He made that point clearly to
Mr. Aziz.''
	   The U.N. spokesman said Aziz showed a less hard-line side during
the meeting with Annan.
	   ``Aziz didn't give a clear sign of whether Iraq would let UNSCOM
resume its inspections prior to such a review,'' he said.
	   Pressed by reporters afterwards on this question, Aziz refused
to say yes or no.
	   The Iraqi minister insisted that his country has already
complied fully with U.N. resolutions demanding that it destroy its
banned weapons. And he said the council has ``a legal and moral
obligation'' to carry out a comprehensive review.
	   ``I would like to say that the idea of a comprehensive review is
not a reward to be given to Iraq and then Iraq has to make
concessions before such a review takes place,'' Aziz told
reporters.
	   He said the focus should shift to the wider issue of what Iraq
has done over the past 7 1/2 years to comply ``and what the
Security Council has to do in the course of lifting sanctions.''
	   But council members appeared adamant that there would be no
review without Iraqi compliance with the weapons inspectors.
	   ``We hope that the Iraqi side realizes that it's very important
to resume cooperation with UNSCOM,'' said Shen Guofang, China's
deputy ambassador.
	   China, France and Russia are Baghdad's strongest allies on the
council while the United States and Britain typically take a harder
line.
	   Hans Dahlgren, Sweden's ambassador and the current council
president, said: ``I believe it's both legal and logical to ask
Iraq to cooperate first and then to take the comprehensive
review.''
	   Aziz said he would to meet with council members during the
course of the week, apparently testing their willingness to give
some indication of when sanctions would be lifted. He also planned
another meeting with Annan.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
