<SLUG> BC-India-Award, 1st Ld-Writethru,0336 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Veiled, illiterate mother of three wins UNDP's ``Race Against
</HEADLINE>
Poverty'' award &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with details of UNDP programs in region, minor edits
throughout. STANDS as first story to some points. &QL; 
 &UR; By K.N. ARUN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   HYDERABAD, India (AP) _ An illiterate mother of three who
mobilized hundreds of women to improve roads, drains, quality of
drinking water and education in her southern Indian village has won
this year's ``Race against Poverty'' award, the United Nations
announced Monday.
	   Fatima Bi, who wears the all enveloping Islamic veil or burqa,
will go to New York to receive the award Oct. 17 from U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan on International Poverty Eradication
Day. The U.N. Development Program, which gives the award, made the
announcement Monday.
	   	   Fatima Bi was chosen from among a nominees in South Asia where
the UNDP funds small-scale health, education and building programs
to help eradicate poverty at the village level, said Brende Gael
McSweeney, the program's resident representative in India.
	   Overcoming illiteracy and restricted roles for women, Fatima Bi
and her villagers raised rupees two million (dlrs 47,600) for small
loans to let villagers improve their economic situation. Part of
the money came from the savings of 300 village women, the rest from
the UNDP, a bank and a private non-government organization.
	   ``This is a great honor not only for me but for the entire
village,'' she said. ``Whatever development we have in this
village, it is because of the united efforts of all the women in
the village.''
	   Fatima Bi, who uses the term of respect ``Bi'' instead of her
last name, was elected head of Kalva village, 1500 kilometers (900
miles) south of the Indian capital, New Delhi, in 1995. She
benefited from an Indian law that reserves a third of seats in
local governments for women.
	   The UNDP did not say if the award carries extra funding for the
winner's project.
</TEXT>
