<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Soccer-US-MLS Playoff Preview,0655 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
United after third straight title
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By BRIAN TRUSDELL &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ With its two league titles and a CONCACAF
Champions Cup already in its trophy case, D.C United is the
acknowledged class of U.S. Major League Soccer.
	   Yet in a 3-year-old league where inconsistency regularly marks
games, upsets _ especially in the playoffs _ wouldn't be shocking.
	   Last year, Colorado struggled, losing six of its last seven,
qualified last in the Western Conference, then won four straight in
the playoffs to make the MLS Cup title game.
	   With the playoffs starting Wednesday night, and only three of
the eight teams entering with winning records, many wonder who will
be this year's Colorado.
	   ``D.C. United, when it's all said done, are still the
favorites,'' said Bob Bradley, coach of the Chicago Fire (20-12),
who open their Western Conference semifinal series against Colorado
(16-16) in Soldier Field on Thursday. ``They set the standard. I
think Los Angeles had a tremendous year. And there are a number of
other teams. They all had stretches to show they can play very good
soccer.
	   ``I think D.C. and L.A. are two teams you put a little higher
than the rest. But Colorado is a perfect example. They actually
struggled last year to make playoffs. But they got a result, some
confidence, a run starts. It's a perfect example of what can happen
in the game of soccer.''
	   Both expansion clubs qualified for the playoffs in their first
season, albeit via different roads.
	   Bradley righted his team from a 2-5 start and led it to the
third-best record in the league.
	   Miami (15-17), conversely, needed a coaching change midway
through the season. After Ivo Wortmann replaced Cacho Cordoba on
July 24, the Fusion more than doubled their goal production over
the final 13 games, finished 7-6 and even split the season series
with United.
	   The Fusion will open their best-of-3 series Wednesday night at
Washington.
	   Columbus (15-17) is home to New York-New Jersey (15-17) in the
other game Wednesday night. Los Angeles (24-8) takes on Dallas
(15-17) in the Rose Bowl to start the final Western Conference
series Thursday night.
	   Despite its 24-8 season, the United did not have an easy time
with Miami, even losing their last meeting 3-1 in RFK Stadium.
	   ``They put their whole team back behind the ball,'' Arena said.
``They defend on a full-time basis. They win by breaking the
passing lanes and counter-attacking.''
	   For an attack-minded team like D.C., it can be frustrating.
	   ``Maybe it was a good thing, losing to Miami,'' United
midfielder John Harkes said. ``It's a little kick in the butt,
makes us focus.''
	   Columbus first-year forward Stern John of Trinidad won the
league scoring title with 26 goals in 27 games. But the Crew have
lost their last five, and perhaps their only saving grace is that
the MetroStars (15-17) are playing even worse.
	   The Metros lost six straight before Saturday's shootout victory
over lowly New England (and that after a 0-0 draw).
	   New York-New Jersey is pinning its hopes on Bora Milutinovic,
soccer's itinerant coach who was hired last week to work his latest
``miracle.''
	   Los Angeles and Chicago dominated the West and managed to get a
grudge rivalry going thanks to Galaxy coach Octavio Zambrano's
comments early in the season that the Fire were a defense-only
team.
	   The Galaxy won Sunday's finale over the Fire 1-0 on an
87th-minute goal by Cobi Jones in the Rose Bowl, the site of the
MLS Cup championship on Oct. 25.
	   Los Angeles won the season series with Dallas 3-1, as did the
Fire over Colorado.
	   ``We're hoping they take us lightly,'' Colorado captain Marcelo
Balboa said. ``It's a crapshoot. If Chicago comes out slow, we come
out fast, it could be like last year.''
</TEXT>
