<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Cricket-Women Admitted, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
211-year-old Marylebone Cricket Club votes to admit women
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: ADDS quotes; opposition quotes &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ After 211 years of keeping them out, the world's
oldest cricket club voted Monday to admit women.
	   The Marylebone Cricket Club, whose membership includes former
British prime minister John Major and the Rolling Stone's Mick
Jagger, voted 69.8 percent in favor of the move, meeting the
required two-thirds majority.
	   Earlier this year a majority _ 55.7 percent _ voted to admit
women, falling short of the required two-thirds.
	   The vote was 9,394 in favor and 4,072 against.
	   ``I am absolutely delighted,'' said MCC President Colin
Ingleby-Mackenzie. ``It is great news for cricket and the club.''
	   ``From a personal point of view it gives my presidency a lift
two days before I stand down from office.''
	   The moves also opens the way for the club at Lord's in West
London to receive funds from Britain's national lottery, which some
observers suggested was a reason for the historic change in a
highly tradition-bound sport.
	   Of the 17,250 members, 13,482 voted with 16 ballots declared
void.
	   ``I'm highly delighted,'' said Barbara Daniels, vice-captain of
the England women's team. ``I am very pleased that the MCC has
taken this step and we all now carry on, now that this is over, and
get on with promoting the game.''
	   There was, however, hard-core opposition. One member, Robert
Titchener-Barratt, said the proposition was shoved down the club's
throat.
	   ``The committee have acted with arrogance and self-importance
saying `we're going to push this through whether you members like
it or not','' he said. ``The president has set his heart on making
this the crowning glory of his time in office.''
	   Other speakers at Monday's meeting, where the vote was
announced, said the move was pushed through like ``propagandists in
a communist state.''
	   (scw)	   
</TEXT>
