<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Netherlands-Srebrenica Investigation, 1st Ld-Writethru,0578 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Report clears Dutch military of Bosnia cover-up
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with background on allegations,
investigation, Background on surrender. &QL; 
 &UR; By MIKE CORDER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   THE HAGUE, Netherlands (AP) _ An independent inquiry Monday
cleared the Dutch military of trying to cover up its troops'
failings in the 1995 fall of the Bosnian Muslim enclave of
Srebrenica.
	   But the inquiry, ordered last month by Defense Minister Frank de
Grave, did find ``many shortcomings and much carelessness in the
information process'' following one of the worst debacles in Dutch
military history.
	   Charged by the United Nations with protecting Srebrenica, a
group of 300 Dutch soldiers could only look on helplessly as rebel
Serbs overran the area in July 1995.
	   More than 6,000 Muslims are believed to have been massacred in
the aftermath of the takeover.
	   In the face of international criticism, Dutch top brass insisted
the troops were outnumbered, outgunned and barred by their U.N.
mandate from engaging in combat. They also claimed that NATO
airstrikes _ requested by the Dutch but not deployed at Srebrenica
_ could have saved the enclave.
	   Many Dutch peacekeepers were forced at gunpoint to hand over
their weapons to rebel Serbs. A Dutch current affairs show recently
claimed that Serb forces in Kosovo were using a Dutch tank stolen
from Srebrenica.
	   In the three years since the humiliation, Dutch media have
reported a string of other embarrassing incidents linked to the
Srebrenica fall.
	   In addition to the destruction of film said to show peacekeepers
helping Serbs separate Muslim men from women for deportation, Dutch
troops drove a tank through a crowd of fleeing Muslims, killing up
to 30. Four medics also say they were ordered not to treat wounded
Muslims.
	   Former peacekeepers themselves reported the incidents, and went
to the media because they believed military authorities were doing
nothing with their testimony.
	   Military prosecutors who did investigate said they saw no reason
to file criminal charges.
	   The peacekeepers' concerns and a growing public feeling that the
whole truth about Srebrenica was being withheld by authorities
prompted Defense Minister Frank de Grave to order the inquiry who
results were published Monday.
	   The inquiry's author, senior civil servant Jos van Kemenade, was
charged with investigating whether the lack of information was a
deliberate attempt to hide the truth.
	   After speaking to troops, former defense minister Joris
Voorhoeve, and other officials linked to the affair, Van Kemenade
said it was not.
	   ``There is no question of this being swept under the carpet,''
concluded Van Kemenade. ``But the gathering, distribution and use
of information about peacekeeping missions can, in possible future
operations, be considerably better than it was in this case.''
	   Defense Minister De Grave said he would study the report's
findings and make changes if necessary.
	   ``A minister can only work well if communication (within the
ministry) is good,'' he said. The now-retired general in charge of
the Dutch Army at the time of Srebrenica had no immediate comment.
	   The respected State Institute for War Documentation is also
compiling a definitive report on the fall of Srebrenica, based on
all available evidence. No date has been set for publication of its
report.
</TEXT>
