w1523 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Nigeria-US-Military     09-28 0548
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Nigeria-US-Military </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. official spells out conditions for military aid to Nigeria
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By GILBERT DA COSTA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ABUJA, Nigeria (AP) _ The U.S. is willing to give military aid
to Nigeria if the country's ruling army brass follows through on
promises to step down, hand over power to elected civilians and
crack down on drugs and corruption, a top Pentagon official said
Monday.
	   U.S. Assistant Defense Secretary Franklin Kramer said in a
speech at Nigeria's National War College in the capital that
Washington is prepared to give ``training, education and other
cooperation on other particular military problems.''
	   However, military rulers in this oil-rich West African country
must first keep promises to allow free elections, and also
cooperate with the U.S. on ``meaningful'' measures against the
narcotics trade and government graft, Kramer said.
	   Military ruler Gen. Abdulsalami Abubakar has promised national
elections in February and a handover of power to the civilian
winners by the end of May.
	   ``Before we can initiate a new bilateral military relationship,
Nigeria must first complete the important tasks lying before it,''
Kramer said.
	   Details of the Nigerian military assistance package have not
been hashed out, Kramer said, adding that Gen. Wesley K. Clark,
NATO's supreme allied commander in Europe, will visit Nigeria next
week to begin several months of ``intensive dialogue'' with
military counterparts.
	   ``It is very important that the process go forward and democracy
in fact comes out of it. Then we will be very pleased to work with
the Nigerian military,'' Kramer said.
	   Kramer said the Pentagon was prepared to establish a new African
Center for African Security Studies next year to train African
military officers and promote better civilian-army relations.
	   Talks between Abubakar and U.S. officials on Monday had touched
on Nigeria possibly providing instructors and students for the
school, Kramer said.
	   Since taking power in June following the death of his
predecessor, the late dictator Gen. Sani Abacha, Abubakar has
released dozens of political prisoners and announced government
reforms intended to reduce crime and steer the country towards
democracy.
	   ``We now see a timetable for elections, an independent electoral
commission, the formation of political parties and the release of
detainees,'' Kramer said. ``We can now visualize a future in which
Nigeria completes its transition to democracy, ensures basic human
rights and takes more concrete efforts to combat corruption and the
drug trade,'' Kramer said.
	   Nigeria, Africa's most populous nation, has been ruled by
military regimes for all but 10 years since independence from
Britain in 1960.
	   The country is a key drug transit point in Africa, and official
corruption under Abacha and earlier leaders has all but destroyed
the economic infrastructure and social services despite massive
petroleum sector earnings.
	   Kramer, who was accompanied by about eight other U.S. officials
on his arrival in Abuja on Sunday, was expected to return home on
Tuesday. He is the first ranking U.S. official to visit Nigeria
since Undersecretary of State Thomas Pickering came in early
August.
	   (gdc-gam) 	   
</TEXT>
