<SLUG> BC-Albania, 1st Ld-Writethru,0458 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Embattled Albanian premier resigns
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; URGENT &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES throughout with background on conflict &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   TIRANA, Albania (AP) _ Albanian Socialist Premier Fatos Nano
resigned Monday, some two weeks after rioting over a politician's
assassination pushed the Balkan nation to the brink of anarchy.
	   Nano's resignation was announced Monday after a meeting of the
Socialist Party leadership in the Albanian capital, Tirana.
	   A statement said that Pandeli Majko, the 31-year-old
general-secretary of the Socialist Party, would be the party's
candidate for prime minister.
	   The resignation came two days after former Albanian President
Sali Berisha promised thousands of supporters that street protests
would continue until the government steps down.
	   Speaking in the capital before a crowd of about 3,000 people,
Berisha called Nano a ``killer,'' and blamed him for the current
political turmoil.
	   The unrest in Europe's poorest country erupted after a popular
opposition leader was killed outside Berisha's Democratic Party
headquarters on September 12. Berisha blamed his political rival
Nano for the killing and demanded his resignation.
	   Immediately after word of Nano's resignation spread in Tirana,
gunfire erupted in several parts of the capital. But it was not
clear whether it was just celebratory shooting by his political
foes _ supporters of rival Berisha.
	   Nano became prime minister last year after his Socialist Party
of former communists defeated Berisha's Democratic Party in
parliamentary elections.
	   That internationally supervised ballot followed widespread
lawlessness and chaos that erupted with the collapse of phony
pyramid schemes in which many Albanians lost their entire savings.
	   Nano stepped down Monday after he told President Rexhep Meidani
that he had been unable to put together a new Cabinet according to
his own wishes and ideas.
	   More important, Nano has failed to institute key economic
reforms, attract foreign investors and instill in Albanians hope
for a better future.
	   There is enmity between Nano's Socialists and Berisha's
Democrats who kept calling for his resignation and boycotted
parliament most of the time.
	   Political tensions reached fever pitch with the Sept. 12
assassination by unidentified gunmen of Azem Hajdari, a close
Berisha associate.
	   The next day, angry protesters burned the first floor of the
building housing Nano's office as well as seven government cars
parked outside.
	   On Sept. 14, the day of Hajdari's funeral, rioters rampaged
through Tirana, taking control of state television and ravaging
Nano's office and other government buildings. Several people were
killed in a battle with police.
</TEXT>
