<BODY>
<SLUG> AM-Caribbean-Hurricane,0612 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Critics wonder why music and soap operas played as hurricane hit
</HEADLINE>
Dominican Republic &QL; 
 &UR; With Hurricane Georges &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos PAP201,SJU101 &QL; 
 &UR; By JOSE MONEGRO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SANTO DOMINGO, Dominican Republic (AP) _ Critics are wondering
why radio stations played music and TV ran soap operas while
Hurricane Georges pounded the Dominican Republic with deadly 110
mph (175 kph) winds.
	   Dominican officials are being blamed for discounting clear
information from the Miami-based National Hurricane Center, and for
opening shelters only after the storm arrived.
	   ``When the thing hit, they were totally unprepared to respond,''
said Hugh Parmer, who is coordinating the Dominican relief effort
for the U.S. Agency for International Development.
	   The Dominican Republic is one of the Caribbean's poorest
countries, and the government's underfunded disaster relief agency
is ill-equipped. With more than 200 people killed and 100,000
homeless, the country hasn't seen a natural disaster of this
magnitude since Hurricane David in 1979.
	   Elsewhere in the Caribbean, storm victims took issue with the
responses of their governments to the disaster.
	   In Haiti, farmers in the central Artibonite Valley said
officials' failure to clear silt-clogged irrigation canals, despite
repeated warnings, contributed to deadly flooding. At least 94
Haitians were killed.
	   In Puerto Rico, where the hurricane killed three people and
caused more than dlrs 2 billion in damage, opposition leader Anibal
Acevedo accused the government of neglecting disaster relief in the
island's interior.
	   In all, Georges killed more than 300 people in its march across
the Caribbean.
	   In the Dominican Republic, newspaper editorials said both the
newly appointed civil defense chief, Elpidio Baez, and the head of
the National Meteorological Office, Felix Abreu, failed to issue
warnings under the pretext of not wanting to alarm the population.
	   Officials insist they thought the storm would hit farther north
than it did on Sept. 22, and that they believed evacuations would
only be necessary in the northeastern region of Samana.
	   ``This is a natural phenomenon, and unfortunately every time
these things happen, some people want to look for a guilty party,''
said the armed forces chief, Adm. Ruben Paulino Alvarez.
	   A specialist in the meteorological office, who spoke to The
Associated Press on condition of anonymity, said he warned his
bosses of Georges' potential for devastation 72 hours before it
hit.
	   One forecaster at the office defied his bosses' orders and
broadcast a warning the day before the storm, but the message
failed to reach most Dominicans.
	   Most Dominican victims died in flooding or mudslides;
substandard homes proved no match for the hurricane's destructive
power and the raging rivers it flooded.
	   Relief efforts continued throughout the Caribbean on Monday. The
United States sent tons of bottled water and thousands of plastic
tarps to provide roofs for 20,000 Dominican homes. Washington also
gave the Dominican Republic 20,000 pounds of food and medicine.
	   Peace Corps volunteers used rented aircraft to drop food in
areas inaccessible by road. The New York City Fire Department sent
63 search and rescue experts with four dog teams.
	   Nineteen U.S. disaster relief experts arrived in Santo Domingo
from Puerto Rico, which was struggling to clean up its own mess
Monday.
	   U.S. first lady Hillary Rodham Clinton was to arrive in Puerto
Rico on Tuesday to survey Georges' damage and visit one of the 232
shelters housing more than 17,000 people left homeless by the
hurricane.
</TEXT>
