<SLUG> BC-UN-Palestinians, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0439 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Arafat says will of Palestinians is statehood
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; URGENT &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: COMBINES pvs, UPDATES with speech given, more quotes. &QL; 
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Yasser Arafat asked world leaders Monday
to support Palestinian statehood next May, saying it was the will
of his people.
	   ``I would like to call upon all of you ... to stand by our
people,'' Arafat told the General Assembly. The Oslo peace accords
will expire on May 4, ``and our people demand of us to shoulder our
responsibilities and they await the establishment of their
independent state,'' he said.
	   ``This independent Palestinian state must be established as an
embodiment of the right of our people to self-determination,'' he
said.
	   Arafat delivered the speech after returning from Washington,
where he held a last-minute summit with U.S. President Bill Clinton
and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on an Israeli troop
pullback from the West Bank.
	   Arafat had previously said he would use the General Assembly
speech to restate his intention of unilaterally declaring an
independent Palestinian state next year _ even if there is no final
peace agreement with Israel.
	   Palestinian aides had said Arafat wanted to seek support of U.N.
member states, many of whom traditionally back the Palestinian
cause over Israeli interests.
	   Over the weekend, however, diplomatic sources had said Arafat
would tone the speech down in the wake of apparent movement in the
peace process in consultations with U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, and later Clinton.
	   But the speech Arafat gave appeared to conform with his original
intention.
	   ``We appeal to you to continue your support for us, as has
always been the case in the decisive moments of the history, the
present and the future of our people,'' Arafat said.
	   ``Help us to achieve the national goal of our people.''
	   Arafat's speech before the General Assembly has particular
significance: Never before has Arafat _ or any other Palestinian _
addressed the audience from the podium during the regular debate.
The Palestinian observer mission was granted that right earlier
this summer.
	   Arafat noted the occasion in his opening statement, thanking the
assembly for giving the Palestinians the enhanced status ``which we
consider to be an essential step towards full membership.''
	   Arafat had been expected to address the morning session, but his
appearance was postponed to allow him to travel to Washington to
meet with Netanyahu and Clinton.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-UN-Palestinians, 3rd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
