<SLUG> BC-Israel-Palestinian Killed,0223 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Two Israeli youths convicted for killing Palestinian
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   JERUSALEM (AP) _ Two Israeli youths were convicted Monday of
killing a Palestinian pedestrian by striking him across the back of
the head with a stick as they rode past in a van.
	   One of them was convicted of manslaughter, the other of causing
death by negligence.
	   On June 16, as the two were being driven home to the West Bank
Jewish settlement of Beit Hagai, one of the two boys leaned out of
the window and struck a Palestinian farmer, Mahmoud Majid
Abu-Turki, on the back of the head.
	   Abu-Turki, 52, who was married and had nine children, died
shortly afterwards at a hospital in Hebron.
	   The youths cannot be identified under Israeli law because they
are minors. The teen-ager who actually struck the blow was 16 at
the time of the offense and he faces a maximum sentence of 20
years, although the penalty imposed for manslaughter is usually
much less.
	   The other youth, who supplied the stick from a carpentry shop
where he was employed, was also charged with manslaughter. However
the Jerusalem District Court convicted him on the lesser count of
causing death by negligence.
	   The adult driver of the van, William Ohana, was acquitted of any
wrongdoing.
	   Sentencing will be scheduled for a later date.
</TEXT>
