<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Palestinians, 4th Ld-Writethru,0571 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Arafat says will of Palestinians is statehood
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with more comments, ADDS final quote of speech, ADDS 1
graf at end with details on Clinton summit; details throughout. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo UNI113 &QL; 
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ In a historic speech to the General
Assembly, Yasser Arafat asked world leaders Monday to support
Palestinian statehood next May, saying this was the will of the
Palestinian people.
	   ``I would like to call upon all of you ... to stand by our
people,'' Arafat told the leaders gathered at the assembly's annual
debate. ``This independent Palestinian state must be established as
an embodiment of the right of our people to self-determination.''
	   Arafat had said previously that he would use the General
Assembly speech to restate his intention of unilaterally declaring
an independent Palestinian state next year _ even if there is no
final peace agreement with Israel.
	   The Oslo peace accords expire on May 4, ``and our people demand
of us to shoulder our responsibilities and they await the
establishment of their independent state.''
	   The Palestinian leader delivered the speech after returning from
Washington, where he held a last-minute summit with U.S. President
Bill Clinton and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on an
Israeli troop pullback from the West Bank.
	   Palestinian aides had said Arafat wanted to seek support of
United Nations member states, many of whom traditionally back the
Palestinian cause over Israeli interests.
	   Over the weekend, however, diplomatic sources had said Arafat
would tone the speech down in the wake of apparent movement in the
peace process in consultations with U.S. Secretary of State
Madeleine Albright, and later Clinton.
	   The speech appeared to conform with his original intention,
though there was no explicit threat that he would unilaterally
declare an independent state May 4.
	   ``We appeal to you to continue your support for us, as has
always been the case in the decisive moments of the history, the
present and the future of our people,'' Arafat said.
	   ``Help us to achieve the national goal of our people in the
establishment of the state,'' he said.
	   Arafat's speech before the General Assembly had particular
significance: Never before had Arafat _ or any other Palestinian _
addressed the audience from the podium during the regular debate.
The Palestinian observer mission was granted that right earlier
this summer.
	   Arafat noted the occasion in his opening statement, thanking the
assembly for giving the Palestinians the enhanced status ``which we
consider to be an essential step towards full membership.''
	   He closed his speech by saying ``I look forward to speaking with
you once more when Palestine has taken its natural place in the
community of nations as an independent state ...''
	   Arafat had been expected to address the morning session, but his
appearance was postponed to allow him to travel to Washington to
meet with Netanyahu and Clinton.
	   Netanyahu said he and Arafat had achieved a breakthrough on a
long-elusive deal over West Bank territory. Clinton set up a
compressed schedule for concluding the accord.
	   ``I believe that we all agreed that we have made progress on the
path to peace,'' Clinton said after the three leaders met.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-UN-Palestinians, 4th Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
