<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Latin American Briefs,0636 </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Contains items from Brazil, Mexico, Chile.

<TEXT>
	   BRASILIA, Brazil (AP) _ Peru's President Alberto Fujimori and
Ecuadorian counterpart Jamil Mahuad have agreed to remove land
mines on disputed parts of their border, Mahuad said Monday.
	   After two days of talks here, Fujimori said the presidents
continued to be ``optimistic'' that a definitive peace deal could
be made over the territory this year.
	   Peru and Ecuador have fought a series of wars dating back to
1942 over the disputed territory. Most recently, in 1995, conflict
was over 49 miles (78 kms) of unmarked border.
	   In August, the countries agreed to create a demilitarized zone
to be patrolled by international peacekeepers.
	   ___
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Mexican police have arrested an executive
accused of helping banking magnate Angel Rodriguez bilk a financial
firm out of dlrs 50 million, authorities said Monday.
	   Agustin Marquez Carrillo was arrested Sunday on charges of
violating the country's banking laws by helping Rodriguez make a
series of questionable loans in 1994 that left his Banpais bank in
ruins.
	   The arrest comes amid a campaign by President Ernesto Zedillo to
clamp down on white-collar crimes in the wake of the country's 1995
banking crisis, which saddled taxpayers with dlrs 55 billion in bad
debts left by private banks.
	   Marquez Carrillo was arraigned at a Mexico City penitentiary on
the charges. Rodriguez is currently free on bail.
	   ___
	   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) _ A conference of first ladies from around
the Americas opened in the Chilean capital on Monday, with
participants set to discuss sex education, the plight of rural
women and other regional issues.
	   Chilean President Eduardo Frei opened the Eighth Conference of
Wives of Chiefs of State and Government of the Americas by calling
for improved education, saying it is ``the most efficient tool to
give dignity to the poor'' and improve their living conditions.
	   First Lady Hillary Rodham Clinton is scheduled to arrive
Wednesday and address the conference in a speech about the
political and economic advancement of women. The conference closes
Wednesday.
	   ___
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Mexico will not allow U.S. anti-drug agents
to carry guns here, and officials said they will no longer discuss
the issue and consider it a ``closed case,'' Foreign Secretary
Rosario Green said.
	   Describing her talks with U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright during recent U.N. sessions in New York, Green said Sunday
that Mexico will not yield to pressure from the U.S. congress to
change its policy.
	   ``For us, this is a closed case ... the most closed case we
have,'' Green said, according to a press statement.
	   Green said Mexico's position would not be affected by a
Congressional proposal to condition U.S. anti-drug aid to Mexico on
the country's willingness to let armed U.S. agents operate here.
	   ``Mexico ... has never accepted conditions on aid,'' Green said.
	   ___
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ A leading Mexican journalist said in an
interview Monday that media here were censored by the government in
the days after the Oct. 2, 1968 massacre of hundreds of student
demonstrators by soldiers.
	   Former news anchor Jacobo Zabludovsky told daily La Jornada he
received a phone call from then-president Gustavo Diaz Ordaz
scolding him for wearing a black tie on air the day after the
massacre.
	   Foreign media reported after the shootings _ known as the
`Massacre of Tlatelolco'' after the plaza where they occurred _
that as many as 300 people died. Most Mexican media published army
reports that only 27 people were killed.
	   President Ernesto Zedillo's administration has refused requests
by an opposition-led Congress to release government records of the
massacre.
</TEXT>
