<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Croatia,0331 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Security Council: Croatian police better but ethnic incidents up
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ The performance of local police in Croatia
has improved but violent ethnic incidents are increasing and the
judicial system isn't following them up, the U.N. Security Council
said Monday.
	   The council also noted ``a lack of progress'' in the
implementation of Croatia's program for national reconciliation.
	   Hans Dahlgren, Sweden's ambassador and the current council
president, said the council believes its July 2 statement
expressing grave concern about the number of Serbs who have fled
Croatia because of intimidation and evictions ``was still valid.''
	   After a closed-door meeting, he said the 15-member council
believes U.N. civilian police had greatly contributed to the
improved performance of local police. The council also supported
the handover of police monitoring in Croatia in mid-October from
the United Nations to the Organization for Security and Cooperation
in Europe.
	   ``Council members also noted that there are a number of serious
outstanding issues to be addressed by the authorities of Croatia
including an increase in the number of violent ethnic incidents, a
poor judicial follow-up to reported incidents, and also lack of
progress in the implementation of the program for national
reconciliation,'' Dahlgren said.
	   Large numbers of Serbs continue to emigrate because of
ethnically-related intimidation, a ``dire'' economic situation,
bureaucratic obstacles, discriminatory legislation and the stalled
refugee program, the council said.
	   The council has repeatedly expressed concern about Croatia's
commitment to granting full rights and protections to ethnic Serbs
in the eastern Slavonia region, which was seized by Serb rebels
during the ethnic conflict in the former Yugoslavia. The region
returned to Croatian control Jan. 15 after two years under U.N.
administration.
</TEXT>
