<SLUG> BC-Yugoslavia-Kosovo, 9th Ld Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Serb premier says special police units will be pulled out of Kosovo
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECASTS to raise Monday's attacks, recent casualties, ADDS
that 300 were arrested in past several days; EDITS. &QL; 
 &UR; By DUSAN STOJANOVIC &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BELGRADE, Yugoslavia (AP) _ Trying to avert a NATO attack, the
Serbian premier Monday declared Kosovo's separatists have been
defeated and promised to withdraw special police units from the
province _ a condition demanded by the United States and Europe.
	   But Premier Mirko Marjanovic said the Serb crackdown will resume
if the rebels stage new attacks, and his deputy threatened to take
hostage all pro-Western Serbs who work for independent media, peace
and human right groups in case of NATO strikes.
	   The Kosovo Liberation Army, which is fighting for Kosovo's
independence, issued a statement pledging to continue what it
called ``the holy war'' against Serbia and demanding NATO action.
The statement also criticized pacifist Kosovo Albanian leaders
``whose actions are hindering this holy war.''
	   Despite word of special forces' imminent pullout, more fighting
was reported in Kosovo Monday.
	   The Kosovo Information Center, which is close to the ethnic
Albanian leadership, reported Serbian shelling in the region of the
Suva Reka village and Urosevac town south of Pristina.
	   Reporters saw thick columns of smoke blurring the horizon of
Suva Reka where open flames consumed at least four villages
sprawling over nearby hills Monday. Police and the Yugoslav army,
backed by tanks and heavy artillery, had surrounded several
villages in the area and denied entry to journalists and foreign
diplomatic observers.
	   ``There are still many KLA,'' said one Serb police officer in
Suva Reka, which sits at the foot of the hills where Sunday's
police offensive devastated several villages.
	   The state Tanjug news agency later said that ``all (remaining)
strongholds of terrorists'' in the region of Suva Reka were
``destroyed'' Monday, and that dozens of ``terrorists'' were killed
and hundreds were arrested, a reference to a mopping-up operation
during the last several days.
	   The Kosovo Information Center also claimed that two ethnic
Albanian families, including 15 members, were ``massacred'' by
withdrawing Serb troops in the central Drenica region on Sunday.
The report could not be independently confirmed.
	   Hundreds of people have been killed and about 275,000 have fled
their homes since Yugoslav President Slobodan Milosevic's forces
began cracking down on ethnic Albanians in Kosovo in February.
	   Kosovo is part of Serbia, the dominant republic in Yugoslavia.
Most of Kosovo's ethnic Albanians _ who make up 90 percent of the 2
million inhabitants _ favor independence.
	   Marjanovic said the government will grant amnesty to Kosovo
Albanians who surrender weapons within the next 10 days unless they
have committed ``war crimes.''
	   He also said that by MOnday ``anti-terrorist activities'' had
been completed but could resume if the rebels strike again.
	   ``I wish to declare that with this day ... the armed terrorist
groups have been defeated,'' Marjanovic asserted.
	   A NATO spokesman in Brussels, who spoke on condition of
anonymity, repeated the alliance's official position that Milosevic
has to fulfill all the conditions laid down in the U.N. resolution
last Wednesday which called for an immediate cease-fire.
	   There was no visible withdrawal of the police units Monday.
Marjanovic said Serb and Yugoslav forces would remain in their
barracks for an unspecified period to guard against any resumption
of attacks by the KLA, which has been largely routed.
	   The leading ethnic Albanian party, the Democratic League of
Kosovo, stated the premier's claims were a ``manipulation of the
world public by the Belgrade regime,'' and called for an
``immediate NATO action in Kosovo to stop the humanitarian
catastrophe.''
	   The U.N. Security Council has insisted since March that Serbs
withdraw special police units and other forces from Kosovo and
begin talks with ethnic Albanians on the province's future.
	   On Wednesday, the council threatened additional action if
Milosevic did not stop the offensive against Kosovos's separatists
and allow for the safe return of refugees.
	   NATO defense chiefs then stepped up plans for airstrikes in the
event that Milosevic failed to comply.
	   During the parliamentary session, Serbia's ultra-nationalist
vice premier Vojislav Seselj threatened to take pro-Western Serbs
as hostages in case of NATO strikes.
	   Seselj told Serbia's parliament that if they decide to strike
against Serbia, the U.S. and other Western countries ``should
better withdraw'' all Serb ``traitors'' from Yugoslavia ``before we
grab them'' and take them ``hostage.''
	   Seselj's list of pro-Western ``traitors'' included journalists
of Serbia's independent newspapers and members of independent human
rights, intellectual and peace groups.
	   Seselj's address was greeted with loud applause from the
deputies.
	   (pvs/ds/rp) 	   
</TEXT>
