<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Albania, 2nd Ld-Writethru,0620 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Albanian premier resigns
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with interior minister's resignation, explosion heard
in Tirana, police cars, APC patrolling street, analysis; ADDS
byline. &QL; 
 &UR; By MERITA DHIMGJOKA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TIRANA, Albania (AP) _ Albanian Socialist Premier Fatos Nano
resigned Monday, two weeks after rioting over a politician's
assassination pushed the Balkan nation to the brink of anarchy.
	   Nano's resignation was announced after a meeting of the
Socialist Party leadership in the Albanian capital, Tirana.
	   A statement said that Pandeli Majko, the 31-year-old general
secretary of the Socialist Party, would be the party's candidate
for prime minister.
	   Nano's resignation was a main demand by the opposition
Democratic Party of former President Sali Berisha.
	   Majko's nomination was seen as a further distancing from
officials who associated with the former Communist party that ruled
Albania for 46 years.
	   Unlike Nano, Majko, a trained engineer respected for his
moderate stance, is not a former communist but took part in 1990
student demonstrations that helped topple the communists.
	   Immediately after word of Nano's resignation spread in Tirana,
gunfire erupted in several parts of the capital city. But it was
not clear whether it was just celebratory shooting by his political
foes _ supporters of his rival, former President Sali Berisha.
	   Later a loud explosion could be heard, but there was no
immediate word on the nature of the blast.
	   Hours before Nano resigned, Interior Minister Perikli Teta, a
member of the small Democratic Alliance, also quit under mounting
pressure for apparent failure to improve public security.
	   The departure of the two top government leaders apparently
prompted police to increase patrols after nightfall in a show of
regained authority after the recent chaos. At least three convoys
of police cars and an armored personnel carrier were driving
through Tirana's streets.
	   Nano became prime minister last year after his Socialist Party
of former communists defeated Berisha's Democratic Party in
parliamentary elections.
	   That internationally supervised ballot followed widespread
lawlessness and chaos that erupted with the collapse of phony
pyramid schemes in which many Albanians lost their life savings.
	   Nano stepped down Monday after he told President Rexhep Meidani
that he had been unable to put together a new Cabinet according to
his own wishes and ideas.
	   He did not manage to restructure the government because he
failed to reach agreement with all coalition parties on the makeup
of the new government, sources said.
	   More important, Nano has failed to institute key economic
reforms, attract foreign investors and instill in Albanians hope
for a better future. He was also unsuccessful in fighting
corruption and widespread weapons smuggling across the
Albanian-Yugoslav border.
	   The worsening enmity between his Socialists and Berisha's
Democrats who kept calling for his resignation and boycotted
parliament most of the time also weakened his government.
	   Political tensions reached fever pitch with the assassination by
unidentified gunmen of Azem Hajdari, a close Berisha associate on
Sept. 12.
	   Rioting began a day later with angry protesters burning the
first floor of the government building housing Nano's office as
well as seven government cars parked outside.
	   On Sept. 14, the day of Hajdari's funeral, rioters rampaged
through Tirana, taking control of state television and ravaging
Nano's office, parliament and other government buildings. At least
three people were killed in pitched battled with police and scores
were injured.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Albania, 2nd Ld-Writethru; CT:i; 
