<SLUG> BC-Cuba-Sugar,0160 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Extent of hurricane damage to Cuba's sugar crop remains unclear
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HAVANA (AP) _ The extent of harm done by Hurricane Georges to
Cuba's crucial sugar crop _ and the rest of the island's
agriculture _ was unknown Monday as authorities continued to assess
the damages.
	   Government media have steered away from the subject of sugar,
focusing instead on damage done to banana and coffee plantations by
the hurricane's march across the island on Thursday and Friday.
	   Specific damage figures for those crops have not been provided,
either.
	   Sugar still accounts for nearly half of the nation's export
revenue. Tourism recently took over as the country's No. 1 source
of income.
	   Even before the hurricane, Cuba was expecting perhaps its worst
sugar crop in half a century. Production had been expected to fall
to 3.5 million metric tons (3.9 million US tons), down from 4.6
million metric tons (5 million US tons) in 1997.
</TEXT>
