<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Britain-Cricket-Women Admitted </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
211-year-old Marylebone Cricket Club votes to admit women
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: A version moved on sports wires &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ The world's oldest cricket club, a bastion of male
exclusivity for 211 years, voted Monday to admit women.
	   The Marylebone Cricket Club, whose membership includes former
British Prime Minister John Major and the Rolling Stones' Mick
Jagger, was founded in 1787 and until 30 years ago was the
governing body for the sport.
	   Not only were women barred from membership, but with the
exception of Queen Elizabeth II, women also were not allowed to
enter the club's pavilion during play at the Lord's cricket ground,
in west London, where it is based.
	   ``I'm highly delighted,'' Barbara Daniels, vice-captain of the
England Women's Cricket Team, said after news of Monday's decision.
	   After several years of struggle within MCC to overcome the
``neanderthal'' image of its membership rules, nearly 70 percent of
the 13,482 members who voted approved the change.
	   This overturned the result of a ballot taken in February, when
55.7 percent voted to admit women, falling short of the required
two-thirds.
	   The government criticized the February failure, and the club's
governing committee warned members, whose average age is 57, that
continuing the ban would disqualify the MCC from receiving National
Lottery money for its development.
	   The England and Wales Cricket Board, which now runs the game,
has tried to extend cricket's popularity among women.
	   Most female applicants will have to join the waiting list - now
about 18 years long _ along with the men. But a few honorary
members could be expected quite soon.
	   There was hard-core opposition. One member, Robert
Titchener-Barratt, said the proposition was shoved down the club's
throat.
	   ``The committee have acted with arrogance and self-importance
saying `we're going to push this through whether you members like
it or not','' he said.
	   Rachel Heyhoe Flint, a former captain of the English women's
team who has been trying to join since 1991, said Monday night, ``I
reckon that over the last two or three years the club has been
looked on in a very poor light but now its image is brilliant.''
	   Sir Tim Rice, the lyricist and collaborator of Sir Andrew Lloyd
Webber, was one of the first to attempt to win membership for women
seven years ago.
	   ``I think it is important that the MCC for its own sake has got
rid of this albatross, because it got an unfair Neanderthal
image,'' Rice said Monday night.
	   ``Unfortunately people like my daughter Eva, who is very keen on
cricket, will have to go to the back of the queue like everyone
else and it may well be 15 or 20 years before she can join.''
	   (acw)
</TEXT>
