r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Turkey-US-Strike     09-28 0363
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Turkey-US-Strike,0363 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. Air Force reaches deal with Turkish union to end base strikes
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By SELCAN HACAOGLU &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   ANKARA, Turkey (AP) _ U.S. Air Force officials reached an
agreement Monday with a Turkish labor union to end a two-month
strike at NATO bases in Turkey, just days before a scheduled
exercise.
	   Some 1,800 Turkish workers walked off their jobs on July 23
demanding higher salaries and fringe benefits at Incirlik Air Base
_ the hub of operations for U.S. and British patrol flights over
the no-fly zone in northern Iraq _ and at two other bases in Ankara
and Aegean port city of Izmir.
	   Mustafa Acet, an official of the Harb-Is, the Union of Defense
Industry and Allied Workers that organized the strike, said that
the workers will return to work Wednesday after ratifying a Tuesday
accord with the U.S. Air Force.
	   ``We will sign the contract at 10 a.m. (0700 GMT) Tuesday,''
Acet told The Associated Press by telephone from the southern city
of Adana, where the Incirlik Air Base is located.
	   A breakthrough came only three days before a planned NATO
exercise in Turkey, Greece and Italy, scheduled to run through Oct.
21. The U.S. Air Force agreed to lay off no strikers.
	   The strikes have shut down the commissary, gas station, dining
halls and other facilities at Incirlik, where 1,446 of the workers
were employed. The other bases were similarly affected.
	   ``They were really fed up,'' Acet said of the military
personnel. ``They even could not play bowling during the strike.''
	   U.S. officials were not available for comment.
	   Acet said the U.S. officials agreed on a one-time payment of
dlrs 800 to compensate for losses during the strike, to raise
salaries by 50 percent, followed by monthly increases in line with
inflation.
	   With the increases, the workers will make more than 900 dollars
per month, nearly nine times the minimum wage of 110 per month.
	   Inflation currently runs at around 70 percent a year.
	   Since the Gulf War, U.S. and British planes monitor Iraq's
treatment of the Kurds in northern Iraq from Incirlik, some 10
kilometers (6 miles) northeast of Adana.
</TEXT>
