<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Flooding, 3rd Ld-Writethru,0522 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mudslides kill 5 in Mexico City
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; EDS: LEADS throughout to ADD quotes and description. RAISES details
of deaths; EDITS to TRIM and CONFORM. ADDS byline and photo line. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos &QL; 
 &UR; By JULIE WATSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Heavy rains swelled rivers in central Mexico
and triggered mudslides in Mexico City which killed five people and
injured four others Monday.
	   A stream of mud roared down gullies and swept away three homes
in a squatter community perched on the steep hillsides south of the
capital.
	   The slide buried a 13-year-old girl, Lourdes Barrera Orozco, who
was found still clutching her school notebook. All that remained of
the homes were a muddy pile of appliances and clothing flung
against a row of trees.
	   The girl's 6-year-old brother and a 9-year-old relative also
were caught in the slide and suffered head injuries. They were
flown by helicopter to a downtown hospital.
	   ``I heard a loud rumble and I went outside and saw my neighbors
buried there,'' one neighbor, 55-year-old Pedro Ramirez, said.
	   In a nearby neighborhood, another slide buried a family inside
their home, killing the mother and father. Two teen-age children
were pulled out alive by police. Two other people died when a muddy
hillside collapsed on top of a containment wall, crushing their
house.
	   In all, half a dozen houses were destroyed in slides and
avalanches.
	   It was a disaster city officials had predicted months earlier,
when they began urging residents to leave the shanty towns. They
had warned the squatters that the houses _ many supported only by
sandbags _ would be in danger during Mexico's rainy season.
	   But many residents refused to leave even after seeing their
neighbors' wood-and-scrap-metal homes wash down the hillside
Monday.
	   Mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas declared a state of alert due to the
flooding and mudslides. City officials warned people living near an
almost-overflowing dam in the western part of the city to prepare
to evacuate.
	   Cardenas said squatters would be encouraged to leave endangered
communities, but noted ``it would have to be voluntary.''
	   A local gymnasium was turned into a shelter capable of housing
up to 700 people, but it remained empty Monday afternoon, Garcia
said.
	   Mexico's National Meteorological Service predicted more rain.
	   Some neighborhoods in a low-lying former lake bed east of Mexico
City have been flooded for days, and to the west, the Lerma River
overflowed its banks and left some villages inundated in sewage.
	   A mudslide blocked Mexico City's main highway to the western
part of the country Monday.
	   Officials in neighboring Puebla state said a child drowned in
the swollen Atoyac River on Sunday.
	   Elsewhere, rains caused rivers to overflow in the southern state
of Chiapas, where severe flooding earlier this month killed 185
people and left hundreds of towns and villages cut off from the
outside world.
	   Two temporary bridges built to replace ones destroyed in that
flooding were washed away again Sunday, local media reported.
</TEXT>
