<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Golf-Equipment Test,0650 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Manufacturers question test for golf clubs
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; AP Photo &QL; 
 &UR; By JEFFREY GOLD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BASKING RIDGE, New Jersey (AP) _ Some of the heaviest hitters in
the golf equipment industry insist there is no need for a new test
that could render illegal the next generation of clubs.
	   At a public forum Monday on a test to measure the spring-like
effect in new drivers, club manufacturers said their products _
designed by rocket scientists using complex computer models _ have
not altered the game.
	   They said the test, which the United States Golf Association
proposed two months ago, was technically flawed and would stifle
innovation.
	   And they left little doubt that unless the USGA withdraws the
proposal, it could face a lawsuit that challenges its authority to
make rules in this country.
	   ``Why try to fix something that is not broken,'' said John A.
Solheim, president of Karsten Manufacturing Corp., maker of Ping
golf clubs. ``Innovation is one of the important traditions of
golf.''
	   USGA president F. Morgan ``Buzz'' Taylor Jr. declined to
speculate on the fate of the test, which could be decided when the
executive committee meets at the end of October.
	   Earlier this year, Taylor shook up the industry that does dlrs
1.7 billion in wholesale business of clubs when he suggested it was
time to rein in advancing technology, saying the skill factor was
eroding and that historic venues were becoming obsolete because of
how much farther players were hitting the ball.
	   But the USGA backed off at a news conference on the eve of the
U.S. Open in June. After saying that virtually every driver met
specifications, it proposed a test to measure the spring-like
effect when the ball is struck.
	   The proposed test was also to clarify its 1984 rule on the
spring-like effect, a tricky task because the USGA conceded that
all clubfaces deflect, or bend in, to some degree when striking the
ball.
	   Clubs that do not conform to ``The Rules of Golf,'' published by
the USGA and The Royal and Ancient Golf Club of St. Andrews, cannot
be used in sanctioned tournaments. The PGA Tour adheres to USGA
policy.
	   Lightweight materials, such as titanium heads and graphite
shafts, let golfers swing a longer club without added weight.
Longer clubs develop greater head speed when swung with the same
force, giving the potential for greater distance.
	   Manufacturers such as Callaway, Titleist and Ping maintain that
golf remains challenging despite the hoopla surrounding big hitters
like Tiger Woods and John Daly, and that the new clubs have allowed
less gifted players to enjoy the game.
	   Wally Uihlein, president and CEO of Acushnet Co., maker of
Titleist, Cobra and FootJoy brands, urged the USGA to withdraw the
test and form a joint committee of technical personnel from the
association and manufacturers.
	   Acushnet engineer Steve Aoyama said he dissected the USGA test
and found it difficult for others to replicate because it was
vague. He also said the method _ shooting a ball out of cannon
against a flat titanium plate _ failed to account for the loft of
clubs.
	   Callaway Golf, whose line of Big Bertha metal woods resulted in
dlrs 800 million in sales last year, was not at the hearing. In
written comments sent to the USGA, Callaway said the ``USGA has
failed to carry its burden of showing a threat to the game of golf
that would justify a ban on new technology.''
	   All other speakers, such as Daiwa, agreed. The exception was
George Montgomery, CEO of Taylor Made. He said five years of
research by his engineers identified a spring-like effect in
various designs and that the ``fundamentally sound'' USGA test
would not limit innovation.
	   Montgomery suggested limiting how much spin a clubface could
impart on a ball.
</TEXT>
