<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Track-Obit-Heino,0157 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Last of the Flying Finns dead at 84
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   HELSINKI, Finland (AP) _ Viljo Akseli Heino, the last of the
track stars called the ``Flying Finns,'' has died at age 84, the
International Amateur Atheltic Federation said Monday.
	   Heino died Sept. 15 in Tampere. The cause of death was not
given.
	   Although Heino was not as well known as others known by the
nickname, such as Paavo Nurmi and Viljam Ritola, he set world
records even after suffering a leg injury in Finland's 1939 war
against the Soviet Union.
	   In 1944, Heino set the world record for 10,000 meters of 28:38.6
at a race in Helsinki. He was also given credit in the same race
for setting a world 6-mile record.
	   ``Had Heino's athletics career not been compromised by the ...
war, who knows what he might have achieved?''' the IAAF said in its
statement.
	   There was no information about a funeral or survivors.
</TEXT>
