<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Dominican-Hurricane-Town Regained,0462 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Relief arrives in Dominican town cut off by hurricane for six days
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By JARED KOTLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN JUAN DE LA MAGUANA, Dominican Republic _ Hurricane victims
stranded by fallen bridges and washed-out roads waded into
subsiding waters Monday to guide the first relief trucks into this
western Dominican town.
	   Seventy-six people died in San Juan de la Maguana, a farm town
of about 20,000 people 75 miles (125 kilometers) west of Santo
Domingo, the Red Cross said. Local hospital officials said they had
documented 19 dead, but suspected that many more have been buried
by relatives.
	   In a small cemetery outside town, the graves of eight people
were marked by a two-foot-high (60-centimeter-high) mound covered
with red and purple flowers and crosses made of sticks. Nine other
storm victims were buried nearby.
	   San Juan de la Maguana had been incommunicado since Sept. 22,
when Hurricane Georges' rains caused floodwaters to crash through
the town, swallowing up shantytowns along the San Juan River.
	   Flooding was aggravated when workers at a dam upstream opened
floodgates to relieve pressure on the dam.
	   Residents said they had some warning but were unprepared for the
disaster.
	   ``They told us before it happened, but I didn't think it would
be this bad,'' said Alejandro Mateo, 68, who fled his yellow
clapboard house in the Monte de Oca neighborhood as the water rose.
The house now is filled with mud.
	   Until Monday, downed trees and bridges and raging streams
prevented rescuers from reaching the town by land or landing by
helicopter. Both the U.S. Peace Corps and the U.S. Agency for
International Development had said getting to San Juan was a top
priority.
	   Children dashed across a field Monday to collect packets of
disaster supplies dropped by a small airplane buzzing the town.
Doctors waited anxiously for medical supplies to vaccinate
residents against diseases and prepared for a surge in dengue and
malaria, both carried by mosquitoes that breed in stagnant water.
	   Patients also were being vaccinated to prevent tetanus and
diphtheria, said hospital physician Idana Castillo.
	   Two flatbed trailers carrying 110-pound (50-kilogram) bags of
rice donated by Australia arrived Monday afternoon, and workers
prepared the trucks for a push across a flooded roadway leading to
town.
	   A barefoot boy squatted in the shade beneath one of the trucks,
collecting falling grains of rice in a tattered red baseball cap.
	   U.S. helicopters were expected to fly more supplies into the
area on Tuesday.
	   Georges killed more than 200 people in the Dominican Republic
and at least 94 in nearby Haiti as it spun westward through the
Caribbean last week.
</TEXT>
