r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Iran-Newspapers     09-28 0304
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Iran-Newspapers,0303 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Iranian papers banned for insulting Khomeini
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TEHRAN, Iran (AP) _ A Tehran press court on Monday banned two
Iranian publications for insulting the late spiritual leader
Ayatollah Ruhollah Khomeini, Iranian television reported.
	   The court revoked the publishing licenses of the daily Tous and
the monthly Jameah-e Salem. The owner of the monthly was given a
five-year suspended jail sentence for ``publishing lies, insulting
the state authorities, and distorting the utterances'' of Khomeini,
who died in 1989, the station said. It gave no further details.
	   The case against the daily Zan, on charges of ``publishing lies,
defaming public figures and causing public concern,'' was adjourned
to allow further investigations, said the TV, monitored by the
British Broadcasting Corporation.
	   Zan, or Woman, is owned by Faezeh Hashemi, daughter of former
President Hashemi Rafsanjani.
	   Authorities had already shut down Tous temporarily for allegedly
publishing articles ``detrimental to national interests.'' Three of
its senior staffers have also been arrested since the paper closed
on Sept. 16.
	   Tous angered hard-liners with its anti-war stance. The newspaper
has called for a diplomatic solution rather than military strikes
in the conflict with the Taliban in Afghanistan.
	   The newspaper also angered hard-liners by questioning the
authority of Ayatollah Ali Khamenei, Iran's spiritual guide.
	   The deputy director and an editor of Iran's official Islamic
Republic News Agency were also arrested earlier this month but
later released.
	   They were detained after a hard-line official filed a complaint
with a Tehran court.
	   Khamenei, also a hard-liner, has called on the judiciary to deal
with what he calls ``the abuse of press freedom'' by the media.
</TEXT>
