<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Markets,0169 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Mexican stocks end higher; peso strengthens
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Expectations that the Federal Reserve will
cut U.S. interests rates this week helped Mexican stocks withstand
a late bout of selling and close higher, along with the peso.
	   The market's key IPC index closed up 0.4 percent, or 13.49
points, to 3,717.18 points. At the end of 1997, the IPC stood at
5,229.35.
	   The Federal Reserve's Open Market Committee is expected to lower
interest rates when it meets Tuesday, which would favor emerging
markets, traders said.
	   In Mexico City on 48-hour spot dollar markets, banking leader
Banamex quoted the peso closing at a midrate of 10.11 per dollar,
weaker from its open of 10.075 per dollar but stronger from
Friday's 10.12 close.
	   Spreads at the close were 10.1 to 10.12 compared with 10.105 to
10.135 on Friday.
	   In Mexican peso futures trading on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange, December contracts ended at 10.8021 after closing Friday
at 10.7585.
</TEXT>
