<SLUG> BC-Panama-Prison Strike,0147 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Foreigners demand TVs at Panamanian prison
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   PANAMA CITY (AP) _ Twenty foreigners imprisoned in Panama began
a hunger strike Monday to demand that legal proceedings against
them be speeded up and for permission to keep televisions and
radios in their cells.
	   The prisoners, who include Colombians, one Israeli and one Costa
Rican, called on their Panamanian counterparts to join the strike
but the Panamanians declined, the Government and Justice Ministry
said in a statement.
	   Authorities said security restrictions do not allow electronic
equipment in jail cells.
	   The inmates on strike at the La Joyita prison, 40 kilometers (25
miles) east of the capital, mostly are jailed on drug-trafficking
charges, radio reports said.
	   Some 80 percent of the 1,300 inmates are awaiting trial, local
newspapers reported.
</TEXT>
