<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AP Top Financial News,0766 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS:
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   A summary of financial and business news from The Associated
Press at 0000 GMT. Stories carry ``f'' or ``i'' category codes and
move on this circuit in expanded form:
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ Stocks gave up sharp early gains and turned
mixed Monday in advance of a meeting of Federal Reserve
policy-makers that is expected to lower interest rates in a bid to
revive the global economy. The Dow Jones industrial average, which
rose 133.11 points last week, added as much as 131.56 in the early
going before giving up some of its gains. It closed up 80.07, or by
1 percent, at a one-month high of 8,108.84. (US-CLOSING STOCKS)
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ With Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan
expressing alarm about a deteriorating world economy, Fed
policy-makers are expected to cut interest rates for the first time
in nearly three years on Tuesday. While they don't believe the
outcome of the Fed's meeting is in doubt, private economists said
Monday that the big question is how much success the world's most
powerful central bank will have in containing a currency crisis
that so far has proven unstoppable. Emphasizing the sense or
urgency, international monetary authorities were busy working
behind the scenes on a rescue package for Brazil. The largest
economy in South America is being hit by the same panicked rush to
the exits by foreign investors that has already flattened a number
of Asian countries and Russia. (US-FINANCIAL CRISIS)
	   RIO DE JANEIRO, Brazil (AP) _ Battered by a never-ending Asian
crisis, Brazil is looking for some good news this week at the
annual meeting of the International Monetary Fund in Washington
D.C. The government's economic team heads to Washington on Tuesday
amid rumors that a major loan package is in the works to avert a
possibly disastrous devaluation of the Brazilian real. One estimate
puts the loan package for Brazil at dlrs 30 billion. Another says
dlrs 50 billion will be earmarked for all of Latin America. But
after a costly bailout for Russia, it's not clear how much the IMF
can come up with, or whether the Group of Seven industrialized
countries will pitch in. (BRAZIL-IMF)
	   MOSCOW (AP) _ In a blow to market-oriented economic reforms, the
country's tough-talking tax chief was fired Monday, the last step
in a purge that leaves only one of the previous Cabinet's young
reformers remaining in the government. Boris Fyodorov, who strongly
supported economic reform and opposed printing new money, had
promised to get tough on tax deadbeats in an effort to fill the
country's empty coffers. Also dumped was acting Deputy Prime
Minister Viktor Khristenko, who advocated tightening control over
government spending and cutting down waste. The firings were
announced during a meeting between Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov
and President Boris Yeltsin aimed at completing a new Cabinet, a
process that has already taken three weeks, and is still not
finished. (RUSSIA-ECONOMY)
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ German industry leaders voiced concern
Monday that the left's election victory threatened the economy, but
the stock market welcomed the prospect of a stable government under
future chancellor Gerhard Schroeder. Schroeder, a Social Democrat,
said Monday he would seek a coalition with the environmentalist
Greens as junior partner _ a shock for organized industry, which
strongly backed defeated Chancellor Helmut Kohl. ``I believe, as I
always have, that the Greens are an anti-industry party,'' said
Hans Peter Stihl, head of the German Chamber of Industry and
Commerce. The Frankfurt Stock Exchange took a more favorable view,
though, ending the day 2 percent higher. (GERMANY-ELECTION
INDUSTRY)
	   ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) _ Algeria's prime minister said Monday the
government would stick to its massive program of privatization,
assuring that the nation's disgruntled main union would be
consulted along the way. ``We will continue to implement reforms,''
Ahmed Ouyahia said after marathon 19-hour talks with Abdelmadjid
Sidi-Said, head of the General Union of Algerian Workers (UGTA),
Algeria's largest union. ``We will continue privatization within
the framework of the law, transparently and with dialogue,'' he
added. Unemployment is already around 30 percent of the active
population, and the government's program of privatizing state
industries, under the pressure of the International Monetary Fund,
is translating into further job losses. (ALGERIA-ECONOMY)
</TEXT>
