<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Today In History,0530 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sunday, October 4
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   Today is Sunday, October 4th, the 277th day of 1997. There are
88 days left in the year.
 &UR; Highlights in history on this date:
	   1530 - Ivan the Terrible, first russian czar, well-known for his
cruelty.
	   1539 - Marriage treaty is signed for England's King Henry VIII
to wed Anne of Cleves.
	   1824 - Republic of Mexico is proclaimed.
	   1853 - Turkey declares war on Russia.
	   1865 - Napoleon III and Otto von Bismarck meet at Biarritz,
where Napoleon III agrees to Prussian supremacy in Germany and to a
united Italy.
	   1910 - Portugal's King Manuel II flees to England on outbreak of
revolution in Lisbon.
	   1930 - Brazilian revolution, with Getulio Vargas becoming new
President.
	   1945 - French wartime collaborator Pierre Laval is put on trial
in Paris as traitor in World War II, and he later is executed.
	   1957 - Soviet Union puts first spacecraft into orbit around
earth, heralding start of space age.
	   1966 - Lesotho gains independence from Britain.
	   1969 - China announces two nuclear weapons tests, including
hydrogen bomb explosion in atmosphere.
	   1973 - Peace talks begin in Northern Ireland in attempt to end
five years of conflict that has taken almost 900 lives.
	   1977 - India's former Prime Minister Indira Gandhi is released
from police custody less than 24 hours after her arrest on charges
of political corruption.
	   1980 - Islamic representatives from 38 nations move to have U.N.
General Assembly call for Soviet troop withdrawal from Afghanistan.
	   1986 - Fire breaks out in Soviet nuclear-powered submarine
carrying ballistic missiles, and three people are reported dead.
	   1988 - Brazil enacts new Constitution, completing long-awaited
``transition to democracy.''
	   1989 - Lebanese hijacker Fawaz Younis sentenced to 30 years in
U.S. prison.
	   1992 - Government and Mozambique National Resistance rebels sign
a peace treaty to end 15 years of civil war.
	   1993 - Russian parliament leaders surrender to soldiers loyal to
President Boris Yeltsin, at least 300 dead in two days of fighting.
	   1994 - Undersea earhquake kills at least 16 people in Russia's
Kuril Islands.
	   1995 - Sidestepping differences on such issues as abortion, U.S.
President Bill Clinton joined Pope Pail II in an impassioned plea
for social policies that protect the poor and keep families
together.
	   1996 - Armed Taliban fighters haul men off the streets and force
them into mosques to hear fiery sermons during the first Muslim
sabbath in Kabul since the new Islamic rulers took over.
	   1997 - Hundreds of thousands of Christian men, the ``Promise
Keepers'' rally in Washinngton admitting their own failingts and
hoping to reverse what they believe is the United States'' moral
decline as a nation.
	   Today's Birthdays:
	   Francois Guizot, French politician-historian (1787-1874);
Charlton Heston, U.S. actor (1924--); Patti LaBelle, U.S.
singer-actress (1944--).
	   Thought For Today:
	   Liberty is not a means to a higher political end. It is itself
the highest political end _ Lord Acton, English historian
(1834-1902).
</TEXT>
