<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-US-Merger Slowdown,0469 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Stock market volatility will slow merger frenzy
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By ERIC R. QUINONES &QC; 
 &UR; AP Business Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ After the bull market drove mergers to dizzying
heights, the stock market's summer swoon will likely force
dealmakers to the sidelines.
	   Wall Street's plunge since mid-July has erased all of this
year's gains and undercut the lofty stock prices that have paid for
1998's record-high mergers. As investors struggle to determine
whether turmoil in Asia and Russia will infect the American
economy, the blistering pace of mergers is expected to cool.
	   ``As long as the market stays very volatile, I think deal
activity generally is going to slow down a lot,'' said Rob Kindler,
a takeover partner at the law firm Cravath, Swaine and Moore.
	   Merger professionals and analysts say it is too soon to judge
whether dealmaking has slowed in response to the market's recent
decline, since August is normally a slow month for mergers with so
many people taking vacations.
	   But the mergers that did occur last month showed a sharp rise in
cash deals, which is expected to become a rising trend if stocks
slide further.
	   Of the U.S. mergers announced in August, 47.6 percent were cash
deals, up from 41.7 for the first seven months of the year,
according to Mergerstat, a division of Los Angeles investment bank
Houlihan, Lokey, Howard and Zukin.
	   ``If the market continues to go down and interest rates continue
to go down, which has been the case, I don't think there's any
question that we'll find a lot of cash deals at the end of this
year and early next year,'' Kindler said.
	   The risks associated with stock swaps, which had seemed minimal
during the market's meteoric rise over the past few years, are
highlighted by the billions of dollars in value slashed from many
of this year's megamergers.
	   Most notably, the Travelers-Citicorp deal was worth dlrs 70
billion _ the richest deal ever _ when announced in April, but has
plunged to dlrs 44.3 billion and dropped to fourth on the all-time
list. The current No. 1 deal, SBC Communications' merger with
Ameritech, itself has dropped from dlrs 62 billion when announced
in May to about dlrs 56 billion.
	   If stocks fall far enough, deals may have to be revalued or
scrapped altogether.
	   In another megadeal from this year, Wells Fargo agreed in June
to a dlrs 34 billion merger with rival bank Norwest that is now
worth dlrs less than 25 billion because Norwest's shares have
skidded. But Norwest spokesman Larry Haeg said the deal had no
provisions to adjust the terms if Norwest stock declined and the
merger is proceeding as planned.
	   The stock market closed up 80.07 points at 8,108.84 on Monday,
still down 1,229 points, or 13.2 percent, from its July 17 peak of
9,337.97.
</TEXT>
