w1692 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Australia-Election     09-28 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Election </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Howard endorses view that big Aboriginal land councils are
</HEADLINE>
`bloodsuckers' &QL; 
 &UR; By PETER JAMES SPIELMANN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Racial politics, never far below the
surface in Australia, erupted into the national campaign Tuesday
when Prime Minister John Howard endorsed his deputy's attack on
large Aboriginal agencies as ``bureaucratic bloodsucking''
organizations.
	   On Monday, Deputy Prime Minister Tim Fischer called the Alice
Springs-based Central Land Council and the Darwin-based Northern
Land Council ``giant bureaucratic bloodsucking land councils which
take away from smaller communities resources and flexible
infrastructure and leadership.''
	   Aboriginal land councils advise the government on the allocation
of grants and resources for Aboriginal health, welfare, and other
projects.
	   Howard on Tuesday backed the thrust of Fischer's attack, saying:
``I haven't seen what Tim said but he's right when he wants the
resources available for indigenous people to go to them rather than
to bureaucracies.''
	   The Aboriginal and Torres Strait Islander Commission (ATSIC),
which represents the interests of Aborigines on a national level,
demanded an apology from Fischer.
	   ``Mr. Howard can't talk about reconciliation one day and excuse
this type of language from his deputy the next.
	   ``His remarks do nothing for race relations in this country.
They demean the office of deputy prime minister,'' ATSIC chairman
Gatjil Djerrkura said.
	   Opposition leader Kim Beazley said he was sorry Fischer had
resorted to such language in the final days of the campaign for
Saturday's election.
	   ``I think Mr. Fischer faces terrible struggles on many fronts
but he does not need to break away and make an intemperate
statement,'' Beazley said.
	   The 350,000 or so Aborigines among Australia's 18 million people
are collectively the poorest and least healthy minority in the
country, with the highest rates of unemployment, high infant
mortality and much shorter life spans.
	   Two new polls on Tuesday show Howard's governing conservatives
and the Labor Party opposition in a dead heat before Saturday's
election, with a hung Parliament a possibility.
	   The Newspoll published in The Australian newspaper showed
Howard's conservative coalition edging ahead of Beazley's Labor
Party by 43-42 percent, but with a margin of error of 2.3 percent.
	   Meanwhile, The Bulletin news magazine poll put the conservatives
at 40 percent and Labor at 39 percent, with a 2 percent margin of
error.
	   But with the right-wing populist One Nation party polling at 7
percent, the Australian Democrats at 8 percent in both polls, there
is a possibility that neither the conservatives nor Labor will win
a majority in the House of Representatives, where government is
formed.
	   To win government, Labor would have to take 27 House seats away
from Howard's ruling conservative coalition.
	   On Monday, the Labor party's most senior strategist said Labor
would have to pull off the biggest political comeback in Australian
history to win Saturday's election.
	   Labor national secretary Gary Gray said no party had won more
than eight seats back after one term in opposition.
	   In the House of Representatives, Howard's governing Liberal
Party and rural National coalition holds 90 seats, the Labor Party
holds 49, independents 8 and the Northern Territory's Country
Liberal Party, 1.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Australia-Election; CT:i; 
