w1700 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UN-Iraq-VX     09-28 0346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Iraq-VX,0350 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Swiss VX tests negative, French tests incomplete, sources say
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Swiss tests of Iraqi missile warheads
suspected of containing the deadly nerve agent VX have turned up
negative, diplomatic sources said Monday.
	   Similar tests in France aren't complete, but may contradict
results of a U.S. army laboratory which disclosed in June that
scientists had determined missile fragments contained traces of the
gas.
	   The Swiss results are a blow to the United Nations and in
particular the United States, which had held the U.S. results as
clear evidence that Iraq had been untruthful about its chemical
weapons program.
	   Iraq, which has had to endure seven years of intrusive U.N.
weapons inspections, has admitted it tried to make VX but has
denied it was ever able to make enough of it or stabilize it
sufficiently to load into weapons.
	   A few drops of the nerve agent can be fatal.
	   The Swiss tests were conducted on fragments taken from the same
location as the parts tested in the U.S. laboratory and turned up
negative, the sources said, speaking on condition of anonymity.
	   The chief U.N. weapons inspector has said that even if the
European tests are negative, Iraq still has to answer for the U.S.
tests, which were conducted at the Aberdeen Proving ground in
Maryland.
	   U.N. arms experts must certify Iraq has destroyed its chemical,
biological and nuclear weapons _ and the long-range missiles to
deliver them _ before the Security Council will lift crippling
sanctions imposed after Baghdad invaded Kuwait in 1990.
	   The test results are contained in a report given to Butler by a
team of experts who gathered at U.N. headquarters late last week to
review the data from the laboratories.
	   Butler was considering whether to release the report to the
Security Council or wait to include it in a six-month report on the
status of inspections that he is set to prepare next week, U.N.
officials said.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
