<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Canadian Briefs,0805 </SLUG>

 &UR; Eds: Dollar amounts are in Canadian dollars &QL; 
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TORONTO (AP) _ They called it The Most, but a bold move to offer
long-distance callers unlimited evening and weekend service for a
flat, monthly fee of $20 proved to be Too Much for Sprint Canada.
	   The alternative long-distance company scaled back its wildly
popular discount plan Monday after receiving complaints about
constant busy signals on a clogged telephone network.
	   The flat-rate pricing scheme, introduced in July and copied by
most of Sprint's competitors, has led some people to keep their
phone lines constantly busy, either through marathon chats or a
binge on the Internet.
	   As of next Monday, Sprint callers will be limited to a maximum
of 800 minutes a month for calls made inside Canada during off-peak
hours. Any calls made above that limit will cost 10 cents a minute.
	   ---
	   TORONTO (AP) _ The new agency managing Canada's blood supply
officially took control of collection and distribution Monday with
a mandate to ensure ``the tragedies of the past don't happen
again.''
	   The blood system is ``as safe as any system can be, but it can
never be 100 per cent safe,'' said Lynda Cranston, chief executive
officer of Canadian Blood Services, which replaces the Canadian Red
Cross Society.
	   Cranston _ a former cable industry executive _ told a national
satellite-linked news conference there will be an ``open,
transparent and accountable'' way of giving Canadians the ``gift of
life.''
	   The agency, which has an estimated operating budget of $350
million a year, receives provincial and territorial funding. It
will operate at arm's length from the government so its
``responsibility is to the consumer, and not the government,''
Cranston added.
	   It will work closely with Hema-Quebec, Quebec's blood-supply
body which also began operations Monday.
	   ---
	   VANCOUVER (AP) _ The commercial fishing industry as it now
exists in British Columbia is finished, says a report prepared for
the David Suzuki Foundation.
	   ``We all have to recognize that it's over,'' Terry Glavin, who
wrote the report for the Vancouver-based environmental group, said
Monday.
	   ``The conventional industrial fisheries on this coast are
gone.''
	   The report comes near the end of another troubled salmon-fishing
season here, with hundreds of boats tied to the dock because of
drastic fishing restrictions to preserve threatened coho salmon
stocks.
	   Salmon returns have been disappointing for years and some stocks
have already experienced East Coast-style collapse, said Glavin.
	   His report also recommends replacing the Canada-U.S. Pacific
Salmon Treaty, because it is unworkable. Glavin wants a new
agreement whose priority is conservation instead of divvying up the
West Coast salmon catch.
	   ---
	   VICTORIA (AP) _ Canada continues to roll over and do nothing to
help hundreds of animals facing extinction, protesters pushing for
federal endangered species legislation said Monday.
	   About 150 people, some wearing fur bear masks and paper salmon
heads, chanted ``Save our species'' outside a hotel where federal
and provincial wildlife ministers were meeting.
	   Wildlife artist Robert Bateman said there are 307 animal species
on the national endangered list, but the federal government appears
afraid to offer them protection.
	   Canada needs a strong federal law to protect endangered grizzly
bears, Vancouver Island marmots and Pacific salmon stocks, he said.
	   ---
	   OTTAWA (AP) _ The federal government won't tap into the rich
Employment Insurance fund without giving Canadians a chance to talk
about it, Finance Minister Paul Martin said Monday.
	   Martin also denied reports he submitted to cabinet a formal
proposal to use the fund, expected to hit $20 billion by next
spring.
	   But the minister did acknowledge discussing the idea with
cabinet colleagues.
	   Martin spent much of the day explaining himself after word
leaked he's been eyeing the fund's huge surplus to ensure he
delivers on promises of lower taxes, a lower federal debt and more
spending on health and education.
	   ---
	   OTTAWA (AP) _ Three veterans of the Second World War Merchant
Navy began a hunger strike Monday to win government benefits for
themselves and their former comrades.
	   But Veterans Affairs Minister Fred Mifflin, himself a retired
admiral, said they won't get the money they want.
	   The three, Ozzie Osbourne, Rudolph Hope and Ward Duke, all in
their 70s, want payments of $20,000 for each of the surviving
Merchant Navy vets or surviving spouses.
	   The money is intended to make up for the benefits denied the
merchant seamen in the years immediately after the war.
</TEXT>
