<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Bank Strike </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
South Korean bank clerks vow strike after talks break down
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ Bank union leaders failed to reach
agreement with management representatives in overnight negotiations
over layoffs Tuesday, setting the stage for a strike by employees
of five major South Korean commercial banks.
	   Riot police, armed with helmets and batons, were deployed to
guard the head and branch offices of the five financially shaky
banks which have been ordered by the government to restructure or
face closure or merger.
	   A key part of the restructuring involves layoffs.
	   ``We did our best but were unable to reach agreement on the
extent of layoffs,'' said Chu Kyong-su, head of the Korea
Federation of Bank and Financial Unions, after six hours of
overnight negotiations.
	   ``It's regrettable that the unions are shortsighted and did not
see the reality,'' said Ryu Si-yul, who represented the managers.
	   Less than two hours before the banks were to open for business,
7,000 unionized bank clerks continued a rally at a Roman Catholic
church in downtown Seoul, vowing to go on strike as scheduled.
	   But a fissure emerged in their ranks as the unions of four banks
_ Korea First, Kangwon, Chungbuk, and Peace _ accepted layoff
proposals by their managers and agreed to return to work.
	   Five banks facing strikes include Chohung, Hanil, Korea
Commercial, Korea Exchange and Seoul. Together, they have 17,000
unionized employees.
	   A major point of disagreement was a proposal by the managers to
cut total manpower by 33 percent by the end of this year but with
an offer of enhanced severance pay.
	   The unions demanded that the layoffs be spread over three years
with bigger financial compensation.
	   Restructuring its bloated, inefficient banking sector is a key
promise South Korea has made in return for a dlrs 58 billion
economic bailout provided by the International Monetary Fund in
December.
	   Five banks were closed earlier as part of the restructuring.
	   South Korean banks maintained cozy relations with past
military-backed governments. Their lending was frequently affected
by political and government policies.
	   When dozens of financially shaky businesses collapsed late last
year, many banks were left with piles of non-performing loans. That
eroded investor confidence, fueling a flight of foreign capital. 	   
</TEXT>
