<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Election-Poll </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Latest poll shows conservatives just ahead in Australian vote
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING to fix slug

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Just days ahead of Australia's Oct. 3
national election, Prime Minister John Howard's government has
nosed ahead of the opposition Labor Party in the latest opinion
poll released Tuesday.
	   But the race is so close that the government may not win the
election if the poll result is repeated on election day.
	   The Newspoll published in The Australian newspaper shows
Howard's conservative coalition ahead of Labor with a primary vote
of 43 percent, compared to Labor's 42 percent. That marks a
reversal of the previous Newspoll survey a week earlier, which had
Labor at 43 percent and the coalition at 42 percent.
	   Newspoll surveyed 1,729 people on Sept. 26 and Sept. 27. No
margin of error was published, but it is generally between two and
three percent.
	   The poll also shows, however, that Labor continues to lead the
government on a two-party preferred basis, garnering 51 percent
support, while the government attracts 49 percent.
	   That would give Labor a narrow victory after the distribution of
preference votes from minor parties.
	   Under Australia's preferential voting system, if no candidate in
an electorate gains 50 percent of votes, the one with the fewest
votes is excluded.
	   That candidate's votes are transferred to the other candidates
according to the preferences shown on voting cards. The process
continues until one candidate has more than 50 percent of the votes
and is declared elected.
	   The Australian said the distribution of right-wing populist One
Nation party preferences would be vital to the outcome of the
election.
	   Another poll published this week put Labor one point ahead of
the coalition with 50.5 percent of the primary vote against 49.5
percent for the coalition.
	   Labor needs a swing to it of about 4 percent nationally to win
the 27 electorates which would deliver the party government.
	   Labor's most senior strategist Gary Gray on Monday said Labor
would have to pull off the biggest political comeback in Australian
history to win Saturday's election.
	   No party had won more than eight seats after one term in
opposition, he said. 	   
</TEXT>
