u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EuropeanLeft     09-28 0604
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-European Left,0603 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Schroeder's victory in Germany continues leftward swing
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With Germany-Election
 &UR; By ROBERT BARR &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   LONDON (AP) _ When Helmut Kohl took command in Germany in 1982,
conservatism was at high tide. Ronald Reagan was in the White
House, Margaret Thatcher led Britain and the socialist President
Francois Mitterrand was a glaring French exception to the rule.
	   Kohl's defeat in Germany's national elections on Sunday by
Gerhard Schroeder followed a moderate swing to the left led by Bill
Clinton in the United States, Romano Prodi in Italy, Tony Blair in
Britain and Lionel Jospin in France.
	   Clinton and Blair in particular personify a new breed of
media-savvy leftist who feels most comfortable in the center.
Jospin and Prodi are less slick, both coming from academic
backgrounds.
	   Former British Prime Minister John Major, who lost to Blair last
year, said Monday that time catches up to all politicians.
``Politics is a little like a stream. It tends to move on,'' said
Major, whose Conservative Party was in power for 18 consecutive
years.
	   Blair beat Major with some typically conservative promises: no
income tax hikes, a determination to whip inflation, and a strong
national defense. But there was a strong sense that Britons had
simply tired of the Conservatives and were ready to try something
new.
	   In office, Blair suffers the strongest criticism from
disappointed constituents from the left of the party. This week,
party members registered their concern by electing leftists to four
of the six seats at stake on the Labor Party executive.
	   ``I know that while most Labor supporters were prepared to bite
their tongues to win, and were delighted when Tony Blair ended
Labor's decades in the wilderness, they did not intend doing so in
perpetuity,'' Mark Seddon, one of the newly elected members of the
executive, wrote in Monday's Evening Standard newspaper.
	   Jospin, 60, a loser to the conservative Jacques Chirac in the
presidential race in 1995, became prime minister two years later
and returned the left to grace in France with a surprise
performance as a consensus builder and crowd pleaser who remains
faithful to his socialist goals.
	   On practical matters, Jospin kept his promise to tackle
unemployment. Under him, the 12.8 percent unemployment rate has
dropped to 11.8 percent.
	   To quell critics, he softened his approach, but did not abandon
the 35-hour work week, and eased tough immigration laws without
ruffling feathers. He also went ahead with the right's planned sale
of state companies and held down the budget to prepare for the
single currency.
	   After a year in office, a poll published in the leftist
newspaper Liberation said that seven out of 10 rated Jospin
``courageous'' and ``open.''
	   In Italy, Romano Prodi's center-left ``Olive Tree'' coalition
government including ex-Communists, former Christian Democrats and
Greens, has been in office since 1996. An economist and academic
with little public experience, Prodi has seemed uncomfortable on
television and at political rallies. But voters evidently approve
the contrast to his predecessor, the conservative television
magnate Silvio Berlusconi.
	   For the first two years, Prodi pursued strict economic policies
to get Italy in line to join a European single currency.
	   With that achieved, he is now aiming to cut unemployment,
especially in Italy's depressed south where the jobless rate is
nearly double the national average of 12.5 percent. He also is
trying to slim the welfare state without upsetting his Communist
allies.
</TEXT>
