r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UN-Palestinians     09-28 0565
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Palestinians,0574 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Arafat says will of Palestinians is statehood
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS previous &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photo UNI113 &QL; 
 &UR; By NICOLE WINFIELD &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Yasser Arafat heeded U.S. pleas in his
first speech to the General Assembly's annual debate, asking world
leaders to support Palestinian statehood but refraining from a
unilateral threat to declare a state next May.
	   Israel's U.N. ambassador, Dore Gold, welcomed the restraint.
	   ``Clearly he has preferred the option of negotiations over the
option of a unilateral act,'' Gold told reporters. ``And in that
sense, we have something we can express our satisfaction with.''
	   Arafat delivered the speech after returning from Washington,
where he held a last-minute summit Monday morning with President
Bill Clinton and Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu on an
Israeli troop pullback from the West Bank.
	   In what Netanyahu said was a breakthrough meeting, Clinton set
up a compressed schedule for concluding the West Bank accord.
	   ``Israel and the Palestinians can now move on in an attempt to
conclude a negotiated settlement, which will have to balance the
requirements and address the needs of both sides,'' Gold said.
	   Arafat had said as recently as Friday that he would use the
General Assembly speech to restate his intention of declaring an
independent Palestinian state next year regardless of whether a
final peace agreement with Israel was in place.
	   Palestinian aides had said Arafat wanted to seek support of U.N.
member states who traditionally back the Palestinian cause over
Israeli interests.
	   Over the weekend, however, diplomatic sources said that Arafat
would tone the speech down in the wake of apparent movement in the
peace process in consultations with Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright, and on Monday, Clinton.
	   The speech didn't rule out his original intention, though there
was no explicit threat that he would unilaterally declare an
independent state in May.
	   Arafat said repeatedly that statehood was not a debatable issue
and concluded by announcing that he looked forward to speaking to
the assembly once more ``when Palestine has taken its natural place
in the community of nations as an independent state.''
	   Arafat stressed that the Oslo peace accords expire on May 4.
``Our people demand of us to shoulder our responsibilities and they
await the establishment of their independent state.''
	   ``This independent Palestinian state must be established as an
embodiment of the right of our people to self-determination,'' he
said.
	   ``We appeal to you to continue your support for us, as has
always been the case in the decisive moments of the history, the
present and the future of our people,'' Arafat said.
	   ``Help us to achieve the national goal of our people in the
establishment of the state,'' Arafat said.
	   Arafat's speech before the General Assembly has particular
significance: Never before has Arafat _ or any other Palestinian _
addressed the audience from the podium during the regular debate.
The Palestinian observer mission was granted that right earlier
this summer.
	   Arafat noted the occasion in his opening statement, thanking the
assembly for giving the Palestinians the enhanced status ``which we
consider to be an essential step towards full membership.''
</TEXT>
