w1724 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Baseball-Sosa'     09-28 0558
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Baseball-Sosa's Homers,0567 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Sosa's spectacular regular season draws to a close
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By NANCY ARMOUR &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   CHICAGO (AP) _ Even Michael Jordan has Sammy Sosa fever.
	   With one last chance to add to his 66 home runs and put the
Chicago Cubs in the playoffs, Sosa got a visit from Chicago's other
favorite athlete Monday night.
	   Wearing a Chicago Cubs jacket, Jordan was greeted with a huge
roar when he trotted out to the mound to throw out the first pitch.
	   The cheers grew even louder when Jordan shed the jacket and
turned around to show everyone that not only was he wearing a Cubs
jersey, but it was Sosa's No. 21 jersey. And Sosa laughed as Jordan
honored him with his own, chest-thumping, finger-kissing salute.
	   Then Sosa hunkered down behind home plate as Jordan, who played
minor league baseball for a season during his brief retirement from
basketball, wound up. But Jordan's throw sailed far above Sosa's
head, and Sosa had to run back to grab the ball.
	   Jordan walked off the mound laughing as he greeted Sosa with a
hug. The two, who've become friends during Sosa's spectacular
season, walked off the field arm in arm.
	   With 70 home runs Mark McGwire practically has a lock on the
home run record. But Sosa is chasing the playoffs, and if you have
any doubt about which is more important to him, you haven't been
listening.
	   ``I've been saying all year that he's `The Man,''' Sosa said
Sunday. ``(But) Mark McGwire is going to go home ... and maybe go
to the beach. And I'm going to play.''
	   McGwire hit five homers in his last three games to finish with a
whopping 70. The Cubs' wild-card playoff Monday night against the
San Francisco Giants gave Sosa one more chance, but even he knows
catching McGwire is unlikely.
	   But stranger things have happened, and it's been a wild season
for the Cubs. One fan posted a sign along the first-base line
reading, ``Hey Sammy! Gimme 5!''
	   Sosa fell short in his first at-bat, grounding into a double
play on check swing to end the first inning.
	   ``I cannot go out there and think about hitting home runs,''
said Sosa, who didn't talk before Monday's game. ``I have to get
base hits.''
	   Who'd have thought in spring training _ in May, even _ that Sosa
would have this kind of year? Sure, he had 30-homer seasons the
past few years, but this, this has been, to use one of Sosa's
favorite words, unbelievable.
	   ``They're both pretty humble about what has happened,'' said
Gary Gaetti, who started the season with the Cardinals and finished
with the Cubs. ``It doesn't even look right. It doesn't look right
at all for one guy to have those numbers.''
	   When the year began, the money was on McGwire and Ken Griffey
Jr. to challenge Roger Maris' single-season record of 61 homers.
Sosa, who trailed McGwire 24-9 in late May, wasn't even on the
radar.
	   Then came June 1. Sosa hit two homers off the Florida Marlins,
and he was off on a binge. By the end of the month, he'd hit 20
home runs and the chase for Maris was a three-man race.
	   Sosa has done more than just hit homers. His 158 RBIs going into
Monday's game are best in the majors and fourth-best in NL history.
His 414 total bases also lead the majors, as do his 132 runs
scored. After starting the season having never hit a grand slam,
he's now hit three.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Sports-Baseball-Sosa's Homers; CT:s; 
