w1731 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Germany-HowKohlLost     09-28 0831
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-How Kohl Lost,0830 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Failure to tackle unemployment cost Kohl his job
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With Germany-Election &QL; 
 &UR; By PAUL GEITNER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BERLIN (AP) _ Everybody said it would be a tight race. Everybody
thought the unpredictable former communist east would provide the
decisive swing votes. In the end, it wasn't even close. And it
wasn't only jobless easterners who were angry with Chancellor
Helmut Kohl.
	   A measure of Kohl's sweeping defeat: he lost even in his home
district of Ludwigshafen on the Rhine River.
	   While Kohl talked about historic accomplishments like unifying
Germany and promoted himself as a reliable, ``world-class'' leader
in a time of global turmoil, voters were worried about something
much closer to home: Germany's stubborn, double-digit jobless rate.
	   His challenger, Gerhard Schroeder, hung the ``chancellor of
unemployment'' label around Kohl's neck. And he promised to change
things just enough to get Germans, known for their love of
stability, to give Kohl the boot. It was the first time voters had
completely rejected all parties in the previous government.
	   ``If you ask Germans what they really want, they want peace,
happiness and six weeks vacation. But they don't really want
changes,'' says Reinhard Schlinkert, managing director of the
Infratest polling agency.
	   Yet Kohl's failure to put Germans back to work not only angered
the hapless easterners, still struggling with the transition to a
market economy, but it became a gnawing worry even for those with
jobs in traditionally conservative strongholds like southern
Germany.
	   For many it came down to the wire; a quarter of Germans were
undecided until just before Sunday's election. Then they decided to
take a chance on Schroeder's cautious appeal to a ``new center.''
	   ``They were looking for new possibilities,'' Schlinkert said.
``When Schroeder said `I don't want to change everything but I will
make it better,' they believed him.''
	   Kohl's conservative Christian Democratic Union came out of
Sunday's election with 35 percent of the vote, down more than 6
points from 1994 and the worst showing since 1949.
	   Most ex-CDU voters went to Schroeder's Social Democrats, who
finished up 4.5 percent at 41 percent. A big chunk just stayed
home, analysts say.
	   A third of the drop was attributed to the east where, with
unemployment stuck near 20 percent, Kohl's role as the ``unity
chancellor'' wasn't enough to guarantee voter loyalty.
	   In those states, the CDU fell 11 points compared with 1994.
Party officials were stung.
	   ``Chancellor Kohl had put his whole energy into rebuilding the
east, and to drop by double digits is certainly bitter,'' general
secretary Peter Hintze told German television.
	   But voters weren't surprised.
	   ``It was long overdue. They made big promises and they didn't
keep them,'' said Hans Juergen Riez, 52, as he sipped a morning
beer in the northeastern city of Schwerin. He lost his job in a
plastics factory in 1991 and has been looking for another ever
since _ without success.
	   ``I don't see any `flourishing landscapes' like he promised,''
said Annamarie Fenne, also out of work, referring to Kohl's 1990
pledge to revitalize the eastern economy after four decades of
communism.
	   ``The election wasn't only decided in the east, but easterners
made the decision even clearer,'' admitted Angela Merkel, Kohl's
environmental minister and party chairwoman in eastern
Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania state.
	   In fact, the drop-off in the west, where 80 percent of the
electorate lives, was less dramatic but significantly more
damaging. People there are relatively better off but still worried
about the future.
	   The feeling was that Kohl ``just doesn't care enough anymore
about the cares, needs, fears and problems of the `little
people,''' said Martin Guellner, head of the Forsa polling
institute.
	   _Kohl lost 5 percent in Baden-Wuerttemberg, home to Daimler-Benz
and a Christian Democratic stronghold.
	   _He lost almost 5 percent in his home state of
Rhineland-Palatinate, as well as his direct seat representing
Ludwigshafen. (Under Germany's complex political system, he stays
in parliament anyway as the party's top candidate in the state.)
	   _In Bavaria, his political allies easily won a statehouse race
two weeks ago, but recorded a 3.5 percent slide when it came to the
federal election. The drop in a state the conservatives have
dominated for decades was such a stunner that the chairman of the
Bavarian party announced on Monday he would step down.
	   Meanwhile, in one of life's little ironies, the successor party
to the East German communists _ which Kohl had attacked as a danger
to democracy _ made it over the 5 percent hurdle for the first time
to become a full-fledged faction in parliament.
	   The Party of Democratic Socialism even managed to pick up
support in the west, getting 1.2 percent of the vote, compared with
1 percent in 1994.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
