<SLUG> BC-New Zealand-Japan Killing </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Family devastated by Japanese tourist's apparent killing
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   AUCKLAND, New Zealand (AP) _ Friends and family of a missing
Japanese tourist are distraught after learning she appears to have
been murdered while on a sightseeing trip, police said Tuesday.
	   Kayo Matsuzawa, 29, had not been seen since she checked into a
backpackers' hostel in downtown Auckland on Sept. 11, Det. Senior
Sgt. Kevin Baker said.
	   Police suspect the naked, decaying body found last week in a
locked cupboard in a building only a couple of hundred meters
(yards) from Queen Street Backpackers hostel is Matsuzawa's.
	   The woman's family has been contacted in Yamagata, northern
Japan, and detectives on Tuesday began checking dental records to
confirm the body's identity.
	   The body was found in a fire alarm battery cupboard off a
stairwell last Tuesday by a serviceman and police say it had been
there for about a week.
	   Baker said Matsuzawa arrived in Christchurch from Japan late
last year, working in a restaurant and also sharing a flat with
another Japanese woman.
	   Police were making inquiries at the backpackers hostel, where
she paid a deposit and left her belongings before vanishing.
	   A colleague at the Thai Tasty restaurant in Christchurch, who
did not want to be named, said Matsuzawa went to Auckland by
herself for sightseeing and was supposed to be back in two weeks.
	   He said she planned to move on to Australia in November.
	   A Japanese tour guide in Christchurch, Stuart Henwood, said he
was concerned that many Japanese still came to New Zealand
`thinking it is so safe they can wander off and do whatever they
like,''
	   The director of the Nippon New Zealand Friendship Association,
Robin de Clive-Lowe, said the Japanese government would probably
issue a warning to tourists visiting New Zealand. The death would
impact on inbound tourism.
	   rl/pjs
</TEXT>
