<SLUG> BC-Mexico-Flooding ,0474 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Six dead in Mexico City mudslides, flooding
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: RECAPS and UPDATES to RAISE death toll to six from five, ADDS
color. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos MO108-109 &QL; 
 &UR; By JULIE WATSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   MEXICO CITY (AP) _ Heavy rains have swollen rivers in central
Mexico and triggered mudslides in Mexico City that killed six
people and injured four others.
	   Monday's rain soaked squatter communities perched on the steep
slopes of hillsides south of the city. Television footage showed a
stream of mud roaring down gullies and the ruins of three homes
that had been swept away.
	   The slide killed a 13-year-old girl, Lourdes Barrera Orozco, who
was found still clutching her school notebook, witnesses said. All
that remained of the homes were a muddy pile of appliances and
clothing flung against a row of trees.
	   The girl's 6-year-old brother and a 9-year-old relative also
were caught in the slide and suffered head injuries. They were
flown by helicopter to a downtown hospital.
	   ``I heard a loud rumble and I went outside and saw my neighbors
buried there,'' said Pedro Ramirez, 55.
	   City officials had predicted the rainy season could bring
disaster to the shantytowns that ring the city's hillsides, but
most people refused to relocate.
	   ``It's very difficult to convince them. They don't want to leave
their houses,'' said Aurelio Garcia, a spokesman for the Magdalena
Contreras precinct, where the deaths happened.
	   Another family was buried in their home when mud came streaming
down on top of it earlier in the day. Two teen-agers were pulled
from the house alive by local police, but both their parents died.
	   Two other people were killed when a muddy hillside collapsed on
top of a containment wall, crushing their house. The Televisa
network reported another body was pulled from a mudslide in the
city, raising the number of deaths to six. In all, half a dozen
houses were destroyed in slides.
	   Mayor Cuauhtemoc Cardenas declared a state of alert, government
news agency Notimex reported. City officials issued evacuation
warnings to people living near a dam in the western part of the
city that was on the verge of overflowing.
	   Cardenas said the government would not force squatters from
their homes.
	   Some neighborhoods in a low-lying area east of Mexico City have
been flooded for days, and to the west, the Lerma River overflowed
its banks and left some villages inundated in sewage.
	   Mexico City's main highway to the western part of the country
also was blocked by a mudslide Monday. Rains are expected to
continue, the National Meteorological service said.
	   Rains also caused rivers to overflow in the southern state of
Chiapas, hit by flooding earlier this month that killed 185 people
and left many towns and villages cut off from the outside world.
</TEXT>
