<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Germany-Elections,0507 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Schroeder reassures Germans and the world after victory
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; RETRANSMITTING to fix slug &QL; 
 &UR; With Germany-How Kohl Lost &QL; 
 &UR; By TONY CZUCZKA &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BONN, Germany (AP) _ The nation's future chancellor, Gerhard
Schroeder, made one thing clear after winning power as the voice of
change: Change will happen, but not too much for the good of
Germans, who cherish predictability.
	   The Social Democrat sought to reassure the world, too, declaring
Monday in his first news conference after Sunday's vote that his
administration will represent steady foreign policy and ``economic
stability.''
	   Much of that stability came from 16 years of consistent
conservative leadership by Chancellor Helmut Kohl, swept from
office by voters who wanted a fresh face and new ideas for solving
problems at home _ chiefly unemployment stuck at over 10 percent.
	   Not only has Schroeder vowed to continue Kohl's foreign policies
but the future chancellor also said Monday he may be consulting his
predecessor directly for advice on diplomacy.
	   As a first sign of continuity, Schroeder planned to visit Paris
on Wednesday in a symbolic trip to the capital of Germany's closest
European partner. Kohl made the same journey in 1982, when he, like
Schroeder, was elevated from state governor to the leader of the
nation.
	   ``Nobody needs to be afraid. We will ensure continuity in
foreign policy,'' Schroeder said. ``The international community can
rely on Germans to remain good partners.''
	   Some of Schroeder's first tests as chancellor will be on the
international stage, with NATO planning air strikes to quell
violence in the Serb-ruled Yugoslav province of Kosovo and with the
Jan. 1 introduction of Europe's common currency, the euro.
	   Germany is at the center of both developments: Kohl was
instrumental in starting European monetary union, and his
government has promised German fighter planes and soldiers for any
NATO action in the current Balkan conflict.
	   Grinning with exuberance, Schroeder dodged tough questions _
such as how he would handle Kosovo. He and Social Democrat party
chief Oskar Lafontaine apparently were unwilling to commit their
new government to any plan as they head into tough talks Friday on
forming a coalition with the enviromentalist Greens party.
	   But Schroeder made clear that the Social Democrats, as the
dominant partner, would not tolerate radical pacifist and
environmentalist causes pushed by many Greens. Fischer is a
moderate.
	   In an interview with Der Spiegel news magazine, he warned the
Greens ``not to be pushy with their demands.''
	   Eager to enter government for the first time, the Greens
emphasized ideas the two parties share: combating unemployment,
scrapping nuclear energy and giving long-time foreign residents of
Germany dual nationality.
	   Joschka Fischer, the leader of the Greens' moderate wing, was
pegged as a possible foreign minister in the new government. But
Schroeder has refused to discuss any cabinet posts.
</TEXT>
