<SLUG> BC-Japan-Markets </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Dollar higher in Tokyo, Japanese stocks slip in early trading
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ The U.S. dollar rose against the yen early Tuesday
ahead of the Federal Reserve Board's policy-making meeting later in
the day. Japanese stock prices slipped.
	   The dollar bought 136.35 yen in early trading, up 0.63 yen from
late Monday in Tokyo and also above its late New York level of
135.85 yen overnight.
	   Traders were awaiting the outcome of the Federal Open Market
Committee meeting amid increasing speculation the Fed will announce
a cut in interest rates after the gathering in a bid to revive the
global economy.
	   In New York overnight, the dollar moved higher in line with a
rise on Wall Street before losing some of its early gains. The U.S.
currency's intermittent spurts higher were also cut short by
remarks from Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin.
	   Rubin reiterated his ``great concern'' over the recent weakness
of the Japanese currency.
	   The Dow Jones industrial average closed up 80.07, or 1 percent,
to a one-month high of 8,108.84 points.
	   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, many investors were holding back to
await the outcome of the Fed meeting, traders said.
	   The benchmark 225-issue Nikkei Stock Average fell 76.20 points,
or 0.55 percent, to 13,833.17 points in the first 30 minutes of
trading. On Monday, the Nikkei gained 185.53 points, or 1.35
percent.
	   The broader Tokyo Stock Price Index of all issues listed on the
first section was down 2.81 points, or 0.26 percent, 1,060.71
points. The TOPIX closed up 13.59 points, or 1.29 percent.
	   Meanwhile, the yield on the benchmark No. 182 10-year Japanese
government bond fell to 0.795 percent from Monday's finish of 0.800
percent, driving its price up to 109.06 yen from 109.01 yen.
 &UR; (km)
