<SLUG> BC-Britain-Politics ,0483 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Blair seeks to rally his increasingly restive Labor Party
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: Blair's keynote address expected to begin about 1400 GMT &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos BLK102-103 &QL; 
 &UR; By MAUREEN JOHNSON &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   BLACKPOOL, England (AP) _ Despite continuing popularity with
voters after 17 months in office, Prime Minister Tony Blair is
facing increased restiveness within his Labor Party over what
critics see as an authoritarian, conservative style of government.
	   Blair, in his keynote address Tuesday to the party's annual
conference, has a key challenge: convincing party left-wingers and
uneasy trade union leaders that economic stringency will bring
long-term stability rather than betray Labor's left-of-center
philosophy.
	   Left-wingers, buoyed by successes in elections to the party's
governing National Executive Committee, accused Blair at fringe
meetings outside the main conference of ignoring dissent over his
``New Labor'' centrist policies.
	   ``This control-freakery represents an actual danger to our
democracy if it continues,'' lawmaker Ken Livingstone declared
Monday night at a meeting of the Labor Left Briefing group in the
northern town of Blackpool.
	   Left-wingers accuse Blair of expunging dissidents as candidates
for next year's European Parliament elections; reducing the six-day
conference to a rally by permitting few votes on policy; and having
party headquarters decide which delegates are called for debates.
	   In addition, the largely moderate trade union bosses, whose
unions are major funders of the party, are uneasy about the
government's emphasis on keeping inflation at a low 2.5 percent.
They would prefer pay hikes.
	   State spending curbs have held down public service wages, and
the 7.5 percent interest rate has helped stoke the value of the
British pound. This makes exports, which the unionists make, more
expensive and encourages cheap imports.
	   Rodney Bickerstaffe, leader of the country's biggest union,
UNISON, which represents hundreds of thousands of public service
workers, received thunderous applause Monday when he criticized
appeals by government ministers for patience.
	   ``Don't just give us a vision of the promised land, give us a
place in it,'' said Bickerstaffe.
	   But Blair was expected to take a no-change line _ spelled out
Monday by his treasury chief, Chancellor of the Exchequer Gordon
Brown, that Labor, out of office for 18 years until its May 1997
election victory, has learned from past mistakes.
	   ``We will not go back to the idea that in the first two years of
a Labor government you have a binge, which means you spend the next
two years picking up the pieces,'' Brown said in a British
Broadcasting Corp. interview Monday night.
	   Earlier, Brown received subdued applause when he told delegates
``there is no other way, no solution, or even comfort, in soft
options.''
</TEXT>
