<SLUG> BC-UN-Tanzania,0228 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tanzania foreign minister decries terrorism, cites embassy blasts
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Tanzania's foreign minister called for a
stronger international effort to fight terrorism and thanked
nations who helped his country recover from the terrorist attack on
the U.S. embasssy.
	   ``Terrorism is a heinous crime against humanity,'' Jakaya Mrisho
Kikwete told the General Assembly on Monday. ``Whatever cause may
have prompted the perpetrators to resort to it, we do not believe
that it is any way justifiable.''
	   Two bombs exploded almost simultaneously in the U.S. embassies
in Nairobi, Kenya and Dar es Salaam, Tanzania on Aug. 7, killing
259 people. Eleven people died in the Tanzania attack, all of them
Africans.
	   ``In the wake of the attack, many friends sent us messages of
condolence and solidarity,'' Kikwete said, adding that the
government was particularly grateful for those that sent material
support to help the victims.
	   ``Of particular mention here is the people and government of the
United States of America who extended medical support and assisted
in the investigations through the FBI.''
	   He called for greater international cooperation to bring the
perpetrators to justice, so ``that they will find no solace or
refuge anywhere.''
</TEXT>
