w1760 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ANALYSIS-US-Clinton-F     09-28 0688
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANALYSIS-US-Clinton-Foreign Stage,0699 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Clinton takes foreign policy stage as a tonic to his personal
</HEADLINE>
trouble &QL; 
 &UR; An AP News Analysis &QC; 
 &UR; By ROBERT BURNS &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   WASHINGTON (AP) _ For an American president weakened at home by
the embarrassment of personal scandal, President Bill Clinton's
impromptu Middle East summit offered a politically welcome stage to
show he can still lead.
	   The scene in the Oval Office on Monday, live on CNN: Clinton,
standing between Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and
Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat, proclaimed ``progress on the path
to peace.'' No dramatic breakthrough just yet, he cautioned
reporters, but ``all told, it was a good day.''
	   Simply bringing these two reluctant partners to the table was a
small victory, writ large for the beleaguered president.
	   For the past week or so Clinton has kept an unusually busy
foreign policy schedule, starting with a visit to United Nations
headquarters in New York for a speech on international cooperation
in the fight against terrorism. Over the next few days he held
separate meetings with the leaders of seven nations, then basked in
the public praise of widely respected South African President
Nelson Mandela.
	   ``It's his best turf at the moment,'' said John Steinbruner, a
senior foreign policy expert at the Brookings Institution, a think
tank.
	   With an eye on the November elections, Clinton appears
determined to keep hammering for a deal on a further Israeli
withdrawal from the West Bank. He said Monday that Netanyahu and
Arafat agreed to return to Washington for a potentially decisive
round of negotiations in mid-October. That time table would fall
smack into the final stretch of the campaign.
	   Steinbruner believes that despite the political wounds Clinton
sustained from his Monica Lewinsky scandal, he remains able to push
for progress in traditional foreign policy areas like the Middle
East peace process. But his ability to generate new policies to
address problems like Russia's economic distress or the civil
unrest in Kosovo has been ``seriously jeopardized,'' the analyst
said.
	   From the start of his first term Clinton has focused more on
domestic than foreign affairs, yet he has managed to build a
reputation as a peacemaker, an image bolstered by his successful
push for peace in Northern Ireland. Since his public admission in
August that he had a sexual affair with Ms. Lewinsky and then lied
about it, critics have questioned whether it cost him the moral
authority to lead and whether he had lost the respect and trust of
key foreign leaders.
	   At his first news conference since admitting to the Lewinsky
affair, this was the first matter put to him.
	   ``I have never stopped leading this country in foreign affairs
in this entire year, and I never will,'' Clinton said sternly.
``The issues are too important and they affect the way Americans
live at home.''
	   The president addressed it again in an interview with syndicated
columnist Trude Feldman.
	   ``Those who have telephoned me with encouragement,'' Clinton
said of his recent conversations with foreign leaders, ``believe I
have done nothing in my public life to forfeit their trust, and
that in my private life, whether its is good or bad or troubled or
happy, is not their business.''
	   Dimitri Simes, president of the Nixon Center think tank, Monday
that Clinton has never enjoyed a high standing abroad.
	   ``While the Monica Lewinsky problem did not undermine his
already diminished moral authority, it has made him less
effective'' in foreign policy, Simes said.
	   Fred Greenstein, a political science professor at Princeton
University, takes a more positive view. He thinks the scandal, by
threatening Clinton's political life, has forced him to focus
harder and press for concrete results.
	   ``In a sense, all Bill Clinton has to seize upon to redeem the
situation is competence, so that's what he's going to try to do,''
Greenstein said.
	    &UR; ___
	   EDITOR'S NOTE: Robert Burns has covered national security and
foreign affairs for The Associated Press since 1990.
</TEXT>
