w1763 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Australia-GasShortage     09-28 0508
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Australia-Gas Shortage </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Economist predicts gas crisis could stunt Australia's economy
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   MELBOURNE, Australia (AP) _ Not only are millions of Australians
taking cold showers during Victoria state's natural gas shortage,
but the industrial shutdown it has forced may hobble the nation's
growth, a economist predicted Tuesday.
	   ANZ chief economist Saul Eslake said the crisis, which resulted
from a huge fire at Esso's Longford gas plant on Friday that killed
two men and injured eight, could seriously affect the national
economy.
	   The plant supplied more than 80 percent of the natural gas for
Australia's second-most populous state, and some 1.4 million
households and 100,000 businesses may be without natural gas for
two weeks.
	   Esso has so far been unable to determine the cause of the blaze
and explosions, which took two days to extinguish.
	   Up to 100,000 workers in Victoria are expected to be laid off
this week as the Ford and Toyota auto factories, glass and
brick-making plants and many other industries shut down.
	   In Adelaide in South Australia, Mitsubishi and General Motors
Holden are preparing for shutdowns Wednesday because of a lack of
parts from Victoria.
	   The Australian Industry Group estimates the shutdown could cost
100 million Australian dollars (U.S. dlrs 58 million) each day it
goes on.
	   ``If the disruption of the gas supply persists for more than a
week, then the impact on September quarter's gross domestic product
(GDP) could be of the order of 0.1 of a percentage point, perhaps a
third of the increase in GDP that forecasters had been expecting
for the September quarter,'' Eslake told Australian Broadcasting
Corp. radio.
	   ``Of course it now seems that this disruption may last for at
least two weeks, with some effects lingering beyond that, so
there'll be an impact on the December quarter figures as well.
	   Hundreds of thousands of state residents are taking cold
showers, and are looking for electric griddles and fry pans to cook
their food. Many restaurants said they plan to close until the
weekend due to the gas shortage.
	   The CUB Malthouse Theater offered patrons a ``Show and Shower''
package, with theater-goers getting to use the electric-heated
showers backstage before the show.
	   The Australian Hotels Association spokesman Darryl Washington
said some Melbourne hotels were sending their laundry to Sydney for
cleaning.
	   He said all but a small percentage were offering only cold
showers and all would feel the full brunt later this week of
dwindling supplies, such as bread.
	   Victorian residents, facing fines of 500 Australian dollars
(U.S. dlrs 290), were forced to turn off their gas meters Saturday
after the state's supply authority, VENCorp., ordered the shutdown
of the state's system.
	   Prime Minister John Howard offered federal assistance to
Victoria, ``In particular, both governments are concerned to ensure
the crisis does not hurt the sick, the elderly or the frail in the
community.''
	   pjs
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
(WS SL:BC-Australia-Gas Shortage; CT:i; 
(REG:ASIA;)
(REG:ENGL;)
(LANG:ENGLISH;))
)
