</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Motorcycle Racing-Doohan </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Doohan set to quit after next year
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   SYDNEY, Australia (AP) _ Australia's four-time 500cc motorcycle
racing world champion Mick Doohan said Tuesday he would likely quit
after next season.
	   ``I've decided to continue again for next year but I doubt I'll
go for 2000. I think new century, new job,'' Doohan told an
Australian television network.
	   Doohan, who is in line for a fifth world title this year, said
he would like to top Italian Giacomo Agostini's long standing
victory record.
	   Agostini won 68 500cc races between 1965 and 1976, and won the
championship eight times between 1966 and 1975.
	   ``I don't think I have the motivation to go for eight world
championships but it would be good to have a go at the amount of
wins he had,'' Doohan said. ``I've won 52 so I'd have to have a
really good year. Top this season off with a few wins but also have
a really good year next year.''
	   Monaco-based Doohan said he wanted to remain involved in
motorcycle racing in some capacity.
	   ``I think I'd always do something within the sport but I'll
probably take a year off and really work out what I want to do and
where I want to be,'' said Doohan.
	   He expects to remain living in Europe, rather than returning
home to Australia. ``Everything's so familiar to me over there and
I think to just chop out that part of my life will be difficult,''
Doohan said.
	   Doohan's quest for a fifth world title was boosted by news that
the Brazilian Grand Prix, due to be held on Oct. 18, had been
canceled because the Nelson Piquet track in Rio de Janeiro failed
to pass a safety inspection.
	   With Doohan leading the championship standings by 21 points from
Italy's Max Biaggi and Spaniard Alex Criville a further seven
points back, the cancellation leaves just two rounds remaining in
the world championship _ the Australian GP on Sunday and in Buenos
Aires, Argentina on Oct. 25.
 &UR; (tjh)
</TEXT>
