w1775 &Cx1f; wstm-
r i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Dominican-Hurricane-T     09-28 0581
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Dominican-Hurricane-Town Regained,0580 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Relief arrives in Dominican town cut off by hurricane for six days
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds; RECAPS pvs. &QL; 
 &UR; AP Photos SDO101-03,105,106 &QL; 
 &UR; By JARED KOTLER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SAN JUAN DE LA MAGUANA, Dominican Republic (AP) _ Fallen bridges
and washed-out roads had left this western town isolated since
Hurricane George pounded it a week ago, but relief workers are
finally glimpsing the devastation.
	   Shantytowns perched on a river's edge were buried under several
feet (a meter) of mud. Dazed residents trudged through the muck to
examine their flattened adobe and plywood homes while rescue
workers searched for bodies.
	   Residents walked nonchalantly Monday past the rotting carcass of
a horse buried chest deep in mud, its head arching toward the sky.
	   At least 76 people were killed here, the Red Cross has reported.
The exact toll remained unclear, however. Local hospital officials
said they had documented 19 dead, but suspected that many more have
been buried by relatives or lay trapped under the mud.
	   While all Dominicans were affected one way or the other, it
appears the vast majority of the 200 dead nationwide were those too
poor to afford a better place to live. Most of the victims lived in
flimsy low-lying homes which were no match for the hurricane.
	   Flooding in this farming center of 20,000 people located 75
miles (125 kilometers) west of the capital Santo Domingo was
aggravated when workers at a dam upstream opened floodgates to
relieve pressure on the dam.
	   After a week of waiting for help to arrive, hurricane victims on
Monday waded into subsiding waters to guide the first relief trucks
into town.
	   In a small cemetery outside town, the graves of eight people
were marked by a two-foot-high (60-centimeter) mound covered with
red and purple flowers and crosses made of sticks. Nine other storm
victims were buried nearby.
	   Residents said they had some warning but were unprepared for the
disaster.
	   ``They told us before it happened, but I didn't think it would
be this bad,'' said Alejandro Mateo, 68, who fled his yellow
clapboard house in the Monte de Oca neighborhood as the water rose.
	   The house, which 20 years ago survived the last major hurricane
to hit the Dominican Republic, is now filled with mud and may not
be salvageable.
	   Until Monday, downed trees and bridges and raging streams
prevented rescuers from reaching the town by land or helicopter.
Both the U.S. Peace Corps and the U.S. Agency for International
Development had said getting to San Juan was a top priority.
	   Children dashed across a field Monday to collect packets of
disaster supplies dropped by a small Peace Corps plane buzzing over
the town. Doctors waited anxiously for medical supplies to
vaccinate residents against diseases and prepared for a surge in
dengue and malaria, both carried by mosquitoes that breed in
stagnant water.
	   Two flatbed trailers carrying 110-pound (50-kilogram) bags of
rice donated by Australia arrived Monday afternoon, and workers
prepared the trucks for a push across a flooded roadway leading to
town.
	   A barefoot boy squatted in the shade beneath one of the trucks,
collecting falling grains of rice in a tattered red baseball cap.
	   U.S. helicopters were expected to fly more supplies into the
area on Tuesday.
	   Georges killed more than 300 people, including at least 94 in
nearby Haiti, as it spun westward through the Caribbean last week.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
