<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SKorea-Bank Strike, 1st Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Widespread bank strike fizzles in South Korea
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with only two banks struck
 &UR; AP Photo

<TEXT>
	   SEOUL, South Korea (AP) _ A threatened strike by 35,000
unionized employees of nine major banks largely evaporated Tuesday,
leaving only two of the institutions struck but still operating.
	   Employees of seven of the nine financially shaky banks reached
last-minute settlements with management on the question of layoffs
and went to work shortly after normal opening hours.
	   But 11,000 employees went on strike at Chohung Bank and Korea
Exchange Bank after failing to settle the layoff issue in overnight
negotiations.
	   The two struck banks were operating normally, with nonunion
employees filling in for the striking workers. Riot police guarded
their head and branch offices.
	   The nine banks have been ordered by the government to
restructure or face closure or merger. A key part of the
restructuring involves layoffs.
	   The banks sought to cut manpower by 33 percent by the end of
this year, but offered dismissed workers enhanced severance pay.
The unions initially demanded that the layoffs be spread over three
years with greater financial compensation.
	   Five banks were closed earlier this year as part of a
restructuring process South Korea promised in exchange for a dlrs
58 billion bailout from the International Monetary Fund.
	   South Korean banks maintained cozy relations with past
military-backed governments. Their lending was frequently affected
by political and government policies.
	   When dozens of financially shaky businesses collapsed late last
year, many banks were left with piles of non-performing loans. That
eroded investor confidence, fueling a flight of foreign capital. 	   
</TEXT>
