<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-Kazakstan,0299 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Kazakstan Urges Caspian Sea Oil, Gas Development At U.N.
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Kazakstan's foreign minister called Monday
for a ``complete settlement'' of legal issues that have stymied
development of the oil- and gas-rich Caspian Sea.
	   In his address Monday to the U.N. General Assembly, Kassymjomart
K. Tokaev also called for speedy implementation of the Caspian
Pipeline Consortium project.
	   The group, which includes Chevron and Mobil, is planning a
900-mile (1,440-kilometer), dlrs 2.2 billion oil export pipeline
from the Tengiz oil field in Kazakstan to the Russian Black Sea
port of Novorossisk.
	   Most of the oil and gas reserves in the Caspian region remain
undeveloped. An estimated 15.4 to 29 billion barrels of proven oil
reserves lies in the region. The region also holds 236 to 337
trillion cubic feet of proven gas reserves, according to the
Petroleum Finance Group, a Washington-based industry analyst.
	   But production in the region has been delayed by legal issues.
One question is whether development rights are governed by treaties
between the former Soviet Union and Iran, which didn't establish
seabed boundaries or discuss oil and gas production. It's also
unclear whether the Caspian Sea is covered by the Law of the Sea.
	   In July, Russia and Kazakstan agreed to divide the northern part
of the Caspian seabed into two separate sectors. Iran and
Turkmenistan criticized the deal, arguing the riches of the Caspian
Sea should be divided equally among bordering countries.
	   Nevertheless, Tokaev called for ``concrete steps'' to implement
the bilateral agreement which, he said ``lays the foundations for a
complete settlement of the Caspian problem.''
</TEXT>
