<SLUG> BC-UN-Algeria,0282 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Algerian FM pledges defense of human rights
</HEADLINE>

<TEXT>
	   UNITED NATIONS (AP) _ Algeria's foreign minister pledged Monday
that his country was committed to protecting human rights and
keeping the issue from being manipulated by politics.
	   Speaking to the U.N. General Assembly, Ahmed Attaf noted that
the United Nations was celebrating the 50th anniversary of the
Universal Declaration on Human Rights this year.
	   ``The situation is, surely, better today than it was 50 years
ago,'' he said.
	   Human rights groups routinely decry the rights situation in
Algeria, where a Muslim insurgency has ranged for six years.
	   The insurgency began after the army canceled parliamentary
elections in January 1992 that an Islamic party was poised to win.
Since then, an estimated 75,000 people have been killed.
	   The Algerian government blames Muslim insurgents for the
massacres, but human rights groups, such as Amnesty International,
say the government has also carried out atrocities.
	   ``I would in this context reaffirm our solid adherence to the
universality, the indivisibility and the interdependence of all
human rights,'' Attaf told world leaders gathered for the annual
debate. He stated Algeria's ``firm pledge to defend them and
promote them _ safe from all political manipulation.''
	   The United Nations recently sent a team of high-ranking
diplomats to look into the insurgency. Their report, released
earlier this month, condemned terrorism as a whole and made a few
recommendations, such as urging the government rein in its security
forces who have been accused in some attacks.
</TEXT>
