w1785 &Cx1f; wstm-
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-Sports-Tennis-Glance     09-28 0952
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Sports-Tennis-Glance,0971 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Tennis Glance
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By The Associated Press &QC; 
 &UR; By BOB GREENE &QC; 
 &UR; AP Sports Writer &QC; 
 &UR; STARS &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   _ Monica Seles captured her third straight Princess Cup
championship in Tokyo, defeating Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario 4-6, 6-3,
6-4.
	   _ Jimmy Connors defeated John McEnroe 6-7 (2-7), 6-2, 11-9 to
win the PricewaterhouseCoopers Champions in Irving, Texas.
	   _ Andrea Gaudenzi, Davide Sanguinetti, Diego Nargiso and
Gianluca Pozzi helped Italy upset the United States and advance to
the Davis Cup final where it will play Sweden.
	   _ Jonas Bjorkman, Thomas Johansson and Nicklas Kulti powered
Sweden to a 4-1 victory over Spain and into the Davis Cup final.
	   _ Lindsay Davenport led the way as the Sacramento Capitals
successfully defended their World TeamTennis title by crushing the
New York OTBzz 30-13.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; SPEAKING &QC; 
	   ``These days players have to be better athletes, but I still
think with nostalgia about the old times, when people like John
McEnroe played.'' _ Martina Navratilova, commenting on today's
tennis players.
	   ``It really doesn't matter who is playing or how old they are. I
just worry about what I can control. It doesn't give me more or
less motivation.'' _ Monica Seles, when asked if she gets more
motivation out of playing the younger players.
	   ``The boys (Davis Cup team) have all got together amongst
themselves this week and they're happy for Mark to come back as
long as he's part of the team.'' _ John Newcombe, saying he's ready
to welcome Mark Philippoussis back to the Australian Davis Cup
squad.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; STORMY CLASH &QC; 
	   When a fan hollered at Jimmy Connors to ``just play fair,''
Connors stormed off the court in the opening set of the
PricewaterhouseCoopers Champions title match against John McEnroe.
Although he was defaulted by umpire Myron Krueger, Connors
eventually was talked into returning to the court by McEnroe and
Nuveen Tour officials after a 20-minute delay. Connors eventually
overcame a match point in the Champions tiebreak to win 6-7 (2-7),
6-2, 11-9 and collect the dlrs 40,000 winner's share. McEnroe, who
earned dlrs 25,000, and Connors refused to shake hands at the end
of the match in Irving, Texas.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; STEADY WORK &QC; 
	   Arantxa Sanchez-Vicario reached the title match of the Toyota
Princess Cup in Tokyo for the fifth consecutive year. And for the
third straight year, she lost the final to Monica Seles. The
Spaniard won in 1994, but has lost the last four, including 1995 to
Mary Pierce.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; STRUGGLING IN VAIN &QC; 
	   Leander Paes spent plenty of time on the court in a losing
effort as India lost to Britain 3-2 in a Davis Cup qualifying
battle. Paes lost to Greg Rusedski 2-6, 6-3, 3-6, 6-2, 11-9 on the
first day, then teamed with Mahesh Bhupathi to capture the doubles
7-6 (7-2), 6-3, 7-6 (7-3), before falling to Tim Henman 7-6 (7-3),
6-2, 7-6 (7-5) in the reverse singles.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; SWITCHING SPONSORS &QC; 
	   After next year, The Lipton Championships will have a new name.
Ericsson Mobile Phones will become the title sponsor in the year
2000 and the tournament will be called the Ericsson Open. Now the
fifth largest tennis tournament in the world in terms of prize
money, The Lipton is the only 11-day, 96-man and 96-woman draw
tournament on the professional tennis calendar.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; SUCCESS, FINALLY &QC; 
	   Russian teen-ager Anna Kournikova is one of the world's
best-known tennis players because of her cover-girl look. But when
she teamed with Monica Seles to capture the doubles at the Toyota
Princess Cup in Tokyo, it was the first time she had won a tennis
title in her pro career. Kournikova and Seles beat Arantxa
Sanchez-Vicario and Mary Joe Fernandez 6-4, 6-4 to share the
winner's prize of dlrs 23,750.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; SPOTLIGHT ON WT.
	   Larisa Neiland, who helped the Springfield Lasers to a 10-4
regular season record, was named World TeamTennis Most Valuable
Player during Championship Weekend in Sacramento, Calif. Nana
Miyagi of the OTBzz was named Rookie of the Year, while OTBzz's
Inderjit Singh was named DuPont WTT Coach of the year.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; SINGLES WINNER &QC; 
	   Jana Nejedly of Canada downed Lilia Osterloh of Canal
Winchester, Ohio, 6-1, 6-3 to capture the singles title at the
inaugural HealthSouth/USTA Challenger of Seattle. The eighth-seeded
Nejedly earned dlrs 8,800 with the crown. The top-seeded team of
Els Callens of Belgium and Liezel Horn of South Africa won the
doubles, defeating Osterloh and Mashona Washington of Houston 6-2,
3-6, 6-3.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; START TO GREATNESS?
	   Jean-Julien Rojer of the Netherlands defeated Chul-Dong Lee of
South Korea 6-1, 6-4 to win the Boys 18 title at the Port
Washington International Championships in Port Washington, N.Y.
Winning the Girls 18 crown was Zsofia Gubacsi of Hungary, who
defeated Olivia Dubovikov of New York City 6-1, 6-0.
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; SITES TO SURF &QC; 
	   Grand Slam Cup: www.compaqgrandslam.net
	   Mallorca Open: www.atptour.com
	   Swiss Indoors: www.swissindoors.ch
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; Tournaments this week &QC; 
 &UR; ATP Tour &QC; 
	   dlrs 475,000 Mallorca Open, clay, Mallorca, Spain
	   dlrs 375,000 Adidas Open de Toulouse, hard, Toulouse, France
 &UR; International Tennis Federation &QC; 
	   Grand Slam Cup, hard, Munich (men and women)
 &UR; Nuveen Tour &QC; 
 &UR; Sept. 30-Oct. 4 &QC; 
	   dlrs 150,000 BTI Champions, clay, Atlanta
	   ___ &QC; 
 &UR; Tournaments week of Oct. 5 &QC; 
 &UR; ATP Tour &QC; 
	   dlrs 975,000 Davidoff Swiss Indoors, carpet, Basel, Switzerland
	   dlrs 315,000 Campionati Internazionali di Sicilia, clay,
Palermo, Italy
	   dlrs 315,000 Heineken Open, hard, Shanghai, China
