<SLUG> BC-Albright-Mideast,0258 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Albright: negotiators close to ``finish line'' in Mideast peace
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; With US-Mideast &QL; 

<TEXT>
	   NEW YORK (AP) _ U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright said
she found her recent meetings with Israeli and Palestinian leaders
to be fruitful in pushing the Middle East peace process ahead.
	   ``In those meetings, the air was cleared and we were able to
focus on what remains to be done and how to get it done,'' she said
Monday at a dinner sponsored by the Business Council for the United
Nations.
	   ``We're getting close to the finish line of an agreement,'' she
said in a speech that also advocated that the United States pay its
U.N. arrears.
	   ``We were able to narrow the gaps on the two most important
issues _ further redeployment and the security issues,'' she said
without elaborating.
	   Albright's announcement echoed similar statements made earlier
Monday by President Bill Clinton who met with Israeli Prime
Minister Benjamin Netanyahu and Palestinian leader Yasser Arafat
	   Clinton plans to send Albright and U.S. mediator Dennis Ross to
the region next week. The new timetable for an accord also calls
for Netanyahu and Arafat to return to the White House for a meeting
with Clinton in mid-October.
	   Albright, who was the guest of honor at the U.N. dinner, said
Mideast peace negotiations had become bogged down before the latest
meetings.
	   ``Too much focus has been placed on what divides the parties,
rather than what united them in the seach for peace,'' she said.
</TEXT>
