<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Malaysia-Politics, 2nd Ld-Writethru </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Malaysia's ex-deputy premier brought to court for arraignment
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; Eds: UPDATES with announcement of charges; ADDS byline
 &UR; AP Photos
 &UR; By JOCELYN GECKER &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   KUALA LUMPUR, Malaysia (AP) _ Malaysia's ousted deputy prime
minister was brought to a courthouse Tuesday for the beginning of
what could be a landmark legal case in this Southeast Asian nation.
	   Anwar was led into the the Jalan Raja Court 15 minutes before it
was scheduled to open. Hundreds of policemen threw a ring around
the colonial building to prevent his supporters from thronging the
area for a glimpse of their leader not seen since his arrest on
Sept. 20.
	   Anwar was marched off by armed police under the harsh Internal
Security Act. He faces accusations ranging from illegal homosexual
acts to treason.
	   On Tuesday, Anwar was expected to be charged on nine counts of
corruption and ``unnatural'' sex acts, the national news agency,
Bernama, reported. The punishment for each count could be several
years imprisonment.
	   A tenth charge will be brought against him in another court in a
Kuala Lumpur suburb on Wednesday, Bernama said, quoting a statement
by the Attorney-General's Chambers.
	   After he was fired on Sept. 2 by Prime Minister Mahathir
Mohamad, Anwar had led a campaign against his former boss, who has
ruled Malaysia for 17 years.
	   Since Anwar's arrest, Kuala Lumpur has been rocked by street
protests demanding his release and Mahathir's resignation.
	   On Monday, riot police chased a few thousand pro-reform
activists through the neon-lit streets of downtown Kuala Lumpur as
protesters defied warnings to gather for a second consecutive week
near the courthouse.
	   Chanting ``Reformasi'' or ``Reforms,'' the demonstrators marched
from a courthouse, carrying banners that said, ``Free Anwar.''
	   At least 16 of Anwar's associates have been held under a harsh
security law that allows indefinite imprisonment without trial.
	   Anwar has denied the charges, saying they were politically
motivated.
	   Mahathir has promised that Anwar would be given a speedy and
fair tried in an open court. 	   
</TEXT>
