r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FEA-Chile-PensionFund 1stLd-Writethru   09-28 0757
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FEA-Chile-Pension Funds, 1st Ld-Writethru,0769 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Chile's privatized pension funds system has advice for others,
</HEADLINE>
self &QL; 
 &UR; Eds: Fixes spelling of `advice' in overline and 1st graf &QL; 
 &UR; By EDUARDO GALLARDO &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) _ Seventeen years after privatizing its
pension funds system, Chile may have some advice for other nations
adopting or planning a similar change.
	   But the Chilean experience, while generally considered
successful, also needs corrections, including cutting management
costs, experts say.
	   Since the private system was established in 1981 by the former
military regime of Gen. Augusto Pinochet, it has accumulated dlrs
31 billion _ in a country with a GNP of dlrs 83 billion _ from
deposits by workers and interest earnings.
	   The old state-owned and -managed system was abandoned because
over the years it became broke. Critics say it was too dependent on
the condition of the nation's finances, especially on the fiscal
deficit which in the '70s was large in most Latin American
countries. It was also seriously affected by galloping inflation,
which reached more than 600 percent annually in Chile in the
mid-70s.
	   In the new privatized system, the funds are managed by 12
private companies known as Administrators of Pension Funds, or
AFPs, and workers may freely pick which one they want to send up to
13 percent of their monthly salaries to feed their retirement
funds.
	   The AFPs invest in stocks, bonds and other financial instruments
at home and abroad, under regulation of a government agency called
Superintendency of AFPs.
	   Returns to the investments boomed to 12 percent a year until
five years ago, but since then they have dropped consistently and
posted a 1.7 percent loss during the first half of this year.
	   Superintendent of AFPs Julio Bustamante attributed the decline
to a slower pace of the Chilean economy which is expected to grow
by around 5 percent in 1998, compared to over 7 percent annually in
recent years.
	   Experts point out that the law that created the system took into
account the volatility of markets and set rules to prevent excess
risks. Among them is a provision that requires that a large portion
of the money be invested in ``fixed income instruments,'' with
yields guaranteed by the state after a certain time and immune to
markets' fluctuations.
	   Pedro Corona, who heads an association of AFPs, called the
system ``the engine that has fueled Chile's development and one of
the biggest social reforms ever made'' in the country.
	   Bustamante and others agree that corrections are needed in a
system that has been or is being implemented in other Latin
American nations, such as Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Peru,
Mexico, and El Salvador.
	   Reducing management costs, increasing investments abroad and
finding a wider variety of investments at home are needed to
perfect the system, said Bustamante's deputy, Andres Cuneo. Also
pressing is adopting special safeguards for the funds of workers in
the final years of their work life.
	   Workers have freedom to move from one AFP to another, which
creates competition among the AFPs to attract them. Some were known
to offer bicycles and other presents to lure customers.
	   But the practice, Cuneo told The Associated Press, has led the
AFPs to spend much money for marketing, thus making their
administration costs to skyrocket.
	   ``An estimated 3 percent of the money deposited by workers is
actually a fee they pay to the AFP for administering their money,''
he said, and the competition for clients is mostly responsible for
that.
	   The Superintendency recently took steps to reduce administrative
spending by the AFPs, especially by making switching from one AFP
to another more difficult, ``but not prohibiting it, as the basis
of the system is freedom of choice,'' Cuneo said.
	   At retirement age _ 65 for men and 60 for women _ workers can
use their accumulated funds to calculate a monthly pension, or
leave the income linked to the performance of those funds in the
market.
	   Most workers choose the first option, and monthly pensions in
the private system equal up to 80 percent of the workers' average
monthly salary in the last three years prior to retirement. This is
almost twice as much as it was in the old state-run system.
	   Despite the obvious results, Jorge Millan, a leader of the
Central Workers Federation, said one criticism of the system
remains: Workers should have a bigger say in the way their funds
are invested.
</TEXT>
(PROFILE
