<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Japan-NKorea Rocket </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
Japan refutes North Korea's claim it launched a satellite
</HEADLINE>
 &UR; By TODD ZAUN &QC; 
 &UR; Associated Press Writer &QC; 

<TEXT>
	   TOKYO (AP) _ There is little chance the rocket launched by North
Korea last month carried a satellite, Japan's Defense Agency said
Tuesday, contradicting claims by both the North and the U.S.
intelligence community.
	   No trace of a satellite has been found and investigators have
been unable to pick up broadcast signals that North Korea claimed
it transmitted, a Defense Agency investigation has determined.
	   The agency also contends the rocket, fired from a launch pad on
North Korea's east coast Aug. 31, did not reach the velocity
necessary to put a satellite into orbit, said an agency official,
who spoke on condition of anonymity.
	   The rocket flew over Japan's main island, causing deep concern
here and indicating that the North has acquired much better rocket
capabilities than previously suspected.
	   Determining exactly what was launched has proven to be extremely
difficult, however.
	   The North says it launched a ``Bright Star'' satellite that went
into earth orbit and transmitted patriotic songs.
	   U.S. intelligence agencies said the North had tested a
multi-stage ballistic missile, with one stage dropping into the Sea
of Japan between Japan and Russia, and another overshooting Japan
to crash into the Pacific.
	   American officials initially expressed doubt about the North's
satellite claim, but have since said a satellite was indeed
launched _ but failed to achieve orbit.
	   Japan's Defense Agency, however, said it believes the U.S.
position on the launch contains ``estimations'' and requires
further study to be more conclusive.
	   Officials on both sides have said that even if the launching did
involve a satellite, it was still a serious challenge to Japanese
security.
	   The launch came amid U.S. efforts to curb the communist state's
missile sales to Middle Eastern countries. North Korea reportedly
is trying to develop ballistic missiles with ranges long enough to
hit Hawaii and Alaska.
	   The Japanese protested the launch to the U.N. Security Council
and suspended its dlrs 1 billion contribution to a dlrs 4.6 billion
project to build nuclear reactors in North Korea.
	   The launch also prompted the United States and Japan to agreed
to conduct joint research on a missile defense system that could
protect the island nation from attack.
	   In response, North Korea this week accused the United States and
``other hostile forces'' of slander and threatened to use its new
rocket system for military purposes.
	   The United States has 100,000 troops in North Asia, about
one-half in Japan and one-third guarding the tense demilitarized
zone between North and South Korea.
 &UR; (tz-et)	   
</TEXT>
